[2026-05-06 09:54:13 +0700] [CODEX] ## AGI-9466 · NNP / RTP language-register boundary
[2026-05-06 09:54:13 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-06 09:54:13 +0700] [CODEX] **Why.** **NNP (No Negotiation Possible)** and **RTP (Refuse to Pay)** were easily confused — both surface as "I won't pay" patterns. Without a clear **language-register** boundary, the classifier defaulted to RTP for soft refusals, missing the NNP signal. The two need different downstream actions: **NNP** suggests the customer is open to alternatives if approached differently; **RTP** is a hard wall that ends negotiation.
[2026-05-06 09:54:13 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-06 09:54:13 +0700] [CODEX] > ### 🛠 What I did
[2026-05-06 09:54:13 +0700] [CODEX] > Pinned the boundary criterion explicitly: **NNP = soft / neutral / non-committal language; RTP = hard / unambiguous; the count of declines does not determine the code** — a customer can decline 5 times softly (still NNP) or once hard ("I refuse" — RTP). Ran `paco-agi9466-v2@d43bc8e` against NNP × 3 cases on both classifier paths to validate.
[2026-05-06 09:54:13 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-06 09:54:13 +0700] [CODEX] **Result.** **3/3 exact match plus found-in for NNP × 3 in both NORMAL and BASIC classifier paths.** Boundary criterion validated end-to-end. Captured in `memory/project_nnp_rtp_boundary_may04.md`.
[2026-05-06 09:54:13 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-06 09:54:13 +0700] [CODEX] **Links.**
[2026-05-06 09:54:13 +0700] [CODEX] - `memory/project_nnp_rtp_boundary_may04.md` — captures the criterion wording + the 3-case validation.
[2026-05-06 09:54:13 +0700] [CODEX] - `paco-agi9466-v2@d43bc8e` — pinned build.
