[2026-05-07 22:01:35 +0700] [CODEX] > **OKR scope.** Work today serves **O2-KR2** *(Auto QC for call codes — reduce human-QC bug reports by ≥75%)* and **O4-KR1** *(Automated pipeline for data collection, annotation, prompt optimization and evaluation for call codes)* under the [Hai-group OKR 2026Q2](https://trustingsocial1.atlassian.net/wiki/spaces/LR/pages/5142773771). Not tracked as JIRA comments today per direction.
[2026-05-07 22:01:35 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-07 22:01:35 +0700] [CODEX] ## What the OKRs target
[2026-05-07 22:01:35 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-07 22:01:35 +0700] [CODEX] **O2-KR2** asks for an automated QC layer over call codes so that the volume of bug-report-driven manual investigation drops by 75% or more. **O4-KR1** asks for an end-to-end pipeline that closes the loop from "we have a call we want to investigate" through to "explanation grounded in evidence" — without humans hand-stitching commands. Both KRs share the same bottleneck: today, when product flags a call-code looking wrong, an analyst has to SSH to the zero server, run `postcall_qa_v1`, read JSON artifacts, and write up the why. That round-trip is what we want to compress.
[2026-05-07 22:01:35 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-07 22:01:35 +0700] [CODEX] ## What we did
[2026-05-07 22:01:35 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-07 22:01:35 +0700] [CODEX] Built and shipped **Phase 2A + Phase 2A2 of PACO** — the postcall-agent bot. PACO accepts natural-language operator questions in English or Vietnamese (*"what is the postcall for X?"*, *"why is X coded WRN?"*, *"why is X not PAY?"*, *"rerun it"*), classifies intent via `openai/gpt-5.3-codex` over the TS LLM Hub, routes to one of three typed mission contracts (`postcall_qa` justify/rerun, `pull_conversation` transcript extract, `whynot` desired-vs-actual diagnosis), pulls evidence from cached postcall artifacts on disk (with a narrow Datadog `@app:postcall_analysis` fallback), enriches with the call-code definition from `main.yaml`, and rewrites the structured analysis into a grounded Q&A reply in the user's language. Slot-based session memory resolves anaphora ("rerun it" → last call_id). A mock Slack UI exposes it for hand-testing with a live `/info` event trace. Full engineering detail (test cases, bug fixes, file map, architectural decisions) is at `paco/docs/paco_phase2a_engineering_log_20260507.md`.
[2026-05-07 22:01:35 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-07 22:01:35 +0700] [CODEX] ## What we got so far
[2026-05-07 22:01:35 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-07 22:01:35 +0700] [CODEX] - **112 / 112 hermetic tests** passing in 0.44 s; **live 4/4** on the test phrasings in `paco/docs/addition_test.md` against the real cached call `Yv7gbbcidQbcuQGieZPOMw` (final code WRN). Off-topic queries land on the polite "out-of-scope" template via the narrow-intelligence guard.
[2026-05-07 22:01:35 +0700] [CODEX] - **Loop time compression toward O2-KR2.** A bug-report investigation that used to be a multi-step manual sequence is now `@paco why is X coded WRN?` in chat → ~14 s reply citing the call-code definition + actual transcript line as evidence. The 75% reduction target is the next thing to actually measure (need a baseline cohort of QC tickets to compare against).
[2026-05-07 22:01:35 +0700] [CODEX] - **Pipeline coverage toward O4-KR1.** Three mission contracts cover the four canonical operator questions (postcall summary / why-this-code / why-final-code / why-not-other-code). Adding a new mission is now a self-contained `MissionContract` in one file plus a registry entry — no router edits — which is the shape O4-KR1 needs to scale to "data collection, annotation, prompt optimization and evaluation" coverage.
[2026-05-07 22:01:35 +0700] [CODEX] - **Open follow-ups:** wire PACO output into the existing QC ticket flow (so closures get auto-counted toward the 75% target), and add a *prompt-optimization* mission that proposes call_code_descriptions edits when whynot diagnoses repeat boundary failures.
[2026-05-07 22:01:35 +0700] [CODEX] 
