[2026-05-12 22:02:10 +0700] [CODEX] ## What I Did
[2026-05-12 22:02:10 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-12 22:02:10 +0700] [CODEX] Converted the Q2 postcall work into an execution brief centered on two measurable KRs: **Binh-KR1** means increasing call-code test data to at least 750 rows and at least 10 rows per call code; **Binh-KR2** means using Auto-QC to reduce human-QC bug reports by at least 75%.
[2026-05-12 22:02:10 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-12 22:02:10 +0700] [CODEX] For KR1, I anchored the plan on the current dataset baseline: v1 has 124 rows, v1b has 127 rows after adding 3 SIF rows, the total gap to 750 is 623 rows, and the current holes are absent or under-sampled codes such as `NKP`, `CSM`, `FTP`, `PAY`, `PIF`, `LGH`, `PRS`, and `WFR`. I also kept completion codes quality-gated because `PAY`, `SIF`, `PIF`, and `FTP` need terminal payment or transfer evidence before they count as solved.
[2026-05-12 22:02:10 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-12 22:02:10 +0700] [CODEX] For KR2, I framed PACO as the automation foundation that still needs a measurement loop. The shipped PACO capabilities include Brain Router, MissionContract registry, session memory/anaphora, `postcall_qa`, `pull_conversation`, `whynot`, LLM rewrite, Mock Slack UI, `/info` trace, and 112/112 hermetic tests. The next gap is turning those capabilities into an `auto_qc_result` table and a human-QC bug-reduction baseline.
[2026-05-12 22:02:10 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-12 22:02:10 +0700] [CODEX] I also documented the planning handoff: the Cline weekly and Q2 drafts are review drafts, Claude created a parallel weekly draft for comparison, and the immediate Monday decision is which weekly planner to promote. The same recap records the main blocker: the canonical human-QC bug source is still unknown, so the fallback is a proxy denominator from v1b sanity-eval failures tagged `denominator=proxy_v0`.
[2026-05-12 22:02:10 +0700] [CODEX] 
