[2026-05-12 22:03:03 +0700] [CODEX] docs/session_recap/20260511_weekly-planner-cline-handoff.md:70:- TODO: consider promoting to memory — **Permission-rule path strings are literal, not normalized.** A `//Users/...` typo silently voids an allow rule; downstream reads/writes hit the default deny with no error pointing at the bad rule. When permission errors look inexplicable, grep the settings file for the exact path string the harness is being asked about. `Write(/Users/.../postcall/**)` and `Write(//Users/.../postcall/**)` are different rules.
[2026-05-12 22:03:03 +0700] [CODEX] docs/session_recap/20260511_weekly-planner-cline-handoff.md:71:- TODO: consider promoting to memory — **Settings edits don't hot-reload in "don't ask" mode.** Even with a corrected rule on disk, the in-memory permission cache from session start blocks new writes. The fixes: (a) `/permissions` slash command updates both file and in-memory cache, (b) toggling permission mode (Shift+Tab), (c) restart the session. Verbal approval in chat doesn't propagate to either.
[2026-05-12 22:03:03 +0700] [CODEX] docs/session_recap/20260511_weekly-planner-cline-handoff.md:72:- TODO: consider promoting to memory — **Prior-Claude provenance.** Auto-written permission rules from past sessions can carry typos forward indefinitely. When asking the user to fix settings, check first whether Claude itself authored the broken rule — own the cleanup framing.
