[2026-05-12 22:05:10 +0700] [CODEX] ## MECE Risk
[2026-05-12 22:05:10 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-12 22:05:10 +0700] [CODEX] ### EPE Removed
[2026-05-12 22:05:10 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-12 22:05:10 +0700] [CODEX] Risk level: Medium, unless product confirms payment deferral is no longer an available bot outcome.
[2026-05-12 22:05:10 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-12 22:05:10 +0700] [CODEX] Removing EPE does not create a mutual-exclusivity problem. It actually removes an overlap with nearby financial-resolution and hardship codes. The risk is collectivity: if the conversation still reaches an approved deferral outcome, the active taxonomy no longer has a precise bucket for "customer enrolled in payment deferral."
[2026-05-12 22:05:10 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-12 22:05:10 +0700] [CODEX] Likely fallback classifications:
[2026-05-12 22:05:10 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-12 22:05:10 +0700] [CODEX] | Scenario after removal | Best active fallback | Residual hole |
[2026-05-12 22:05:10 +0700] [CODEX] | --- | --- | --- |
[2026-05-12 22:05:10 +0700] [CODEX] | Customer has hardship, requests deferral, and deferral is approved/enrolled | HCH | Loses the terminal resolution. HCH says why they needed help, not that deferral was granted. |
[2026-05-12 22:05:10 +0700] [CODEX] | Customer accepts a structured altered payment arrangement instead of explicit deferral enrollment | PPA | Acceptable only if the transcript has concrete plan terms. Not equivalent to a formal deferral program. |
[2026-05-12 22:05:10 +0700] [CODEX] | Customer verified, asks about options, no clear commitment/payment outcome | IDV | Large reporting loss: verified engagement with product relief becomes generic IDV. |
[2026-05-12 22:05:10 +0700] [CODEX] | Human transfer happens because deferral needs specialist handling | EPT / TSR / TLM depending transcript | Captures transfer path, not approval/enrollment. |
[2026-05-12 22:05:10 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-12 22:05:10 +0700] [CODEX] MECE conclusion: EPE removal leaves a real coverage hole if payment deferral approval can still occur. If product has retired the deferral flow, no hole remains.
[2026-05-12 22:05:10 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-12 22:05:10 +0700] [CODEX] ### EPD Removed
[2026-05-12 22:05:10 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-12 22:05:10 +0700] [CODEX] Risk level: Low to medium.
[2026-05-12 22:05:10 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-12 22:05:10 +0700] [CODEX] Removing EPD also improves exclusivity because "deferral denied" often co-occurs with hardship, refusal, or later payment negotiation. The collectivity risk is narrower than EPE because denial usually leads to another customer outcome.
[2026-05-12 22:05:10 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-12 22:05:10 +0700] [CODEX] Likely fallback classifications:
[2026-05-12 22:05:10 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-12 22:05:10 +0700] [CODEX] | Scenario after removal | Best active fallback | Residual hole |
[2026-05-12 22:05:10 +0700] [CODEX] | --- | --- | --- |
[2026-05-12 22:05:10 +0700] [CODEX] | Customer requested deferral, was denied, then says they cannot pay | HCH | Reasonable if the hardship remains the substantive outcome. Loses denial-specific reporting. |
[2026-05-12 22:05:10 +0700] [CODEX] | Customer requested deferral, was denied, then refuses alternatives | RTP or NNP | Reasonable if refusal/soft decline is explicit. Loses denial context. |
[2026-05-12 22:05:10 +0700] [CODEX] | Customer disputes denial/eligibility or debt validity | DIS or CPR | Only valid if complaint/dispute language exists. |
[2026-05-12 22:05:10 +0700] [CODEX] | Customer is denied deferral and call ends with no further outcome | IDV or HCH | This is the main gap: the terminal outcome "deferral denied" is gone. |
[2026-05-12 22:05:10 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-12 22:05:10 +0700] [CODEX] MECE conclusion: EPD removal is safer than EPE because downstream outcomes often absorb it, but a "denied then call ends" case becomes under-specified.
[2026-05-12 22:05:10 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-12 22:05:10 +0700] [CODEX] ## Overall Assessment
[2026-05-12 22:05:10 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-12 22:05:11 +0700] [CODEX] The removal is ME-safe only if Affirm no longer wants payment-deferral disposition reporting. If the product can still approve or deny payment deferrals, removing EPE/EPD creates a collectivity gap, not an overlap gap.
[2026-05-12 22:05:11 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-12 22:05:11 +0700] [CODEX] Recommended operating rule after removal:
[2026-05-12 22:05:11 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-12 22:05:11 +0700] [CODEX] | Removed code | Active fallback policy |
[2026-05-12 22:05:11 +0700] [CODEX] | --- | --- |
[2026-05-12 22:05:11 +0700] [CODEX] | EPE | Use HCH only when hardship is explicit; use PPA only when concrete payment-plan terms are agreed; otherwise IDV/transfer code based on actual terminal event. |
[2026-05-12 22:05:11 +0700] [CODEX] | EPD | Use the next substantive outcome after denial: HCH, NNP, RTP, DIS, CPR, or IDV if no stronger outcome appears. |
[2026-05-12 22:05:11 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-12 22:05:11 +0700] [CODEX] Recommended product question:
[2026-05-12 22:05:11 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-12 22:05:11 +0700] [CODEX] Can an Affirm bot still enroll or deny a customer in a payment deferral program? If yes, do not leave this as pure prompt removal; either restore EPE/EPD as postprocess-only product-signal codes or add explicit fallback mapping in downstream reporting.
[2026-05-12 22:05:11 +0700] [CODEX] 
