[2026-05-13 22:02:21 +0700] [CODEX] output/from_zero/signal_experiment_40_dtmf_rerun_20260513_1655/per_conversation/0017_4rFEYd2JTyrR4IPi-vpqiw/llm_call_0004.json:28:      "content": "You are an expert at writing a concise email or sms to customer for wraping-up and following-up call. Given a conversation PHONE_CALL_TRANSCRIPT, extract follow up email or sms according to the main idea of the conversation transcript but do not repeat the same content. \n\n# General rules for both email and sms:\n- No greeting, no sign-off, no company, no hotline numbers, no portal links, or no compliance footers branding should be included in the response\n- Tone: empathetic, supportive, friendly, human tone\n- Take into account the situation of customer (e.g. hardship, confusion, dispute)\n- No include hotline numbers, portal links, or compliance footers\n\n## For email\nEmail can have up to 5 sentences. Pay attention to the customer's situation - show empathy when necessary. Pay attention to call outcome, such as: Dispute \u2192 waiting for updates / next steps, callcode: RTP \u2192 suggest considering payment options, callcode: PTP \u2192 confirm what was discussed and agreed. Portal-leading sentence: If a payment plan has been confirmed, repeat the payment plan details; If there is no payment plan confirmed, gently lead the customer toward reviewing available resolution options (without mentioning links, portals, access steps, or instructions). State next step or expectation.\n\n## For sms\nSMS can have up to 60 characters. Acknowledge the call, reflect the call outcome, include ONE clear follow-up intent.\n\n\n## PHONE_CALL_TRANSCRIPT\n```\nassistant: Hi, my name is Becca. Thank you for calling Kompato AI. We're on a recorded line. How can I assist you today?\nuser: What is this?\nassistant: This is Kompato AI. Uh, am I speaking with Kevin Shaw?\nuser: Yeah.\nassistant: Hi, Kevin. Um, so again, this is Kompato AI reaching out regarding a personal business matter. We can continue the call if you can verify either date of birth or last four of social on file.\nuser: 6-12-82.\nassistant: Thank you. I'll advise that this is an attempt to collect a debt by a debt collector. Any information obtained is used for that purpose. Kevin, we're reaching out on behalf of Unity Asset Management LLC regarding a $1,319.74 balance. The original creditor was Credit Ninja. What are we able to do to get this resolved today?\nuser: Please stop calling me. How about that? I don't, I don't know what you guys are talking about.\nassistant: We can add you to the do not call list. Okay, we're happy to provide validation information or confirm, you know, the open date,\nuser: No, I don't,\nassistant: whatever would\u2014 Okay,\nuser: I don't need, I don't, I don't need any information from you guys. I just need you to stop calling me. I, I don't, I don't know what you're talking about. Nope,\nassistant: we'll add you to the do not call list. Is there anything else I can do to assist you today?\nuser: just stop calling me.\nassistant: Have a great day.\n```\n\n# Response Format\nReturn ONLY the email or sms content as plain text without any tags or formatting."
[2026-05-13 22:02:21 +0700] [CODEX] output/from_zero/signal_experiment_40_dtmf_rerun_20260513_1655/per_conversation/0006_DWdQ_XF6hNSl0FLbjj8ESA/llm_call_0001.json:28:      "content": "You are a Collection Agent specialized in classifying conversations into the one to three most relevant call codes.\nGiven abstracted conversation history, list of call codes with their descriptions, and reflection variable values with their descriptions (optional) and  your task to analyze and classify the conversation into the one to three most relevant call codes.\n\n# Instruction\n- Thoroughly analyze the conversation history, dictionary variable values, state variable descriptions, and call code descriptions.\n- Carefully review the conversation to select the one to three call codes that best fit the context and details of the exchange.\n- When reasoning, you may reference reflection variable values and descriptions if they help justify your choices, but focus primarily on the conversation context and call code descriptions.\n- Your justification should combine insights from the conversation, call code descriptions, and other inputs as relevant.\n\n#  Notes:\n- Consider all possible angles and variable values, not just the most direct or frequent call code.\n- Make sure the reasoning is clear, specific, and references the data provided.\n\n\n# Output Format\n- Return your reasoning in <reasoning> </reasoning> tags\n- Return list potential call code wrapped in <call_code_list> </call_code_list> tags.\n\n# Input Information\n\n## Conversation History\n```\nassistant: Hi, this is Reason Dixon speaking on a recorded line here at Kompato AI. How may I assist you today?\nuser: I'm here. So this is Connie Parrish. They had me, um, to set up a payment for $150 one week, $150 the next week, through credit\u2014 I mean, through Citric Bank. Is this the right person I'm talking to?\nassistant: Uh, you said for Citric Bank? Wait,\nuser: Yes.\nassistant: hold on.\nuser: Hi.\nassistant: Just to confirm we have the right party on the line, I show a date of birth of December 28th,\nuser: That's great.\nassistant: 1965. Is that correct?\nuser: That's\nassistant: Thank you. Every caller must state that this is an attempt to collect the debt by debt collector and any information obtained will be used for that purpose. Oh, we did speak with you, it looks like last week, but we were speaking with you about a Republic Finance account that you had set up with, not the other company.\nuser: Yeah, but I can't do that to the 13th. But he also said I had one with Citric Bank for $338. Am I got the wrong number?\nassistant: Yeah, that's\u2014 yes, you called the wrong number for that. I'm sorry.\nuser: Okay, well, I need to inform you that the bank told me a story. It's going to be the 14th, but I'm still going to pay it. But now I don't know what number I got to call for them because I thought that he told me to call this, this number.\nassistant: Oh yeah, I'm sorry, I apologize about that. I wouldn't be able to help you out with that one because we\u2014 that's a completely different company than us. I'm sorry, man.\nuser: Okay, well, just keep me on form.\nuser: As soon as I get the, the money for the, the, the The other one, I'll call you back, but I got to find the number to that other man, and I don't know, I thought it was through y'all.\nassistant: No, that's not us. I'm sorry, I apologize.\nuser: Okay, just, uh, I'll call you back on the 14th, 13th or the 14th, sir, whenever they turn it loose at the bank. I want to write this morning,\nassistant: Okay. Ah, this there. Thank you.\nuser: still won't turn it loose, but They got to turn it loose, but I don't know when. So just give me to the 13th and see if,\nassistant: Right.\nuser: uh, they\u2014 that I can\u2014 I'm a new customer and it's like a 14-day hold on it. So just as soon as I get it, sir, I'll give it to you.\nuser: Thank you.\nassistant: Okay. All right, give us a call on that time and we'll go from there. You're welcome.\n```\n\n## List of Call Codes and Their Descriptions\n- `NLM`: Description: Agent encounters a voicemail system, automated/answering system or a person confirming the customer is unavailable, and no substantive message or actionable instruction is left.\nUse when: Agent reaches voicemail/automated system or is told the person is unavailable. Call ends without leaving a callback number, stated reason for call, or formal identification after the beep. Agent may provide initial introduction (name, company, customer name) but does not leave actionable requests.\nEdge cases: Agent speaks in confusion to the voicemail machine (e.g., \"May I please speak with [Name]?\") without leaving a formal message \u2192 NLM, not LM. Brief interactions ending immediately after unavailability is confirmed \u2192 NLM. If agent intentionally leaves a callback number or states the reason for the call \u2192 LM, not NLM. This code excludes calls where the number reached does not belong to the intended customer (use WRN).\nFew-shots: Agent hears \"leave a message after the tone,\" says \"May I speak with John?\" then hangs up \u2192 NLM. Person answers \"She's not available,\" agent says \"Okay, thank you\" \u2192 NLM.\n\n\n- `LM`: Description: Agent encounters a voicemail, automated/answering system AND leaves a substantive message (callback number, reason for call, or formal identification) after the beep.\nUse when: Voicemail system is detected (system prompts like \"record your name,\" \"after the tone,\" \"state your reason\"). Agent explicitly leaves a callback number, states reason for call, or provides formal identification AFTER the recording tone.\nEdge cases: Agent merely speaks in confusion to the machine without leaving a formal message \u2192 NLM, not LM. Must have substantive, actionable content (callback number, stated reason, or formal identification) AFTER the beep. If call terminates or agent gets confused without leaving a formal message \u2192 NLM.\nFew-shots: Agent hears beep, then says \"This is Anna from Kompato, please call us back at 1-888-555-1234\" \u2192 LM. Agent hears beep, says \"May I speak with John?\" then disconnects \u2192 NLM (not LM).\n\n\n- `HUP`: Description: Hang Up - Call ends or is effectively abandoned before any meaningful two-way conversation occurs and before any identity or account information is verified. This includes cases where the agent only delivers the opening, the customer says nothing further, the line goes silent, the customer disconnects immediately, or the customer gives only a cryptic, random, or irrelevant phrase (e.g., random nouns, a business name like \"Orange Wagon\" or \"Joe's Pizza\") without clearly expressing intent to engage or continue the conversation. CRITICAL: A customer answering with what sounds like a business name (e.g., \"Orange Wagon\") is NOT the same as the customer explicitly stating \"this is a business\" or \"you have the wrong number.\" Answering with a business-sounding phrase alone \u2014 without the caller explicitly confirming they are NOT the intended person \u2014 does NOT qualify as WRN. Use HUP. WRN requires the caller to EXPLICITLY state it is a wrong number or that they are a business, not merely answer with a phrase that could be a business name.\nUse when: The interaction never progresses beyond the initial contact attempt and the customer's response does not confirm their identity or a clear intent to continue the conversation. A single unrelated, cryptic, or nonsensical phrase does not qualify as engagement unless the customer provides further input indicating an intent to engage, continue, or clarify their response.\nEdge cases: Distinguish from NVR \u2014 If the agent asks \"Is this [Name]?\" and the customer engages in a SUBSTANTIVE back-and-forth exchange (asking questions, demanding context, showing hostility) without confirming identity, use NVR. If the customer provides only a brief response (\"Hello?\") and the call ends quickly without real engagement, use HUP. The key question: was there a meaningful exchange after the name question, or did the call just die? Do NOT use HUP if voicemail is reached (use NLM/LM), if the person explicitly refuses name or ID verification after substantive engagement (use NVR/HUA), if identity was confirmed and the call dropped during authentication (use HUA), or if the person clearly states they are the wrong party (use WRN). WRN requires EXPLICIT confirmation of wrong number. Simply answering with a business name or unrelated phrase without explicitly stating it is a wrong number does NOT qualify as WRN \u2014 use HUP instead.\nFew-shots: Customer says \"Orange Wagon\" then call ends \u2192 HUP (not WRN) \u2014 answering with a business-sounding name without explicitly saying \"this is a business\" or \"wrong number\" is HUP. Customer answers, says nothing, line goes silent \u2192 HUP. Customer says \"Hello?\" then immediately disconnects \u2192 HUP. Even if reflection variable says response=business, if the caller never EXPLICITLY said \"this is a business\" or \"wrong number,\" classify as HUP.\n\n\n- `IDF`: Description: ID Verification Failed - Customer confirms the right name, but DOB/SSN/zip information does not match with data in the system, OR customer refuses to verify their identity through standard verification protocols.\nUse when: Customer says \"No\" when asked if DOB on file is correct (data mismatch). Customer provides a DOB, SSN, or zip that does not match system records. Customer says \"No,\" \"Nope,\" \"I'm not giving you that,\" \"I refuse\" when asked for DOB/SSN (active refusal while still on the line). Customer confirms they are not the intended person during verification.\nEdge cases: Key distinction from HUA \u2014 IDF = customer provided WRONG data (DOB/SSN doesn't match) OR customer is still on the line ACTIVELY refusing/engaging (saying \"No,\" asking questions, arguing). HUA = customer confirmed name but the call ENDED (hung up, went silent, line dropped, timed out) during verification \u2014 no active engagement, just disconnection. If the customer says \"No\" to DOB and CONTINUES the conversation (asks questions, argues, refuses more) \u2192 IDF. If the customer goes silent and call times out \u2192 HUA. If the customer provided wrong data earlier but then the call also drops \u2192 still IDF (data mismatch occurred).\nFew-shots: Customer says \"No\" to \"Is Feb 22 1961 your DOB?\" then says \"It's not\" \u2192 IDF (data mismatch). Customer provides SSN 2549 that doesn't match \u2192 IDF. Customer says \"Nope\" repeatedly to DOB while still talking \u2192 IDF (active refusal). Customer provides wrong DOB \"2 3 65\" that doesn't match \u2192 IDF (data doesn't match even if conversation continues). Customer says \"No\" to DOB on file, then provides different DOB + wrong SSN, then goes silent \u2192 IDF (data mismatch happened before silence). Customer confirms name, agent asks for DOB, customer goes silent \u2192 call ends \u2192 HUA (no data provided, just disconnected).\n\n\n- `HUA`: Description: Hang Up During Authentication - Customer confirmed their name but the call ENDED (hung up, disconnected, went silent) during the ID verification process. The verification was never completed \u2014 the call was cut short.\nUse when: Customer confirmed their name but the call ended during verification \u2014 customer hung up, went silent (multiple SILENCE markers), line dropped, or call timed out. The customer did NOT provide any DOB/SSN data and did NOT actively refuse \u2014 the call simply ended. Also applies when customer asks context questions (\"Who is this?\", \"What\u2019s this about?\") but the call ends before any verification data is exchanged.\nEdge cases: Key distinction from IDF \u2014 If the customer says \"No\" to the DOB on file (data mismatch) or actively says \"Nope,\" \"I refuse\" while still engaging \u2192 IDF (not HUA). HUA is for calls that ENDED during auth without data being checked. If the customer asks \"Who is this?\" then goes silent \u2192 HUA (call ended, no verification data). If the customer says \"I don\u2019t know\" to DOB and the call continues \u2192 IDF (refusal while engaged). If the customer says \"I don\u2019t know\" and immediately hangs up \u2192 HUA (call ended).\nFew-shots: Customer confirms name, agent asks for DOB, customer goes silent \u2192 call ends \u2192 HUA. Customer confirms name, asks \"Who is this? What\u2019s this about?\" \u2192 call ends \u2192 HUA. Customer confirms name, DOB question asked, customer says \"What\u2019s this concerning?\" then silence \u2192 HUA. Customer confirms name, says \"I don\u2019t know it\" to DOB and call ends \u2192 HUA (call ended, no data checked). Customer says \"No\" to DOB on file \u2192 IDF (not HUA \u2014 data mismatch). Customer says \"Nope\" repeatedly while still on line \u2192 IDF (not HUA \u2014 active refusal). Call truncated right after DOB question is asked, before customer responds \u2192 HUA (not IDV \u2014 verification was never completed).\n\n\n- `NVR`: Description: Name Verification Refused - Customer failed to confirm their name/identity following agent\u2019s attempt, through explicit refusal, evasion, incoherence, or hostility.\nUse when: After the agent asks \"Is this [Name]?\" or similar, the customer responds with SUBSTANTIVE verbal engagement that avoids confirming identity \u2014 defensive questions (\"Who\u2019s calling?,\" \"What do you want?\"), evasion (\"Hold on,\" \"Wait a minute\"), incoherent/irrelevant answers, hostility (profanity, aggression), or repeated demands for context. The key signal: the customer engages in a back-and-forth exchange with the agent without confirming their name.\nEdge cases: Distinguish from HUP \u2014 NVR requires SUBSTANTIVE verbal interaction after a name verification attempt (multiple exchanges, questions, hostility). A single \"Hello?\" or brief response followed by immediate disconnection is still HUP if no real exchange occurred. Use NVR when: (1) the customer asks questions about the caller/company, (2) the customer responds with hostility or profanity, (3) the customer engages in multiple turns without confirming identity. Use HUP when: the call ends before any meaningful exchange, or the customer provides only a brief/single-word response before disconnecting. Distinguish from CAB \u2014 if callback arranged specifically because identity could not be verified \u2192 NVR.\nFew-shots: Agent asks \"Is this John Smith?\" and customer says \"Who is calling? What do you want?\" \u2192 NVR. Agent asks for name, customer says \"Kiss my ass, bitch\" \u2192 NVR. Agent asks \"Is this Jeffrey Soliz?\" and customer asks \"Who\u2019s this?\" then \"Big Sky?\" (multiple turns) \u2192 NVR. Customer picks up, says \"Hello?\" once, then disconnects \u2192 HUP (not NVR).\n\n\n- `IDV`: Description: ID Verification Successful - Customer successfully passed all required identity verification checks \u2014 confirmed name AND at least one additional identifier (DOB, or SSN). This becomes the mandatory default classification for the rest of the call unless a more specific terminal disposition is reached.\nUse when: Customer explicitly confirms name AND provides/confirms at least one additional identifier. IDV stays as the default unless a more specific outcome occurs. Switch away from IDV when: the customer declines one or more payment offers (use NNP), a payment arrangement is made (use PPA/PPIF/PSIF), the customer explicitly refuses to pay any amount (use RTP), or any other terminal disposition applies.\nEdge cases: Customer expresses uncertainty about debt or agency \u2192 still IDV. Customer gives non-committal response to payment offer (\"I'm not sure,\" \"Maybe,\" \"Possibly,\" \"I'll think about it\") without clearly declining \u2192 still IDV (not NNP \u2014 non-committal is not a clear decline). Declining to share personal circumstances or explain default reasons is NOT a refusal to pay and NOT NNP \u2192 still IDV. If no specific payment amounts were offered at all, the call remains IDV. CRITICAL \u2014 If a payment offer was made but NO customer response to that offer is present in the conversation (the conversation ends immediately after the offer, or the customer's reply to the offer is missing), this is NOT NNP \u2192 still IDV. NNP requires the customer's explicit decline to be visible in the conversation. If payment was offered AND the customer explicitly said \"No\" or clearly declined, use NNP (not IDV). Only override with RTP if customer makes direct, unambiguous statement refusing to pay ANY amount (e.g., \"I won't pay,\" \"I refuse\"). Hostility, profanity, or incoherent outbursts (e.g., \"don't fuck yourself,\" random aggressive words) without explicit payment refusal \u2192 still IDV, NOT RTP and NOT CPR. A customer who becomes hostile or disengaged after verification but has NOT made a formal complaint about service/practices is NOT CPR \u2014 general hostility or profanity directed at no specific service issue is just a failed conversation, which remains IDV.\nFew-shots: Customer confirms name + DOB, then says \"No\" to sharing circumstances \u2192 IDV. Customer verified, payment discussed but customer says \"Possibly\" or \"Maybe\" without committing or declining \u2192 IDV (not NNP). Customer verified, declines to explain default circumstances, no payment amounts offered \u2192 IDV (not NNP). Customer verified, becomes hostile and uses profanity (\"don't fuck yourself\") but never explicitly refuses to pay \u2192 IDV (not RTP, not CPR). Customer verified, says incoherent hostile things and call ends \u2192 IDV. Customer verified, says \"I'm not familiar with this agency\" \u2192 IDV. Agent asks about circumstances, customer says \"No,\" agent then offers monthly payment amount, conversation ends with no customer response to the offer \u2192 IDV (customer only declined to share circumstances \u2014 no explicit decline of payment offer was shown).\n\n\n- `TSR`: Description: Transfer to Representative - Customer explicitly requests to speak with a live person, or a structural handoff to a live agent occurs during the call. Once a transfer request is made or handoff occurs, this code remains the classification for the entire call. IMPORTANT: If the conversation ends with the AI agent transferring to a live agent (e.g., \"Let me connect you with a live agent\"), this is ALWAYS TSR regardless of what happened earlier in the call.\nUse when: Customer says \"customer service,\" \"representative,\" \"human,\" \"operator,\" \"transfer me,\" or similar. Agent says \"while I check availability for a live agent\" followed by a live person introduction. Transfer request is made even if the virtual assistant fails to fulfill it. ALSO use when the AI agent initiates a transfer to a live agent due to a system failure (e.g., payment processing error, unable to retrieve payment information, \"The system can not retrieve your payment information\") \u2014 this is a structural handoff even though the customer did not request it. RULE: Look at the FINAL outcome of the call. If the call ends with a transfer to a live agent, classify as TSR \u2014 not the code that was applicable before the transfer.\nEdge cases: TSR overrides IDV, NCV, CAB, PPIF, PSIF, PPA, NNP, RTP, and other standard operational codes. CRITICAL OVERRIDE: Even if the customer agreed to pay in full (PPIF), provided a PIN, and the system attempted payment \u2014 if the payment system FAILED and the AI agent then transfers to a live agent, you MUST select TSR, NOT PPIF. The transfer is the FINAL disposition and supersedes ALL prior payment commitments. Even if the live agent performs verification, updates addresses, or discusses payment, you MUST select TSR. HUA, DIS, CDS still take precedence over TSR. If customer refuses secondary verification AND requests live agent \u2192 HUA (not TSR; refusal takes precedence). Once transfer request is made or system-initiated handoff occurs, TSR remains classification regardless of prior payment commitments or subsequent content. Key indicators: \"Let me connect you with a live agent,\" \"while I check availability,\" \"customer service,\" \"The system can not retrieve your payment information.\"\nFew-shots: Customer agrees to pay full $2112.50, provides PIN 123456, system repeatedly says \"retrieving your payment information,\" then fails and agent says \"The system can not retrieve your payment information. Let me connect you with a live agent\" \u2192 TSR (NOT PPIF \u2014 the transfer at the END of the call is the final disposition, overriding the earlier payment commitment). Customer says \"customer service\" at the start, then agent transfers to live person who handles the whole call \u2192 TSR. Customer says \"Representative. Representative.\" and agent fails to transfer \u2192 TSR. Customer says \"I want a person\" while refusing DOB \u2192 HUA (not TSR).\n\n\n- `INC`: Description: Consumer Incapacitated - A third party (or the customer) reports the account holder is deceased, severely ill, hospitalized long-term, or mentally incapacitated.\nUse when: Caller states the account holder has passed away (deceased, died). Caller states account holder has a severe or long-term condition preventing engagement (dementia, coma, brain injury, long-term hospitalization, brain fog).\nEdge cases: Minor/temporary illness (\"they have a cold,\" \"they're sleeping\") \u2192 NOT INC. \"Brain fog\" qualifies as mental incapacity \u2192 INC. Incapacitation must imply serious, potentially long-term inability to engage.\nFew-shots: \"She's not available, sir. She's deceased now. This is her husband.\" \u2192 INC. \"She has brain fog. How can I help you?\" \u2192 INC. \"She's been in the hospital for a couple of weeks, she's battling cancer.\" \u2192 INC.\n\n\n- `LGB`: Description: Language Barrier - Communication could not proceed effectively due to language differences between agent and customer.\nUse when: Customer indicates inability to understand or communicate in the language being used. Language barrier makes meaningful conversation impossible.\nEdge cases: N/A\nFew-shots: Customer responds only in Spanish to English-speaking agent \u2192 LGB. Customer says \"I don't understand English\" \u2192 LGB.\n\n\n- `RTP`: Description: Refusal to Pay - Customer explicitly and unambiguously refused to make any payment on the account ONLY after the creditor presented the balance AND made MULTIPLE attempts to negotiate payment options. RTP requires: (1) identity verification was completed, (2) the balance was presented, (3) the creditor offered multiple payment plans or settlement options, and (4) the customer explicitly rejected ALL of them or stated they will not pay any amount.\nUse when: Customer uses explicit refusal language such as \"I can\u2019t pay anything,\" \"None,\" \"I\u2019m not paying,\" \"It\u2019s not possible,\" \"I refuse to pay,\" or \"I will never pay.\" RTP requires an unambiguous statement of intent NOT to pay \u2014 not merely saying \"No\" to specific offered amounts. Simply declining offered payment amounts without explicit refusal language is NNP, not RTP. The customer must have been given a genuine opportunity to negotiate before RTP applies.\nEdge cases: CRITICAL \u2014 Declining to share personal circumstances or explain default reasons is NOT RTP (use IDV). Profanity or hostility alone does NOT automatically qualify as RTP \u2014 the customer must have explicitly refused to pay or been given multiple payment options which they all rejected. Random profanity, frustration, or incoherent hostile outbursts (e.g., \"don\u2019t fuck yourself\") WITHOUT an explicit statement refusing payment is NOT RTP. If the conversation never reached the payment negotiation stage (i.e., no specific payment amounts were offered and rejected), profanity alone should be classified as IDV (if verified) or the appropriate pre-negotiation code. RTP requires the conversation to have progressed to active financial negotiation where specific payment options were presented and explicitly refused. A customer who becomes hostile or disengaged before any payment discussion occurs should NOT be classified as RTP.\nFew-shots: Customer rejects $66/month, then rejects $50/month, then says \"I\u2019m not paying anything\" \u2192 RTP. Customer says \"No\" to sharing circumstances but no payment options were discussed yet \u2192 IDV. Customer uses profanity and disconnects before any payment offer \u2192 IDV (not RTP). Customer becomes extremely hostile, uses profanity, AND explicitly says \"I\u2019m not paying\" or \"None\" when offered payment amounts \u2192 RTP (not CPR \u2014 the explicit payment refusal takes precedence over the hostility/complaint aspect).\n\n\n- `RCR`: Description: Recording Consent Refused - Customer explicitly declined consent for the call to be recorded.\nUse when: Customer says \"I do not consent to be recorded,\" \"I don't want to be recorded,\" \"No\" when asked for recording consent, or similar refusal of recording. This applies even if the customer also complains about other issues during the call.\nEdge cases: RCR takes PRIORITY over CPR (Complaint). If a customer refuses recording consent AND also complains about practices, the recording refusal is the primary classification \u2014 use RCR, not CPR. The complaint is secondary to the compliance-critical consent refusal.\nFew-shots: Agent says \"This call is being recorded\" and customer says \"I don't want to be recorded\" \u2192 RCR. Customer says \"No\" when asked for recording consent \u2192 RCR.\n\n\n- `NCV`: Description: Not Convenient - Customer confirmed their identity but indicated current time is inconvenient for financial discussion; no callback timeframe agreed.\nUse when: Customer explicitly says \"now is not a good time,\" \"I can't talk,\" \"I'm busy,\" \"I have to go,\" \"Let's do this later.\" Customer abruptly disengages after confirming identity due to circumstantial factors.\nEdge cases: Identity verified BUT user then disengages due to circumstances \u2192 NCV (not IDV). No specific alternative contact time needed for NCV. Distinguish from CAB: NCV has no agreed future callback; CAB requires a confirmed outbound callback with specific timeframe. If customer says they're busy but STILL engages in conversation (e.g., \"I have a minute, go ahead\"), the call is convenient enough \u2014 do NOT use NCV.\nFew-shots: Customer says \"I'm at work, I can't talk right now\" and hangs up \u2192 NCV. Customer says \"Now is not a good time\" without specifying when to call back \u2192 NCV. Customer says \"I'm busy but go ahead\" and continues talking \u2192 NOT NCV.\n\n\n- `CAB`: Description: Callback Requested - The ACCOUNT HOLDER (or someone confirmed/claimed as the account holder) explicitly requests or agrees to a future outbound callback and the callback arrangement is the clear final disposition of the call.\nUse when: The account holder (confirmed or claimed) requests or agrees to be called back at a specific future time. A \"reasonably specific\" window includes \"tomorrow,\" \"Monday,\" \"next week,\" \"in a couple of weeks,\" \"anytime tomorrow,\" provided the assistant acknowledges and confirms. A timeframe tied to a financial event (e.g., \"call me when I get my check\" + \"in two weeks\") is valid. CAB strictly means scheduling an OUTBOUND call from the agent to the account holder.\nEdge cases: CRITICAL PREREQUISITE \u2014 CAB only applies when the ACCOUNT HOLDER themselves requests a callback. If a THIRD PARTY (someone who is NOT the account holder \u2014 e.g., a spouse, family member, roommate, or unknown person) provides a callback time for reaching the account holder, classify as TPC (Third-Party Contact), NOT CAB. The key distinction: TPC = third party provides info to help reach the account holder; CAB = the account holder schedules their own callback. MANDATORY OVERRIDE \u2014 CAB takes absolute precedence over HCH, RTP, and failed negotiations. If assistant says \"I will call you back on [Timeframe]\" and user agrees, STOP evaluating for Hardship. Once callback is confirmed, it remains the disposition regardless of subsequent administrative turns. Do NOT use CAB for vague statements like \"call me later\" or \"whenever\" where NO timeframe is established.\nFew-shots: Account holder says \"call me back in 2 weeks when I get paid,\" agent confirms \u2192 CAB. Third party says \"She's not here, call back after 7:30\" \u2192 TPC (not CAB). Wife says \"He's not available, try later\" \u2192 TPC (not CAB). Customer mentions job loss but schedules own callback \u2192 CAB (not HCH).\n\n\n- `WCR`: Description: Written Communication Only Requested - Customer requested all future communications be conducted in writing only (mail/email), with no further phone calls.\nUse when: Customer directs phone contact to cease and specifies an alternative written channel. This applies even if prompted by frustration with call frequency, provided the customer specifies writing as the preferred method.\nEdge cases: Distinguish from DNC \u2014 WCR allows written contact; DNC refuses all phone contact but doesn't specify a preference for writing. Distinguish from CDS \u2014 CDS stops ALL communication; WCR redirects to written methods. Distinguish from CPR \u2014 WCR requires a specific demand to cease phone contact in favor of writing only.\nFew-shots: Customer says \"Don't call me, just send everything by mail\" \u2192 WCR. Customer says \"I only want emails, no more phone calls\" \u2192 WCR. Customer says \"Stop calling\" without specifying written preference \u2192 DNC (not WCR).\n\n\n- `CDS`: Description: Cease and Desist - The VERIFIED account holder (IDV passed: name confirmed AND DOB or SSN matched) has explicitly requested complete cessation of ALL communication methods regarding this account, including calls, emails, and texts.\nUse when: ALL THREE conditions are met simultaneously: (1) IDV passed \u2014 caller confirmed name AND DOB or SSN was verified, (2) caller is confirmed as the account holder (not a 3rd party, not a wrong number, not a business), AND (3) caller explicitly requests cessation of ALL communication methods using phrases like \"stop all communication,\" \"cease all contact,\" \"cease and desist,\" or \"remove me from everything.\"\nEdge cases: CRITICAL \u2014 IDV MUST PASS before CDS can apply. If IDV was not completed, failed (DOB denied or refused), or the caller refused to verify \u2014 classify as DNC (not CDS), regardless of how broadly the caller phrases their request. \"Stop all communication\" from an unverified caller = DNC, not CDS. CRITICAL \u2014 Reflection variable `rpc = unknown` means the caller's identity was NOT confirmed \u2014 CDS cannot apply when rpc is unknown. Even if `exc_comms = cease_all` and `exc_comms_confirmed = confirmed`, if rpc is unknown or IDV states (verify_dob, verify_ssn) are absent from list_current_state \u2192 use DNC, NOT CDS. The exc_comms variable records the scope of the request but does NOT confirm identity. CRITICAL \u2014 `third_party = no` does NOT mean the caller is the verified account holder. It only means no third-party pattern was detected. The caller must still pass IDV (rpc must NOT be unknown) for CDS to apply. `third_party = no` + `rpc = unknown` = unidentified caller \u2192 DNC, not CDS. CRITICAL \u2014 If the caller is a confirmed wrong party (said \"This is not the right person,\" denied being the named person, used 3rd-person pronouns, said \"nobody here received a call\") \u2014 classify as WRN (not CDS), even if they say \"restrict all communication\" or use legal cease-and-desist language. Scope language is evaluated ONLY after both identity and IDV gates pass. Distinct from DNC (phone-only stop, no IDV required) and WRN (wrong party, number removed only).\nFew-shots: Wrong party (DOB mismatch, said \"This is not the right person\") says \"Restrict all communication\" \u2192 WRN (not CDS \u2014 wrong party gate fires first). Inbound caller skips IDV, says \"Stop all communication\" \u2192 DNC (not CDS \u2014 IDV not completed). Caller confirms name but DOB denied \u2192 DNC (not CDS \u2014 IDV failed). Verified account holder (name + DOB confirmed) says \"Cease all contact, phone email everything\" \u2192 CDS. Caller who identifies as a business says \"I don't wanna be contacted at all\" \u2192 WRN (not CDS). CRITICAL NEGATIVE EXAMPLE \u2014 Inbound caller says \"Stop calling me\" then \"All communication\" then \"Yes\" (exc_comms=cease_all, exc_comms_confirmed=confirmed, third_party=no) BUT rpc=unknown and list_current_state shows only inbound_opening \u2192 exc_cease_comms with NO verify_dob or verify_ssn states \u2192 DNC (NOT CDS). The absence of IDV states in list_current_state means identity was never verified \u2014 exc_comms_confirmed only records that the caller confirmed their request, NOT that their identity was confirmed.\n\n\n- `CPR`: Description: Complaint Received - Customer expressed dissatisfaction, frustration, or concern regarding their account, collection practices, communication methods, or service experience, whether stated formally or implied through behavior. This includes complaints about confusing or unhelpful notifications (SMS, email, letters), annoyance with automated systems, or dissatisfaction with how they were contacted.\nUse when: Customer is unhappy with lack of notification details, expresses annoyance with SMS/text/email content (e.g., \"The text didn\u2019t say who this was,\" \"I didn\u2019t click the link because it looked like spam\"), rejects provided responses as unhelpful, repeatedly demands a live agent when unavailable, or persistently questions the assistant\u2019s inability to help. Key indicator: dissatisfaction with communication quality or practices WITHOUT disputing the debt itself.\nEdge cases: CRITICAL DISTINCTION FROM DIS \u2014 Complaints about HOW the customer was contacted (confusing texts, unclear notifications, spam-like messages) are CPR, NOT DIS. A customer calling to find out who texted them and expressing frustration about unclear communications is making a complaint about contact quality, not disputing the debt. DIS requires an explicit challenge to the debt\u2019s validity, accuracy, or legitimacy. If the customer expresses willingness to pay or asks for payment details while complaining about communication, this reinforces CPR over DIS. Also distinct from HCH: a customer who is frustrated about communications but not describing financial hardship should be CPR, not HCH.\nFew-shots: Customer says \"I didn\u2019t know who was texting me, the message didn\u2019t include any details\" and asks for payment address \u2192 CPR (not DIS). Customer says \"I wasn\u2019t clicking links because of scams\" but wants to pay \u2192 CPR. Customer repeatedly asks for a live agent and expresses frustration \u2192 CPR.\n\n\n- `HCH`: Description: Hardship Concern - ONLY for LONG-TERM, severe hardships where the consumer sees NO ability to resolve the account in the foreseeable future. HCH means the consumer has NO path forward \u2014 not just \"broke right now.\" IMPORTANT: Do NOT include HCH in your call_code_list if (a) a callback is arranged, OR (b) the customer expresses any willingness to pay in the future. If either condition is true, HCH does not apply at all \u2014 exclude it entirely from your output.\nUse when: ALL conditions must be true: (1) Customer describes a LONG-TERM hardship with no foreseeable end \u2014 permanent job loss, long-term disability, ongoing serious medical condition, homelessness, or chronic financial inability; (2) The customer explicitly conveys they see NO way to pay now or in the near future AND shows no willingness to pay later; (3) NO callback or follow-up arrangement exists in the conversation; (4) The hardship is substantively discussed (not just a passing mention). If ANY of these conditions is false, do NOT include HCH in your call_code_list.\nEdge cases: SHORT-TERM \u2260 HCH. \"I'm broke right now,\" \"I can't pay today,\" \"I don't have a credit card,\" \"I'm going through a separation\" are SHORT-TERM situational difficulties, NOT long-term hardship \u2014 do NOT include HCH. Customer says \"I'll pay when I get a chance\" or \"when things improve\" = willing to pay = NOT HCH \u2014 exclude HCH entirely. If ANY callback is arranged (reflection variable exc_cb_consent=yes, or agent says \"I'll call you back,\" or customer says \"call me back in X\"), completely exclude HCH from your call_code_list \u2014 output CAB instead. Even if the customer describes extreme financial difficulty, if they show ANY willingness to engage later or ANY callback is set, HCH does not belong in the list at all. A brief mention of difficulty (e.g., \"facing difficulties,\" \"got arrested,\" \"family issues\") without substantive long-term hardship discussion \u2192 use IDV (if verified), not HCH.\nFew-shots: Customer describes permanent disability, no income, no prospect of recovery, no callback \u2192 HCH. Customer says \"I'm broke currently\" + callback in 2 weeks \u2192 exclude HCH, use CAB. Customer says \"I can't pay today but I'll pay when I can\" \u2192 exclude HCH (willingness to pay = short-term). Customer explains separation, agrees to callback \u2192 exclude HCH, use CAB. Customer says \"I have no job, no income, no way to pay, and I don't see that changing\" with no callback \u2192 HCH.\n\n\n- `PPA`: Description: Payment Plan Agreed - Customer agreed to a structured payment plan with specific terms (amounts, frequency, and duration) for resolving the debt. Also applies when the customer agreed to pay, the DTMF payment flow was initiated but failed, and the call ended BEFORE a transfer to a live agent was triggered.\nUse when: Customer formally accepts a structured payment arrangement with defined payment amounts and schedule. Customer mentions a payment made within the last 14 days via any channel, providing payment date and amount. Also use when the customer agreed to pay, the system initiated DTMF payment but it failed (e.g., PIN authentication failed, payment instrument retrieval failed), and the call ended/hung up before the system could trigger a transfer to a live agent. The payment was attempted but failed, and no transfer followed.\nEdge cases: Special case \u2014 customer unable to respond at the time and requests later contact \u2192 same PPA classification applies. Requires clear, focused confirmation of payment terms \u2014 casual \"yeah\" or \"okay\" as filler while distracted does NOT qualify. CRITICAL DISTINCTION \u2014 PPA applies when DTMF payment failed AND call ended before transfer was triggered. If transfer WAS triggered \u2192 use TSR (connected) or WFR (busy) instead. If DTMF failed and no transfer and no hang-up \u2192 use FTP.\nFew-shots: Customer agrees to $50/month for 6 months and gets transferred to payment \u2192 PPA. Customer says \"I already paid $100 last week via check\" with details \u2192 PPA. Customer agrees to pay full $500, enters DTMF, PIN fails, call hangs up before transfer is triggered \u2192 PPA (not PPIF, not FTP). Customer says \"yeah, sure\" while talking about unrelated topics \u2192 NOT PPA.\n\n\n- `PPIF`: Description: Promise to Pay in Full - Customer verbally committed to paying 100% of the full outstanding balance in a single payment, with no discounts or settlement reductions. IMPORTANT: Do NOT use PPIF if the call ends with a transfer to a live agent \u2014 when a transfer occurs after a payment failure, the final disposition is TSR, not PPIF.\nUse when: Customer confirms the full amount due and agrees to a specific payment date or time (e.g., \"I'll take care of it later today,\" \"Call me back at noon to get my card\"). Use even if a callback is required to collect payment details or finalize the transaction. PPIF requires that NO transfer to a live agent occurs after the payment commitment.\nEdge cases: CRITICAL \u2014 Do NOT classify as CAB when a clear commitment to pay full balance is made. If the customer commits to paying the full balance AND arranges a callback to provide card details, this is ALWAYS PPIF, never CAB. The payment commitment takes precedence over the callback arrangement. Distinguish from PSIF \u2014 PPIF = 100% original balance; PSIF = discounted/reduced settlement amount. TRANSFER EXCEPTION \u2014 If the customer agreed to pay BUT the system fails to process payment (e.g., \"The system can not retrieve your payment information\") AND the AI agent then transfers to a live agent (\"Let me connect you with a live agent\"), classify as TSR, NOT PPIF. The transfer overrides the payment commitment. Distinguish from PPA \u2014 if the DTMF payment flow was initiated but failed, and the call ended before a transfer to a live agent was triggered, classify as PPA (not PPIF).\nFew-shots: Customer says \"I'll pay the full $393.92 tomorrow\" \u2192 PPIF. Customer says \"Call me back at noon, I'll have my card ready to pay it all\" \u2192 PPIF (not CAB). Customer agrees to pay $248 settlement instead of $352 full balance \u2192 PSIF (not PPIF). Customer agrees to pay full $2112.50, provides PIN 123456, system fails to retrieve payment info, agent says \"Let me connect you with a live agent\" \u2192 TSR (NOT PPIF \u2014 transfer overrides payment commitment). Customer enters DTMF payment flow, payment fails, call hangs up before transfer is triggered \u2192 PPA (not PPIF).\n\n\n- `PSIF`: Description: Promise to Settle in Full - Customer agreed to a discounted settlement offer that will fully resolve the account for less than the original outstanding balance.\nUse when: Customer accepts a reduced settlement amount with a specific payment timeline that fully settles the account. No further payments are required after the agreed discounted amount is paid.\nEdge cases: Distinguish from PPIF \u2014 PSIF = reduced/discounted amount; PPIF = 100% original balance. Full settlement must be confirmed \u2014 account fully resolved with no remaining balance.\nFew-shots: Customer agrees to pay $248 instead of $352.90 full balance to settle \u2192 PSIF. Customer agrees to pay full $352.90 \u2192 PPIF (not PSIF).\n\n\n- `WRN`: Description: Wrong Number - The person who answered or called is confirmed NOT the account holder: they explicitly denied being the intended recipient, identified as a 3rd party or business, stated wrong number, used 3rd-person pronouns about the account holder, denied the DOB/identity while expressing confusion (\"I have no idea what you're talking about\"), or signaled the number is not associated with the account holder. Only the phone number is removed \u2014 no account-level restriction.\nUse when: ANY of these wrong-party signals are present: (a) explicit denial \u2014 \"This is not the right person,\" \"No, I'm not [name],\" \"You have the wrong number,\" (b) 3rd-party pronoun \u2014 \"Take HIM off your list,\" \"She doesn't want contact,\" (c) business identification \u2014 \"This is a business,\" (d) nobody-here signal \u2014 \"Nobody by that name lives here,\" \"There's no [name] here\" \u2014 explicit statement that the named person does not exist at this number, (e) confusion + DOB denial \u2014 caller says \"I have no idea what you're talking about\" after DOB is read (suggests wrong number, not just IDV failure), (f) caller explicitly says \"No\" when asked \"Is this [name]?\". An explicit denial of identity or identification as a wrong party is sufficient regardless of any additional requests (even \"stop all communication\" or \"restrict all communication\" \u2014 scope is irrelevant when caller is confirmed not the account holder). NOTE: ambiguous phrases like \"nobody ever received a call from you\" or \"take me off your list\" without an explicit identity denial \u2192 prefer DNC over WRN (no confirmed wrong-party signal).\nEdge cases: CRITICAL PRIORITY \u2014 WRN TAKES PRIORITY OVER DNC when an explicit wrong-party signal is present. If the caller says \"This is not the right person,\" \"No\" to \"Is this [name]?\", \"wrong number,\" or any equivalent explicit denial \u2014 classify as WRN even if IDV also failed or the caller then requests stop-contact. The wrong-party signal overrides the unverified-identity DNC pattern. CRITICAL \u2014 When a wrong party says \"Restrict all communication,\" \"Stop all contact,\" or uses legal cease-and-desist language \u2014 this is still WRN, NOT CDS and NOT DNC. A confirmed wrong party CANNOT authorize account-level restrictions regardless of what they request. The identity gate fires before the scope gate. CRITICAL \u2014 When a caller denies the DOB AND expresses confusion (\"I have no idea what you're talking about\"), treat as wrong-party \u2192 WRN (not IDF or DNC), because the denial signals they are not the account holder. Distinct from DNC (unknown-identity inbound caller with NO explicit wrong-party signal \u2014 prefer DNC only when there is no clear evidence the caller is not the account holder).\nFew-shots: Outbound call, DOB mismatch, caller says \"This is not the right person\" then \"Restrict all communication\" \u2192 WRN (not CDS \u2014 wrong party gate fires first, scope irrelevant). Outbound, AI asks \"Is this [name]?\" \u2014 caller says \"No. Don't call again.\" \u2192 WRN. Caller confirms name but says \"That DOB is totally incorrect, I have no idea what you're talking about. Leave me alone.\" \u2192 WRN (complete confusion + DOB denial signals wrong party, not failed IDV). Inbound caller says \"Take my number off the list, this is a business\" \u2192 WRN. Caller says \"You have the wrong number\" \u2192 WRN. Caller says \"Nobody by that name lives here\" \u2192 WRN.\n\n\n- `TPC`: Description: Third-Party Contact - Person other than the account holder provided information or context to help reach the intended recipient, including callback times or availability windows.\nUse when: Third party acknowledges knowing the account holder. Third party provides alternative phone number, address, availability time, or any contextual detail about the recipient. Third party offers to relay messages or suggests future contact times. Third party provides a callback time or availability window for reaching the account holder (e.g., \"call back after 7:30,\" \"she'll be home in the morning\").\nEdge cases: Distinguish from WRN \u2014 TPC requires explicit evidence of a relationship (acknowledging knowing the person, providing info about them). Even vague or incomplete info that aids in locating the recipient qualifies as TPC. No relationship evidence \u2192 WRN. CRITICAL DISTINCTION FROM CAB \u2014 If a third party (not the account holder) provides a callback time for reaching the account holder, this is TPC, NOT CAB. CAB requires the account holder themselves to schedule a callback. A third party arranging a callback time is providing information to reach the recipient, which is the core function of TPC.\nFew-shots: Person says \"He's not here, try calling after 5pm\" \u2192 TPC (not CAB). Wife says \"He's not available, call back later\" \u2192 TPC (not CAB). Person says \"That's my son, I'll tell him you called\" \u2192 TPC. Sister calls and agent arranges callback for 9am \u2192 TPC (not CAB). Person says \"I don't know that person, wrong number\" \u2192 WRN (not TPC).\n\n\n- `FRA`: Description: Fraud Reported - Customer claims the account was opened fraudulently, through identity theft, or without their knowledge or consent.\nUse when: Customer explicitly alleges fraud or identity theft. Customer categorically denies the account's existence or their responsibility for creating it (even without using the word \"fraud\").\nEdge cases: Distinguish from DIS \u2014 FRA = customer denies they ever created/owned the account; DIS = disputes accuracy or balance of a recognized account. Categorical denial of account ownership \u2192 FRA (not DIS). Requires immediate escalation for fraud investigation.\nFew-shots: Customer says \"I never opened that account, someone stole my identity\" \u2192 FRA. Customer says \"I have no connection to this debt whatsoever\" \u2192 FRA. Customer says \"The balance is wrong, I already paid some\" \u2192 DIS (not FRA).\n\n\n- `DNC`: Description: Do Not Call - The caller (NOT a business or clearly wrong number) has requested to be removed from phone contact lists or to cease calls to the specific phone number. Identity verification is NOT required for DNC \u2014 an angry caller demanding \"stop calling\" is sufficient.\nUse when: Caller says \"stop calling,\" \"don't call this number,\" \"put me on your do not call list.\" Formal or informal/frustrated language qualifies equally. DNC applies even if the caller refuses to confirm their name \u2014 the explicit demand to stop phone calls is the primary signal. If the assistant interprets the statement as an opt-out request, this supports DNC. Applies specifically to phone contact at this number \u2014 differs from CDS (all communication).\nEdge cases: DNC overrides NVR and HUA when the caller explicitly demands to stop calls. If the caller refuses to verify identity AND demands \"stop calling,\" classify as DNC (not NVR). CRITICAL \u2014 When rpc = unknown (caller identity not confirmed) AND exc_comms = cease_all, classify as DNC (not CDS). An unidentified caller requesting \"all communication\" stopped cannot authorize account-level CDS \u2014 only a verified account holder can. Even if exc_comms_confirmed = confirmed, if rpc is unknown \u2192 DNC. CRITICAL \u2014 An unidentified inbound caller saying \"Stop calling me\" or \"Take me off your list. All.\" with no IDV \u2192 DNC (not CDS). The scope of the request (this number vs all communication) is irrelevant when the caller is unidentified \u2014 DNC applies to the number regardless. EXCEPTION: If the caller identifies as a BUSINESS or explicitly denies being the account holder AND says the person doesn't live there (e.g., \"There's no [Name] here, stop calling\"), classify as WRN \u2014 the number is simply wrong. DNC is for callers who COULD be the account holder (didn't deny it) but refuse to engage and want calls stopped.\nFew-shots: Caller says \"I don't give a damn. Stop calling my damn phone\" without confirming name \u2192 DNC (not NVR). Caller says \"Don't call this damn phone again\" \u2192 DNC. CRITICAL PATTERN \u2014 Inbound caller says \"Stop calling me\" \u2192 \"All communication\" \u2192 \"Yes\" with rpc=unknown, exc_comms=cease_all, exc_comms_confirmed=confirmed, third_party=no, AND list_current_state=[inbound_opening, exc_cease_comms, exc_cease_comms, ...] (no verify_dob or verify_ssn states present) \u2192 DNC (NOT CDS). Reasoning: list_current_state shows the call went from opening directly to communication restriction \u2014 IDV was never attempted. exc_comms_confirmed=confirmed means the caller confirmed their STOP REQUEST, not their identity. rpc=unknown confirms identity was never established. Despite third_party=no, the caller is still unidentified. Inbound caller says \"Nobody ever received a call. Take me off your list. All.\" with no identity denial \u2192 DNC (no confirmed wrong-party signal, identity unknown). Caller says \"This is a business, take my number off the list\" \u2192 WRN (not DNC). Caller says \"There's no Robin here, stop calling\" \u2192 WRN (not DNC \u2014 wrong number). Verified account holder (IDV passed) says \"Stop all communication\" \u2192 CDS (not DNC \u2014 IDV passed and scope is all communication).\n\n\n- `DIS`: Description: Debt Disputed - The customer explicitly challenged the accuracy, validity, or legitimacy of the debt itself. This includes explicitly stating the debt is not theirs, the amount is wrong, previous payments are not reflected, or asserting the debt is void, canceled, settled, or legally discharged. This code also applies if the customer challenges the creditor's right to collect or the legality of the debt transfer (e.g., \"sold without consent\"). DIS takes precedence over CAB if the customer disputes the debt even if a callback is scheduled.\nUse when: Customer explicitly states the debt is not theirs, the amount is wrong, previous payments are not reflected, or asserts the debt is void/canceled/settled. Also applies when customer claims not to recognize the amount or implies the balance is incorrect (e.g., \"I wasn't aware it was that much\"). If a customer requests to stop contact specifically because they dispute the debt (e.g., \"Stop calling, I don't owe this\"), classify as DIS.\nEdge cases: CRITICAL \u2014 Do NOT classify as DIS if the customer is merely complaining about HOW they were contacted (confusing texts, unclear SMS, spam-looking links). Asking for details because a notification lacked specifics is a communication complaint (CPR), NOT a dispute. A dispute must be an explicit challenge to the DEBT ITSELF \u2014 its existence, amount, validity, or legitimacy. Also do NOT classify as DIS for \"sticker shock\" (e.g., \"Wow, that's a lot\") without questioning accuracy. Do NOT apply if customer made a payment within the last 14 days. If the customer expresses willingness to pay (e.g., \"I was gonna pay\") while complaining about notifications, this is strong evidence AGAINST DIS \u2014 use CPR instead.\nFew-shots: Customer says \"I don't owe this money\" \u2192 DIS. Customer says \"The text didn't say who this was for\" but asks for payment address \u2192 CPR (not DIS). Customer says \"I wasn't aware it was that much\" \u2192 DIS.\n\n\n- `CSM`: Description: SCRA Coverage Reported - Customer verified active military service status invoking Servicemembers Civil Relief Act protections.\nUse when: Customer provides details about military service (branch, status, anticipated service period) invoking SCRA protections. SCRA protections include interest rate caps, foreclosure prevention, and other accommodations that must be immediately applied.\nEdge cases: N/A\nFew-shots: Customer says \"I'm active duty military, you need to apply SCRA protections\" \u2192 CSM. Customer says \"I'm deployed overseas with the Army\" \u2192 CSM.\n\n\n- `PRS`: Description: In Prison - Customer or third party confirmed that the account holder is CURRENTLY incarcerated in a correctional facility.\nUse when: Incarceration in a correctional facility is confirmed as a CURRENT, ongoing status. Specific facility name or release date not required.\nEdge cases: PRS takes precedence over financial codes if both are mentioned. CRITICAL \u2014 PRS requires CURRENT incarceration. Past-tense references to arrest or jail (e.g., \"I got arrested\" as an explanation for default circumstances) do NOT qualify if the customer is clearly not currently incarcerated (e.g., they are on the phone freely discussing the account). Use the surrounding context to determine if the arrest is current or historical.\nFew-shots: Customer says \"I'm currently in jail\" \u2192 PRS. Third party says \"He's incarcerated at the county jail right now\" \u2192 PRS. Customer says \"I got arrested\" as an explanation for why they defaulted, but is freely conversing on the phone \u2192 NOT PRS (use IDV or appropriate code based on conversation outcome).\n\n\n- `LGH`: Description: Legal Guardian Handling - A legally authorized guardian is managing the account holder's affairs due to the account holder's incapacity or death.\nUse when: Guardian provides verifiable information about their legal relationship and authority to discuss the account. Third party presents power of attorney (POA) or demonstrates legal authority over the account. Communication must be directed exclusively to this authorized representative.\nEdge cases: Distinguish from ATY \u2014 use LGH for general guardian/POA scenarios; use ATY when a specific attorney or legal counsel is mentioned. Distinguish from TPC \u2014 LGH requires demonstrated legal authority (guardian, POA); TPC is any third party providing info without legal standing.\nFew-shots: Third party calls with power of attorney, negotiates settlement on account holder's behalf \u2192 LGH. \"She's deceased... her daughter has financial power of attorney\" \u2192 LGH. Agent confirms caller has power of attorney over incapacitated account holder \u2192 LGH.\n\n\n- `ATY`: Description: Attorney Representation - Customer stated they have retained or are seeking legal counsel, or legal representation is indicated through any signal in the conversation.\nUse when: Customer mentions \"my attorney,\" \"I'm getting a lawyer,\" \"my attorney has contacted you,\" or references a POA/legal authority. Agent prompts caller for proof of POA or legal representation documentation. Multiple or repeated references to an attorney, even if brief or fragmented. Consumer indicates attorney involvement even indirectly or amidst emotional distress.\nEdge cases: ATY takes priority over ALL other codes including RTP. Fragmented speech about attorney (\"her attorney,\" even amidst distress) still qualifies \u2014 scan the ENTIRE conversation for any mention of \"attorney,\" \"lawyer,\" or \"legal counsel.\" Agent's prompt for POA is a secondary signal even if caller gives unclear response. Distinguish from LGH \u2014 ATY = specific attorney/legal counsel mentioned; LGH = general guardian without specific attorney reference. CRITICAL DISTINCTION FROM DSA \u2014 If the customer uses the word \"lawyer\" or \"attorney\" ANYWHERE in their description, classify as ATY even if they also mention debt consolidation/settlement context. \"Debt consolidation LAWYER\" = ATY (the word \"lawyer\" is the decisive signal). Only use DSA if the customer names a financial program/agency WITHOUT any mention of a lawyer or attorney.\nFew-shots: Customer says \"Talk to my lawyer\" \u2192 ATY. Customer says \"I turned my account over to a debt consolidate lawyer\" \u2192 ATY (word \"lawyer\" overrides \"debt consolidate\"). Fragmented speech \"on her journey... her attorney\" \u2192 ATY. Customer says \"I'm working with National Debt Relief\" (no mention of lawyer) \u2192 DSA (not ATY).\n\n\n- `BKP`: Description: Bankruptcy Pending - Customer reported current bankruptcy proceedings or intent to file bankruptcy that would include this account.\nUse when: Customer provides specific bankruptcy details (case number, chapter, filing date) or states intent to file. Triggers immediate cessation of collection activities per automatic stay provisions.\nEdge cases: Requires verification with bankruptcy court records. Intent to file is sufficient even without specific details.\nFew-shots: Customer says \"I filed Chapter 7 last month, case number 12345\" \u2192 BKP. Customer says \"I'm about to file for bankruptcy\" \u2192 BKP.\n\n\n- `NNP`: Description: Negotiated No Payment - Customer passed identity verification, at least one specific payment option was offered by the agent, customer clearly declined the offered option(s) without using explicit refusal language, expressed no hardship or dispute, and the call ended without a payment commitment.\nUse when: ALL of the following must be true: (1) Customer verified identity successfully, (2) the agent offered at least one specific payment amount or plan, (3) customer clearly declined or said \"No\" to the offered amount(s), (4) customer did NOT use explicit refusal language (e.g., \"I won't pay,\" \"I refuse to pay,\" \"I will never pay\"), (5) no hardship or financial difficulty was expressed, (6) no dispute was raised about the debt, and (7) the call ended with no payment arrangement.\nEdge cases: CRITICAL DISTINCTION FROM IDV \u2014 If the customer gave non-committal responses (\"possibly,\" \"maybe,\" \"I'm not sure,\" \"I'll think about it\") without clearly declining, use IDV (not NNP). If the customer declined to share personal circumstances or explain default reasons but no specific payment amounts were offered and declined, use IDV (not NNP). CRITICAL \u2014 NNP requires the customer's explicit decline to be PRESENT AND VISIBLE in the conversation. If the conversation ends after a payment offer with no customer response shown, the customer did NOT decline \u2014 use IDV (not NNP). Do NOT infer a decline from a truncated or incomplete conversation. NNP requires a CLEAR DECLINE of at least one specific offer \u2014 vague, ambiguous, non-committal responses, or absent responses do NOT qualify. CRITICAL DISTINCTION FROM RTP \u2014 RTP requires explicit, unambiguous refusal language (\"I refuse,\" \"I won't pay,\" \"I will never pay\"). Simply saying \"No\" to offered amounts is NNP, not RTP. CRITICAL DISTINCTION FROM HCH \u2014 If the customer mentions any hardship language (job loss, medical issues, financial difficulty, inability to afford), classify as HCH, not NNP. CRITICAL DISTINCTION FROM DIS \u2014 If the customer challenges the debt's validity, existence, or amount, classify as DIS, not NNP. If mixed signals appear (hardship AND refusal together), assign HCH.\nFew-shots: Agent offers $76/month, customer says \"No,\" agent offers $61/month, customer deflects and call ends with no commitment \u2192 NNP. Agent offers $66/month, customer clearly says \"No\" to that offer and call ends \u2192 NNP (customer explicitly responded to the payment offer). Customer declines all payment options saying \"I just can't do those amounts right now\" with no hardship or refusal language \u2192 NNP. Customer verified, declines to share circumstances of default, no payment amounts offered \u2192 IDV (not NNP \u2014 no payment negotiation occurred). Customer says \"Possibly\" or \"Maybe\" to a payment offer without declining \u2192 IDV (not NNP \u2014 non-committal is not a decline). Customer verified, payment amount mentioned but conversation ends before customer clearly declines \u2192 IDV (not NNP \u2014 no clear decline visible). Agent asks about default circumstances, customer says \"No\" (declining to share circumstances), agent then offers monthly payment amount, conversation ends with no further customer response \u2192 IDV (not NNP \u2014 the \"No\" was about sharing circumstances, not a response to the payment offer; no customer response to the offer is shown). Customer says \"I refuse to pay this\" \u2192 RTP (not NNP \u2014 explicit refusal). Customer says \"I lost my job, I can't pay\" \u2192 HCH (not NNP \u2014 hardship language present).\n\n\n- `DSA`: Description: Debt Settlement Agreement - Customer indicates they are working with a third-party debt settlement, consolidation, or relief program to manage their debt.\nUse when: Customer explicitly or implicitly directs agent to contact a named debt relief/settlement program (Beyond Finance, National Debt Relief, Debt Solutions, etc.). Customer states \"a company is handling that for me\" or \"check with my debt negotiator.\" Consumer or representative claims they are working with a program for debt/credit settlement, consolidation, relief, management, or financial solutions.\nEdge cases: Distinguish from ATY \u2014 DSA = financial relief/settlement program; ATY = law office or attorney. If third party is not explicitly identified as a law office, assume it is a debt settlement service. Directing agent to contact a named debt relief agency is sufficient signal regardless of explicit confirmation. Do not let identity verification attempts or other conversational elements distract from settlement agency signals. Do not let the assistant\u2019s mention of \"attorney\" trigger ATY if the consumer only identifies a financial program.\nFew-shots: Customer says \"You need to call National Debt Relief, they\u2019re handling my account\" \u2192 DSA. Customer says \"A company is managing my debts\" \u2192 DSA. Customer says \"Talk to my lawyer about this\" \u2192 ATY (not DSA).\n\n\n\n\n\n\n# Example Output\n<reasoning>\nYour concise reasoning for the classification.\n</reasoning>\n<call_code_list>\n[\"CALL_CODE_1\", \"CALL_CODE_2\", \"CALL_CODE_3\"]\n</call_code_list>"
