[2026-05-13 22:02:21 +0700] [CODEX] output/from_zero/signal_experiment_40_dtmf_rerun_20260513_1655/per_conversation/0023_PmVT8hG7m4pkn5UHlG65jg/llm_call_0006.json:28:      "content": "# Objective\nYou are a reviewer agent in the finance and banking sector.\nYou will receive a transcript of a phone call related to debt collection and recovery, located in the section PHONE_CALL_TRANSCRIPT.\nThe transcript records the conversation of 2 roles: the debt collector (assistant/agent) and the customer (user/customer).\n\nYour task is to analyze this transcript and extract information about any DSC (Debt Settlement Company) or CCCS (Consumer Credit Counseling Service) that the customer mentions they are working with.\n\n## IMPORTANT: What is a DSC/CCCS?\n- DSC (Debt Settlement Company): Organizations that negotiate debt settlements on behalf of consumers (e.g., \"National Debt Relief\", \"Freedom Debt Relief\", \"Debt Consolidation Services\")\n- CCCS (Consumer Credit Counseling Service): Non-profit credit counseling organizations (e.g., \"Credit Counseling Services\", \"Consumer Credit Counseling\")\n- **NOT attorneys or law firms** - If the caller is from a law office or attorney firm, this is attorney representation, NOT DSC/CCCS\n- **NOT the debt collector's own company** - Information about the assistant/agent's company should NEVER be extracted\n\n## Assistant/Agent Company contact info:\n```\n- Company name: Kompato\n- Company mailing address: 3710 Rawlins Street, Suite 1420, Dallas, Texas 75219\n- Company phone: 18885667280\n- Company email: support at kompato A-I dot com\n```\nNote: The above information represents the debt collector/agent company. If any fields show \"Not provided\" or are empty, ignore them.\n\n## CRITICAL Guidelines - Role Identification\n**CAREFULLY identify who is speaking and what information they are providing:**\n\n1. **The assistant/agent role** = The debt collector's representative\n  - When assistant/agent says \"our mailing address\", \"our company\", \"our phone number\" \u2192 This is the DEBT COLLECTOR's info, NOT the DSC/CCCS\n  - DO NOT extract any information the assistant/agent provides about their own company\n  - DO NOT extract mailing addresses for payments that the assistant provides\n\n2. **ONLY extract DSC/CCCS information when:**\n  - User/customer explicitly mentions they are working WITH a debt settlement or credit counseling company\n  - User/customer provides contact info for a debt settlement or credit counseling organization\n  - The organization is clearly a DSC/CCCS, NOT an attorney or law firm\n\n3. **DO NOT extract when:**\n  - The caller is from a law office, attorney firm, or legal representation (e.g., \"Law Offices of...\", \"calling from [Attorney Name]\")\n  - Assistant/agent provides information about their own company (the debt collector)\n  - User asks \"what's your mailing address?\" and assistant answers \u2192 This is debt collector's address\n  - Any contact info where assistant/agent says \"our\", \"my\", \"we\", \"the company\"\n  - The user is an attorney or legal representative calling on behalf of the debtor\n\n4. **Additional rules:**\n  - Extract information about the DSC/CCCS company or organization only\n  - DSC/CCCS must be explicitly mentioned as a debt settlement or credit counseling service\n  - If only an attorney or law firm is mentioned, return null for all fields\n  - Extract contact info as-is from the transcript without normalization\n  - If multiple pieces of information are provided, use the most recent or corrected version\n\n## Field definitions\n- **dsc_name:** The name of the DSC or CCCS company/organization. Return null if not available.\n- **dsc_address_1:** The first line of the company address. Return null if not available.\n- **dsc_address_2:** The second line of the company address. Return null if not available.\n- **dsc_city:** The city of the company. Return null if not available.\n- **dsc_state:** The state of the company. Return null if not available.\n- **dsc_zip:** The zip code of the company. Return null if not available.\n- **dsc_phone:** The phone number of the company. Return null if not available.\n- **dsc_email:** The email of the company. Return null if not available.\n\n## PHONE_CALL_TRANSCRIPT\n```\nuser: Hello?\nassistant: [happy] Hey, this is Emily, a virtual agent on a recorded line.\nuser: Hello?\nassistant: Is this Teresa Leroy?\nuser: Yes.\nassistant: [confident] To protect your privacy and proceed with the call, I have June 10, 1957 as your birthdate on file. Is that correct?\nuser: Yes.\nassistant: Thank you for confirming. I'm calling from Kompato on behalf of Bureaus Investment Group Portfolio Number 15 LLC. [supportive] I must advise that this is an attempt to collect a debt by a debt collector. Any information obtained will be used for that purpose. [supportive] Teresa, I'm calling about your account with Capital One, National Association, with a balance of seven hundred and thirty-nine dollars and seventeen cents. Could you please tell me about the circumstances that led to the default?\nuser: Yes. Um, I can't work right now.\nassistant: [compassionate] I'm sorry to hear that, Teresa. That must be a challenging situation for you. To help me find the best-\nuser: It is.\nassistant: [understanding] I can imagine how difficult this must be for you. [supportive] Your account balance is seven hundred and thirty-nine dollars and seventeen cents. To assist you, we can settle the total balance to five hundred and eighteen dollars, saving you two hundred and twenty-two dollars. This would reduce your monthly payment to eighty-seven dollars for six months, with the last installment being eighty-three dollars. Would this adjusted amount be manageable for you?\nuser: No.\nassistant: [understanding] I see. -\nuser: two i.\nassistant: [confused] I'm sorry, could you clarify what you mean by \"two i\"?\nuser: Too high. I won't be able to pay for my medicine.\nassistant: [compassionate] I understand, Teresa. Your health is a priority, and I want to help find a solution that works for you. [supportive] We can explore a lower settlement option. We could settle your account for four hundred and forty-four dollars, which reduces your monthly payment to seventy-four dollars for six months. Would this be more manageable for you?\nuser: No.\nassistant: -\nuser: No. Fifty.\nassistant: [supportive] I understand you're suggesting fifty dollars. The minimum monthly amount for the settlement offer is seventy-four dollars. [encouraging] Would it be possible to adjust slightly closer to that amount?\nuser: It'd be hard.\nassistant: [understanding] I see how that could be difficult. [supportive] If seventy-four dollars isn't feasible, we can schedule a keep-in-touch arrangement for three months with a minimum monthly amount of fifty dollars. Would that work better for you?\nuser: Yes.\nassistant: [supportive] Great. Could you let me know a convenient date within the next 30 days to start the first payment of fifty dollars?\nuser: The twenty seventh.\nassistant: [supportive] Just to confirm, you'll be making a monthly payment of fifty dollars starting on May 27, 2026. Is that correct?\nuser: Yes.\nassistant: Please note that nothing we discuss overshadows your rights as expressed in our email to you. For any reason we get disconnected, do we have permission to call you back?\nuser: Yes.\nuser: I have no email anyway.\nassistant: [professional] Thank you for confirming. Since you mentioned you don't have an email, we can send any necessary information via text. Which payment method are you planning to use\u2014debit card, credit card, or-\nuser: Money order.\nassistant: Understood-\nuser: Money order. I have bank account.\nassistant: [professional] Thank you for sharing that. If you're planning to send a money order, you can mail it to our address at three seven one zero  Rawlins Street, Suite one four two zero , Dallas, Texas seven five two one nine . [supportive] We also have an online payment portal at kompatoai. com for your convenience. [supportive] Now, let's ensure we have your most up-to-date contact information. I have CHRISLEROY two one zero nine at GMAIL dot COM as your email address in my records. Is this still accurate?\nuser: I don't have an email address.\nassistant: [supportive] Thank you for letting me know. I'd appreciate it if you could provide me with a new email address to reach you. May I have the best email to contact you?\nuser: I don't have one.\nassistant: [understanding] That's okay. We'll proceed without an email address for now. [supportive] I also have nine three zero  E 1st Street Unit two three , Long Beach, California, nine zero eight zero two as your mailing address in my records. Is this still accurate?\nuser: Yes.\nuser: Yes.\nassistant: [appreciative] Thank you for confirming. [supportive] Lastly, I have five six two six six one zero zero five one as your contact number. Is this still the best way to reach you?\nuser: Yes.\nuser: Yes.\nassistant: [appreciative] Thank you for confirming all your contact details. [supportive] If you have any further questions or need assistance, feel free to reach out. Have a good day!\nuser: <SILENCE_5s>\nassistant: \n```\n\n# Response Format\nReturn ONLY the extracted info in JSON format.\n{\n  \"dsc_name\": null,\n  \"dsc_address_1\": null,\n  \"dsc_address_2\": null,\n  \"dsc_city\": null,\n  \"dsc_state\": null,\n  \"dsc_zip\": null,\n  \"dsc_phone\": null,\n  \"dsc_email\": null\n}\n\n# Examples\n- Customer says \"I'm working with ABC Debt Settlement\" \u2192 Extract \"ABC Debt Settlement\" for dsc_name\n- Customer says \"My counselor is with Credit Help Services, their number is (phone number)\" \u2192 Extract company name and phone\n- Customer mentions only their counselor's name but not the organization \u2192 Return null for all fields\n- Customer asks \"What's your mailing address?\" and agent responds \"Our address is [address]\" \u2192 DO NOT extract (this is agent's company address)\n- Agent says \"You can reach us at (phone number)\" \u2192 DO NOT extract (this is agent's company phone)\n- User says \"I'm calling from the [firm name], located at [address]\" \u2192 Return null for all fields (this is attorney representation, not DSC/CCCS)\n- User says \"I'm working with [firm name], their number is (phone number)\" \u2192 Extract \"[firm name]\" and phone number"
[2026-05-13 22:02:21 +0700] [CODEX] output/from_zero/main_yaml_v1_full/per_conversation/0039_Wuq6cp4qpbDiro3akK1zlQ/llm_call_0001.json:28:      "content": "You are an expert in call disposition classification.\nClassify the ## Conversation History into 1 to 3 most relevant call codes.\nUse # Context and # Instruction to guide your decision.\n\n# Context:\n- The conversation is transcribed from a phone call by Automatic Speech Recognition (ASR). The text may contain typos, recognition errors, missing punctuation, or incomplete sentences.\n- The collection agent is marked as \"assistant|agent|bot\", and the caller is marked as \"user|customer|human\".\n- Available call codes below are the codes you can output; definitions and descriptions are authoritative.\n- Use only MASTER codes from the source-of-truth call-disposition reference. Do not use external alias code systems.\n\n# Instruction:\n- Read ## Call Code Descriptions first, then ## Conversation History.\n- Use user utterances as primary evidence of intent. Use assistant prompts only to interpret what the user is responding to.\n- Select only codes supported by evidence in the transcript to reflect the latest intent of the caller/ customer. Output 1 to 3 codes.\n- Prefer concise reasoning tied to explicit transcript evidence and code definitions.\n- Respect code boundaries and stage context (Phone Number / Pre-IDV / Post-IDV).\n- Prioritize call codes that reflect the latest intent of the caller/ customer of the call. Explicitly stated intent is more important than implicit intent.\n- If user updated their intent, update the call code accordingly. For example, if user requests to speak to a live agent, and then changes their mind and agrees to continue the conversation, update the call code to the latest intent. Or if user expressed harship (HCH), but the agreed to pay and went through with payment --> the PAY is valid, drop the HCH as HCH is no longer valid.\n- Stage guidance: treat as Post-IDV only when identity verification is completed (or Mini-Miranda appears, typically after successful IDV). Otherwise stay in Phone Number / Pre-IDV space.\n- If available, use ### Reflection Variable Descriptions and Values for additional context, reasoning for your decision. \n- Output plain text wrapped in XML tags exactly as shown in # Output.\n\n#  Notes:\n- Make sure the reasoning is clear, specific, and grounded to the conversation history and the call code descriptions.\n- Consider alternatives, but do not over-label when evidence is weak.\n- The call code is used to capture the latest status of the call, and use to plan the next action of the call.\n\n# Input Information\n## Call Code Descriptions\n- `PIF`: Description: Paid in Full - Customer paid full balance.\nUse when: Customer successfully paid the full outstanding balance during the call.\nEdge cases: Distinguish from PAY \u2014 PAY is any successful in-call payment and may be partial; PIF requires the total overdue balance to be paid successfully during the call. Distinguish from PPIF/FDP \u2014 those are promises or scheduled future payments, not completed in-call payment.\nFew-shots: Customer agrees to pay the full overdue balance, the payment is processed successfully during the call \u2192 PIF. Customer makes only a partial successful payment \u2192 PAY (not PIF). Customer promises to pay full balance later \u2192 PPIF or FDP (not PIF).\n\n- `TLM`: Description: Transfer Loan Modification - Verified customer requests loan-modification assistance that is beyond AI capability. Transfer to Collections representative.\nUse when: Customer asks for loan-modification options, terms restructuring, payment-term change outside supported AI flow, or explicitly requests a specialist for loan modification.\nEdge cases: Tie-break vs EPT \u2014 use EPT when the limitation is payment assistance capability (amount/method/payment handling). Use TLM when the request is specifically about loan modification options. Tie-break vs HTT \u2014 use HTT only when a technical/system failure blocks completion; use TLM when there is no system failure and the request is business-support escalation.\nFew-shots: Customer says \"I need loan modification options, please transfer me\" \u2192 TLM. Customer asks to restructure loan terms beyond bot capability \u2192 TLM.\n\n- `FDP`: Description: Future Dated Payment - Verified customer commits to a SPECIFIC FUTURE DATE to pay the FULL balance in a single payment.\nUse when both (a) a specific calendar date in the future is named (\"Friday the 25th\", \"next Tuesday\", \"May 10th\"), AND (b) full-balance commitment is given for that date.\nDTMF capture is the typical flow but NOT REQUIRED \u2014 agreed-and-scheduled future-dated payment counts as FDP even if card collection is deferred to a callback or a transfer to a specialist. The bot's transfer-to-specialist does NOT downgrade FDP to TSR; if the user gave a specific future date and full-balance commitment, FDP is the primary code.\nDistinct from: PAY (same-day completed), PPA (structured multi-installment plan), PPIF (commit to pay full but NO specific date), TSR (bare transfer request without future-date commitment), EPT (partial today, not full-future).\n\n- `TPM`: Description: Third-Party Message - A third party answers and the agent leaves a message for the account holder without disclosing account details.\nUse when: Non-account-holder confirms target person is unavailable, and agent leaves a compliant callback/return-call message with no account disclosure.\nEdge cases: Tie-break vs TPC \u2014 TPC requires third party providing new contact details or actionable recipient-location info; TPM is message-left behavior only. Tie-break vs LM \u2014 LM is voicemail/answering-system path; TPM is a live third-party human interaction.\nFew-shots: Third party says \"He's not here,\" agent leaves callback request \u2192 TPM. Family member answers and agrees to pass message, no account details shared \u2192 TPM.\n\n- `ECH`: Description: Robot Call - Pre-recorded call or IVR detected. No human response received. No message left and no transfer initiated.\nUse when: Pre-recorded message or IVR system answers (including iOS call screening). No human picks up.\nEdge cases: Tie-break vs NKP \u2014 ECH = IVR/pre-recorded system detected; NKP = silent connection with no IVR signal.\nFew-shots: Call answered by \"Thank you for calling XYZ, press 1 for...\" \u2192 ECH. iOS call screening intercepts the call with automated response \u2192 ECH.\n\n- `HTT`: Description: Technical Issue Transfer - Any API call or technical process failure during the call prevents the AI agent from completing the collections interaction. Transfer to human Collections agent.\nUse when: Any system failure (including /pay API errors) prevents the AI from running the collections interaction normally.\nEdge cases: CRITICAL \u2014 Use HTT for system/technical failures. Use EPT when the failure is due to payment scope limitations (amount or method beyond AI capability), not a technical error.\nFew-shots: /pay API fails mid-call and AI cannot complete the interaction \u2192 HTT. System error prevents account retrieval \u2192 HTT.\n\n- `EPT`: Description: Elevated Payment Transfer - Verified customer offers a partial payment AND asks for human/specialist help on the remainder of the balance. Bot transfers to Collections.\nUse when both (a) a specific partial-pay amount or partial-pay willingness is in the user's turns (\"I can pay $X today\"), AND (b) a request for a human/specialist for the rest of the balance.\nEven if the bot completes the transfer (\"connecting you to a live agent\"), the primary code is EPT \u2014 the user's intent is partial-payment scope, NOT bare transfer. EPT is preferred over TSR whenever partial-pay framing is present in the transcript.\nDistinct from: HTT (system/API failure, not user-side scope), TLM (loan-modification request, not partial-pay-this-cycle), TSR (bare human-agent request with NO partial-pay framing), FDP (future-dated full payment, not partial today).\n\n- `DCP`: Description: Already Paid (other channel, same day) - Customer states that today's payment was made via a channel OTHER than this call's DTMF (online portal, prior agent, check, bank transfer). The AI does not pursue further payment.\nUse when: Customer explicitly claims a payment was made today via another channel, providing enough specificity to make the claim concrete (channel, amount, or confirmation number). Must be a SAME-DAY payment.\nEdge cases: Tie-break vs PAY \u2014 PAY = successful DTMF payment in THIS call; DCP = payment made today via a different channel. Tie-break vs DIS \u2014 DIS = customer disputes the debt, including claims that the debt was already paid in the past (prior-day or earlier). DCP is specifically for SAME-DAY alternate-channel payments. If the customer claims payment from a prior day or further back, that's a balance dispute \u2192 DIS, not DCP.\nFew-shots: Customer says \"I paid this online today before you called, confirmation XYZ123\" \u2192 DCP. Customer says \"I just paid through the portal an hour ago\" \u2192 DCP. Customer says \"I paid this off three months ago, why are you calling?\" \u2192 DIS (not DCP \u2014 prior-payment balance dispute).\n\n- `DEC`: Description: Deceased - A third party informs the agent that the account holder has passed away. The AI closes the call respectfully with no payment pressure and no transfer.\nUse when: A third party (family, spouse, executor) unambiguously states the account holder is deceased (\"died,\" \"passed away,\" \"deceased\"). The statement must be definite, not hypothetical or uncertain.\nEdge cases: Tie-break vs INC \u2014 INC = account holder is incapacitated but alive (hospitalized, dementia, coma, brain injury); DEC = account holder has died. Statements like \"she's not well\" or \"he's very ill\" without mentioning death \u2192 INC, not DEC. Tie-break vs LGH \u2014 DEC is the notification of death; LGH is for a guardian/POA who then engages substantively on account matters. If a family member notifies of death AND then substantively discusses the estate account as POA, both DEC and LGH may apply \u2014 LGH primary if substantive account discussion follows.\nFew-shots: Spouse says \"He passed away last month\" \u2192 DEC. Daughter says \"My mother is deceased\" \u2192 DEC. Executor says \"She died, I'm handling her estate, let's talk about the account\" \u2192 DEC + LGH (LGH primary if substantive engagement). Caller says \"She's not available, very ill\" without saying deceased \u2192 INC (not DEC).\n\n- `NLM`: Description: Voicemail - Agent encounters a voicemail or automated answering system, the agent may speak briefly in confusion, say nothing useful after the beep, or terminate the call without leaving a formal message containing a callback number, reason for call, or identification.\nUse when: Voicemail system is detected but the agent does not leave a substantive, actionable message after the tone. Includes cases where the agent says \"May I speak with [Name]?\" into the machine, utters filler words, or disconnects without leaving callback info.\nEdge cases: Tie-break vs LM \u2014 LM = voicemail reached AND substantive message (callback number, stated reason, or formal identification) left AFTER the beep; NLM = voicemail reached but no such message left. Tie-break vs NKP \u2014 NKP = no voicemail system detected at all (silent connection); NLM = voicemail system was reached.\nFew-shots: Agent hears voicemail greeting, says \"May I speak with John?\" then disconnects \u2192 NLM. Agent hears beep but call drops with no message \u2192 NLM. Agent hears beep, leaves name and callback number \u2192 LM (not NLM).\n\n- `LM`: Description: Voicemail - Agent encounters a voicemail, automated/answering system AND leaves a substantive message (callback details, reason for call, and CUSTOMER's NAME).\nUse when: Voicemail system is detected (system prompts like \"record your name,\" \"after the tone,\" \"state your reason\"). Agent explicitly leaves a callback number, states reason for call, AND LEAVE CUSTOMER's NAME AFTER the recording tone.\nEdge cases: Agent merely speaks in confusion to the machine without leaving a formal message \u2192 NLM, not LM. Must have substantive, actionable content (callback number, stated reason, and CUSTOMER's NAME) AFTER the beep. If call terminates or agent gets confused without leaving a formal message \u2192 NLM.\nFew-shots: Agent hears beep, then says \"This is Anna from Kompato, please call us back at 1-888-555-1234, could I talk to [CUSTOMER NAME]\" \u2192 LM. Agent hears beep, says \"May I speak with John?\" then disconnects \u2192 NLM (not LM).\n\n- `NKP`: Description: No Pick Up - Connection established but no substantive customer response followed. No voicemail was reached. The transcript contains only the agent's greeting (or similar system output) with no meaningful customer text.\nUse when: The conversation transcript shows the agent opening followed by silence or system noise with no customer speech. No voicemail prompt or system answering message detected.\nEdge cases: Tie-break vs LM/NLM \u2014 LM/NLM = voicemail system reached (with/without substantive message left); NKP = no voicemail system reached, the line simply never produced a customer response. Tie-break vs HUP \u2014 HUP = customer DID pick up and produced a brief/cryptic/unrelated phrase before the call ended; NKP = no response at all (silent connection). Tie-break vs ECH \u2014 ECH = IVR / pre-recorded system answered; NKP = silence with no IVR signal. In practice this code is often assigned by system rules from call-duration/no-transcript signals; the LLM should use NKP only when the transcript itself confirms no customer engagement.\nFew-shots: Transcript shows agent opening, then silence, then call end \u2192 NKP. Transcript shows \"Hello?\" then disconnect \u2192 HUP (not NKP \u2014 brief pickup). Transcript shows \"You have reached the voicemail of...\" \u2192 LM/NLM (not NKP). Transcript shows a recorded business greeting (\"Thank you for calling XYZ...\") \u2192 ECH (not NKP).\n\n- `TPC`: Description: Third-Party Contact - Person other than the account holder provided information or context to help reach the intended recipient, including callback times or availability windows.\nUse when: Third party acknowledges knowing the account holder. Third party provides alternative phone number, address, availability time, or any contextual detail about the recipient. Third party offers to relay messages or suggests future contact times. Third party provides a callback time or availability window for reaching the account holder (e.g., \"call back after 7:30,\" \"she'll be home in the morning\").\nEdge cases: Distinguish from WRN \u2014 TPC requires explicit evidence of a relationship (acknowledging knowing the person, providing info about them). Even vague or incomplete info that aids in locating the recipient qualifies as TPC. No relationship evidence \u2192 WRN. CRITICAL DISTINCTION FROM CAB \u2014 If a third party (not the account holder) provides a callback time for reaching the account holder, this is TPC, NOT CAB. CAB requires the account holder themselves to schedule a callback. A third party arranging a callback time is providing information to reach the recipient, which is the core function of TPC.\nFew-shots: Person says \"He's not here, try calling after 5pm\" \u2192 TPC (not CAB). Wife says \"He's not available, call back later\" \u2192 TPC (not CAB). Person says \"That's my son, I'll tell him you called\" \u2192 TPC. Sister calls and agent arranges callback for 8AM \u2192 TPC (not CAB). Person says \"I don't know that person, wrong number\" \u2192 WRN (not TPC).\n\n- `WRN`: Description: Wrong Number - The person who answered or called explicitly denied being the intended recipient (e.g., \"No, this is not [name]\", \"You've got the wrong number\") or identified themselves as a business or non-consumer entity unrelated to the account holder (e.g., \"This is a business\", \"This is [Business Name]\"). This code is used when there is an identity mismatch and the respondent has no connection to the account holder.\nUse when: The person explicitly denies being the intended recipient, states the number belongs to a business, identifies themselves as a non-consumer entity, or otherwise confirms the number is not associated with the account holder. An explicit denial of identity or identification as a business line is sufficient regardless of any additional engagement or requests to stop contact. To classify as TPC instead of WRN, there must be explicit evidence of a relationship (acknowledging knowing the recipient or providing info about them).\nEdge cases: CRITICAL \u2014 When a caller identifies as a business or non-consumer and requests to stop contact (\"take my number off the list,\" \"I don't wanna be contacted at all\"), this is WRN, NOT CDS or DNC. The business identification is the primary signal \u2014 it means the number is wrong. Even if the caller says \"stop all communication\" or uses strong language about ceasing contact, the fact that they are NOT the account holder means only the phone number should be removed (WRN behavior), not account-level restrictions applied (CDS/DNC behavior). CDS and DNC require the caller to be the verified account holder or a potential debtor. An unverified business caller CANNOT trigger account-level restrictions.\nFew-shots: Inbound caller says \"Take my number off the list\" + \"This is a business. I don't wanna be contacted at all\" \u2192 WRN (not CDS). Caller says \"You have the wrong number\" \u2192 WRN. Caller says \"No, this is not [name]\" \u2192 WRN. Caller says \"Stop calling this number, this is a business\" \u2192 WRN (not DNC).\n\n- `IDF`: Description: ID Verification Failed - Customer confirms the right name, but DOB/SSN/zip information does not match with data in the system, OR customer refuses to verify their identity through standard verification protocols.\nUse when: Customer says \"No\" when asked if DOB on file is correct (data mismatch). Customer provides a DOB, SSN, or zip that does not match system records. Customer says \"No,\" \"Nope,\" \"I'm not giving you that,\" \"I refuse\" when asked for DOB/SSN (active refusal while still on the line). IDF should stay in neutral-to-positive customer confirmation space.\nEdge cases: Key distinction from HUA \u2014 IDF = customer provided WRONG data (DOB/SSN doesn't match) OR customer is still on the line ACTIVELY refusing/engaging (saying \"No,\" asking questions, arguing). HUA = customer confirmed name but the call ENDED (hung up, went silent, line dropped, timed out) during verification \u2014 no active engagement, just disconnection. If the customer says \"No\" to DOB and CONTINUES the conversation (asks questions, argues, refuses more) \u2192 IDF. If the customer goes silent and call times out \u2192 HUA. If the customer provided wrong data earlier but then the call also drops \u2192 still IDF (data mismatch occurred).\nFew-shots: Customer says \"No\" to \"Is Feb 22 1961 your DOB?\" then says \"It's not\" \u2192 IDF (data mismatch). Customer provides SSN 2549 that doesn't match \u2192 IDF. Customer says \"Nope\" repeatedly to DOB while still talking \u2192 IDF (active refusal). Customer provides wrong DOB \"2 3 65\" that doesn't match \u2192 IDF (data doesn't match even if conversation continues). Customer says \"No\" to DOB on file, then provides different DOB + wrong SSN, then goes silent \u2192 IDF (data mismatch happened before silence). Customer confirms name, agent asks for DOB, customer goes silent \u2192 call ends \u2192 HUA (no data provided, just disconnected).\n\n- `NVR`: Description: Name Verification Refused - Customer failed to confirm their name/identity following agent's attempt, through explicit refusal, evasion, incoherence, or hostility.\nUse when: After the agent asks \"Is this [Name]?\" or similar, the customer responds with SUBSTANTIVE verbal engagement that avoids confirming identity \u2014 defensive questions (\"Who's calling?,\" \"What do you want?\"), evasion (\"Hold on,\" \"Wait a minute\"), incoherent/irrelevant answers, hostility (profanity, aggression), or repeated demands for context. The key signal: the customer engages in a back-and-forth exchange with the agent without confirming their name.\nEdge cases: Distinguish from HUP \u2014 NVR requires SUBSTANTIVE verbal interaction after a name verification attempt (multiple exchanges, questions, hostility). A single \"Hello?\" or brief response followed by immediate disconnection is still HUP if no real exchange occurred. Use NVR when: (1) the customer asks questions about the caller/company, (2) the customer responds with hostility or profanity, (3) the customer engages in multiple turns without confirming identity. Use HUP when: the call ends before any meaningful exchange, or the customer provides only a brief/single-word response before disconnecting. Distinguish from CAB \u2014 if callback arranged specifically because identity could not be verified \u2192 NVR.\nFew-shots: Agent asks \"Is this John Smith?\" and customer says \"Who is calling? What do you want?\" \u2192 NVR. Agent asks for name, customer says \"Kiss my ass, bitch\" \u2192 NVR. Agent asks \"Is this Jeffrey Soliz?\" and customer asks \"Who's this?\" then \"Big Sky?\" (multiple turns) \u2192 NVR. Customer picks up, says \"Hello?\" once, then disconnects \u2192 HUP (not NVR).\n\n- `IDV`: Description: ID Verification Successful - Customer successfully passed all required identity verification checks \u2014 confirmed name AND at least one additional identifier (DOB, or SSN). This becomes the mandatory default classification for the rest of the call unless a more specific terminal disposition is reached.\nUse when: Customer explicitly confirms name AND provides/confirms at least one additional identifier. IDV stays as the default unless a more specific outcome occurs. Switch away from IDV when: the customer declines one or more payment offers (use NNP), a payment arrangement is made (use PPA/PPIF/PSIF), the customer explicitly refuses to pay any amount (use RTP), or any other terminal disposition applies.\nEdge cases: Customer expresses uncertainty about debt or agency \u2192 still IDV. Customer gives non-committal response to payment offer (\"I'm not sure,\" \"Maybe,\" \"Possibly,\" \"I'll think about it\") without clearly declining \u2192 still IDV (not NNP \u2014 non-committal is not a clear decline). Declining to share personal circumstances or explain default reasons is NOT a refusal to pay and NOT NNP \u2192 still IDV. If no specific payment amounts were offered at all, the call remains IDV. CRITICAL \u2014 If a payment offer was made but NO customer response to that offer is present in the conversation (the conversation ends immediately after the offer, or the customer's reply to the offer is missing), this is NOT NNP \u2192 still IDV. NNP requires the customer's explicit decline to be visible in the conversation. If payment was offered AND the customer explicitly said \"No\" or clearly declined, use NNP (not IDV). Only override with RTP if customer makes direct, unambiguous statement refusing to pay ANY amount (e.g., \"I won't pay,\" \"I refuse\"). Hostility, profanity, or incoherent outbursts (e.g., \"don't fuck yourself,\" random aggressive words) without explicit payment refusal \u2192 still IDV, NOT RTP and NOT CPR. A customer who becomes hostile or disengaged after verification but has NOT made a formal complaint about service/practices is NOT CPR \u2014 general hostility or profanity directed at no specific service issue is just a failed conversation, which remains IDV.\nFew-shots: Customer confirms name + DOB, then says \"No\" to sharing circumstances \u2192 IDV. Customer verified, payment discussed but customer says \"Possibly\" or \"Maybe\" without committing or declining \u2192 IDV (not NNP). Customer verified, declines to explain default circumstances, no payment amounts offered \u2192 IDV (not NNP). Customer verified, becomes hostile and uses profanity (\"don't fuck yourself\") but never explicitly refuses to pay \u2192 IDV (not RTP, not CPR). Customer verified, says incoherent hostile things and call ends \u2192 IDV. Customer verified, says \"I'm not familiar with this agency\" \u2192 IDV. Agent asks about circumstances, customer says \"No,\" agent then offers monthly payment amount, conversation ends with no customer response to the offer \u2192 IDV (customer only declined to share circumstances \u2014 no explicit decline of payment offer was shown).\n\n- `DIM`: Description: Debt Sale 2025 - Customer raises questions about the sale of their loan to a third-party buyer, or explicitly asks about a debt sale letter/email they received. Requires transfer to a human Collections agent.\nUse when: Customer mentions receiving a notice about their debt being sold, questions who now owns the debt, or asks about a third-party buyer taking over the account.\nEdge cases: Tie-break vs DIS \u2014 DIM = customer asking about a debt sale/transfer event; DIS = customer disputing the validity or amount of the debt. If the customer disputes that the sale was legal or authorized, both DIM and DIS may apply.\nFew-shots: Customer says \"I got a letter saying my loan was sold, what does that mean?\" \u2192 DIM. Customer says \"Who did you sell my debt to?\" \u2192 DIM.\n\n- `GVT`: Description: Government Shutdown Impact - Customer identifies themselves as affected by a US federal-government shutdown (furloughed federal employee, federal contractor without pay, etc.) and ties that impact to their ability to pay on this account.\nUse when: Customer explicitly names a federal-government-shutdown impact on income/employment and connects it to payment ability. The shutdown must be specifically identified as the cause \u2014 not generic unemployment or hardship language.\nEdge cases: Tie-break vs HCH \u2014 HCH = general long-term hardship; GVT = government-shutdown-specific hardship that may trigger distinct handling. Use GVT when the shutdown is explicitly named; HCH otherwise. Tie-break vs CSM \u2014 CSM = active military service under SCRA; GVT = federal civilian impacted by shutdown. Different legal bases.\nFew-shots: Customer says \"I'm a federal worker, I've been furloughed since the shutdown, I can't pay until it ends\" \u2192 GVT. Customer says \"I'm a government contractor and haven't been paid because of the shutdown\" \u2192 GVT. Customer says \"I lost my job, I have no income\" without referring to the shutdown \u2192 HCH (not GVT).\n\n- `INC`: Description: Consumer Incapacitated - A third party (or the customer) reports the account holder is alive but unable to handle debt-related matters due to severe illness, long-term hospitalization, or mental/physical incapacity.\nUse when: Caller states account holder has a severe or long-term condition preventing engagement (dementia, coma, brain injury, long-term hospitalization, severe cognitive impairment).\nEdge cases: Deceased reports belong to DEC, not INC. Minor/temporary illness (\"they have a cold,\" \"they're sleeping\") \u2192 NOT INC. Incapacitation must imply serious, potentially long-term inability to engage.\nFew-shots: \"She has brain fog. How can I help you?\" \u2192 INC. \"She's been in the hospital for a couple of weeks, she's battling cancer.\" \u2192 INC. \"He passed away last month.\" \u2192 DEC (not INC).\n\n- `LGB`: Description: Language Barrier - Communication could not proceed effectively due to language differences between agent and customer.\nUse when: Customer indicates inability to understand or communicate in the language being used. Language barrier makes meaningful conversation impossible.\nEdge cases: N/A\nFew-shots: Customer responds only in Spanish to English-speaking agent \u2192 LGB. Customer says \"I don't understand English\" \u2192 LGB.\n\n- `RCR`: Description: Recording Consent Refused - Customer explicitly declined consent for the call to be recorded.\nUse when: Customer says \"I do not consent to be recorded,\" \"I don't want to be recorded,\" \"No\" when asked for recording consent, or similar refusal of recording. This applies even if the customer also complains about other issues during the call.\nEdge cases: RCR takes PRIORITY over CPR (Complaint). If a customer refuses recording consent AND also complains about practices, the recording refusal is the primary classification \u2014 use RCR, not CPR. The complaint is secondary to the compliance-critical consent refusal.\nFew-shots: Agent says \"This call is being recorded\" and customer says \"I don't want to be recorded\" \u2192 RCR. Customer says \"No\" when asked for recording consent \u2192 RCR.\n\n- `TSR`: Description: Transfer to Representative (Post-IDV) \u2014 BARE human-agent request with no other meaningful context.\nUse when: Customer requests a human/representative AND the conversation contains NO payment commitment, NO specific future date, NO partial-pay framing, NO loan-mod request, and NO technical-failure signal. Transfer connects in post-IDV path.\nPrecedence: TSR is the FALLBACK for transfer-shaped conversations. If the transcript carries any of these signals, the more-specific code is primary (TSR may co-appear in list_call_codes but NOT as primary):\n  - FDP if customer commits to a specific future date + full balance\n  - EPT if partial-pay willingness + human help on the remainder is in the transcript\n  - TLM if loan-modification language is present\n  - HTT if a technical/system failure is mentioned in the transfer reason\n  - PPIF if customer commits to pay full balance but without a specific date\nPre-IDV equivalent: PTSR (post-process rule). Transfer attempted but not connected: WFR (post-IDV) or PWFR (pre-IDV). Customer refuses verification + requests live agent: HUA/IDF based on evidence.\n\n- `NCV`: Description: Not Convenient - Customer confirmed identity and indicated the current time is inconvenient for financial discussion. NCV describes the customer's STATE (\"now is not good\"), not a mechanism. It can co-occur with CAB when the inconvenience prompts a callback to be scheduled.\nUse when: Customer explicitly says \"now is not a good time,\" \"I can't talk,\" \"I'm busy,\" \"I have to go,\" \"Let's do this later.\" Customer disengages after identity verification due to circumstantial factors.\nEdge cases: Identity verified BUT user then disengages due to circumstances \u2192 NCV (not IDV). If customer says they're busy but STILL engages substantively in conversation (e.g., \"I have a minute, go ahead\"), the call is convenient enough \u2014 do NOT use NCV. Tie-break vs CAB/HCH: NCV = transient inconvenience (no specific time, no long-term reason); CAB = callback mechanism arranged at a specific time; HCH = long-term hardship state. NCV and CAB CAN co-exist \u2014 if the customer expresses inconvenience AND a callback is scheduled, include both in `list_call_code`. NCV and HCH do NOT typically co-occur \u2014 a long-term hardship is not the same as \"bad time right now.\" Pre-IDV equivalent: PNCV (post-process rule handles the mapping).\nFew-shots: Customer says \"I'm at work, I can't talk right now\" and hangs up \u2192 NCV. Customer says \"Now is not a good time\" without specifying when to call back \u2192 NCV. Customer says \"Now is not a good time, can you call me tomorrow at 3pm?\" with agent confirmation \u2192 NCV + CAB (both). Customer says \"I'm busy but go ahead\" and continues talking \u2192 NOT NCV.\n\n- `CAB`: Description: Callback Requested - The ACCOUNT HOLDER explicitly requests or agrees to a future outbound callback at a reasonably specific time. CAB is the MECHANISM (callback scheduled), not a state \u2014 it can co-occur with HCH (hardship state) or NCV (inconvenience state) in `list_call_code` when the callback is arranged because of those states.\nUse when: The account holder (confirmed or claimed) requests or agrees to be called back at a specific future time. A \"reasonably specific\" window includes \"tomorrow,\" \"Monday,\" \"next week,\" \"in a couple of weeks,\" provided the assistant acknowledges and confirms. A timeframe tied to a financial event (e.g., \"call me when I get my check\") is valid. CAB strictly means scheduling an OUTBOUND call from the agent to the account holder.\nEdge cases: CRITICAL PREREQUISITE \u2014 CAB only applies when the ACCOUNT HOLDER themselves requests a callback. If a THIRD PARTY (spouse, family member, roommate, unknown person) provides a callback time for reaching the account holder, classify as TPC, NOT CAB. Tie-break vs HCH/NCV: CAB = callback scheduled (mechanism); HCH = long-term hardship state; NCV = transient inconvenience state. CAB CAN co-occur with HCH or NCV \u2014 if the customer describes hardship AND a callback is arranged, include both in `list_call_code`. CAB is a mechanism, not a veto on state codes. Vs PPIF \u2014 if the customer commits to paying the full balance AND arranges a callback to provide card details, this is PPIF (primary), not CAB alone. Do NOT use CAB for vague statements like \"call me later\" or \"whenever\" where NO timeframe is established. Pre-IDV equivalent: PCAB (post-process rule handles the mapping).\nFew-shots: Account holder says \"call me back in 2 weeks when I get paid,\" agent confirms \u2192 CAB. Customer describes long-term medical hardship AND schedules a callback \u2192 CAB + HCH (both in `list_call_code`). Third party says \"She's not here, call back after 7:30\" \u2192 TPC (not CAB). Customer commits to pay full balance and asks to be called at noon with card ready \u2192 PPIF (not CAB).\n\n- `WCR`: Description: Written Communication Only Requested - Customer explicitly requested all future communications be in writing (mail / email / letter), with no further phone calls. WCR REQUIRES the customer to name a written channel as the preference \u2014 generic \"stop calling\" without a written preference is DNC, not WCR.\nUse when: Customer directs phone contact to cease AND specifies an alternative written channel (mail, email, letter, text-only, \"send it in writing,\" \"write me a letter\"). Both parts must be present \u2014 the phone-stop AND the written-channel preference. This applies even when prompted by frustration with call frequency.\nEdge cases: Tie-break vs CDS/DNC (channel scope): WCR = redirect to written only (phone out, written in); DNC = stop THIS phone (written still OK, not specified); CDS = stop ALL channels (phone + written + electronic). Distinguish from CPR \u2014 WCR is a specific channel-preference demand; CPR is a general complaint about communication practice without specifying the fix. If the customer only says \"stop calling\" without naming a written alternative \u2192 DNC, not WCR. If the customer says \"send it all in writing\" without asking phone calls to stop \u2192 still WCR (the written-only demand implies phone-stop).\nFew-shots: Customer says \"Don't call me, just send everything by mail\" \u2192 WCR. Customer says \"I only want emails, no more phone calls\" \u2192 WCR. Customer says \"Send me a letter, I don't want calls\" \u2192 WCR. Customer says \"Stop calling\" with no written preference \u2192 DNC (not WCR). Customer says \"Stop all contact, don't mail, don't call, nothing\" \u2192 CDS (not WCR \u2014 all channels stopped).\n\n- `CDS`: Description: Cease and Desist - The account holder (or someone reasonably presumed to be the account holder) has requested the complete cessation of all communication attempts regarding this account across all methods, including calls, emails, and texts.\nUse when: The caller explicitly demands cessation of ALL communication methods using phrases like \"stop all communication,\" \"cease all contact,\" \"remove me from everything,\" or \"cease and desist.\" Agent acknowledgment can be brief. This takes precedence even if the caller also requests documentation. Formal legal terminology is not required if intent is clear. The caller does not need to have completed full identity verification, but they must NOT have identified themselves as a third party or business.\nEdge cases: CRITICAL EXCLUSION \u2014 If the caller identifies as a BUSINESS or explicitly states they are NOT the account holder (e.g., \"This is a business,\" \"I'm not that person\"), classify as WRN (not CDS), because the caller is not the debtor and cannot trigger account-level restrictions. CDS applies when: (1) the caller is the verified account holder, OR (2) the caller is reasonably presumed to be the account holder (e.g., they are at the account holder's number and have not denied being the account holder). Distinct from DNC (phone-only stop) and WCR (written preference).\nFew-shots: Caller at account holder's number says \"Stop all communication\" without completing verification \u2192 CDS. Caller who identifies as a business says \"I don't wanna be contacted at all\" \u2192 WRN (not CDS). Verified account holder says \"Cease and desist\" \u2192 CDS. Caller says \"Can you take me off your call list? All communication.\" \u2192 CDS.\n\n- `CPR`: Description: Complaint Received - Customer expressed dissatisfaction, frustration, or concern regarding their account, collection practices, communication methods, or service experience, whether stated formally or implied through behavior. This includes complaints about confusing or unhelpful notifications (SMS, email, letters), annoyance with automated systems, or dissatisfaction with how they were contacted.\nUse when: Customer is unhappy with lack of notification details, expresses annoyance with SMS/text/email content (e.g., \"The text didn't say who this was,\" \"I didn't click the link because it looked like spam\"), rejects provided responses as unhelpful, repeatedly demands a live agent when unavailable, or persistently questions the assistant's inability to help. Key indicator: dissatisfaction with communication quality or practices WITHOUT disputing the debt itself.\nEdge cases: CRITICAL DISTINCTION FROM DIS \u2014 Complaints about HOW the customer was contacted (confusing texts, unclear notifications, spam-like messages) are CPR, NOT DIS. A customer calling to find out who texted them and expressing frustration about unclear communications is making a complaint about contact quality, not disputing the debt. DIS requires an explicit challenge to the debt's validity, accuracy, or legitimacy. If the customer expresses willingness to pay or asks for payment details while complaining about communication, this reinforces CPR over DIS. Also distinct from HCH: a customer who is frustrated about communications but not describing financial hardship should be CPR, not HCH.\nFew-shots: Customer says \"I didn't know who was texting me, the message didn't include any details\" and asks for payment address \u2192 CPR (not DIS). Customer says \"I wasn't clicking links because of scams\" but wants to pay \u2192 CPR. Customer repeatedly asks for a live agent and expresses frustration \u2192 CPR.\n\n- `ATY`: Description: Attorney Representation - Customer stated they have retained or are seeking legal counsel, or legal representation is indicated through any signal in the conversation.\nUse when: Customer mentions \"my attorney,\" \"I'm getting a lawyer,\" \"my attorney has contacted you,\" or references a POA/legal authority. Agent prompts caller for proof of POA or legal representation documentation. Multiple or repeated references to an attorney, even if brief or fragmented. Consumer indicates attorney involvement even indirectly or amidst emotional distress.\nEdge cases: ATY captures explicit attorney engagement or intent to seek one. Distinguish from LGH \u2014 ATY = specific attorney/legal counsel mentioned; LGH = guardian/POA handling without attorney framing. Distinguish from DSA \u2014 keep DSA priority for debt-settlement-program handling unless attorney/legal counsel is explicitly the primary representation path.\nFew-shots: Customer says \"Talk to my lawyer\" \u2192 ATY. Customer says \"I turned my account over to a debt consolidate lawyer\" \u2192 ATY (word \"lawyer\" overrides \"debt consolidate\"). Fragmented speech \"on her journey... her attorney\" \u2192 ATY. Customer says \"I'm working with National Debt Relief\" (no mention of lawyer) \u2192 DSA (not ATY).\n\n- `DIS`: Description: Debt Disputed - The customer explicitly challenged the accuracy, validity, or legitimacy of the debt itself. This includes explicitly stating the debt is not theirs, the amount is wrong, previous payments are not reflected, or asserting the debt is void, canceled, settled, or legally discharged. This code also applies if the customer challenges the creditor's right to collect or the legality of the debt transfer (e.g., \"sold without consent\"). DIS takes precedence over CAB if the customer disputes the debt even if a callback is scheduled.\nUse when: Customer explicitly states the debt is not theirs, the amount is wrong, previous payments are not reflected, or asserts the debt is void/canceled/settled. Also applies when customer claims not to recognize the amount or implies the balance is incorrect (e.g., \"I wasn't aware it was that much\"). If a customer requests to stop contact specifically because they dispute the debt (e.g., \"Stop calling, I don't owe this\"), classify as DIS.\nEdge cases: CRITICAL \u2014 Do NOT classify as DIS if the customer is merely complaining about HOW they were contacted (confusing texts, unclear SMS, spam-looking links). Asking for details because a notification lacked specifics is a communication complaint (CPR), NOT a dispute. A dispute must be an explicit challenge to the DEBT ITSELF \u2014 its existence, amount, validity, or legitimacy. Also do NOT classify as DIS for \"sticker shock\" (e.g., \"Wow, that's a lot\") without questioning accuracy. DIS and PPA are opposite planes: DIS challenges debt validity/amount; PPA confirms willingness to resolve via payment terms.\nFew-shots: Customer says \"I don't owe this money\" \u2192 DIS. Customer says \"The text didn't say who this was for\" but asks for payment address \u2192 CPR (not DIS). Customer says \"I wasn't aware it was that much\" \u2192 DIS.\n\n- `FRA`: Description: Fraud Reported - Customer claims the account was opened fraudulently, through identity theft, or without their knowledge or consent.\nUse when: Customer explicitly alleges fraud or identity theft. Customer categorically denies the account's existence or their responsibility for creating it (even without using the word \"fraud\").\nEdge cases: Distinguish from DIS \u2014 FRA = customer denies they ever created/owned the account; DIS = disputes accuracy or balance of a recognized account. Categorical denial of account ownership \u2192 FRA (not DIS). Requires immediate escalation for fraud investigation.\nFew-shots: Customer says \"I never opened that account, someone stole my identity\" \u2192 FRA. Customer says \"I have no connection to this debt whatsoever\" \u2192 FRA. Customer says \"The balance is wrong, I already paid some\" \u2192 DIS (not FRA).\n\n- `BKP`: Description: Bankruptcy Pending - Customer reported current bankruptcy proceedings or intent to file bankruptcy that would include this account.\nUse when: Customer provides specific bankruptcy details (case number, chapter, filing date) or states intent to file. Triggers immediate cessation of collection activities per automatic stay provisions.\nEdge cases: Requires verification with bankruptcy court records. Intent to file is sufficient even without specific details.\nFew-shots: Customer says \"I filed Chapter 7 last month, case number 12345\" \u2192 BKP. Customer says \"I'm about to file for bankruptcy\" \u2192 BKP.\n\n- `PPA`: Description: Payment Plan Agreed - Customer agreed to a structured payment plan with specific terms (amounts, frequency, and duration) for resolving the debt. Also applies when the customer agreed to pay, the DTMF payment flow was initiated but failed, and the call ended BEFORE a transfer to a live agent was triggered.\nUse when: Customer formally accepts a structured payment arrangement with defined payment amounts and schedule. Also use when the customer agreed to pay, the system initiated DTMF payment but it failed (e.g., PIN authentication failed, payment instrument retrieval failed), and the call ended/hung up before the system could trigger a transfer to a live agent. The payment was attempted but failed, and no transfer followed.\nEdge cases: Special case \u2014 customer unable to respond at the time and requests later contact \u2192 same PPA classification applies. Requires clear, focused confirmation of payment terms \u2014 casual \"yeah\" or \"okay\" as filler while distracted does NOT qualify. CRITICAL DISTINCTION \u2014 PPA applies when DTMF payment failed AND call ended before transfer was triggered. If transfer WAS triggered \u2192 use TSR (connected) or WFR (busy) instead. If DTMF failed and no transfer and no hang-up \u2192 use FTP.\nFew-shots: Customer agrees to $50/month for 6 months and gets transferred to payment \u2192 PPA. Customer agrees to pay full $500, enters DTMF, PIN fails, call hangs up before transfer is triggered \u2192 PPA (not PPIF, not FTP). Customer says \"yeah, sure\" while talking about unrelated topics \u2192 NOT PPA.\n\n- `RTP`: Description: Refusal to Pay - Verified customer EXPLICITLY refuses with HARD, UNAMBIGUOUS language. The customer signals intent NOT TO PAY AT ALL \u2014 not just \"not today\" but a flat, unconditional rejection of the debt itself.\nUse ONLY when the customer's wording is HARD and explicit. Examples that qualify: \"I refuse to pay\", \"I'll never pay this\", \"I'm not paying, period\", \"I'm not paying anything\", \"Absolutely not. I won't pay.\", \"You can take this to court\", \"I don't owe this and I won't pay\", \"There's no way I'm paying this\", \"Forget it, I'm not paying\".\nPrecedence: A polite decline of multiple offers using SOFT language (\"I'll pass\", \"not today\", \"I'd rather not\", \"perhaps another time\", \"won't be doing that today\") is NNP \u2014 even after 5+ attempts. Number of declines is NOT a signal for RTP; only HARD refusal language is. The customer must signal INTENT NOT TO PAY AT ALL.\nDistinct from: NNP (soft/neutral declines that leave the door open). HCH (hardship-driven inability: \"I can't afford it\"). DIS (disputes the debt's validity). IDV (no specific payment offer was made and declined).\nEdge cases: Profanity or hostility alone is NOT RTP \u2014 RTP requires an explicit refusal statement. A customer who becomes hostile or disengaged before any payment discussion occurs should NOT be classified as RTP.\n\n- `CSM`: Description: SCRA Coverage Reported - Customer verified active military service status invoking Servicemembers Civil Relief Act protections.\nUse when: Customer provides details about military service (branch, status, anticipated service period) invoking SCRA protections. SCRA protections include interest rate caps, foreclosure prevention, and other accommodations that must be immediately applied.\nEdge cases: N/A\nFew-shots: Customer says \"I'm active duty military, you need to apply SCRA protections\" \u2192 CSM. Customer says \"I'm deployed overseas with the Army\" \u2192 CSM.\n\n- `PRS`: Description: In Prison - Customer or third party confirmed that the account holder is CURRENTLY incarcerated in a correctional facility.\nUse when: Incarceration in a correctional facility is confirmed as a CURRENT, ongoing status. Specific facility name or release date not required.\nEdge cases: PRS takes precedence over financial codes if both are mentioned. CRITICAL \u2014 PRS requires CURRENT incarceration. Past-tense references to arrest or jail (e.g., \"I got arrested\" as an explanation for default circumstances) do NOT qualify if the customer is clearly not currently incarcerated (e.g., they are on the phone freely discussing the account). Use the surrounding context to determine if the arrest is current or historical.\nFew-shots: Customer says \"I'm currently in jail\" \u2192 PRS. Third party says \"He's incarcerated at the county jail right now\" \u2192 PRS. Customer says \"I got arrested\" as an explanation for why they defaulted, but is freely conversing on the phone \u2192 NOT PRS (use IDV or appropriate code based on conversation outcome).\n\n- `LGH`: Description: Legal Guardian Handling - A legally authorized guardian is managing the account holder's affairs due to the account holder's incapacity or death.\nUse when: Guardian provides verifiable information about their legal relationship and authority to discuss the account. Third party presents power of attorney (POA) or demonstrates legal authority over the account. Communication must be directed exclusively to this authorized representative.\nEdge cases: Distinguish from ATY \u2014 use LGH for general guardian/POA scenarios; use ATY when a specific attorney or legal counsel is mentioned. Distinguish from TPC \u2014 LGH requires demonstrated legal authority (guardian, POA); TPC is any third party providing info without legal standing.\nFew-shots: Third party calls with power of attorney, negotiates settlement on account holder's behalf \u2192 LGH. \"She's deceased... her daughter has financial power of attorney\" \u2192 LGH. Agent confirms caller has power of attorney over incapacitated account holder \u2192 LGH.\n\n- `PSIF`: Description: Promise to Settle in Full - Customer agreed to a discounted settlement offer that will fully resolve the account for less than the original outstanding balance.\nUse when: Customer accepts a reduced settlement amount with a specific payment timeline that fully settles the account. No further payments are required after the agreed discounted amount is paid.\nEdge cases: Distinguish from PPIF \u2014 PSIF = reduced/discounted amount; PPIF = 100% original balance. Full settlement must be confirmed \u2014 account fully resolved with no remaining balance.\nFew-shots: Customer agrees to pay $248 instead of $352.90 full balance to settle \u2192 PSIF. Customer agrees to pay full $352.90 \u2192 PPIF (not PSIF).\n\n- `HCH`: Description: Hardship Concern - Customer describes a LONG-TERM, substantive hardship that materially limits ability to pay \u2014 permanent or long-duration job loss, long-term disability, ongoing serious medical condition, homelessness, or chronic financial inability. HCH is a STATE code describing the customer's situation, not an outcome override. HCH may co-occur with CAB (callback scheduled because of hardship) or PPA (payment plan structured around the hardship) in `list_call_code`.\nUse when: Customer substantively discusses a long-term hardship \u2014 not a passing mention. The hardship must be (1) long-term or open-ended in duration, and (2) described with enough context that a reviewer can identify the specific hardship (unemployment duration, medical condition, etc.). Short passing phrases without elaboration do not qualify.\nEdge cases: SHORT-TERM \u2260 HCH. \"I'm broke right now,\" \"I can't pay today,\" \"I don't have a credit card with me\" are situational difficulties without long-term context \u2014 do NOT include HCH. A brief mention of difficulty (e.g., \"facing difficulties,\" \"got arrested,\" \"family issues\") without substantive discussion \u2192 use IDV (if verified), not HCH. Tie-break vs CAB/NCV: CAB = callback scheduled (mechanism); NCV = transient inconvenience (no callback); HCH = long-term hardship state. CAB and HCH CAN co-exist \u2014 if the customer describes real hardship AND a callback is arranged, include both in `list_call_code`. Tie-break vs RTP: HCH describes inability; RTP describes unwillingness after multiple payment offers.\nFew-shots: Customer describes permanent disability, no income, no foreseeable recovery \u2192 HCH (may also include CAB if callback is set). Customer says \"I lost my job six months ago and still haven't found work, I'm trying but can't afford payments\" \u2192 HCH. Customer says \"I'm broke currently\" without elaborating on duration or cause \u2192 NOT HCH (short-term situational). Customer mentions \"got arrested\" briefly while freely conversing \u2192 NOT HCH (use IDV). Customer describes chronic illness and agrees to a callback in 2 weeks \u2192 HCH + CAB (both).\n\n- `HUA`: Description: Hang Up During Authentication - Customer confirmed their name but the call ENDED (hung up, disconnected, went silent) during the ID verification process. The verification was never completed \u2014 the call was cut short.\nUse when: Customer confirmed their name but the call ended during verification \u2014 customer hung up, went silent (multiple SILENCE markers), line dropped, or call timed out. The customer did NOT provide any DOB/SSN data and did NOT actively refuse \u2014 the call simply ended. Also applies when customer asks context questions (\"Who is this?\", \"What's this about?\") but the call ends before any verification data is exchanged.\nEdge cases: Key distinction from IDF \u2014 If the customer says \"No\" to the DOB on file (data mismatch) or actively says \"Nope,\" \"I refuse\" while still engaging \u2192 IDF (not HUA). HUA is for calls that ENDED during auth without data being checked. If the customer asks \"Who is this?\" then goes silent \u2192 HUA (call ended, no verification data). If the customer says \"I don't know\" to DOB and the call continues \u2192 IDF (refusal while engaged). If the customer says \"I don't know\" and immediately hangs up \u2192 HUA (call ended).\nFew-shots: Customer confirms name, agent asks for DOB, customer goes silent \u2192 call ends \u2192 HUA. Customer confirms name, asks \"Who is this? What's this about?\" \u2192 call ends \u2192 HUA. Customer confirms name, DOB question asked, customer says \"What's this concerning?\" then silence \u2192 HUA. Customer confirms name, says \"I don't know it\" to DOB and call ends \u2192 HUA (call ended, no data checked). Customer says \"No\" to DOB on file \u2192 IDF (not HUA \u2014 data mismatch). Customer says \"Nope\" repeatedly while still on line \u2192 IDF (not HUA \u2014 active refusal). Call truncated right after DOB question is asked, before customer responds \u2192 HUA (not IDV \u2014 verification was never completed).\n\n- `HUP`: Description: Hang Up - Call ends or is effectively abandoned before any meaningful two-way conversation occurs and before any identity or account information is verified. This includes cases where the agent only delivers the opening, the customer says nothing further, the line goes silent, the customer disconnects immediately, or the customer gives only a cryptic, random, or irrelevant phrase (e.g., random nouns, a business name like \"Orange Wagon\" or \"Joe's Pizza\") without clearly expressing intent to engage or continue the conversation. CRITICAL: A customer answering with what sounds like a business name (e.g., \"Orange Wagon\") is NOT the same as the customer explicitly stating \"this is a business\" or \"you have the wrong number.\" Answering with a business-sounding phrase alone \u2014 without the caller explicitly confirming they are NOT the intended person \u2014 does NOT qualify as WRN. Use HUP. WRN requires the caller to EXPLICITLY state it is a wrong number or that they are a business, not merely answer with a phrase that could be a business name.\nUse when: The interaction never progresses beyond the initial contact attempt and the customer's response does not confirm their identity or a clear intent to continue the conversation. A single unrelated, cryptic, or nonsensical phrase does not qualify as engagement unless the customer provides further input indicating an intent to engage, continue, or clarify their response.\nEdge cases: Distinguish from NVR \u2014 If the agent asks \"Is this [Name]?\" and the customer engages in a SUBSTANTIVE back-and-forth exchange (asking questions, demanding context, showing hostility) without confirming identity, use NVR. If the customer provides only a brief response (\"Hello?\") and the call ends quickly without real engagement, use HUP. The key question: was there a meaningful exchange after the name question, or did the call just die? Do NOT use HUP if voicemail is reached (use NLM/LM), if the person explicitly refuses name or ID verification after substantive engagement (use NVR/HUA), if identity was confirmed and the call dropped during authentication (use HUA), or if the person clearly states they are the wrong party (use WRN). WRN requires EXPLICIT confirmation of wrong number. Simply answering with a business name or unrelated phrase without explicitly stating it is a wrong number does NOT qualify as WRN \u2014 use HUP instead.\nFew-shots: Customer says \"Orange Wagon\" then call ends \u2192 HUP (not WRN) \u2014 answering with a business-sounding name without explicitly saying \"this is a business\" or \"wrong number\" is HUP. Customer answers, says nothing, line goes silent \u2192 HUP. Customer says \"Hello?\" then immediately disconnects \u2192 HUP. Even if reflection variable says response=business, if the caller never EXPLICITLY said \"this is a business\" or \"wrong number,\" classify as HUP.\n\n- `NNP`: Description: Negotiated No Payment - Verified customer declines payment options using SOFT, NEUTRAL, NON-COMMITTAL language. The customer says \"no for now\" (door open), NOT \"no forever\" (door slammed shut).\nUse when ALL of these are true: (a) customer verified, (b) agent offered \u22651 specific payment option, (c) customer declined politely without committing, (d) wording is SOFT \u2014 examples (any of these = NNP): \"I'll pass\", \"not today\", \"I'd rather not\", \"won't be doing that today\", \"I'm afraid not today\", \"thank you, but no\", \"I shall pass\", \"not at this time\", \"perhaps another time\", \"I'll have to decline at this time\", \"going to let that one go\", \"Nope, not today\", \"Pass on that one\", \"Maybe later\". (e) customer did NOT use HARD refusal language (see RTP). (f) customer expressed NO hardship or dispute.\nPrecedence: THE NUMBER OF DECLINES DOES NOT MATTER. Multiple polite declines (3, 5, even 8 attempts) remain NNP as long as the language stays soft. Only the LANGUAGE distinguishes NNP from RTP \u2014 not the count.\nDistinct from: RTP (HARD refusal language only \u2014 \"I refuse\", \"I'll never pay\", \"I'm not paying anything\", \"absolutely not\", \"take this to court\"). HCH (hardship: \"I can't afford it\", \"things are tight\", \"I lost my job\"). DIS (questions debt validity). IDV (customer was non-committal \u2014 \"possibly\", \"I'll think about it\" \u2014 without clearly declining a specific offer; or no payment offer was actually made).\n\n- `DSA`: Description: Debt Settlement Agreement - Customer indicates they are working with a third-party debt settlement, consolidation, or relief program to manage their debt.\nUse when: Customer explicitly or implicitly directs agent to contact a named debt relief/settlement program (Beyond Finance, National Debt Relief, Debt Solutions, etc.). Customer states \"a company is handling that for me\" or \"check with my debt negotiator.\" Consumer or representative claims they are working with a program for debt/credit settlement, consolidation, relief, management, or financial solutions.\nEdge cases: Distinguish from ATY \u2014 DSA = financial relief/settlement program; ATY = law office or attorney. If third party is not explicitly identified as a law office, assume it is a debt settlement service. Directing agent to contact a named debt relief agency is sufficient signal regardless of explicit confirmation. Do not let identity verification attempts or other conversational elements distract from settlement agency signals. Do not let the assistant's mention of \"attorney\" trigger ATY if the consumer only identifies a financial program.\nFew-shots: Customer says \"You need to call National Debt Relief, they're handling my account\" \u2192 DSA. Customer says \"A company is managing my debts\" \u2192 DSA. Customer says \"Talk to my lawyer about this\" \u2192 ATY (not DSA).\n\n- `DNC`: Description: Do Not Call - The caller (NOT a business or clearly wrong number) has requested to stop calls to THIS phone number. DNC is a PHONE-level flag; it suppresses further calls to this number without suppressing written channels or account-level activity. Identity verification is NOT required.\nUse when: Caller says \"stop calling,\" \"don't call this number,\" \"put me on your do not call list.\" Formal or informal/frustrated language qualifies equally. DNC applies even if the caller refuses to confirm their name \u2014 the explicit demand to stop phone calls is the primary signal.\nEdge cases: DNC is phone-level and CAN co-occur with post-IDV outcomes in `list_call_code`. If the customer makes a payment commitment (PPA/PPIF) and also says \"don't call me again,\" include DNC alongside the financial outcome \u2014 the phone-stop and the payment arrangement are independent facts. DNC overrides NVR and HUA when the caller explicitly demands to stop calls \u2014 the phone-stop is the terminal disposition, not \"hung up / refused name.\" Tie-break vs CDS/WCR (channel scope): DNC = stop THIS phone; CDS = stop ALL channels (phone + written + electronic); WCR = redirect phone contact to written only. EXCEPTION: If the caller identifies as a BUSINESS or explicitly denies being the account holder AND says the person doesn't live there (e.g., \"There's no [Name] here, stop calling\"), classify as WRN \u2014 the number is simply wrong. DNC requires the caller to COULD be the account holder (didn't deny it).\nFew-shots: Caller says \"Don't call this damn phone again\" without confirming name \u2192 DNC. Caller agrees to a $50/month plan AND says \"but stop calling me about this\" \u2192 primary PPA + DNC in `list_call_code`. Caller says \"This is a business, take my number off the list\" \u2192 WRN (not DNC). Caller says \"There's no Robin here, stop calling\" \u2192 WRN (not DNC \u2014 wrong number). Caller says \"Stop calling\" then \"Do not contact\" then agrees to stop ALL communication channels \u2192 CDS (not DNC \u2014 escalated to all channels).\n\n- `PPIF`: Description: Promise to Pay in Full - Customer verbally committed to paying 100% of the full outstanding balance in a single payment, with no discounts or settlement reductions. IMPORTANT: Do NOT use PPIF if the call ends with a transfer to a live agent \u2014 when a transfer occurs after a payment failure, the final disposition is TSR, not PPIF.\nUse when: Customer confirms the full amount due and agrees to a specific payment date or time (e.g., \"I'll take care of it later today,\" \"Call me back at noon to get my card\"). Use even if a callback is required to collect payment details or finalize the transaction. PPIF requires that NO transfer to a live agent occurs after the payment commitment.\nEdge cases: CRITICAL \u2014 Do NOT classify as CAB when a clear commitment to pay full balance is made. If the customer commits to paying the full balance AND arranges a callback to provide card details, this is ALWAYS PPIF, never CAB. The payment commitment takes precedence over the callback arrangement. Distinguish from PSIF \u2014 PPIF = 100% original balance; PSIF = discounted/reduced settlement amount. TRANSFER EXCEPTION \u2014 If the customer agreed to pay BUT the system fails to process payment (e.g., \"The system can not retrieve your payment information\") AND the AI agent then transfers to a live agent (\"Let me connect you with a live agent\"), classify as TSR, NOT PPIF. The transfer overrides the payment commitment. Distinguish from PPA \u2014 if the DTMF payment flow was initiated but failed, and the call ended before a transfer to a live agent was triggered, classify as PPA (not PPIF).\nFew-shots: Customer says \"I'll pay the full $393.92 tomorrow\" \u2192 PPIF. Customer says \"Call me back at noon, I'll have my card ready to pay it all\" \u2192 PPIF (not CAB). Customer agrees to pay $248 settlement instead of $352 full balance \u2192 PSIF (not PPIF). Customer agrees to pay full $2112.50, provides PIN 123456, system fails to retrieve payment info, agent says \"Let me connect you with a live agent\" \u2192 TSR (NOT PPIF \u2014 transfer overrides payment commitment). Customer enters DTMF payment flow, payment fails, call hangs up before transfer is triggered \u2192 PPA (not PPIF).\n\n## Stage Hints\n- Current state path (if available): []\n- If \"negotiation_from_script\" is present in current states, Post-IDV is likely active.\n- Mini-Miranda language in transcript is a strong cue that Post-IDV has started.\n\n# Output\n<reasoning>\nYour concise reasoning for the classification, reflection of instruction, notes, conversation history, and call code descriptions.\n</reasoning>\n<call_code_list>\n[\"CALL_CODE_1\", \"CALL_CODE_2\", \"CALL_CODE_3\"]\n</call_code_list>\n\n## Reflection Variable Descriptions\n```\n\n```\n\n## Reflection Variable Values\n```\n\n```\n\n## Conversation History\n```\nassistant: Hi, Thank you for calling Kompato. This is Brooke on a recorded line. How can I assist you today?\nuser: I was returning your call.\nassistant: Got it. My name is Brooke. I will be your virtual assistant today. It looks like we're trying to get a hold of Jeremy Kerbo at this number. Is this them?\nuser: Yeah.\nassistant: [supportive] Thank you. To protect your privacy, could you please provide your day and month of birth?\nuser: No.\nassistant: [understanding] I understand your hesitation. The reason I ask for your day and month of birth is to ensure your privacy and security. Could you please provide this information so we can proceed?\nuser: No.\nassistant: [calm] I understand your concern. To proceed and address your request correctly, confirming your identity is necessary. Could you please provide your day and month of birth?\nuser: No.\nassistant: [understanding] Thank you for sharing that. However, we cannot verify your identity without your day and month of birth. [understanding] I understand your concern. To proceed and address your request correctly, confirming your identity is necessary. Could you please provide the last four digits of your Social Security Number?\n```"
[2026-05-13 22:02:21 +0700] [CODEX] output/from_zero/signal_experiment_40_dtmf_rerun_20260513_1655/per_conversation/0023_PmVT8hG7m4pkn5UHlG65jg/llm_call_0007.json:28:      "content": "# Objective\nYou are a reviewer agent in the finance and banking sector.\nYou will receive a transcript of a phone call related to debt collection and recovery, located in the section PHONE_CALL_TRANSCRIPT.\nThe transcript records the conversation of 2 roles: the debt collector (assistant/agent) and the customer (user/customer).\n\nYour task is to analyze this transcript and extract information about any attorney or law firm representing the customer.\n\n## Assistant/Agent Company contact info:\n```\n- Company name: Kompato\n- Company mailing address: 3710 Rawlins Street, Suite 1420, Dallas, Texas 75219\n- Company phone: 18885667280\n- Company email: support at kompato A-I dot com\n```\nNote: The above information represents the debt collector/agent company. If any fields show \"Not provided\" or are empty, ignore them.\n\n## CRITICAL Guidelines - Role Identification\n**CAREFULLY identify who is speaking and what information they are providing:**\n\n1. **The assistant/agent role** = The debt collector's representative\n  - When assistant/agent says \"our mailing address\", \"our company\", \"our phone number\" \u2192 This is the DEBT COLLECTOR's info, NOT the attorney\n  - DO NOT extract any information the assistant/agent provides about their own company\n\n2. **The user/customer role** can be either:\n  - The debtor themselves, OR\n  - An attorney/law firm representative calling ON BEHALF of the debtor\n\n3. **ONLY extract attorney information when:**\n  - User/customer introduces themselves as calling FROM a law firm (e.g., \"I'm calling from Law Offices of...\")\n  - User/customer provides contact info about THEIR OWN office/firm\n  - Information is explicitly described as the attorney's or law firm's information\n\n4. **DO NOT extract when:**\n  - Assistant/agent provides information about their own company (the debt collector)\n  - User asks \"what's your mailing address?\" and assistant answers \u2192 This is debt collector's address\n  - Any contact info where assistant/agent says \"our\", \"my\", \"we\", \"the company\"\n\n5. **Additional rules:**\n  - Extract contact info as-is from the transcript without normalization\n  - If multiple pieces of information are provided, use the most recent or corrected version\n  - Focus on professional contact information (law firm details), not personal attorney info\n\n## Field definitions\n- **attorney_name:** The name of the attorney representing the customer. Return null if not available.\n- **attorney_firm:** The law firm name. Return null if not available.\n- **attorney_address_1:** The first line of the law firm address. Return null if not available.\n- **attorney_address_2:** The second line of the law firm address. Return null if not available.\n- **attorney_city:** The city of the law firm. Return null if not available.\n- **attorney_state:** The state of the law firm. Return null if not available.\n- **attorney_zip:** The zip code of the law firm. Return null if not available.\n- **attorney_phone:** The phone number of the law firm. Return null if not available.\n\n## PHONE_CALL_TRANSCRIPT\n```\nuser: Hello?\nassistant: [happy] Hey, this is Emily, a virtual agent on a recorded line.\nuser: Hello?\nassistant: Is this Teresa Leroy?\nuser: Yes.\nassistant: [confident] To protect your privacy and proceed with the call, I have June 10, 1957 as your birthdate on file. Is that correct?\nuser: Yes.\nassistant: Thank you for confirming. I'm calling from Kompato on behalf of Bureaus Investment Group Portfolio Number 15 LLC. [supportive] I must advise that this is an attempt to collect a debt by a debt collector. Any information obtained will be used for that purpose. [supportive] Teresa, I'm calling about your account with Capital One, National Association, with a balance of seven hundred and thirty-nine dollars and seventeen cents. Could you please tell me about the circumstances that led to the default?\nuser: Yes. Um, I can't work right now.\nassistant: [compassionate] I'm sorry to hear that, Teresa. That must be a challenging situation for you. To help me find the best-\nuser: It is.\nassistant: [understanding] I can imagine how difficult this must be for you. [supportive] Your account balance is seven hundred and thirty-nine dollars and seventeen cents. To assist you, we can settle the total balance to five hundred and eighteen dollars, saving you two hundred and twenty-two dollars. This would reduce your monthly payment to eighty-seven dollars for six months, with the last installment being eighty-three dollars. Would this adjusted amount be manageable for you?\nuser: No.\nassistant: [understanding] I see. -\nuser: two i.\nassistant: [confused] I'm sorry, could you clarify what you mean by \"two i\"?\nuser: Too high. I won't be able to pay for my medicine.\nassistant: [compassionate] I understand, Teresa. Your health is a priority, and I want to help find a solution that works for you. [supportive] We can explore a lower settlement option. We could settle your account for four hundred and forty-four dollars, which reduces your monthly payment to seventy-four dollars for six months. Would this be more manageable for you?\nuser: No.\nassistant: -\nuser: No. Fifty.\nassistant: [supportive] I understand you're suggesting fifty dollars. The minimum monthly amount for the settlement offer is seventy-four dollars. [encouraging] Would it be possible to adjust slightly closer to that amount?\nuser: It'd be hard.\nassistant: [understanding] I see how that could be difficult. [supportive] If seventy-four dollars isn't feasible, we can schedule a keep-in-touch arrangement for three months with a minimum monthly amount of fifty dollars. Would that work better for you?\nuser: Yes.\nassistant: [supportive] Great. Could you let me know a convenient date within the next 30 days to start the first payment of fifty dollars?\nuser: The twenty seventh.\nassistant: [supportive] Just to confirm, you'll be making a monthly payment of fifty dollars starting on May 27, 2026. Is that correct?\nuser: Yes.\nassistant: Please note that nothing we discuss overshadows your rights as expressed in our email to you. For any reason we get disconnected, do we have permission to call you back?\nuser: Yes.\nuser: I have no email anyway.\nassistant: [professional] Thank you for confirming. Since you mentioned you don't have an email, we can send any necessary information via text. Which payment method are you planning to use\u2014debit card, credit card, or-\nuser: Money order.\nassistant: Understood-\nuser: Money order. I have bank account.\nassistant: [professional] Thank you for sharing that. If you're planning to send a money order, you can mail it to our address at three seven one zero  Rawlins Street, Suite one four two zero , Dallas, Texas seven five two one nine . [supportive] We also have an online payment portal at kompatoai. com for your convenience. [supportive] Now, let's ensure we have your most up-to-date contact information. I have CHRISLEROY two one zero nine at GMAIL dot COM as your email address in my records. Is this still accurate?\nuser: I don't have an email address.\nassistant: [supportive] Thank you for letting me know. I'd appreciate it if you could provide me with a new email address to reach you. May I have the best email to contact you?\nuser: I don't have one.\nassistant: [understanding] That's okay. We'll proceed without an email address for now. [supportive] I also have nine three zero  E 1st Street Unit two three , Long Beach, California, nine zero eight zero two as your mailing address in my records. Is this still accurate?\nuser: Yes.\nuser: Yes.\nassistant: [appreciative] Thank you for confirming. [supportive] Lastly, I have five six two six six one zero zero five one as your contact number. Is this still the best way to reach you?\nuser: Yes.\nuser: Yes.\nassistant: [appreciative] Thank you for confirming all your contact details. [supportive] If you have any further questions or need assistance, feel free to reach out. Have a good day!\nuser: <SILENCE_5s>\nassistant: \n```\n\n# Response Format\nReturn ONLY the attorney representation info in JSON format.\n{\n  \"attorney_name\": null,\n  \"attorney_firm\": null,\n  \"attorney_address_1\": null,\n  \"attorney_address_2\": null,\n  \"attorney_city\": null,\n  \"attorney_state\": null,\n  \"attorney_zip\": null,\n  \"attorney_phone\": null\n}\n\n# Examples\n- Customer says \"My attorney is [name] from [firm]\" \u2192 Extract both name and firm\n- Customer says \"You can reach my lawyer at (phone number)\" \u2192 Extract phone number\n- Customer says \"I'm represented by [firm], located at [address]\" \u2192 Extract all address fields\n- Customer says \"I have a lawyer\" but provides no details \u2192 Return null for all fields\n- Attorney calls in: \"I'm calling from [firm]\" and provides email \"[email]\" \u2192 Extract firm name and email\n- Customer asks \"What's your mailing address?\" and agent responds \"Our address is [address]\" \u2192 DO NOT extract (this is agent's company address)\n- Agent says \"You can reach us at [phone number]\" \u2192 DO NOT extract (this is agent's company phone)"
