[2026-05-13 22:02:22 +0700] [CODEX] output/from_zero/signal_experiment_40_dtmf_rerun_20260513_1655/per_conversation/0036_V1odG3MmM-c4Gt8pzk4Ueg/llm_call_0001.json:28:      "content": "You are a Collection Agent specialized in classifying conversations into the one to three most relevant call codes.\nGiven abstracted conversation history, list of call codes with their descriptions, and reflection variable values with their descriptions (optional) and  your task to analyze and classify the conversation into the one to three most relevant call codes.\n\n# Instruction\n- Thoroughly analyze the conversation history, dictionary variable values, state variable descriptions, and call code descriptions.\n- Carefully review the conversation to select the one to three call codes that best fit the context and details of the exchange.\n- When reasoning, you may reference reflection variable values and descriptions if they help justify your choices, but focus primarily on the conversation context and call code descriptions.\n- Your justification should combine insights from the conversation, call code descriptions, and other inputs as relevant.\n\n#  Notes:\n- Consider all possible angles and variable values, not just the most direct or frequent call code.\n- Make sure the reasoning is clear, specific, and references the data provided.\n\n\n# Output Format\n- Return your reasoning in <reasoning> </reasoning> tags\n- Return list potential call code wrapped in <call_code_list> </call_code_list> tags.\n\n# Input Information\n\n## Conversation History\n```\nuser: Hello?\nassistant: [happy] Hey, this is Opal, a virtual agent on a recorded line.\nassistant: Is this Maurice Davis?\nuser: Speaking.\nuser: Speak.\nuser: Speaking.\nassistant: -\nassistant: [professional] Thanks, Maurice.\nassistant: For verification purposes, I need to confirm I have the correct Maurice Davis.\nassistant: I have July 24, 1962 as your birthdate on file.\nassistant: Is that correct?\nuser: Correct.\nassistant: Thank you for confirming.\nassistant: [supportive] I must advise that this is an attempt to collect a debt by a debt collector.\nassistant: Any information obtained will be used for that purpose.\nassistant: [supportive] Maurice, I'm calling about your account with MoneySpot Direct LLC dba Sunshine Loans, with a balance of one hundred and fifty-eight dollars and fifty-two cents.\nassistant: Could you please tell me about the circumstances that led to the default?\nuser: Without the cancer treatments.\nuser: Without the cancer treatment,\nuser: and dedicated for it right now.\nassistant: [compassionate] I'm sorry to hear about your situation, Maurice.\nassistant: I hope your treatments are going well and that you're on the path to recovery.\nassistant: [supportive] To help ease the financial burden, your account balance is one hundred and fifty-eight dollars and fifty-two cents.\nassistant: Instead of paying the full balance, we can settle this at 60 percent of your balance \u2014 that's ninety-six dollars, saving you sixty-four dollars.\nassistant: Would this work for you?\nuser: Yeah. But not right now. I I get I get paid next Wednesday.\nassistant: [supportive] Understood, Maurice.\nassistant: [supportive] Since next Wednesday falls within the next 30 days, we can schedule the payment for that day.\nassistant: Would May 1, 2026, work for you to make the payment of ninety-six dollars?\nuser: Yes.\nuser: Yeah. Let me pay it off. Right?\nassistant: For any reason we get disconnected, do we have permission to call you back?\nuser: Sure.\nassistant: [appreciative] Thank you, Maurice.\nassistant: [supportive] Which payment method are you planning to use\u2014debit card, credit card, or ACH payments?\nuser: <SILENCE_5s>\nuser: I'm not sure yet.\nassistant: [calm] That's okay, Maurice.\nassistant: [supportive] Once you've decided, we can proceed to set up the payment for May 1st, twenty twenty-six.\nassistant: Would you like me to go over the payment methods again to help you decide?\nuser: Yes.\nassistant: [professional] Certainly.\nassistant: You can choose to pay using a debit card, a credit card, or through ACH payments,-\nuser: debit card.\nassistant: [appreciative] Got it, Maurice.\nassistant: Thank you for letting me know.\nassistant: [supportive] To confirm, you are agreeing to pay the amount of ninety-six dollars on May 1st, twenty twenty-six using your debit card.\nassistant: Do you agree to this payment?\nuser: I do. I have a debit debit card, though. What... you have my have on file.\nassistant: [calm] I understand, Maurice.\nassistant: [supportive] Just to clarify, we don't store card details on file for security reasons.\nassistant: Once you're ready, we can proceed with setting up the payment using your debit card.\nuser: Oh,\nassistant: Does that work for you?\nuser: Yes. Large. It's taken out by the... on the first.\nassistant: [supportive] Perfect, Maurice.\nassistant: [professional] To confirm our arrangement today, April 24th, twenty twenty-six, you have authorized Kompato AI to automatically withdraw the following payment arrangement for your MoneySpot Direct LLC dba Sunshine Loans account ending in 3146.\nassistant: This payment will be processed using your debit card:\nassistant: A one-time payment in the amount of ninety-six dollars.\nassistant: This payment will be submitted for processing on May 1st, twenty twenty-six.\nassistant: Please make sure funds are available on that date.\nassistant: Please confirm that you are one of the owners of this debit card and have the right to set up these payments.\nassistant: You are arranging for the payments that we just discussed to be-\nuser: Hi.\nuser: Alright.\nassistant: [supportive] Thank you, Maurice.\nuser: Yes.\nassistant: [professional] As I was saying, you are arranging for the payments that we just discussed to be automatically charged to your debit card.\nassistant: This payment authorization is valid and shall remain in effect unless you notify Kompato AI of its cancellation at any time by contacting us at 8-8-8<break time=\"500ms\"/>5-6-6<break time=\"500ms\"/>7-2-8-0.\nuser: Good.\nassistant: To confirm and authorize this payment, please state \"I agree.\nassistant: \"\nuser: I agree.\nassistant: For your privacy and security, you will now enter your card information using the phone keypad.\nassistant: Please start inputting\nassistant: Thank you for setting up your payment with us.\nassistant: To ensure important account updates reach you timely, could we take a moment to update your contact details?\nuser: Go ahead.\nassistant: [supportive] Thank you.\nassistant: I have MAXAMYLLN seven two four at HOTMAIL dot COM as your email address in my records. Is this still accurate?\nuser: Yes.\nassistant: [appreciative] Thank you for confirming.\nassistant: [supportive] I also have two one West Clearview Avenue, Wilmington, Delaware, one nine eight zero nine as your mailing address in my records. Is this still accurate?\nuser: Yes.\nassistant: [appreciative] Thank you for confirming that as well.\nassistant: -\nuser: Do I get a receipt?\nuser: Do I get a receipt\nassistant: [professional] Yes, Maurice.\nassistant: Once the payment is processed on May 1st, 2026, you will receive a receipt via email.\nassistant: If you need it sent to a different email address, let me know.\nuser: Yeah. I do.\n```\n\n## List of Call Codes and Their Descriptions\n- `NLM`: Description: Agent encounters a voicemail system, automated/answering system or a person confirming the customer is unavailable, and no substantive message or actionable instruction is left.\nUse when: Agent reaches voicemail/automated system or is told the person is unavailable. Call ends without leaving a callback number, stated reason for call, or formal identification after the beep. Agent may provide initial introduction (name, company, customer name) but does not leave actionable requests.\nEdge cases: Agent speaks in confusion to the voicemail machine (e.g., \"May I please speak with [Name]?\") without leaving a formal message \u2192 NLM, not LM. Brief interactions ending immediately after unavailability is confirmed \u2192 NLM. If agent intentionally leaves a callback number or states the reason for the call \u2192 LM, not NLM. This code excludes calls where the number reached does not belong to the intended customer (use WRN).\nFew-shots: Agent hears \"leave a message after the tone,\" says \"May I speak with John?\" then hangs up \u2192 NLM. Person answers \"She's not available,\" agent says \"Okay, thank you\" \u2192 NLM.\n\n\n- `LM`: Description: Agent encounters a voicemail, automated/answering system AND leaves a substantive message (callback number, reason for call, or formal identification) after the beep.\nUse when: Voicemail system is detected (system prompts like \"record your name,\" \"after the tone,\" \"state your reason\"). Agent explicitly leaves a callback number, states reason for call, or provides formal identification AFTER the recording tone.\nEdge cases: Agent merely speaks in confusion to the machine without leaving a formal message \u2192 NLM, not LM. Must have substantive, actionable content (callback number, stated reason, or formal identification) AFTER the beep. If call terminates or agent gets confused without leaving a formal message \u2192 NLM.\nFew-shots: Agent hears beep, then says \"This is Anna from Kompato, please call us back at 1-888-555-1234\" \u2192 LM. Agent hears beep, says \"May I speak with John?\" then disconnects \u2192 NLM (not LM).\n\n\n- `HUP`: Description: Hang Up - Call ends or is effectively abandoned before any meaningful two-way conversation occurs and before any identity or account information is verified. This includes cases where the agent only delivers the opening, the customer says nothing further, the line goes silent, the customer disconnects immediately, or the customer gives only a cryptic, random, or irrelevant phrase (e.g., random nouns, a business name like \"Orange Wagon\" or \"Joe's Pizza\") without clearly expressing intent to engage or continue the conversation. CRITICAL: A customer answering with what sounds like a business name (e.g., \"Orange Wagon\") is NOT the same as the customer explicitly stating \"this is a business\" or \"you have the wrong number.\" Answering with a business-sounding phrase alone \u2014 without the caller explicitly confirming they are NOT the intended person \u2014 does NOT qualify as WRN. Use HUP. WRN requires the caller to EXPLICITLY state it is a wrong number or that they are a business, not merely answer with a phrase that could be a business name.\nUse when: The interaction never progresses beyond the initial contact attempt and the customer's response does not confirm their identity or a clear intent to continue the conversation. A single unrelated, cryptic, or nonsensical phrase does not qualify as engagement unless the customer provides further input indicating an intent to engage, continue, or clarify their response.\nEdge cases: Distinguish from NVR \u2014 If the agent asks \"Is this [Name]?\" and the customer engages in a SUBSTANTIVE back-and-forth exchange (asking questions, demanding context, showing hostility) without confirming identity, use NVR. If the customer provides only a brief response (\"Hello?\") and the call ends quickly without real engagement, use HUP. The key question: was there a meaningful exchange after the name question, or did the call just die? Do NOT use HUP if voicemail is reached (use NLM/LM), if the person explicitly refuses name or ID verification after substantive engagement (use NVR/HUA), if identity was confirmed and the call dropped during authentication (use HUA), or if the person clearly states they are the wrong party (use WRN). WRN requires EXPLICIT confirmation of wrong number. Simply answering with a business name or unrelated phrase without explicitly stating it is a wrong number does NOT qualify as WRN \u2014 use HUP instead.\nFew-shots: Customer says \"Orange Wagon\" then call ends \u2192 HUP (not WRN) \u2014 answering with a business-sounding name without explicitly saying \"this is a business\" or \"wrong number\" is HUP. Customer answers, says nothing, line goes silent \u2192 HUP. Customer says \"Hello?\" then immediately disconnects \u2192 HUP. Even if reflection variable says response=business, if the caller never EXPLICITLY said \"this is a business\" or \"wrong number,\" classify as HUP.\n\n\n- `IDF`: Description: ID Verification Failed - Customer confirms the right name, but DOB/SSN/zip information does not match with data in the system, OR customer refuses to verify their identity through standard verification protocols.\nUse when: Customer says \"No\" when asked if DOB on file is correct (data mismatch). Customer provides a DOB, SSN, or zip that does not match system records. Customer says \"No,\" \"Nope,\" \"I'm not giving you that,\" \"I refuse\" when asked for DOB/SSN (active refusal while still on the line). Customer confirms they are not the intended person during verification.\nEdge cases: Key distinction from HUA \u2014 IDF = customer provided WRONG data (DOB/SSN doesn't match) OR customer is still on the line ACTIVELY refusing/engaging (saying \"No,\" asking questions, arguing). HUA = customer confirmed name but the call ENDED (hung up, went silent, line dropped, timed out) during verification \u2014 no active engagement, just disconnection. If the customer says \"No\" to DOB and CONTINUES the conversation (asks questions, argues, refuses more) \u2192 IDF. If the customer goes silent and call times out \u2192 HUA. If the customer provided wrong data earlier but then the call also drops \u2192 still IDF (data mismatch occurred).\nFew-shots: Customer says \"No\" to \"Is Feb 22 1961 your DOB?\" then says \"It's not\" \u2192 IDF (data mismatch). Customer provides SSN 2549 that doesn't match \u2192 IDF. Customer says \"Nope\" repeatedly to DOB while still talking \u2192 IDF (active refusal). Customer provides wrong DOB \"2 3 65\" that doesn't match \u2192 IDF (data doesn't match even if conversation continues). Customer says \"No\" to DOB on file, then provides different DOB + wrong SSN, then goes silent \u2192 IDF (data mismatch happened before silence). Customer confirms name, agent asks for DOB, customer goes silent \u2192 call ends \u2192 HUA (no data provided, just disconnected).\n\n\n- `HUA`: Description: Hang Up During Authentication - Customer confirmed their name but the call ENDED (hung up, disconnected, went silent) during the ID verification process. The verification was never completed \u2014 the call was cut short.\nUse when: Customer confirmed their name but the call ended during verification \u2014 customer hung up, went silent (multiple SILENCE markers), line dropped, or call timed out. The customer did NOT provide any DOB/SSN data and did NOT actively refuse \u2014 the call simply ended. Also applies when customer asks context questions (\"Who is this?\", \"What\u2019s this about?\") but the call ends before any verification data is exchanged.\nEdge cases: Key distinction from IDF \u2014 If the customer says \"No\" to the DOB on file (data mismatch) or actively says \"Nope,\" \"I refuse\" while still engaging \u2192 IDF (not HUA). HUA is for calls that ENDED during auth without data being checked. If the customer asks \"Who is this?\" then goes silent \u2192 HUA (call ended, no verification data). If the customer says \"I don\u2019t know\" to DOB and the call continues \u2192 IDF (refusal while engaged). If the customer says \"I don\u2019t know\" and immediately hangs up \u2192 HUA (call ended).\nFew-shots: Customer confirms name, agent asks for DOB, customer goes silent \u2192 call ends \u2192 HUA. Customer confirms name, asks \"Who is this? What\u2019s this about?\" \u2192 call ends \u2192 HUA. Customer confirms name, DOB question asked, customer says \"What\u2019s this concerning?\" then silence \u2192 HUA. Customer confirms name, says \"I don\u2019t know it\" to DOB and call ends \u2192 HUA (call ended, no data checked). Customer says \"No\" to DOB on file \u2192 IDF (not HUA \u2014 data mismatch). Customer says \"Nope\" repeatedly while still on line \u2192 IDF (not HUA \u2014 active refusal). Call truncated right after DOB question is asked, before customer responds \u2192 HUA (not IDV \u2014 verification was never completed).\n\n\n- `NVR`: Description: Name Verification Refused - Customer failed to confirm their name/identity following agent\u2019s attempt, through explicit refusal, evasion, incoherence, or hostility.\nUse when: After the agent asks \"Is this [Name]?\" or similar, the customer responds with SUBSTANTIVE verbal engagement that avoids confirming identity \u2014 defensive questions (\"Who\u2019s calling?,\" \"What do you want?\"), evasion (\"Hold on,\" \"Wait a minute\"), incoherent/irrelevant answers, hostility (profanity, aggression), or repeated demands for context. The key signal: the customer engages in a back-and-forth exchange with the agent without confirming their name.\nEdge cases: Distinguish from HUP \u2014 NVR requires SUBSTANTIVE verbal interaction after a name verification attempt (multiple exchanges, questions, hostility). A single \"Hello?\" or brief response followed by immediate disconnection is still HUP if no real exchange occurred. Use NVR when: (1) the customer asks questions about the caller/company, (2) the customer responds with hostility or profanity, (3) the customer engages in multiple turns without confirming identity. Use HUP when: the call ends before any meaningful exchange, or the customer provides only a brief/single-word response before disconnecting. Distinguish from CAB \u2014 if callback arranged specifically because identity could not be verified \u2192 NVR.\nFew-shots: Agent asks \"Is this John Smith?\" and customer says \"Who is calling? What do you want?\" \u2192 NVR. Agent asks for name, customer says \"Kiss my ass, bitch\" \u2192 NVR. Agent asks \"Is this Jeffrey Soliz?\" and customer asks \"Who\u2019s this?\" then \"Big Sky?\" (multiple turns) \u2192 NVR. Customer picks up, says \"Hello?\" once, then disconnects \u2192 HUP (not NVR).\n\n\n- `IDV`: Description: ID Verification Successful - Customer successfully passed all required identity verification checks \u2014 confirmed name AND at least one additional identifier (DOB, or SSN). This becomes the mandatory default classification for the rest of the call unless a more specific terminal disposition is reached.\nUse when: Customer explicitly confirms name AND provides/confirms at least one additional identifier. IDV stays as the default unless a more specific outcome occurs. Switch away from IDV when: the customer declines one or more payment offers (use NNP), a payment arrangement is made (use PPA/PPIF/PSIF), the customer explicitly refuses to pay any amount (use RTP), or any other terminal disposition applies.\nEdge cases: Customer expresses uncertainty about debt or agency \u2192 still IDV. Customer gives non-committal response to payment offer (\"I'm not sure,\" \"Maybe,\" \"Possibly,\" \"I'll think about it\") without clearly declining \u2192 still IDV (not NNP \u2014 non-committal is not a clear decline). Declining to share personal circumstances or explain default reasons is NOT a refusal to pay and NOT NNP \u2192 still IDV. If no specific payment amounts were offered at all, the call remains IDV. CRITICAL \u2014 If a payment offer was made but NO customer response to that offer is present in the conversation (the conversation ends immediately after the offer, or the customer's reply to the offer is missing), this is NOT NNP \u2192 still IDV. NNP requires the customer's explicit decline to be visible in the conversation. If payment was offered AND the customer explicitly said \"No\" or clearly declined, use NNP (not IDV). Only override with RTP if customer makes direct, unambiguous statement refusing to pay ANY amount (e.g., \"I won't pay,\" \"I refuse\"). Hostility, profanity, or incoherent outbursts (e.g., \"don't fuck yourself,\" random aggressive words) without explicit payment refusal \u2192 still IDV, NOT RTP and NOT CPR. A customer who becomes hostile or disengaged after verification but has NOT made a formal complaint about service/practices is NOT CPR \u2014 general hostility or profanity directed at no specific service issue is just a failed conversation, which remains IDV.\nFew-shots: Customer confirms name + DOB, then says \"No\" to sharing circumstances \u2192 IDV. Customer verified, payment discussed but customer says \"Possibly\" or \"Maybe\" without committing or declining \u2192 IDV (not NNP). Customer verified, declines to explain default circumstances, no payment amounts offered \u2192 IDV (not NNP). Customer verified, becomes hostile and uses profanity (\"don't fuck yourself\") but never explicitly refuses to pay \u2192 IDV (not RTP, not CPR). Customer verified, says incoherent hostile things and call ends \u2192 IDV. Customer verified, says \"I'm not familiar with this agency\" \u2192 IDV. Agent asks about circumstances, customer says \"No,\" agent then offers monthly payment amount, conversation ends with no customer response to the offer \u2192 IDV (customer only declined to share circumstances \u2014 no explicit decline of payment offer was shown).\n\n\n- `TSR`: Description: Transfer to Representative - Customer explicitly requests to speak with a live person, or a structural handoff to a live agent occurs during the call. Once a transfer request is made or handoff occurs, this code remains the classification for the entire call. IMPORTANT: If the conversation ends with the AI agent transferring to a live agent (e.g., \"Let me connect you with a live agent\"), this is ALWAYS TSR regardless of what happened earlier in the call.\nUse when: Customer says \"customer service,\" \"representative,\" \"human,\" \"operator,\" \"transfer me,\" or similar. Agent says \"while I check availability for a live agent\" followed by a live person introduction. Transfer request is made even if the virtual assistant fails to fulfill it. ALSO use when the AI agent initiates a transfer to a live agent due to a system failure (e.g., payment processing error, unable to retrieve payment information, \"The system can not retrieve your payment information\") \u2014 this is a structural handoff even though the customer did not request it. RULE: Look at the FINAL outcome of the call. If the call ends with a transfer to a live agent, classify as TSR \u2014 not the code that was applicable before the transfer.\nEdge cases: TSR overrides IDV, NCV, CAB, PPIF, PSIF, PPA, NNP, RTP, and other standard operational codes. CRITICAL OVERRIDE: Even if the customer agreed to pay in full (PPIF), provided a PIN, and the system attempted payment \u2014 if the payment system FAILED and the AI agent then transfers to a live agent, you MUST select TSR, NOT PPIF. The transfer is the FINAL disposition and supersedes ALL prior payment commitments. Even if the live agent performs verification, updates addresses, or discusses payment, you MUST select TSR. HUA, DIS, CDS still take precedence over TSR. If customer refuses secondary verification AND requests live agent \u2192 HUA (not TSR; refusal takes precedence). Once transfer request is made or system-initiated handoff occurs, TSR remains classification regardless of prior payment commitments or subsequent content. Key indicators: \"Let me connect you with a live agent,\" \"while I check availability,\" \"customer service,\" \"The system can not retrieve your payment information.\"\nFew-shots: Customer agrees to pay full $2112.50, provides PIN 123456, system repeatedly says \"retrieving your payment information,\" then fails and agent says \"The system can not retrieve your payment information. Let me connect you with a live agent\" \u2192 TSR (NOT PPIF \u2014 the transfer at the END of the call is the final disposition, overriding the earlier payment commitment). Customer says \"customer service\" at the start, then agent transfers to live person who handles the whole call \u2192 TSR. Customer says \"Representative. Representative.\" and agent fails to transfer \u2192 TSR. Customer says \"I want a person\" while refusing DOB \u2192 HUA (not TSR).\n\n\n- `INC`: Description: Consumer Incapacitated - A third party (or the customer) reports the account holder is deceased, severely ill, hospitalized long-term, or mentally incapacitated.\nUse when: Caller states the account holder has passed away (deceased, died). Caller states account holder has a severe or long-term condition preventing engagement (dementia, coma, brain injury, long-term hospitalization, brain fog).\nEdge cases: Minor/temporary illness (\"they have a cold,\" \"they're sleeping\") \u2192 NOT INC. \"Brain fog\" qualifies as mental incapacity \u2192 INC. Incapacitation must imply serious, potentially long-term inability to engage.\nFew-shots: \"She's not available, sir. She's deceased now. This is her husband.\" \u2192 INC. \"She has brain fog. How can I help you?\" \u2192 INC. \"She's been in the hospital for a couple of weeks, she's battling cancer.\" \u2192 INC.\n\n\n- `LGB`: Description: Language Barrier - Communication could not proceed effectively due to language differences between agent and customer.\nUse when: Customer indicates inability to understand or communicate in the language being used. Language barrier makes meaningful conversation impossible.\nEdge cases: N/A\nFew-shots: Customer responds only in Spanish to English-speaking agent \u2192 LGB. Customer says \"I don't understand English\" \u2192 LGB.\n\n\n- `RTP`: Description: Refusal to Pay - Customer explicitly and unambiguously refused to make any payment on the account ONLY after the creditor presented the balance AND made MULTIPLE attempts to negotiate payment options. RTP requires: (1) identity verification was completed, (2) the balance was presented, (3) the creditor offered multiple payment plans or settlement options, and (4) the customer explicitly rejected ALL of them or stated they will not pay any amount.\nUse when: Customer uses explicit refusal language such as \"I can\u2019t pay anything,\" \"None,\" \"I\u2019m not paying,\" \"It\u2019s not possible,\" \"I refuse to pay,\" or \"I will never pay.\" RTP requires an unambiguous statement of intent NOT to pay \u2014 not merely saying \"No\" to specific offered amounts. Simply declining offered payment amounts without explicit refusal language is NNP, not RTP. The customer must have been given a genuine opportunity to negotiate before RTP applies.\nEdge cases: CRITICAL \u2014 Declining to share personal circumstances or explain default reasons is NOT RTP (use IDV). Profanity or hostility alone does NOT automatically qualify as RTP \u2014 the customer must have explicitly refused to pay or been given multiple payment options which they all rejected. Random profanity, frustration, or incoherent hostile outbursts (e.g., \"don\u2019t fuck yourself\") WITHOUT an explicit statement refusing payment is NOT RTP. If the conversation never reached the payment negotiation stage (i.e., no specific payment amounts were offered and rejected), profanity alone should be classified as IDV (if verified) or the appropriate pre-negotiation code. RTP requires the conversation to have progressed to active financial negotiation where specific payment options were presented and explicitly refused. A customer who becomes hostile or disengaged before any payment discussion occurs should NOT be classified as RTP.\nFew-shots: Customer rejects $66/month, then rejects $50/month, then says \"I\u2019m not paying anything\" \u2192 RTP. Customer says \"No\" to sharing circumstances but no payment options were discussed yet \u2192 IDV. Customer uses profanity and disconnects before any payment offer \u2192 IDV (not RTP). Customer becomes extremely hostile, uses profanity, AND explicitly says \"I\u2019m not paying\" or \"None\" when offered payment amounts \u2192 RTP (not CPR \u2014 the explicit payment refusal takes precedence over the hostility/complaint aspect).\n\n\n- `RCR`: Description: Recording Consent Refused - Customer explicitly declined consent for the call to be recorded.\nUse when: Customer says \"I do not consent to be recorded,\" \"I don't want to be recorded,\" \"No\" when asked for recording consent, or similar refusal of recording. This applies even if the customer also complains about other issues during the call.\nEdge cases: RCR takes PRIORITY over CPR (Complaint). If a customer refuses recording consent AND also complains about practices, the recording refusal is the primary classification \u2014 use RCR, not CPR. The complaint is secondary to the compliance-critical consent refusal.\nFew-shots: Agent says \"This call is being recorded\" and customer says \"I don't want to be recorded\" \u2192 RCR. Customer says \"No\" when asked for recording consent \u2192 RCR.\n\n\n- `NCV`: Description: Not Convenient - Customer confirmed their identity but indicated current time is inconvenient for financial discussion; no callback timeframe agreed.\nUse when: Customer explicitly says \"now is not a good time,\" \"I can't talk,\" \"I'm busy,\" \"I have to go,\" \"Let's do this later.\" Customer abruptly disengages after confirming identity due to circumstantial factors.\nEdge cases: Identity verified BUT user then disengages due to circumstances \u2192 NCV (not IDV). No specific alternative contact time needed for NCV. Distinguish from CAB: NCV has no agreed future callback; CAB requires a confirmed outbound callback with specific timeframe. If customer says they're busy but STILL engages in conversation (e.g., \"I have a minute, go ahead\"), the call is convenient enough \u2014 do NOT use NCV.\nFew-shots: Customer says \"I'm at work, I can't talk right now\" and hangs up \u2192 NCV. Customer says \"Now is not a good time\" without specifying when to call back \u2192 NCV. Customer says \"I'm busy but go ahead\" and continues talking \u2192 NOT NCV.\n\n\n- `CAB`: Description: Callback Requested - The ACCOUNT HOLDER (or someone confirmed/claimed as the account holder) explicitly requests or agrees to a future outbound callback and the callback arrangement is the clear final disposition of the call.\nUse when: The account holder (confirmed or claimed) requests or agrees to be called back at a specific future time. A \"reasonably specific\" window includes \"tomorrow,\" \"Monday,\" \"next week,\" \"in a couple of weeks,\" \"anytime tomorrow,\" provided the assistant acknowledges and confirms. A timeframe tied to a financial event (e.g., \"call me when I get my check\" + \"in two weeks\") is valid. CAB strictly means scheduling an OUTBOUND call from the agent to the account holder.\nEdge cases: CRITICAL PREREQUISITE \u2014 CAB only applies when the ACCOUNT HOLDER themselves requests a callback. If a THIRD PARTY (someone who is NOT the account holder \u2014 e.g., a spouse, family member, roommate, or unknown person) provides a callback time for reaching the account holder, classify as TPC (Third-Party Contact), NOT CAB. The key distinction: TPC = third party provides info to help reach the account holder; CAB = the account holder schedules their own callback. MANDATORY OVERRIDE \u2014 CAB takes absolute precedence over HCH, RTP, and failed negotiations. If assistant says \"I will call you back on [Timeframe]\" and user agrees, STOP evaluating for Hardship. Once callback is confirmed, it remains the disposition regardless of subsequent administrative turns. Do NOT use CAB for vague statements like \"call me later\" or \"whenever\" where NO timeframe is established.\nFew-shots: Account holder says \"call me back in 2 weeks when I get paid,\" agent confirms \u2192 CAB. Third party says \"She's not here, call back after 7:30\" \u2192 TPC (not CAB). Wife says \"He's not available, try later\" \u2192 TPC (not CAB). Customer mentions job loss but schedules own callback \u2192 CAB (not HCH).\n\n\n- `WCR`: Description: Written Communication Only Requested - Customer requested all future communications be conducted in writing only (mail/email), with no further phone calls.\nUse when: Customer directs phone contact to cease and specifies an alternative written channel. This applies even if prompted by frustration with call frequency, provided the customer specifies writing as the preferred method.\nEdge cases: Distinguish from DNC \u2014 WCR allows written contact; DNC refuses all phone contact but doesn't specify a preference for writing. Distinguish from CDS \u2014 CDS stops ALL communication; WCR redirects to written methods. Distinguish from CPR \u2014 WCR requires a specific demand to cease phone contact in favor of writing only.\nFew-shots: Customer says \"Don't call me, just send everything by mail\" \u2192 WCR. Customer says \"I only want emails, no more phone calls\" \u2192 WCR. Customer says \"Stop calling\" without specifying written preference \u2192 DNC (not WCR).\n\n\n- `CDS`: Description: Cease and Desist - The VERIFIED account holder (IDV passed: name confirmed AND DOB or SSN matched) has explicitly requested complete cessation of ALL communication methods regarding this account, including calls, emails, and texts.\nUse when: ALL THREE conditions are met simultaneously: (1) IDV passed \u2014 caller confirmed name AND DOB or SSN was verified, (2) caller is confirmed as the account holder (not a 3rd party, not a wrong number, not a business), AND (3) caller explicitly requests cessation of ALL communication methods using phrases like \"stop all communication,\" \"cease all contact,\" \"cease and desist,\" or \"remove me from everything.\"\nEdge cases: CRITICAL \u2014 IDV MUST PASS before CDS can apply. If IDV was not completed, failed (DOB denied or refused), or the caller refused to verify \u2014 classify as DNC (not CDS), regardless of how broadly the caller phrases their request. \"Stop all communication\" from an unverified caller = DNC, not CDS. CRITICAL \u2014 Reflection variable `rpc = unknown` means the caller's identity was NOT confirmed \u2014 CDS cannot apply when rpc is unknown. Even if `exc_comms = cease_all` and `exc_comms_confirmed = confirmed`, if rpc is unknown or IDV states (verify_dob, verify_ssn) are absent from list_current_state \u2192 use DNC, NOT CDS. The exc_comms variable records the scope of the request but does NOT confirm identity. CRITICAL \u2014 `third_party = no` does NOT mean the caller is the verified account holder. It only means no third-party pattern was detected. The caller must still pass IDV (rpc must NOT be unknown) for CDS to apply. `third_party = no` + `rpc = unknown` = unidentified caller \u2192 DNC, not CDS. CRITICAL \u2014 If the caller is a confirmed wrong party (said \"This is not the right person,\" denied being the named person, used 3rd-person pronouns, said \"nobody here received a call\") \u2014 classify as WRN (not CDS), even if they say \"restrict all communication\" or use legal cease-and-desist language. Scope language is evaluated ONLY after both identity and IDV gates pass. Distinct from DNC (phone-only stop, no IDV required) and WRN (wrong party, number removed only).\nFew-shots: Wrong party (DOB mismatch, said \"This is not the right person\") says \"Restrict all communication\" \u2192 WRN (not CDS \u2014 wrong party gate fires first). Inbound caller skips IDV, says \"Stop all communication\" \u2192 DNC (not CDS \u2014 IDV not completed). Caller confirms name but DOB denied \u2192 DNC (not CDS \u2014 IDV failed). Verified account holder (name + DOB confirmed) says \"Cease all contact, phone email everything\" \u2192 CDS. Caller who identifies as a business says \"I don't wanna be contacted at all\" \u2192 WRN (not CDS). CRITICAL NEGATIVE EXAMPLE \u2014 Inbound caller says \"Stop calling me\" then \"All communication\" then \"Yes\" (exc_comms=cease_all, exc_comms_confirmed=confirmed, third_party=no) BUT rpc=unknown and list_current_state shows only inbound_opening \u2192 exc_cease_comms with NO verify_dob or verify_ssn states \u2192 DNC (NOT CDS). The absence of IDV states in list_current_state means identity was never verified \u2014 exc_comms_confirmed only records that the caller confirmed their request, NOT that their identity was confirmed.\n\n\n- `CPR`: Description: Complaint Received - Customer expressed dissatisfaction, frustration, or concern regarding their account, collection practices, communication methods, or service experience, whether stated formally or implied through behavior. This includes complaints about confusing or unhelpful notifications (SMS, email, letters), annoyance with automated systems, or dissatisfaction with how they were contacted.\nUse when: Customer is unhappy with lack of notification details, expresses annoyance with SMS/text/email content (e.g., \"The text didn\u2019t say who this was,\" \"I didn\u2019t click the link because it looked like spam\"), rejects provided responses as unhelpful, repeatedly demands a live agent when unavailable, or persistently questions the assistant\u2019s inability to help. Key indicator: dissatisfaction with communication quality or practices WITHOUT disputing the debt itself.\nEdge cases: CRITICAL DISTINCTION FROM DIS \u2014 Complaints about HOW the customer was contacted (confusing texts, unclear notifications, spam-like messages) are CPR, NOT DIS. A customer calling to find out who texted them and expressing frustration about unclear communications is making a complaint about contact quality, not disputing the debt. DIS requires an explicit challenge to the debt\u2019s validity, accuracy, or legitimacy. If the customer expresses willingness to pay or asks for payment details while complaining about communication, this reinforces CPR over DIS. Also distinct from HCH: a customer who is frustrated about communications but not describing financial hardship should be CPR, not HCH.\nFew-shots: Customer says \"I didn\u2019t know who was texting me, the message didn\u2019t include any details\" and asks for payment address \u2192 CPR (not DIS). Customer says \"I wasn\u2019t clicking links because of scams\" but wants to pay \u2192 CPR. Customer repeatedly asks for a live agent and expresses frustration \u2192 CPR.\n\n\n- `HCH`: Description: Hardship Concern - ONLY for LONG-TERM, severe hardships where the consumer sees NO ability to resolve the account in the foreseeable future. HCH means the consumer has NO path forward \u2014 not just \"broke right now.\" IMPORTANT: Do NOT include HCH in your call_code_list if (a) a callback is arranged, OR (b) the customer expresses any willingness to pay in the future. If either condition is true, HCH does not apply at all \u2014 exclude it entirely from your output.\nUse when: ALL conditions must be true: (1) Customer describes a LONG-TERM hardship with no foreseeable end \u2014 permanent job loss, long-term disability, ongoing serious medical condition, homelessness, or chronic financial inability; (2) The customer explicitly conveys they see NO way to pay now or in the near future AND shows no willingness to pay later; (3) NO callback or follow-up arrangement exists in the conversation; (4) The hardship is substantively discussed (not just a passing mention). If ANY of these conditions is false, do NOT include HCH in your call_code_list.\nEdge cases: SHORT-TERM \u2260 HCH. \"I'm broke right now,\" \"I can't pay today,\" \"I don't have a credit card,\" \"I'm going through a separation\" are SHORT-TERM situational difficulties, NOT long-term hardship \u2014 do NOT include HCH. Customer says \"I'll pay when I get a chance\" or \"when things improve\" = willing to pay = NOT HCH \u2014 exclude HCH entirely. If ANY callback is arranged (reflection variable exc_cb_consent=yes, or agent says \"I'll call you back,\" or customer says \"call me back in X\"), completely exclude HCH from your call_code_list \u2014 output CAB instead. Even if the customer describes extreme financial difficulty, if they show ANY willingness to engage later or ANY callback is set, HCH does not belong in the list at all. A brief mention of difficulty (e.g., \"facing difficulties,\" \"got arrested,\" \"family issues\") without substantive long-term hardship discussion \u2192 use IDV (if verified), not HCH.\nFew-shots: Customer describes permanent disability, no income, no prospect of recovery, no callback \u2192 HCH. Customer says \"I'm broke currently\" + callback in 2 weeks \u2192 exclude HCH, use CAB. Customer says \"I can't pay today but I'll pay when I can\" \u2192 exclude HCH (willingness to pay = short-term). Customer explains separation, agrees to callback \u2192 exclude HCH, use CAB. Customer says \"I have no job, no income, no way to pay, and I don't see that changing\" with no callback \u2192 HCH.\n\n\n- `PPA`: Description: Payment Plan Agreed - Customer agreed to a structured payment plan with specific terms (amounts, frequency, and duration) for resolving the debt. Also applies when the customer agreed to pay, the DTMF payment flow was initiated but failed, and the call ended BEFORE a transfer to a live agent was triggered.\nUse when: Customer formally accepts a structured payment arrangement with defined payment amounts and schedule. Customer mentions a payment made within the last 14 days via any channel, providing payment date and amount. Also use when the customer agreed to pay, the system initiated DTMF payment but it failed (e.g., PIN authentication failed, payment instrument retrieval failed), and the call ended/hung up before the system could trigger a transfer to a live agent. The payment was attempted but failed, and no transfer followed.\nEdge cases: Special case \u2014 customer unable to respond at the time and requests later contact \u2192 same PPA classification applies. Requires clear, focused confirmation of payment terms \u2014 casual \"yeah\" or \"okay\" as filler while distracted does NOT qualify. CRITICAL DISTINCTION \u2014 PPA applies when DTMF payment failed AND call ended before transfer was triggered. If transfer WAS triggered \u2192 use TSR (connected) or WFR (busy) instead. If DTMF failed and no transfer and no hang-up \u2192 use FTP.\nFew-shots: Customer agrees to $50/month for 6 months and gets transferred to payment \u2192 PPA. Customer says \"I already paid $100 last week via check\" with details \u2192 PPA. Customer agrees to pay full $500, enters DTMF, PIN fails, call hangs up before transfer is triggered \u2192 PPA (not PPIF, not FTP). Customer says \"yeah, sure\" while talking about unrelated topics \u2192 NOT PPA.\n\n\n- `PPIF`: Description: Promise to Pay in Full - Customer verbally committed to paying 100% of the full outstanding balance in a single payment, with no discounts or settlement reductions. IMPORTANT: Do NOT use PPIF if the call ends with a transfer to a live agent \u2014 when a transfer occurs after a payment failure, the final disposition is TSR, not PPIF.\nUse when: Customer confirms the full amount due and agrees to a specific payment date or time (e.g., \"I'll take care of it later today,\" \"Call me back at noon to get my card\"). Use even if a callback is required to collect payment details or finalize the transaction. PPIF requires that NO transfer to a live agent occurs after the payment commitment.\nEdge cases: CRITICAL \u2014 Do NOT classify as CAB when a clear commitment to pay full balance is made. If the customer commits to paying the full balance AND arranges a callback to provide card details, this is ALWAYS PPIF, never CAB. The payment commitment takes precedence over the callback arrangement. Distinguish from PSIF \u2014 PPIF = 100% original balance; PSIF = discounted/reduced settlement amount. TRANSFER EXCEPTION \u2014 If the customer agreed to pay BUT the system fails to process payment (e.g., \"The system can not retrieve your payment information\") AND the AI agent then transfers to a live agent (\"Let me connect you with a live agent\"), classify as TSR, NOT PPIF. The transfer overrides the payment commitment. Distinguish from PPA \u2014 if the DTMF payment flow was initiated but failed, and the call ended before a transfer to a live agent was triggered, classify as PPA (not PPIF).\nFew-shots: Customer says \"I'll pay the full $393.92 tomorrow\" \u2192 PPIF. Customer says \"Call me back at noon, I'll have my card ready to pay it all\" \u2192 PPIF (not CAB). Customer agrees to pay $248 settlement instead of $352 full balance \u2192 PSIF (not PPIF). Customer agrees to pay full $2112.50, provides PIN 123456, system fails to retrieve payment info, agent says \"Let me connect you with a live agent\" \u2192 TSR (NOT PPIF \u2014 transfer overrides payment commitment). Customer enters DTMF payment flow, payment fails, call hangs up before transfer is triggered \u2192 PPA (not PPIF).\n\n\n- `PSIF`: Description: Promise to Settle in Full - Customer agreed to a discounted settlement offer that will fully resolve the account for less than the original outstanding balance.\nUse when: Customer accepts a reduced settlement amount with a specific payment timeline that fully settles the account. No further payments are required after the agreed discounted amount is paid.\nEdge cases: Distinguish from PPIF \u2014 PSIF = reduced/discounted amount; PPIF = 100% original balance. Full settlement must be confirmed \u2014 account fully resolved with no remaining balance.\nFew-shots: Customer agrees to pay $248 instead of $352.90 full balance to settle \u2192 PSIF. Customer agrees to pay full $352.90 \u2192 PPIF (not PSIF).\n\n\n- `WRN`: Description: Wrong Number - The person who answered or called is confirmed NOT the account holder: they explicitly denied being the intended recipient, identified as a 3rd party or business, stated wrong number, used 3rd-person pronouns about the account holder, denied the DOB/identity while expressing confusion (\"I have no idea what you're talking about\"), or signaled the number is not associated with the account holder. Only the phone number is removed \u2014 no account-level restriction.\nUse when: ANY of these wrong-party signals are present: (a) explicit denial \u2014 \"This is not the right person,\" \"No, I'm not [name],\" \"You have the wrong number,\" (b) 3rd-party pronoun \u2014 \"Take HIM off your list,\" \"She doesn't want contact,\" (c) business identification \u2014 \"This is a business,\" (d) nobody-here signal \u2014 \"Nobody by that name lives here,\" \"There's no [name] here\" \u2014 explicit statement that the named person does not exist at this number, (e) confusion + DOB denial \u2014 caller says \"I have no idea what you're talking about\" after DOB is read (suggests wrong number, not just IDV failure), (f) caller explicitly says \"No\" when asked \"Is this [name]?\". An explicit denial of identity or identification as a wrong party is sufficient regardless of any additional requests (even \"stop all communication\" or \"restrict all communication\" \u2014 scope is irrelevant when caller is confirmed not the account holder). NOTE: ambiguous phrases like \"nobody ever received a call from you\" or \"take me off your list\" without an explicit identity denial \u2192 prefer DNC over WRN (no confirmed wrong-party signal).\nEdge cases: CRITICAL PRIORITY \u2014 WRN TAKES PRIORITY OVER DNC when an explicit wrong-party signal is present. If the caller says \"This is not the right person,\" \"No\" to \"Is this [name]?\", \"wrong number,\" or any equivalent explicit denial \u2014 classify as WRN even if IDV also failed or the caller then requests stop-contact. The wrong-party signal overrides the unverified-identity DNC pattern. CRITICAL \u2014 When a wrong party says \"Restrict all communication,\" \"Stop all contact,\" or uses legal cease-and-desist language \u2014 this is still WRN, NOT CDS and NOT DNC. A confirmed wrong party CANNOT authorize account-level restrictions regardless of what they request. The identity gate fires before the scope gate. CRITICAL \u2014 When a caller denies the DOB AND expresses confusion (\"I have no idea what you're talking about\"), treat as wrong-party \u2192 WRN (not IDF or DNC), because the denial signals they are not the account holder. Distinct from DNC (unknown-identity inbound caller with NO explicit wrong-party signal \u2014 prefer DNC only when there is no clear evidence the caller is not the account holder).\nFew-shots: Outbound call, DOB mismatch, caller says \"This is not the right person\" then \"Restrict all communication\" \u2192 WRN (not CDS \u2014 wrong party gate fires first, scope irrelevant). Outbound, AI asks \"Is this [name]?\" \u2014 caller says \"No. Don't call again.\" \u2192 WRN. Caller confirms name but says \"That DOB is totally incorrect, I have no idea what you're talking about. Leave me alone.\" \u2192 WRN (complete confusion + DOB denial signals wrong party, not failed IDV). Inbound caller says \"Take my number off the list, this is a business\" \u2192 WRN. Caller says \"You have the wrong number\" \u2192 WRN. Caller says \"Nobody by that name lives here\" \u2192 WRN.\n\n\n- `TPC`: Description: Third-Party Contact - Person other than the account holder provided information or context to help reach the intended recipient, including callback times or availability windows.\nUse when: Third party acknowledges knowing the account holder. Third party provides alternative phone number, address, availability time, or any contextual detail about the recipient. Third party offers to relay messages or suggests future contact times. Third party provides a callback time or availability window for reaching the account holder (e.g., \"call back after 7:30,\" \"she'll be home in the morning\").\nEdge cases: Distinguish from WRN \u2014 TPC requires explicit evidence of a relationship (acknowledging knowing the person, providing info about them). Even vague or incomplete info that aids in locating the recipient qualifies as TPC. No relationship evidence \u2192 WRN. CRITICAL DISTINCTION FROM CAB \u2014 If a third party (not the account holder) provides a callback time for reaching the account holder, this is TPC, NOT CAB. CAB requires the account holder themselves to schedule a callback. A third party arranging a callback time is providing information to reach the recipient, which is the core function of TPC.\nFew-shots: Person says \"He's not here, try calling after 5pm\" \u2192 TPC (not CAB). Wife says \"He's not available, call back later\" \u2192 TPC (not CAB). Person says \"That's my son, I'll tell him you called\" \u2192 TPC. Sister calls and agent arranges callback for 9am \u2192 TPC (not CAB). Person says \"I don't know that person, wrong number\" \u2192 WRN (not TPC).\n\n\n- `FRA`: Description: Fraud Reported - Customer claims the account was opened fraudulently, through identity theft, or without their knowledge or consent.\nUse when: Customer explicitly alleges fraud or identity theft. Customer categorically denies the account's existence or their responsibility for creating it (even without using the word \"fraud\").\nEdge cases: Distinguish from DIS \u2014 FRA = customer denies they ever created/owned the account; DIS = disputes accuracy or balance of a recognized account. Categorical denial of account ownership \u2192 FRA (not DIS). Requires immediate escalation for fraud investigation.\nFew-shots: Customer says \"I never opened that account, someone stole my identity\" \u2192 FRA. Customer says \"I have no connection to this debt whatsoever\" \u2192 FRA. Customer says \"The balance is wrong, I already paid some\" \u2192 DIS (not FRA).\n\n\n- `DNC`: Description: Do Not Call - The caller (NOT a business or clearly wrong number) has requested to be removed from phone contact lists or to cease calls to the specific phone number. Identity verification is NOT required for DNC \u2014 an angry caller demanding \"stop calling\" is sufficient.\nUse when: Caller says \"stop calling,\" \"don't call this number,\" \"put me on your do not call list.\" Formal or informal/frustrated language qualifies equally. DNC applies even if the caller refuses to confirm their name \u2014 the explicit demand to stop phone calls is the primary signal. If the assistant interprets the statement as an opt-out request, this supports DNC. Applies specifically to phone contact at this number \u2014 differs from CDS (all communication).\nEdge cases: DNC overrides NVR and HUA when the caller explicitly demands to stop calls. If the caller refuses to verify identity AND demands \"stop calling,\" classify as DNC (not NVR). CRITICAL \u2014 When rpc = unknown (caller identity not confirmed) AND exc_comms = cease_all, classify as DNC (not CDS). An unidentified caller requesting \"all communication\" stopped cannot authorize account-level CDS \u2014 only a verified account holder can. Even if exc_comms_confirmed = confirmed, if rpc is unknown \u2192 DNC. CRITICAL \u2014 An unidentified inbound caller saying \"Stop calling me\" or \"Take me off your list. All.\" with no IDV \u2192 DNC (not CDS). The scope of the request (this number vs all communication) is irrelevant when the caller is unidentified \u2014 DNC applies to the number regardless. EXCEPTION: If the caller identifies as a BUSINESS or explicitly denies being the account holder AND says the person doesn't live there (e.g., \"There's no [Name] here, stop calling\"), classify as WRN \u2014 the number is simply wrong. DNC is for callers who COULD be the account holder (didn't deny it) but refuse to engage and want calls stopped.\nFew-shots: Caller says \"I don't give a damn. Stop calling my damn phone\" without confirming name \u2192 DNC (not NVR). Caller says \"Don't call this damn phone again\" \u2192 DNC. CRITICAL PATTERN \u2014 Inbound caller says \"Stop calling me\" \u2192 \"All communication\" \u2192 \"Yes\" with rpc=unknown, exc_comms=cease_all, exc_comms_confirmed=confirmed, third_party=no, AND list_current_state=[inbound_opening, exc_cease_comms, exc_cease_comms, ...] (no verify_dob or verify_ssn states present) \u2192 DNC (NOT CDS). Reasoning: list_current_state shows the call went from opening directly to communication restriction \u2014 IDV was never attempted. exc_comms_confirmed=confirmed means the caller confirmed their STOP REQUEST, not their identity. rpc=unknown confirms identity was never established. Despite third_party=no, the caller is still unidentified. Inbound caller says \"Nobody ever received a call. Take me off your list. All.\" with no identity denial \u2192 DNC (no confirmed wrong-party signal, identity unknown). Caller says \"This is a business, take my number off the list\" \u2192 WRN (not DNC). Caller says \"There's no Robin here, stop calling\" \u2192 WRN (not DNC \u2014 wrong number). Verified account holder (IDV passed) says \"Stop all communication\" \u2192 CDS (not DNC \u2014 IDV passed and scope is all communication).\n\n\n- `DIS`: Description: Debt Disputed - The customer explicitly challenged the accuracy, validity, or legitimacy of the debt itself. This includes explicitly stating the debt is not theirs, the amount is wrong, previous payments are not reflected, or asserting the debt is void, canceled, settled, or legally discharged. This code also applies if the customer challenges the creditor's right to collect or the legality of the debt transfer (e.g., \"sold without consent\"). DIS takes precedence over CAB if the customer disputes the debt even if a callback is scheduled.\nUse when: Customer explicitly states the debt is not theirs, the amount is wrong, previous payments are not reflected, or asserts the debt is void/canceled/settled. Also applies when customer claims not to recognize the amount or implies the balance is incorrect (e.g., \"I wasn't aware it was that much\"). If a customer requests to stop contact specifically because they dispute the debt (e.g., \"Stop calling, I don't owe this\"), classify as DIS.\nEdge cases: CRITICAL \u2014 Do NOT classify as DIS if the customer is merely complaining about HOW they were contacted (confusing texts, unclear SMS, spam-looking links). Asking for details because a notification lacked specifics is a communication complaint (CPR), NOT a dispute. A dispute must be an explicit challenge to the DEBT ITSELF \u2014 its existence, amount, validity, or legitimacy. Also do NOT classify as DIS for \"sticker shock\" (e.g., \"Wow, that's a lot\") without questioning accuracy. Do NOT apply if customer made a payment within the last 14 days. If the customer expresses willingness to pay (e.g., \"I was gonna pay\") while complaining about notifications, this is strong evidence AGAINST DIS \u2014 use CPR instead.\nFew-shots: Customer says \"I don't owe this money\" \u2192 DIS. Customer says \"The text didn't say who this was for\" but asks for payment address \u2192 CPR (not DIS). Customer says \"I wasn't aware it was that much\" \u2192 DIS.\n\n\n- `CSM`: Description: SCRA Coverage Reported - Customer verified active military service status invoking Servicemembers Civil Relief Act protections.\nUse when: Customer provides details about military service (branch, status, anticipated service period) invoking SCRA protections. SCRA protections include interest rate caps, foreclosure prevention, and other accommodations that must be immediately applied.\nEdge cases: N/A\nFew-shots: Customer says \"I'm active duty military, you need to apply SCRA protections\" \u2192 CSM. Customer says \"I'm deployed overseas with the Army\" \u2192 CSM.\n\n\n- `PRS`: Description: In Prison - Customer or third party confirmed that the account holder is CURRENTLY incarcerated in a correctional facility.\nUse when: Incarceration in a correctional facility is confirmed as a CURRENT, ongoing status. Specific facility name or release date not required.\nEdge cases: PRS takes precedence over financial codes if both are mentioned. CRITICAL \u2014 PRS requires CURRENT incarceration. Past-tense references to arrest or jail (e.g., \"I got arrested\" as an explanation for default circumstances) do NOT qualify if the customer is clearly not currently incarcerated (e.g., they are on the phone freely discussing the account). Use the surrounding context to determine if the arrest is current or historical.\nFew-shots: Customer says \"I'm currently in jail\" \u2192 PRS. Third party says \"He's incarcerated at the county jail right now\" \u2192 PRS. Customer says \"I got arrested\" as an explanation for why they defaulted, but is freely conversing on the phone \u2192 NOT PRS (use IDV or appropriate code based on conversation outcome).\n\n\n- `LGH`: Description: Legal Guardian Handling - A legally authorized guardian is managing the account holder's affairs due to the account holder's incapacity or death.\nUse when: Guardian provides verifiable information about their legal relationship and authority to discuss the account. Third party presents power of attorney (POA) or demonstrates legal authority over the account. Communication must be directed exclusively to this authorized representative.\nEdge cases: Distinguish from ATY \u2014 use LGH for general guardian/POA scenarios; use ATY when a specific attorney or legal counsel is mentioned. Distinguish from TPC \u2014 LGH requires demonstrated legal authority (guardian, POA); TPC is any third party providing info without legal standing.\nFew-shots: Third party calls with power of attorney, negotiates settlement on account holder's behalf \u2192 LGH. \"She's deceased... her daughter has financial power of attorney\" \u2192 LGH. Agent confirms caller has power of attorney over incapacitated account holder \u2192 LGH.\n\n\n- `ATY`: Description: Attorney Representation - Customer stated they have retained or are seeking legal counsel, or legal representation is indicated through any signal in the conversation.\nUse when: Customer mentions \"my attorney,\" \"I'm getting a lawyer,\" \"my attorney has contacted you,\" or references a POA/legal authority. Agent prompts caller for proof of POA or legal representation documentation. Multiple or repeated references to an attorney, even if brief or fragmented. Consumer indicates attorney involvement even indirectly or amidst emotional distress.\nEdge cases: ATY takes priority over ALL other codes including RTP. Fragmented speech about attorney (\"her attorney,\" even amidst distress) still qualifies \u2014 scan the ENTIRE conversation for any mention of \"attorney,\" \"lawyer,\" or \"legal counsel.\" Agent's prompt for POA is a secondary signal even if caller gives unclear response. Distinguish from LGH \u2014 ATY = specific attorney/legal counsel mentioned; LGH = general guardian without specific attorney reference. CRITICAL DISTINCTION FROM DSA \u2014 If the customer uses the word \"lawyer\" or \"attorney\" ANYWHERE in their description, classify as ATY even if they also mention debt consolidation/settlement context. \"Debt consolidation LAWYER\" = ATY (the word \"lawyer\" is the decisive signal). Only use DSA if the customer names a financial program/agency WITHOUT any mention of a lawyer or attorney.\nFew-shots: Customer says \"Talk to my lawyer\" \u2192 ATY. Customer says \"I turned my account over to a debt consolidate lawyer\" \u2192 ATY (word \"lawyer\" overrides \"debt consolidate\"). Fragmented speech \"on her journey... her attorney\" \u2192 ATY. Customer says \"I'm working with National Debt Relief\" (no mention of lawyer) \u2192 DSA (not ATY).\n\n\n- `BKP`: Description: Bankruptcy Pending - Customer reported current bankruptcy proceedings or intent to file bankruptcy that would include this account.\nUse when: Customer provides specific bankruptcy details (case number, chapter, filing date) or states intent to file. Triggers immediate cessation of collection activities per automatic stay provisions.\nEdge cases: Requires verification with bankruptcy court records. Intent to file is sufficient even without specific details.\nFew-shots: Customer says \"I filed Chapter 7 last month, case number 12345\" \u2192 BKP. Customer says \"I'm about to file for bankruptcy\" \u2192 BKP.\n\n\n- `NNP`: Description: Negotiated No Payment - Customer passed identity verification, at least one specific payment option was offered by the agent, customer clearly declined the offered option(s) without using explicit refusal language, expressed no hardship or dispute, and the call ended without a payment commitment.\nUse when: ALL of the following must be true: (1) Customer verified identity successfully, (2) the agent offered at least one specific payment amount or plan, (3) customer clearly declined or said \"No\" to the offered amount(s), (4) customer did NOT use explicit refusal language (e.g., \"I won't pay,\" \"I refuse to pay,\" \"I will never pay\"), (5) no hardship or financial difficulty was expressed, (6) no dispute was raised about the debt, and (7) the call ended with no payment arrangement.\nEdge cases: CRITICAL DISTINCTION FROM IDV \u2014 If the customer gave non-committal responses (\"possibly,\" \"maybe,\" \"I'm not sure,\" \"I'll think about it\") without clearly declining, use IDV (not NNP). If the customer declined to share personal circumstances or explain default reasons but no specific payment amounts were offered and declined, use IDV (not NNP). CRITICAL \u2014 NNP requires the customer's explicit decline to be PRESENT AND VISIBLE in the conversation. If the conversation ends after a payment offer with no customer response shown, the customer did NOT decline \u2014 use IDV (not NNP). Do NOT infer a decline from a truncated or incomplete conversation. NNP requires a CLEAR DECLINE of at least one specific offer \u2014 vague, ambiguous, non-committal responses, or absent responses do NOT qualify. CRITICAL DISTINCTION FROM RTP \u2014 RTP requires explicit, unambiguous refusal language (\"I refuse,\" \"I won't pay,\" \"I will never pay\"). Simply saying \"No\" to offered amounts is NNP, not RTP. CRITICAL DISTINCTION FROM HCH \u2014 If the customer mentions any hardship language (job loss, medical issues, financial difficulty, inability to afford), classify as HCH, not NNP. CRITICAL DISTINCTION FROM DIS \u2014 If the customer challenges the debt's validity, existence, or amount, classify as DIS, not NNP. If mixed signals appear (hardship AND refusal together), assign HCH.\nFew-shots: Agent offers $76/month, customer says \"No,\" agent offers $61/month, customer deflects and call ends with no commitment \u2192 NNP. Agent offers $66/month, customer clearly says \"No\" to that offer and call ends \u2192 NNP (customer explicitly responded to the payment offer). Customer declines all payment options saying \"I just can't do those amounts right now\" with no hardship or refusal language \u2192 NNP. Customer verified, declines to share circumstances of default, no payment amounts offered \u2192 IDV (not NNP \u2014 no payment negotiation occurred). Customer says \"Possibly\" or \"Maybe\" to a payment offer without declining \u2192 IDV (not NNP \u2014 non-committal is not a decline). Customer verified, payment amount mentioned but conversation ends before customer clearly declines \u2192 IDV (not NNP \u2014 no clear decline visible). Agent asks about default circumstances, customer says \"No\" (declining to share circumstances), agent then offers monthly payment amount, conversation ends with no further customer response \u2192 IDV (not NNP \u2014 the \"No\" was about sharing circumstances, not a response to the payment offer; no customer response to the offer is shown). Customer says \"I refuse to pay this\" \u2192 RTP (not NNP \u2014 explicit refusal). Customer says \"I lost my job, I can't pay\" \u2192 HCH (not NNP \u2014 hardship language present).\n\n\n- `DSA`: Description: Debt Settlement Agreement - Customer indicates they are working with a third-party debt settlement, consolidation, or relief program to manage their debt.\nUse when: Customer explicitly or implicitly directs agent to contact a named debt relief/settlement program (Beyond Finance, National Debt Relief, Debt Solutions, etc.). Customer states \"a company is handling that for me\" or \"check with my debt negotiator.\" Consumer or representative claims they are working with a program for debt/credit settlement, consolidation, relief, management, or financial solutions.\nEdge cases: Distinguish from ATY \u2014 DSA = financial relief/settlement program; ATY = law office or attorney. If third party is not explicitly identified as a law office, assume it is a debt settlement service. Directing agent to contact a named debt relief agency is sufficient signal regardless of explicit confirmation. Do not let identity verification attempts or other conversational elements distract from settlement agency signals. Do not let the assistant\u2019s mention of \"attorney\" trigger ATY if the consumer only identifies a financial program.\nFew-shots: Customer says \"You need to call National Debt Relief, they\u2019re handling my account\" \u2192 DSA. Customer says \"A company is managing my debts\" \u2192 DSA. Customer says \"Talk to my lawyer about this\" \u2192 ATY (not DSA).\n\n\n\n\n\n## Reflection Variable Descriptions\n```\n- `mini_miranda`: <Determine whether _assistant has delivered the mini-Miranda statement in full - \"This is an attempt to collect a debt by a debt collector. Any information obtained will be used for that purpose.\" ONLY consider whether or not _assistant has completed this statement; it does not matter what _user said.>\n  + `yes` : This mini-Miranda statement has been delivered in full by _assistant without any interruption by _user, \"This is an attempt to collect a debt by a debt collector. Any information obtained will be used for that purpose.\"\n  + `no` : This statement has either not been delivered, or interrupted or otherwise only partially delivered.\n- `willing_to_pay`:\n  + `yes` : The consumer clearly expresses **intent** or **willingness** to resolve the debt. This includes any statement or request to **make a payment**, **arrange a payment plan** (e.g., \"I want to pay,\" \"Can I make a payment?,\" \"Let's set up a payment plan,\" or any opening statement inquiring about resolution options).\n  + `no` : The consumer does not express any intent or willingness to resolve the debt.\n  + `settlement` : The consumer explicitly discusses a **settlement** offer or agreement, indicating their intent to continue with settlement amounts and terms. (e.g. \"I agree to settle, \", \"Some settlement or something.\")\n- `promise`: <Captures _user's commitment to pay, refusal to pay, or an unresolved stance. A clear refusal (`no`) or firm commitment (`yes`) made during the conversation overrides any prior ambiguity or hedging.>\n  + `yes` : _user has clearly agreed to a specific payment plan or resolution, or has confirmed a past payment was made. For a promise to be `yes`, _user must first demonstrate awareness of the debt being discussed.\n    -- A `yes` is indicated when _user agrees to the financial terms of a proposed plan (e.g., \"Yes, that's okay,\" \"That works for me\"). This applies even if they subsequently request a procedural step like a transfer to an agent to finalize the transaction.\n    -- This includes confirmations of past payments (e.g., \"I already sent it,\" \"I mailed the check yesterday\"), as they represent a firm commitment to the debt's resolution.\n    -- A user's counter-proposal or conditional offer is only considered a `yes` once _assistant explicitly accepts or confirms the new terms.\n  + `no` : _user has explicitly stated a definitive inability or unwillingness to make **any** payment towards the debt, or has definitively rejected the obligation entirely. This requires that _user understands the context of the debt being discussed.\n    -- This applies only to unambiguous, complete rejections of payment (e.g., \"I can't pay anything,\" \"I will not pay,\" \"I'm not working and have no income\").\n    -- Rejecting a specific plan proposed by _assistant while offering an alternative or continuing to negotiate is **not** a `no`; this is considered an unresolved negotiation and should be labeled `unknown`. A `no` indicates _user has stopped negotiating and is refusing to pay.\n    -- This does not apply if _user says \"No\" in response to a non-payment, administrative question (e.g., agent: \"Is there anything else?\", user: \"No.\").\n  + `unknown` : _user's intent regarding payment is genuinely ambiguous, conditional and unresolved, or otherwise unclear. This is the default if the strict preconditions for `yes` or `no` are not met.\n    -- **Contextual Confusion:** If _user expresses significant confusion about the caller's identity, the debt's origin, or their obligation (e.g., \"Who are you?\", \"What is this for?\"), their intent is `unknown` until they acknowledge the debt.\n    -- **Unresolved Negotiations:** A promise is `unknown` during an active negotiation where terms have not been mutually agreed upon. This includes:\n      --- _user rejects _assistant's plan but proposes a counter-offer (e.g., a different amount or timeframe).\n      --- The negotiation is deadlocked because _user's offer is below _assistant's stated minimum, but _user has not withdrawn their intent to pay.\n      --- The conversation ends on _user's counter-offer or clarifying question before _assistant can respond.\n    -- **Pre-agreement Agent Request:** The intent is `unknown` if _user requests to speak to _assistant *before* or *instead of* agreeing to proposed financial terms.\n    -- **No Active Obligation:** This category is used when no explicit promise or refusal is made, if the account is already marked as resolved, or if the conversation does not concern _user's direct financial obligation (e.g., _user is not the debtor).\n- `amount` : The total amount of payment in **dollars** that _user clearly and finally commits to pay, expressed as a NUMBER and unit of currency (e.g., '1038 dollars' or '100.42 dollars'). Always use the decimal number, including cents, as a single value with two decimal places if applicable\u2014do **not** express cents as separate terms. For example, return \"650.45 dollars\" instead of \"650 dollars 45 cents.\".\nWhen the assistant proposes an amount that includes cents (e.g., \"six hundred and fifty dollars and forty-five cents\") or a numeric value with cents, the amount variable MUST reflect the full decimal value\u2014e.g., \"650.45 dollars\".\nA commitment is only considered final when _user unambiguously agrees to a specific proposal from _assistant; a _user proposal or counter-offer is not a final commitment until confirmed by both parties. Follow this strict order of priority:\n  1. **Agreed Settlement Amount (Highest Priority):** If _user agrees to a specific **settlement** amount proposed by the assistant, use that settlement amount. This takes highest priority over any other balances or calculations.\n    -- Agreement includes asking about payment terms for the proposed settlement (e.g., \"Can I pay that $1038.55 settlement in three months?\"). This counts as agreement to the total settlement amount.\n    -- Agreement followed by a request to speak with a live agent to finalize details (e.g., \"Yes, I agree to that. But let me talk to an agent.\") is still considered a final commitment to the agreed-upon amount.\n  2. **Agreed Plan to Pay Full Balance:** If no settlement was agreed upon and _user agrees to a payment plan explicitly proposed by _assistant to resolve their \"full balance,\" use the full outstanding balance, `one hundred and fifty-eight dollars and fifty-two cents`. This variable MUST reflect a decimal value (e.g., \"650.45 dollars\") if cents are present. The commitment is to resolve the full balance, even if the installment terms (e.g., \"$190 for 24 months\") calculate to a different total.\n  3. **Calculated Total from an Agreed Plan:** If _user agrees to a payment plan defined by both an installment amount and a duration (e.g., \"Yes, I agree to $100.55 for 12 months\") and the plan is NOT explicitly for a settlement (Rule 1) or the full balance (Rule 2), you MUST calculate the total amount by multiplying the installment by the duration. Use this calculated total as a decimal value if applicable (e.g., 1200.50 dollars).\n  4. **Agreement by Reference:** If _user agrees to a specific amount proposed by the assistant using referential language (e.g., \"I'll pay that amount,\" \"I wanna make the same number for that one\"), use the specific amount mentioned by _assistant, in decimal format if expressed that way, with priority given to Rules 1\u20133.\n  5. **No Final Commitment (Return 'unknown'):** Return 'unknown' if no clear and final commitment to a total amount is made according to the rules above. This is the default if no higher-priority rule applies. This includes:\n    -- **_user Proposals or Counter-offers:** A _user's statement of what they *can* or *want* to pay (e.g., \"I can do $500,\" \"I want to do $200 for 24 months\") is a proposal, NOT a final commitment until the assistant accepts it and _user re-confirms.\n    -- **Contradictory or Conditional Agreement:** An agreement immediately followed by a negation (e.g., \"Yes. No...\") or a condition that cannot be met at the time of the call (e.g., \"Yes, but it has to be next month because my account was tampered with\") voids the commitment.\n    -- **Vague Intent:** Vague promises (e.g., \"I'll pay next week\") are not a commitment to a specific amount.\n    -- **Temporary or \"Keep-in-Touch\" Plans:** An agreement to a short-term, temporary, or partial plan (e.g., \"$50 for 3 months to keep the account current\") is not a commitment to a final total amount.\n    -- **Voided Intent / Rejection:** If a _user states a specific amount, then rejects a subsequent, different proposal, the original amount is voided. If _user rejects all options or withdraws a previous commitment, the commitment is voided. Only the last firmly agreed-upon amount should be used.\n- `first_date` : The specific calendar date (YYYY-MM-DD) when _user expresses a clear and confirmed intention to make their **first** payment, whether it's an initial payment or the first of installments. A \"clear and confirmed intention\" is a direct commitment to *pay on* a specific date, not a promise to call back to arrange a payment or an agreement to an offer with a payment deadline (e.g., 'must be paid by [Date]'). \n  -- The extracted date must always be on or after Today (2026-04-24, which is Friday). The date can be an absolute date (e.g., \"December 15th\") or a relative term (e.g., \"next Monday,\" \"the 30th\"). All relative dates must be calculated as the *next upcoming calendar occurrence* from Today. **Strictly enforce this rule for day-of-week terms:** \"next [Day of Week]\" (e.g., \"next Friday\") must resolve to the single chronologically closest upcoming occurrence of that day. For example, if Today is Tuesday, \"next Friday\" is the Friday of the current week (3 days away), not the Friday of the following week. \n  -- **Strictly enforce futurity for day-of-month terms:** for instance, if Today is the 20th and _user says \"the 15th\" (providing only a day number), the date must resolve to the 15th of the *following* month. This also includes correctly resolving year rollovers for future dates (e.g., 'January 4th' stated in December resolves to January of the *next* calendar year). If _user agrees to pay immediately, they must explicitly state 'today', 'right now', or 'now' to resolve to Today's date (2026-04-24); do not infer immediacy from a general intent to pay (e.g., \"I'm calling to make a payment\") or from agreement to a settlement offer that lacks a specific timing component. \n  -- If the consumer changes their mind or a stated date is unviable, return the *most recent confirmed and viable* payment date. Do not carry over a day of the month from a previously invalidated or past date unless _user explicitly confirms it in their new commitment; for example, if a payment for 'the 15th' is invalidated because it is in the past, and _user then says 'next month', the date is 'unknown' because the day '15th' was not re-confirmed. \n  -- Return 'unknown' if: \n    (1) _user explicitly refuses to pay or denies payment details; \n    (2) _user makes no commitment to a specific calendar date, which includes providing a vague timeframe (e.g., \"sometime next week,\" \"in January,\" \"next month\" without a confirmed day), a general intent lacking a date (e.g., \"I'll make a payment\"), or a commitment to call back to arrange a payment (e.g., \"I will call you back next Friday to start payments\"); \n    (3) _user agrees to an offer with a deadline (e.g., \"must be paid before Dec 13th\") but does not commit to a specific day *for* the transaction; \n    (4) any stated date is unconfirmed, ambiguous, or invalidated. A date is considered ambiguous if _user's intent is unclear due to fragmented sentences (e.g., \"...on the first... pardon?\") or garbled/non-sequitur responses where a number's meaning as a date is not certain (e.g., _user says \"Lease number eleven\" when asked for a date). A date is invalidated if it has already passed (e.g., stating \"November 5th\" when Today is November 13th), contradicts an agreed-upon timeframe, or is mentioned in the past tense (e.g., \"I was paying on the 1st\"). Do not roll invalidated past dates to the next year. \n  -- This variable is ONLY for the first Promise-to-Pay date; do NOT extract other entity types; focus strictly on the initial payment commitment.\n- `months` : the NUMBER of months for installments. \n  -- Use the duration explicitly stated by _user or the inclusive count of months in a confirmed timeline (e.g., \"starting in January and settling in March\" is \"3\"). If _user agrees to, proposes, or counter-offers a specific monthly dollar amount (including saying \"Yes\" to a plan proposed by _assistant, agreeing to \"continue\" an existing plan, or stating an amount like \"One hundred\" in response to a monthly payment discussion) but no specific duration is mentioned, you MUST calculate the value, by dividing the total balance mentioned by _assistant by that monthly amount and round up to the nearest whole number. \n  -- Return \"1\" ONLY for an explicit commitment to pay the full balance or a settlement in a single installment that is specifically scheduled for \"today\", \"now\", \"all at once\", or \"one-time\"; do not return \"1\" for a general expression of intent to pay (e.g., \"I'm calling to make a payment,\" \"I want to settle\") unless a specific timing for a single payment is confirmed. \n  -- Return \"unknown\" if _user agrees to a total settlement amount or expresses a desire to pay but does not specify a timeframe (\"now\", \"today\", \"one-time\") or number of payments, or if _user requests a human representative or ends the call BEFORE any specific amount or duration is agreed upon. If an agreement on a duration or monthly amount is reached, return that value even if _user subsequently requests a human representative, UNLESS the agreement is immediately followed by a contradiction, hedge, or statement of financial hardship that indicates _user cannot actually fulfill the obligation (e.g., \"Yes, but I don't have the money right now\"), in which case return \"unknown\". Also return \"unknown\" for refusals (e.g., \"No\"), even if followed by a vague intent to pay, and for ambiguous phrasing (e.g., \"a payment\", \"same number\"), or vague/conditional promises without a confirmed amount/date (e.g., \"after I get paid\"). A single month or date provided as a start date for a monthly plan does not override the installment calculation. \n  -- For temporary or \"keep-in-touch\" bridge arrangements, return the duration of that specific confirmed schedule even if it does not resolve the full balance.\n- `settlement_2_percentage` : the percentage of settlement as a NUMBER from the conversation that _user clearly stated to pay. If _user rejects to pay or does not respond with the percentage amount, return 'unknown'. If _user changes their mind multiple times, choose the last agreed percentage. If _user refuses to pay or no longer commits to the amount in the latest turns of the conversation, ensure to unset the percentage and return 'unknown'.\n- `review` : A future date or time agreed upon with the user to rediscuss their payment situation, in YYYY-MM-DD format (Today is 2026-04-24, a Friday). This is not a payment date. **Follow this logic hierarchy strictly**: (1) For calculable relative timeframes (e.g., \"in six months,\" \"next week,\" \"two months from now,\" **\"next month\"**), calculate the exact date from today's date, preserving the day of the month. Example: If today is 2025-09-03 and user says \"next month,\" use 2025-10-03. (2) If a time for a same-day callback is agreed upon (e.g., \"call me back after 4 PM\"), use today's date. (3) If **only a bare month name** is given, without a relative modifier like 'next' (e.g., user says just \"August\"), default to the 1st day of that month's next occurrence. Example: If it's 2025-07-24 and user says \"August,\" use 2025-08-01. This rule does not apply to \"next month.\" If no specific review date/time is set, return 'unknown'.\n- `negotiate`: <Reflects _user's current willingness and ability to engage in discussions or actions aimed at resolving their existing payment or debt situation with _assistant in the ongoing conversation.>\n  + `yes` : _user indicates a clear willingness to engage in a discussion or action to resolve the payment within the current conversation. This includes explicitly agreeing to make a payment, or actively negotiating specific terms, amounts, or dates. _user is actively seeking or accepting a path to resolution in the present interaction.\n    -- Rejecting specific offers or stating inability for a particular plan does not negate a `yes` classification if _user continues to explore other options (e.g., \"I can't pay $100, but can you do $50?\", \"Can I settle for a lower amount?\"). The key is sustained engagement in finding an alternative solution within the same conversation.\n    -- User-initiated proposals must be clear and not immediately contradicted by _user upon _assistant's clarification to qualify.\n    -- Requesting to speak with a different agent or supervisor to find a workable payment solution also qualifies as `yes`.\n  + `no` : _user explicitly states an unwillingness or inability to make a payment or discuss payment options at this time, and ceases to explore viable alternatives within the current conversation.\n    -- This includes directly rejecting a payment arrangement without attempting to negotiate a different one (e.g., \"Not at the moment. I'll have to get back with you,\" followed by disengagement).\n    -- This applies even if _user suggests a future follow-up (e.g., \"Call me back in a month\"), as this is a refusal to negotiate *now*.\n    -- This also applies if _user's attempt to propose an alternative is immediately denied or retracted upon clarification (e.g., user: \"I could do X\", assistant: \"So you can do X?\", user: \"No, that's incorrect.\"), thereby failing to establish a clear path forward.\n    -- This includes situations where _user is unable to engage in a coherent discussion about payment, repeatedly providing nonsensical or irrelevant answers that prevent any negotiation from occurring, despite _assistant's attempts to clarify.\n  + `unknown` : _user's stance on negotiating a payment is genuinely unclear, contradictory, or conditional upon an external factor that prevents current negotiation.\n    -- _user gives immediately self-contradictory statements within a single turn (e.g., \"Yes... No, no, sorry.\") that leave their intent genuinely ambiguous.\n    -- _user's willingness is conditional on an external event or information they do not have, and they cease further negotiation pending that factor (e.g., \"I'll pay after I get my next check,\" or \"I need to talk to my spouse,\" without discussing hypothetical terms).\n    -- _user disputes the debt or is only seeking information and is not prompted by _assistant to negotiate a resolution.\n- `confirmed`: <Captures whether _user has explicitly confirmed or denied the core financial terms of a complete payment arrangement immediately after _assistant summarizes the terms for final agreement. The \"payment arrangement\" refers to the amount and timing, not the payment method (e.g., card number).>\n  + `yes` : _user explicitly agrees (e.g., \"Yes,\" \"I would like to proceed,\" \"Okay\") immediately following a valid confirmation phase.\n    -- A valid confirmation phase occurs when _assistant summarizes the key financial terms of a payment arrangement and asks for agreement in the same turn (e.g., \"So that's $100 on the 15th, is that correct?\").\n    -- The summary must contain all required components for the payment type:\n      --- For a **one-time payment**, the summary must contain the **amount** and a specific **date** (e.g., \"today,\" \"on the 15th\").\n      --- For a **recurring payment plan**, the summary must contain the payment **amount**, **schedule** (e.g., \"monthly\"), **start date**, and **frequency/duration** (e.g., \"for 12 months\").\n    -- The \"payment arrangement\" refers only to the financial terms (amount and timing). It does not require discussion of the payment method or source (e.g., \"using your card on file\") to be considered complete.\n    -- A component is considered part of the summary if it is stated by the agent in the confirmation turn OR was explicitly stated by _user in the immediately preceding turn.\n  + `no` : _user explicitly disagrees with the terms immediately following a valid confirmation phase.\n    -- An explicit disagreement can be a complete phrase (e.g., \"No, I can't do that,\" \"That's not right\") or an incomplete phrase that clearly and unambiguously signals rejection, even if _user is cut off (e.g., \"I don't...\", \"That's not...\").\n    -- This label applies only to rejections of a complete, summarized offer. Rejections of partial offers made during negotiation should be `unknown`.\n    -- General refusal to cooperate (e.g., \"I'm not paying anything\") is not a `no` unless it is a direct response to a complete summary and confirmation question.\n  + `unknown` : The conditions for a `yes` or `no` label have not been met.\n    -- This label is used during negotiation, before a complete arrangement has been summarized by _assistant for final confirmation.\n    -- This label MUST be used if _assistant's summary is missing any of the required components for the payment type (e.g., a one-time payment summary is missing the date), even if _user agrees.\n    -- This label applies if _user's response to a valid confirmation question is ambiguous (e.g., \"Hmm,\" \"I guess so\"), non-committal, a question, or if they do not respond.\n    -- An incomplete user utterance is `unknown` unless it clearly signals rejection (in which case it is `no`). For example, if _user says \"I...\" and the transcript ends, the label is `unknown`.\n- `kit`: <Tracks _user's intent regarding a temporary \"Keep-In-Touch\" (KIT) payment arrangement. A KIT is a fallback measure involving nominal payments. This variable specifically tracks firm commitment to the **financial component** of a KIT plan. An agreement is not firm if it is for a non-financial follow-up (like a callback), is immediately retracted, or is made contingent on another action. _user's explicit rejection of financial terms takes precedence over a subsequent agreement to a simple follow-up call.>\n  + `yes` : _user commits to a KIT arrangement. This applies if:\n    -- _user explicitly and firmly agrees to a new KIT offer involving a specific nominal payment amount (e.g., \"Yes, I can do $50 a month\").\n    -- _assistant states that a KIT plan is *already in place*, and _user does not directly dispute or contradict this fact. Any response other than a direct contradiction (e.g., deflecting, changing the subject, requesting a live agent) qualifies as `yes`.\n  + `no` : _user rejects a KIT arrangement or firmly commits to an alternative plan. This applies if:\n    -- _user explicitly declines a KIT offer (e.g., \"No, I can't do that\").\n    -- _user implicitly rejects the financial terms of a KIT offer by stating they cannot afford the proposed payment (e.g., \"I don't have it,\" \"I don't know where I would get it from\"). This label is `no` even if the user subsequently agrees to a non-financial follow-up call.\n    -- _user firmly agrees to a different, more substantial payment plan (e.g., payment in full, a settlement, or a standard installment plan), making the KIT offer irrelevant.\n    -- _user contradicts the agent's premise of a KIT plan by stating they are on a different type of arrangement (e.g., \"I'm already on settlement\") or that no such plan exists.\n  + `unknown` : _user's intent regarding the financial terms of a KIT arrangement is unclear, deferred, or non-committal. This applies if:\n    -- _user agrees to, or themselves requests, a generic follow-up call or to reschedule the conversation, without having first committed to or rejected the financial terms of a specific KIT offer.\n    -- _user gives a vague, dismissive, or non-committal affirmative response to a KIT offer (e.g., \"Yeah, whatever\", \"I guess\", \"Fine\"), as these do not constitute a firm commitment.\n    -- _user agrees to a plan (KIT or otherwise) but then immediately retracts, expresses doubt, or requests to speak to a live agent before the plan is finalized (e.g., \"Yes, but wait...\", \"Okay, but let me talk to someone first\").\n    -- _user and _assistant discuss potential payment amounts for a KIT plan, but the call ends before a specific amount is firmly agreed upon.\n    -- _user's state (e.g., confusion, distress, incoherence) makes their commitment to any financial arrangement unreliable, even if they use an affirmative word like \"yes.\"\n- `monthly` : the installment amount in monthly in dollars that user agreed to pay in NUMBER and unit of currency, if customer reject to pay or don't answer the amount then return 'unknown'\n- `consolidation` : return \"yes\" if Consumer claims they are with a program for debt/credit settlement, consolidation, relief, management or financial solutions. Else, return \"no\"\n- `consolidation_confirmed` : return \"yes\" if the consumer confirms after the agent asks for confirmation that the Consumer is with a program for debt/credit settlement, consolidation, relief, management or financial solutions. Else, return \"no\"\n- `consolidation_program` : return the details of the company or program that is consolidating debt for the consumer. Else, return \"unknown\"\n- `exc`: <Capture special requests and/or objections from _user.>\n  + `inconvenient_time` : Select this if the consumer is alive but they are busy and temporarily unavailable to speak (e.g., 'call me back later', 'cannot talk now'). This includes temporary unavailability due to an event (e.g., working, driving, eating, sleeping) or location (e.g., \"out of town\", \"at a funeral\", \"in the hospital\", \"at work\",  at a doctor's appointment, attending a ceremony (e.g., funeral, wedding, church)).\n  + `cease_comms` : if caller explicitly requests to take them off your calling list or if caller proactively asks to stop receiving communications from us including email, texting, sms or call\n  + `non_english` : if _user says they does not speak English, or requests to speak in a different language, or has spoken in a non-English language\n  + `prison` : if _user is not Maurice Davis AND explicitly says that Maurice Davis is in prison\n  + `deceased` : Select this ONLY if the user explicitly confirms the consumer, Maurice Davis, no longer exists (e.g., died, passed away, no longer with us). Only select this category if the CONSUMER is the SUBJECT of the death. Differentiation Logic, If the user describes an activity the consumer is doing (e.g., \"visiting a grave\", \"going to a funeral\"), the consumer is clearly alive.\n  + `military_service` : if _user is not Maurice Davis AND explicitly says that Maurice Davis is actively serving in the military\n  + `human_agent_request` : if _user explicitly requests to speak to a live agent/representative. Do NOT select this category if _user simply complains about the AI virtual agent without the explicit request\n  + `revoke_record_consent` : if _user explicitly says that they do not want to be RECORDED, or questions the purpose of recording. Do NOT select this category if _user simply saying \"no\" without any other context\n  + `revoke_record_ai_consent` : if _user explicitly says that they do not want to be RECORDED by an AI virtual agent, or questions the purpose of recording by an AI virtual agent. Do NOT select this category if _user simply complains about the AI virtual agent. Do NOT select this category if _user simply saying \"no\" without any other context\n  + `null` : default value, if _user did not mention any above\n- `info_confirm`:\n  + `yes` : if the user has been asked to confirm or update their contact details to ensure they are timely informed about updates and changes to their account after a thorough discussion of potential payment plans and financial circumstances. Such as, \"Could you please confirm your contact information?\", \"I'd like to make sure we have the correct contact information for you.\"\n  + `no` : if the user has not been asked to confirm their contact details\n- `no_notice` : return \"yes\" ONLY when both conditions are satisfied, i.e. (1) when after the agent has explicitly double check if the consumer has received a letter or email from Kompato and (2) the consumer confirmed that they have not received any. Else, return \"no\"\n- `transfer` : return \"yes\" ONLY when the agent lets the consumer know that the agent does not have the authority to approve lower settlement options but the agent will get a live agent to join the call now to discuss lower settlement options. Else, return \"no\"\n- `payment_method`:\n  + `ach` : _user ultimately and clearly chooses to pay by specifying \"ACH\" or \"bank account\", or clearly responds to a direct assistant prompt about ACH or bank transfer with explicit acceptance. Do NOT select `ach` if the user only makes a general reference to \"direct payment\", \"automatic withdrawal\", \"take it out directly\", or similar vague wording\u2014unless they explicitly confirm that this means ACH or bank transfer after being asked by the assistant. If it is NOT clear what method the user intends (for example, if \"direct\" could mean debit, ACH, or something else), select `unknown` instead.\n  + `credit_card` : _user ultimately chooses to pay by credit card or _user persistent in choosing credit card after being informed that this payment method is not accepted for their account.\n  + `debit_card` : _user ultimately chooses to pay by debit card or _user persistent in choosing debit card after being informed that this payment method is not accepted for their account.\n  + `mailing` : _user ultimately chooses to pay by mailing money order or check or _user persistent in choosing mailing money order or check.\n  + `unknown` : it is unclear what payment method _user would like to choose, or the _user has not selected, confirmed, or mentioned a specific payment method yet, or the _user only provides vague or ambiguous statements (such as \"direct\", \"automatic\", or \"set it up\" without specifying the method).\n  + `other` : _user wants to pay by other payment method\n- `struggling_situation`:\n  + `yes` : if the user describes experiencing financial hardship (such as loss of job, medical emergency, disability, or similar circumstances)\n  + `no` : if the user is not struggling with their financial situation or they have not mentioned any financial hardship.\n- `dob` : + If the user confirms that the day of birth the agent states is correct OR explicitly says a corrected day of birth, return it as a two-digit number in the format `dd`. Note that the day may be provided in spoken language format (e.g., \"twenty-seventh\")\n+ If the user refuses to provide or confirm their day of birth (e.g., \"Why do I need to tell you that information?\"), assign `refuse`.\n+ If it's unclear, return `unknown`\n- `mob` : + If the user confirms that the month of birth the agent states is correct OR explicitly says a corrected month of birth, return it as a two-digit number in the format `mm`. Note that the month may be provided in spoken language format (e.g., \"April\")\n+ If the user refuses to provide or confirm their month of birth (e.g., \"Why do I need to tell you that information?\"), assign `refuse` \n+ If it's unclear, return `unknown`\n- `dob_confirmed`:\n  + `confirmed` : _user confirmed their date of birth was recorded correctly\n  + `unknown` : _user hasn't confirmed BOTH their date of birth was recorded correctly or stated that the recored date of birth was not correct\n- `first_payment_amount` : the first amount the user agrees to pay, if the user does not agree to pay or does not mention an amount, return 'unknown'\n- `first_payment_date` : The clearly stated date (YYYY-MM-DD) for the first payment. If the first payment date is not mentioned, return 'unknown'. Do not guess, infer, or fabricate the date. Today is 2026-04-24. First payment date should be today or in the future.\n- `second_payment_amount` : the second amount the user agrees to pay, if the user does not agree to pay or does not mention an amount, return 'unknown'\n- `second_payment_date` : The clearly stated date (YYYY-MM-DD) for the second payment after the first payment. If there is no second payment (e.g., only a single, one-off payment is scheduled), return None.\nToday is 2026-04-24. Second payment date should be in the future.\n- `confidence_score` : A float value between 0 and 1 representing the model's confidence in the accuracy of the extracted payment plan variables.\nA higher score indicates greater certainty that the values detected in the transcript match the customer's intent and the conversation context.\n- `cf_mail` : return \"yes\" ONLY when both conditions are satisfied, i.e. (1) the agent has explicitly read the consumer's mailing address in records, and (2) the user says ok or has EXPLICITYLY said that that mailing address is correct and complete with state, zip code. Else, return \"no\"\n- `cf_email` : return \"yes\" ONLY when both conditions are satisfied, i.e. (1) the agent has explicitly read the consumer's email address in records, and (2) the user says ok or has EXPLICITLY said that that email address is correct and in the right format. Else, return \"no\"\n- `new_mail` : the new updated mail address that _user provided (extracted directly from answer of _user), if not available then return \"unknown\" as default value\n- `new_email` : the new updated email that _user provided (extracted directly from answer of _user), if not available then return \"unknown\" as default value\n- `text_consent`: <Determine whether or not _user agrees to be communicated with via text or email after being asked, \"Do you give us permission to text or email you with account updates?\">\n  + `yes` : _user agrees to be communicated with via text or email.\n  + `no` : _user does not agree to be communicated with via text or email.\n  + `unknown` : It is not clear whether _user agrees or disagrees to be communicated with via text or email. Only assign this to `text_consent` if the question has not been asked, or if it has been asked but _user's response is vague.\n- `human_call`: <Determine whether or not _user agrees to be called back by a human when asked, \"For any reason we get disconnected, do we have permission to call you back?\">\n  + `agree` : If _user explicitly agrees to be specifically called back by a human, then assign `agree` to `human_call`.\n  + `revoke` : If _user explicitly disagrees to be specifically called back by a human, then assign `revoke` to `human_call`.\n  + `unknown` : If it is not clear whether _user agrees or disagrees to a callback, assign `unknown` to `human_call`. Only assign this to `human_call` if the question has not been asked, or if it has been asked but _user's response is vague.\n- `payment_method_insistence`:\n  + `yes` : After the assistant has clearly informed the user that their selected payment method is not accepted, the user continues to choose or insist on that unaccepted payment method. If the assistant then explicitly says the user's choice is not accepted (e.g., assistant says \"Credit card is not accepted for your account.\") and the user continues to insist on that method, return \"yes\".\n  + `no` : The user mentions an unaccepted payment method before being told it is not accepted, or if the user does not persist after being informed, or if the user switches to an accepted method. If the assistant lists accepted payment methods and the user mentions an unaccepted one (e.g., assistant says \"We accept debit card or ACH payments.\", user says \"credit\"), return \"no\".\n- `payment_method_choice_status`:\n  + `unknown` : Select this if the user does not reference any payment method, or gives a vague, unrelated, or ambiguous response when asked about their preferred payment method\u2014without clearly accepting or refusing the payment method proposed such as  **debit card**, **credit card**, **ACH payments**, .\n  + `chosen` : Select this if the user explicitly chooses a payment method.\n  + `declined` : Select this if the user clearly rejects moving forward with the payment method suggested by the assistant, explicitly expressing refusal to use  **debit card**, **credit card**, **ACH payments**,  method.\n- `disclosure_agree`: <Determine whether _user agreed to the payment plan details immediately after _assistant asked a direct confirmation question, \"Do you agree to this payment?\">\n  + `yes` : _user gives a clear, affirmative response (such as \"yes\", \"I agree\", \"agree\", \"okay\", \"correct\", or similar) specifically *immediately after* _assistant asks a direct confirmation question regarding agreement with the payment plan details (e.g., after _assistant says \"Do you agree to this payment?\" or similar question explicitly recapping the payment amount, timing, and terms). Only responses given directly following this explicit \"Do you agree...\" or equivalent confirmation question should be marked as \"yes\".\n  + `no` : _user's response is absent, ambiguous, off-topic, negative, or delayed relative to the assistant's explicit payment confirmation question. Use \"no\" when no clear affirmative was given immediately after the confirmation question.\n- `nacha_confirmation`:\n  + `yes` : Select \"yes\" if _user says \"I agree\" or \"agree\" immediately following _assistant's payment authorization statement for the payment method, which must contain the phrase \"This payment authorization is valid and will remain in effect unless you notify Kompato AI of cancellation.\" This includes cases where _user responds with \"I agree\" after any version or rewording of the authorization statement, or after any clarifying questions have been answered and _assistant again prompts for stated agreement. Do not select \"yes\" for \"I agree\" responses that are delayed, unrelated, or not directly following the payment authorization request.\n  + `no` : Choose \"no\" if _user does not clearly and directly reply with \"I agree\" or \"agree\" right after _assistant's payment authorization statement. This applies if _user's reply is missing, unclear, unrelated, delayed, or does not follow the authorization request, as well as if _assistant has not yet provided the authorization statement or _user does not state agreement after it.\n- `response`: <Capture _user's response after the call begins.>\n  + `voice_mail` : if _user appears to be a voicemail automated answering machine. Common phrases may include \"This is a message for...\", \"Please leave a message after the tone.\", \"I'm not available right now.\", \"At the beep...\", \"You've reached the voicemail of...\", \"Please call me back at...\", \"I'll get back to you soon.\", \"Sorry I missed your call.\", \"[Name] is currently not available\", \"Can't take your call now\", \"This is [Name]...\" (often followed by \"leaving a message\"), \"Press [number] for [department/option]\", \"Enter the extension\", \"May be recorded and used by a third party\", or other similar phrases.\n  + `hello` : if _user says \"hello?\", \"hello\", \"hi\", similar without stating any name. _user's response does not appear to be a voice mail machine, and _user shows the intent to want to continue the current conversation such as \"Yes, who is this?\", \"Can I help you?\", \"Okay\" or \"What do you need?\".\n  + `business` : _user is from a business. Common phrases may include \"This is [Name] from [Business/Location]\", \"Thank you for calling [Business/Location], how may I help you?\", \"This is [Name] at [Business/Location]\" or other similar phrases. Select `voice_mail` instead of `business` if the _user appears to be a voicemail automated answering machine.\n  + `screening_call` : if _user appears to be an automated digital assistant or AI service answering on behalf of the recipient to **screen or filter the call before connecting to a person**. Common phrases include \"Hi, if you record your name and reason for calling I'll see if this person is available\", \"The person you are calling is screening this call\". **Priority Rule:** Only select this if the screening bot is the *current* active speaker. If _user has interrupted or answered with \"hello\", do NOT select `screening_call`. **Exclude:** business IVR systems, automated greetings, or AI assistants that represent the called business itself (e.g., \"I'm [Company]'s AI assistant\", \"This call is being recorded for quality purposes\").\n  + `ios_screen_passed` : if the **LATEST** _user response is ONLY an automated system message confirming the connection (e.g., \"Thanks, please stay on the line\", \"Connecting you now\", \"The party has accepted your call\"). **Priority Rule:** Do NOT select this if _user says \"hello\" (select `hello` instead).\n  + `ios_screen_fail` : if the call was previously in a screening state (asking for name/reason) but has now transitioned to a standard voicemail prompt (e.g., \"Please leave a message after the tone\", \"Record your message\"), this indicates screening failed. **Priority Rule:** Select this instead of `voice_mail` if the voicemail prompt follows a screening attempt.\n  + `matched` : if _user stated their name and the name is Maurice Davis\n  + `unmatched` : if _user stated their name and the name does not match with Maurice Davis\n  + `unknown` : if it is not clear what _user says\n- `cf_phone` : return \"yes\" ONLY when both conditions are satisfied, i.e. (1) the agent has explicitly read the consumer's PHONE NUMBER in records, and (2) the user says ok or has EXPLICITYLY said that that phone number is correct and right format of U.S. phone number. Else, return \"no\"\n- `new_phone` : the new updated phone number that _user provided (extracted directly from answer of _user), if not available then return \"unknown\" as default value\n- `update_refusal` : return \"yes\" if the consumer explicitly declines to update their contact information. Else, return \"no\"\n- `receive` : return \"yes\" when the consumer EXPLICITLY says that they have received a letter or email from Kompato and wish to continue discuss their account. Else, return \"no\"\n- `voice_mail`: <Determine if the call receiver is a voicemail system.>\n  + `yes` : _user appears to be a voicemail automated answering machine. Common phrases may include \"This is a message for...\", \"Please leave a message after the tone.\", \"At the beep...\", \"You've reached the voicemail of...\", \"[Name] is currently not available\", \"Leave me a message\", \"Press [number] for [department/option]\", \"Enter the extension\", \"May be recorded and used by a third party\", \"Hi, if you record your name and reason for calling, I'll see if this person is available\" or other similar phrases\n  + `business` : _user is from a business. Common phrases may include \"This is [Name] from [Business/Location]\", \"Thank you for calling [Business/Location], how may I help you?\", \"This is [Name] at [Business/Location]\" or other similar phrases. Select this category if _user explicitly says that this is a business number.\n  + `no` : if _user is neither a voicemail nor a business, or if what the _user says is unclear\n- `rpc`: <Capture whether the call receiver is the customer (Right Person Contact).>\n  + `cus` : _user confirmed that they were the customer (e.g. \"speaking\", \"okay\", \"yes\", etc) in response to _assistant speaking out their name (e.g., \"Am I speaking with Maurice Davis?\", \"Is this Maurice Davis?\")\n  + `attorney` : _user wanted to assign to their attorney or lawyer, or that they are the attorney or lawyer of the customer\n  + `wrong_number` : _user indicates you have the wrong number entirely - typically when they say \"No\" to being the customer AND \"No\" to having a good contact number, OR when they explicitly say \"wrong number\", \"I'm not her. Stop calling\", \"I don't know him\", \"I don't know her number\" or similar phrases\n  + `not` : _user confirms they are not the specific customer being sought - typically when they say \"No\" to being the customer; _user may or may not know the customer or the customer's contact number\n  + `unknown` : if you are not sure, or the user answers not clearly, gives unrelated responses, or uses non-English without clear intent\n- `confirm_callback`: <Determine whether _assistant has successfully scheduled a callback time with _user ONLY IF _user confirms they are not the intended customer.>\n  + `done` : if _user is NOT Maurice Davis AND _assistant has clarified the callback time with _user (e.g., \"what is the best time for us to call back?\")\n  + `not` : if one of the following cases holds true (1) the _user is Maurice Davis, (2) the _user is NOT Maurice Davis AND the _assistant has NOT clarified the callback time\n- `company_introduced` : \"yes\": if _assistant has mentioned Kompato and MoneySpot Direct LLC dba Sunshine Loans in any turn in the conversation INCLUDING the current turn.\n\"no\": ONLY if _assistant has NEVER mentioned Kompato and MoneySpot Direct LLC dba Sunshine Loans in any turn INCLUDING the current turn.            \n```\n\n## Reflection Variable Values\n```\n- `exc`: null\n- `settlement_2_percentage`: 60\n- `new_email`: unknown\n- `consolidation_program`: unknown\n- `dob_confirmed`: confirmed\n- `receive`: no\n- `text_consent`: unknown\n- `human_call`: agree\n- `info_confirm`: no\n- `promise`: yes\n- `mini_miranda`: yes\n- `no_notice`: no\n- `cf_mail`: yes\n- `consolidation_confirmed`: no\n- `new_phone`: unknown\n- `confidence_score`: 0.95\n- `first_payment_date`: 2026-05-01\n- `cf_phone`: no\n- `kit`: no\n- `second_payment_date`: None\n- `new_mail`: unknown\n- `nacha_confirmation`: yes\n- `mob`: 07\n- `review`: unknown\n- `dob`: 24\n- `struggling_situation`: yes\n- `willing_to_pay`: settlement\n- `confirmed`: yes\n- `consolidation`: no\n- `second_payment_amount`: None\n- `cf_email`: yes\n- `payment_method_insistence`: no\n- `payment_method`: debit_card\n- `negotiate`: yes\n- `update_refusal`: no\n- `months`: 1\n- `transfer`: no\n- `monthly`: unknown\n- `first_date`: 2026-05-01\n- `disclosure_agree`: yes\n- `confirm_callback`: not\n- `first_payment_amount`: 96\n- `amount`: 96.00 dollars\n- `rpc`: cus\n- `payment_method_choice_status`: chosen\n- `response`: hello\n```\n\n\n# Example Output\n<reasoning>\nYour concise reasoning for the classification.\n</reasoning>\n<call_code_list>\n[\"CALL_CODE_1\", \"CALL_CODE_2\", \"CALL_CODE_3\"]\n</call_code_list>"
[2026-05-13 22:02:22 +0700] [CODEX] output/from_zero/signal_experiment_40_dtmf_rerun_20260513_1655/per_conversation/0023_PmVT8hG7m4pkn5UHlG65jg/llm_call_0001.json:28:      "content": "You are a Collection Agent specialized in classifying conversations into the one to three most relevant call codes.\nGiven abstracted conversation history, list of call codes with their descriptions, and reflection variable values with their descriptions (optional) and  your task to analyze and classify the conversation into the one to three most relevant call codes.\n\n# Instruction\n- Thoroughly analyze the conversation history, dictionary variable values, state variable descriptions, and call code descriptions.\n- Carefully review the conversation to select the one to three call codes that best fit the context and details of the exchange.\n- When reasoning, you may reference reflection variable values and descriptions if they help justify your choices, but focus primarily on the conversation context and call code descriptions.\n- Your justification should combine insights from the conversation, call code descriptions, and other inputs as relevant.\n\n#  Notes:\n- Consider all possible angles and variable values, not just the most direct or frequent call code.\n- Make sure the reasoning is clear, specific, and references the data provided.\n\n\n# Output Format\n- Return your reasoning in <reasoning> </reasoning> tags\n- Return list potential call code wrapped in <call_code_list> </call_code_list> tags.\n\n# Input Information\n\n## Conversation History\n```\nuser: Hello?\nassistant: [happy] Hey, this is Emily, a virtual agent on a recorded line.\nuser: Hello?\nassistant: Is this Teresa Leroy?\nuser: Yes.\nassistant: [confident] To protect your privacy and proceed with the call, I have June 10, 1957 as your birthdate on file. Is that correct?\nuser: Yes.\nassistant: Thank you for confirming. I'm calling from Kompato on behalf of Bureaus Investment Group Portfolio Number 15 LLC. [supportive] I must advise that this is an attempt to collect a debt by a debt collector. Any information obtained will be used for that purpose. [supportive] Teresa, I'm calling about your account with Capital One, National Association, with a balance of seven hundred and thirty-nine dollars and seventeen cents. Could you please tell me about the circumstances that led to the default?\nuser: Yes. Um, I can't work right now.\nassistant: [compassionate] I'm sorry to hear that, Teresa. That must be a challenging situation for you. To help me find the best-\nuser: It is.\nassistant: [understanding] I can imagine how difficult this must be for you. [supportive] Your account balance is seven hundred and thirty-nine dollars and seventeen cents. To assist you, we can settle the total balance to five hundred and eighteen dollars, saving you two hundred and twenty-two dollars. This would reduce your monthly payment to eighty-seven dollars for six months, with the last installment being eighty-three dollars. Would this adjusted amount be manageable for you?\nuser: No.\nassistant: [understanding] I see. -\nuser: two i.\nassistant: [confused] I'm sorry, could you clarify what you mean by \"two i\"?\nuser: Too high. I won't be able to pay for my medicine.\nassistant: [compassionate] I understand, Teresa. Your health is a priority, and I want to help find a solution that works for you. [supportive] We can explore a lower settlement option. We could settle your account for four hundred and forty-four dollars, which reduces your monthly payment to seventy-four dollars for six months. Would this be more manageable for you?\nuser: No.\nassistant: -\nuser: No. Fifty.\nassistant: [supportive] I understand you're suggesting fifty dollars. The minimum monthly amount for the settlement offer is seventy-four dollars. [encouraging] Would it be possible to adjust slightly closer to that amount?\nuser: It'd be hard.\nassistant: [understanding] I see how that could be difficult. [supportive] If seventy-four dollars isn't feasible, we can schedule a keep-in-touch arrangement for three months with a minimum monthly amount of fifty dollars. Would that work better for you?\nuser: Yes.\nassistant: [supportive] Great. Could you let me know a convenient date within the next 30 days to start the first payment of fifty dollars?\nuser: The twenty seventh.\nassistant: [supportive] Just to confirm, you'll be making a monthly payment of fifty dollars starting on May 27, 2026. Is that correct?\nuser: Yes.\nassistant: Please note that nothing we discuss overshadows your rights as expressed in our email to you. For any reason we get disconnected, do we have permission to call you back?\nuser: Yes.\nuser: I have no email anyway.\nassistant: [professional] Thank you for confirming. Since you mentioned you don't have an email, we can send any necessary information via text. Which payment method are you planning to use\u2014debit card, credit card, or-\nuser: Money order.\nassistant: Understood-\nuser: Money order. I have bank account.\nassistant: [professional] Thank you for sharing that. If you're planning to send a money order, you can mail it to our address at three seven one zero  Rawlins Street, Suite one four two zero , Dallas, Texas seven five two one nine . [supportive] We also have an online payment portal at kompatoai. com for your convenience. [supportive] Now, let's ensure we have your most up-to-date contact information. I have CHRISLEROY two one zero nine at GMAIL dot COM as your email address in my records. Is this still accurate?\nuser: I don't have an email address.\nassistant: [supportive] Thank you for letting me know. I'd appreciate it if you could provide me with a new email address to reach you. May I have the best email to contact you?\nuser: I don't have one.\nassistant: [understanding] That's okay. We'll proceed without an email address for now. [supportive] I also have nine three zero  E 1st Street Unit two three , Long Beach, California, nine zero eight zero two as your mailing address in my records. Is this still accurate?\nuser: Yes.\nuser: Yes.\nassistant: [appreciative] Thank you for confirming. [supportive] Lastly, I have five six two six six one zero zero five one as your contact number. Is this still the best way to reach you?\nuser: Yes.\nuser: Yes.\nassistant: [appreciative] Thank you for confirming all your contact details. [supportive] If you have any further questions or need assistance, feel free to reach out. Have a good day!\nuser: <SILENCE_5s>\nassistant: \n```\n\n## List of Call Codes and Their Descriptions\n- `NLM`: Description: Agent encounters a voicemail system, automated/answering system or a person confirming the customer is unavailable, and no substantive message or actionable instruction is left.\nUse when: Agent reaches voicemail/automated system or is told the person is unavailable. Call ends without leaving a callback number, stated reason for call, or formal identification after the beep. Agent may provide initial introduction (name, company, customer name) but does not leave actionable requests.\nEdge cases: Agent speaks in confusion to the voicemail machine (e.g., \"May I please speak with [Name]?\") without leaving a formal message \u2192 NLM, not LM. Brief interactions ending immediately after unavailability is confirmed \u2192 NLM. If agent intentionally leaves a callback number or states the reason for the call \u2192 LM, not NLM. This code excludes calls where the number reached does not belong to the intended customer (use WRN).\nFew-shots: Agent hears \"leave a message after the tone,\" says \"May I speak with John?\" then hangs up \u2192 NLM. Person answers \"She's not available,\" agent says \"Okay, thank you\" \u2192 NLM.\n\n\n- `LM`: Description: Agent encounters a voicemail, automated/answering system AND leaves a substantive message (callback number, reason for call, or formal identification) after the beep.\nUse when: Voicemail system is detected (system prompts like \"record your name,\" \"after the tone,\" \"state your reason\"). Agent explicitly leaves a callback number, states reason for call, or provides formal identification AFTER the recording tone.\nEdge cases: Agent merely speaks in confusion to the machine without leaving a formal message \u2192 NLM, not LM. Must have substantive, actionable content (callback number, stated reason, or formal identification) AFTER the beep. If call terminates or agent gets confused without leaving a formal message \u2192 NLM.\nFew-shots: Agent hears beep, then says \"This is Anna from Kompato, please call us back at 1-888-555-1234\" \u2192 LM. Agent hears beep, says \"May I speak with John?\" then disconnects \u2192 NLM (not LM).\n\n\n- `HUP`: Description: Hang Up - Call ends or is effectively abandoned before any meaningful two-way conversation occurs and before any identity or account information is verified. This includes cases where the agent only delivers the opening, the customer says nothing further, the line goes silent, the customer disconnects immediately, or the customer gives only a cryptic, random, or irrelevant phrase (e.g., random nouns, a business name like \"Orange Wagon\" or \"Joe's Pizza\") without clearly expressing intent to engage or continue the conversation. CRITICAL: A customer answering with what sounds like a business name (e.g., \"Orange Wagon\") is NOT the same as the customer explicitly stating \"this is a business\" or \"you have the wrong number.\" Answering with a business-sounding phrase alone \u2014 without the caller explicitly confirming they are NOT the intended person \u2014 does NOT qualify as WRN. Use HUP. WRN requires the caller to EXPLICITLY state it is a wrong number or that they are a business, not merely answer with a phrase that could be a business name.\nUse when: The interaction never progresses beyond the initial contact attempt and the customer's response does not confirm their identity or a clear intent to continue the conversation. A single unrelated, cryptic, or nonsensical phrase does not qualify as engagement unless the customer provides further input indicating an intent to engage, continue, or clarify their response.\nEdge cases: Distinguish from NVR \u2014 If the agent asks \"Is this [Name]?\" and the customer engages in a SUBSTANTIVE back-and-forth exchange (asking questions, demanding context, showing hostility) without confirming identity, use NVR. If the customer provides only a brief response (\"Hello?\") and the call ends quickly without real engagement, use HUP. The key question: was there a meaningful exchange after the name question, or did the call just die? Do NOT use HUP if voicemail is reached (use NLM/LM), if the person explicitly refuses name or ID verification after substantive engagement (use NVR/HUA), if identity was confirmed and the call dropped during authentication (use HUA), or if the person clearly states they are the wrong party (use WRN). WRN requires EXPLICIT confirmation of wrong number. Simply answering with a business name or unrelated phrase without explicitly stating it is a wrong number does NOT qualify as WRN \u2014 use HUP instead.\nFew-shots: Customer says \"Orange Wagon\" then call ends \u2192 HUP (not WRN) \u2014 answering with a business-sounding name without explicitly saying \"this is a business\" or \"wrong number\" is HUP. Customer answers, says nothing, line goes silent \u2192 HUP. Customer says \"Hello?\" then immediately disconnects \u2192 HUP. Even if reflection variable says response=business, if the caller never EXPLICITLY said \"this is a business\" or \"wrong number,\" classify as HUP.\n\n\n- `IDF`: Description: ID Verification Failed - Customer confirms the right name, but DOB/SSN/zip information does not match with data in the system, OR customer refuses to verify their identity through standard verification protocols.\nUse when: Customer says \"No\" when asked if DOB on file is correct (data mismatch). Customer provides a DOB, SSN, or zip that does not match system records. Customer says \"No,\" \"Nope,\" \"I'm not giving you that,\" \"I refuse\" when asked for DOB/SSN (active refusal while still on the line). Customer confirms they are not the intended person during verification.\nEdge cases: Key distinction from HUA \u2014 IDF = customer provided WRONG data (DOB/SSN doesn't match) OR customer is still on the line ACTIVELY refusing/engaging (saying \"No,\" asking questions, arguing). HUA = customer confirmed name but the call ENDED (hung up, went silent, line dropped, timed out) during verification \u2014 no active engagement, just disconnection. If the customer says \"No\" to DOB and CONTINUES the conversation (asks questions, argues, refuses more) \u2192 IDF. If the customer goes silent and call times out \u2192 HUA. If the customer provided wrong data earlier but then the call also drops \u2192 still IDF (data mismatch occurred).\nFew-shots: Customer says \"No\" to \"Is Feb 22 1961 your DOB?\" then says \"It's not\" \u2192 IDF (data mismatch). Customer provides SSN 2549 that doesn't match \u2192 IDF. Customer says \"Nope\" repeatedly to DOB while still talking \u2192 IDF (active refusal). Customer provides wrong DOB \"2 3 65\" that doesn't match \u2192 IDF (data doesn't match even if conversation continues). Customer says \"No\" to DOB on file, then provides different DOB + wrong SSN, then goes silent \u2192 IDF (data mismatch happened before silence). Customer confirms name, agent asks for DOB, customer goes silent \u2192 call ends \u2192 HUA (no data provided, just disconnected).\n\n\n- `HUA`: Description: Hang Up During Authentication - Customer confirmed their name but the call ENDED (hung up, disconnected, went silent) during the ID verification process. The verification was never completed \u2014 the call was cut short.\nUse when: Customer confirmed their name but the call ended during verification \u2014 customer hung up, went silent (multiple SILENCE markers), line dropped, or call timed out. The customer did NOT provide any DOB/SSN data and did NOT actively refuse \u2014 the call simply ended. Also applies when customer asks context questions (\"Who is this?\", \"What\u2019s this about?\") but the call ends before any verification data is exchanged.\nEdge cases: Key distinction from IDF \u2014 If the customer says \"No\" to the DOB on file (data mismatch) or actively says \"Nope,\" \"I refuse\" while still engaging \u2192 IDF (not HUA). HUA is for calls that ENDED during auth without data being checked. If the customer asks \"Who is this?\" then goes silent \u2192 HUA (call ended, no verification data). If the customer says \"I don\u2019t know\" to DOB and the call continues \u2192 IDF (refusal while engaged). If the customer says \"I don\u2019t know\" and immediately hangs up \u2192 HUA (call ended).\nFew-shots: Customer confirms name, agent asks for DOB, customer goes silent \u2192 call ends \u2192 HUA. Customer confirms name, asks \"Who is this? What\u2019s this about?\" \u2192 call ends \u2192 HUA. Customer confirms name, DOB question asked, customer says \"What\u2019s this concerning?\" then silence \u2192 HUA. Customer confirms name, says \"I don\u2019t know it\" to DOB and call ends \u2192 HUA (call ended, no data checked). Customer says \"No\" to DOB on file \u2192 IDF (not HUA \u2014 data mismatch). Customer says \"Nope\" repeatedly while still on line \u2192 IDF (not HUA \u2014 active refusal). Call truncated right after DOB question is asked, before customer responds \u2192 HUA (not IDV \u2014 verification was never completed).\n\n\n- `NVR`: Description: Name Verification Refused - Customer failed to confirm their name/identity following agent\u2019s attempt, through explicit refusal, evasion, incoherence, or hostility.\nUse when: After the agent asks \"Is this [Name]?\" or similar, the customer responds with SUBSTANTIVE verbal engagement that avoids confirming identity \u2014 defensive questions (\"Who\u2019s calling?,\" \"What do you want?\"), evasion (\"Hold on,\" \"Wait a minute\"), incoherent/irrelevant answers, hostility (profanity, aggression), or repeated demands for context. The key signal: the customer engages in a back-and-forth exchange with the agent without confirming their name.\nEdge cases: Distinguish from HUP \u2014 NVR requires SUBSTANTIVE verbal interaction after a name verification attempt (multiple exchanges, questions, hostility). A single \"Hello?\" or brief response followed by immediate disconnection is still HUP if no real exchange occurred. Use NVR when: (1) the customer asks questions about the caller/company, (2) the customer responds with hostility or profanity, (3) the customer engages in multiple turns without confirming identity. Use HUP when: the call ends before any meaningful exchange, or the customer provides only a brief/single-word response before disconnecting. Distinguish from CAB \u2014 if callback arranged specifically because identity could not be verified \u2192 NVR.\nFew-shots: Agent asks \"Is this John Smith?\" and customer says \"Who is calling? What do you want?\" \u2192 NVR. Agent asks for name, customer says \"Kiss my ass, bitch\" \u2192 NVR. Agent asks \"Is this Jeffrey Soliz?\" and customer asks \"Who\u2019s this?\" then \"Big Sky?\" (multiple turns) \u2192 NVR. Customer picks up, says \"Hello?\" once, then disconnects \u2192 HUP (not NVR).\n\n\n- `IDV`: Description: ID Verification Successful - Customer successfully passed all required identity verification checks \u2014 confirmed name AND at least one additional identifier (DOB, or SSN). This becomes the mandatory default classification for the rest of the call unless a more specific terminal disposition is reached.\nUse when: Customer explicitly confirms name AND provides/confirms at least one additional identifier. IDV stays as the default unless a more specific outcome occurs. Switch away from IDV when: the customer declines one or more payment offers (use NNP), a payment arrangement is made (use PPA/PPIF/PSIF), the customer explicitly refuses to pay any amount (use RTP), or any other terminal disposition applies.\nEdge cases: Customer expresses uncertainty about debt or agency \u2192 still IDV. Customer gives non-committal response to payment offer (\"I'm not sure,\" \"Maybe,\" \"Possibly,\" \"I'll think about it\") without clearly declining \u2192 still IDV (not NNP \u2014 non-committal is not a clear decline). Declining to share personal circumstances or explain default reasons is NOT a refusal to pay and NOT NNP \u2192 still IDV. If no specific payment amounts were offered at all, the call remains IDV. CRITICAL \u2014 If a payment offer was made but NO customer response to that offer is present in the conversation (the conversation ends immediately after the offer, or the customer's reply to the offer is missing), this is NOT NNP \u2192 still IDV. NNP requires the customer's explicit decline to be visible in the conversation. If payment was offered AND the customer explicitly said \"No\" or clearly declined, use NNP (not IDV). Only override with RTP if customer makes direct, unambiguous statement refusing to pay ANY amount (e.g., \"I won't pay,\" \"I refuse\"). Hostility, profanity, or incoherent outbursts (e.g., \"don't fuck yourself,\" random aggressive words) without explicit payment refusal \u2192 still IDV, NOT RTP and NOT CPR. A customer who becomes hostile or disengaged after verification but has NOT made a formal complaint about service/practices is NOT CPR \u2014 general hostility or profanity directed at no specific service issue is just a failed conversation, which remains IDV.\nFew-shots: Customer confirms name + DOB, then says \"No\" to sharing circumstances \u2192 IDV. Customer verified, payment discussed but customer says \"Possibly\" or \"Maybe\" without committing or declining \u2192 IDV (not NNP). Customer verified, declines to explain default circumstances, no payment amounts offered \u2192 IDV (not NNP). Customer verified, becomes hostile and uses profanity (\"don't fuck yourself\") but never explicitly refuses to pay \u2192 IDV (not RTP, not CPR). Customer verified, says incoherent hostile things and call ends \u2192 IDV. Customer verified, says \"I'm not familiar with this agency\" \u2192 IDV. Agent asks about circumstances, customer says \"No,\" agent then offers monthly payment amount, conversation ends with no customer response to the offer \u2192 IDV (customer only declined to share circumstances \u2014 no explicit decline of payment offer was shown).\n\n\n- `TSR`: Description: Transfer to Representative - Customer explicitly requests to speak with a live person, or a structural handoff to a live agent occurs during the call. Once a transfer request is made or handoff occurs, this code remains the classification for the entire call. IMPORTANT: If the conversation ends with the AI agent transferring to a live agent (e.g., \"Let me connect you with a live agent\"), this is ALWAYS TSR regardless of what happened earlier in the call.\nUse when: Customer says \"customer service,\" \"representative,\" \"human,\" \"operator,\" \"transfer me,\" or similar. Agent says \"while I check availability for a live agent\" followed by a live person introduction. Transfer request is made even if the virtual assistant fails to fulfill it. ALSO use when the AI agent initiates a transfer to a live agent due to a system failure (e.g., payment processing error, unable to retrieve payment information, \"The system can not retrieve your payment information\") \u2014 this is a structural handoff even though the customer did not request it. RULE: Look at the FINAL outcome of the call. If the call ends with a transfer to a live agent, classify as TSR \u2014 not the code that was applicable before the transfer.\nEdge cases: TSR overrides IDV, NCV, CAB, PPIF, PSIF, PPA, NNP, RTP, and other standard operational codes. CRITICAL OVERRIDE: Even if the customer agreed to pay in full (PPIF), provided a PIN, and the system attempted payment \u2014 if the payment system FAILED and the AI agent then transfers to a live agent, you MUST select TSR, NOT PPIF. The transfer is the FINAL disposition and supersedes ALL prior payment commitments. Even if the live agent performs verification, updates addresses, or discusses payment, you MUST select TSR. HUA, DIS, CDS still take precedence over TSR. If customer refuses secondary verification AND requests live agent \u2192 HUA (not TSR; refusal takes precedence). Once transfer request is made or system-initiated handoff occurs, TSR remains classification regardless of prior payment commitments or subsequent content. Key indicators: \"Let me connect you with a live agent,\" \"while I check availability,\" \"customer service,\" \"The system can not retrieve your payment information.\"\nFew-shots: Customer agrees to pay full $2112.50, provides PIN 123456, system repeatedly says \"retrieving your payment information,\" then fails and agent says \"The system can not retrieve your payment information. Let me connect you with a live agent\" \u2192 TSR (NOT PPIF \u2014 the transfer at the END of the call is the final disposition, overriding the earlier payment commitment). Customer says \"customer service\" at the start, then agent transfers to live person who handles the whole call \u2192 TSR. Customer says \"Representative. Representative.\" and agent fails to transfer \u2192 TSR. Customer says \"I want a person\" while refusing DOB \u2192 HUA (not TSR).\n\n\n- `INC`: Description: Consumer Incapacitated - A third party (or the customer) reports the account holder is deceased, severely ill, hospitalized long-term, or mentally incapacitated.\nUse when: Caller states the account holder has passed away (deceased, died). Caller states account holder has a severe or long-term condition preventing engagement (dementia, coma, brain injury, long-term hospitalization, brain fog).\nEdge cases: Minor/temporary illness (\"they have a cold,\" \"they're sleeping\") \u2192 NOT INC. \"Brain fog\" qualifies as mental incapacity \u2192 INC. Incapacitation must imply serious, potentially long-term inability to engage.\nFew-shots: \"She's not available, sir. She's deceased now. This is her husband.\" \u2192 INC. \"She has brain fog. How can I help you?\" \u2192 INC. \"She's been in the hospital for a couple of weeks, she's battling cancer.\" \u2192 INC.\n\n\n- `LGB`: Description: Language Barrier - Communication could not proceed effectively due to language differences between agent and customer.\nUse when: Customer indicates inability to understand or communicate in the language being used. Language barrier makes meaningful conversation impossible.\nEdge cases: N/A\nFew-shots: Customer responds only in Spanish to English-speaking agent \u2192 LGB. Customer says \"I don't understand English\" \u2192 LGB.\n\n\n- `RTP`: Description: Refusal to Pay - Customer explicitly and unambiguously refused to make any payment on the account ONLY after the creditor presented the balance AND made MULTIPLE attempts to negotiate payment options. RTP requires: (1) identity verification was completed, (2) the balance was presented, (3) the creditor offered multiple payment plans or settlement options, and (4) the customer explicitly rejected ALL of them or stated they will not pay any amount.\nUse when: Customer uses explicit refusal language such as \"I can\u2019t pay anything,\" \"None,\" \"I\u2019m not paying,\" \"It\u2019s not possible,\" \"I refuse to pay,\" or \"I will never pay.\" RTP requires an unambiguous statement of intent NOT to pay \u2014 not merely saying \"No\" to specific offered amounts. Simply declining offered payment amounts without explicit refusal language is NNP, not RTP. The customer must have been given a genuine opportunity to negotiate before RTP applies.\nEdge cases: CRITICAL \u2014 Declining to share personal circumstances or explain default reasons is NOT RTP (use IDV). Profanity or hostility alone does NOT automatically qualify as RTP \u2014 the customer must have explicitly refused to pay or been given multiple payment options which they all rejected. Random profanity, frustration, or incoherent hostile outbursts (e.g., \"don\u2019t fuck yourself\") WITHOUT an explicit statement refusing payment is NOT RTP. If the conversation never reached the payment negotiation stage (i.e., no specific payment amounts were offered and rejected), profanity alone should be classified as IDV (if verified) or the appropriate pre-negotiation code. RTP requires the conversation to have progressed to active financial negotiation where specific payment options were presented and explicitly refused. A customer who becomes hostile or disengaged before any payment discussion occurs should NOT be classified as RTP.\nFew-shots: Customer rejects $66/month, then rejects $50/month, then says \"I\u2019m not paying anything\" \u2192 RTP. Customer says \"No\" to sharing circumstances but no payment options were discussed yet \u2192 IDV. Customer uses profanity and disconnects before any payment offer \u2192 IDV (not RTP). Customer becomes extremely hostile, uses profanity, AND explicitly says \"I\u2019m not paying\" or \"None\" when offered payment amounts \u2192 RTP (not CPR \u2014 the explicit payment refusal takes precedence over the hostility/complaint aspect).\n\n\n- `RCR`: Description: Recording Consent Refused - Customer explicitly declined consent for the call to be recorded.\nUse when: Customer says \"I do not consent to be recorded,\" \"I don't want to be recorded,\" \"No\" when asked for recording consent, or similar refusal of recording. This applies even if the customer also complains about other issues during the call.\nEdge cases: RCR takes PRIORITY over CPR (Complaint). If a customer refuses recording consent AND also complains about practices, the recording refusal is the primary classification \u2014 use RCR, not CPR. The complaint is secondary to the compliance-critical consent refusal.\nFew-shots: Agent says \"This call is being recorded\" and customer says \"I don't want to be recorded\" \u2192 RCR. Customer says \"No\" when asked for recording consent \u2192 RCR.\n\n\n- `NCV`: Description: Not Convenient - Customer confirmed their identity but indicated current time is inconvenient for financial discussion; no callback timeframe agreed.\nUse when: Customer explicitly says \"now is not a good time,\" \"I can't talk,\" \"I'm busy,\" \"I have to go,\" \"Let's do this later.\" Customer abruptly disengages after confirming identity due to circumstantial factors.\nEdge cases: Identity verified BUT user then disengages due to circumstances \u2192 NCV (not IDV). No specific alternative contact time needed for NCV. Distinguish from CAB: NCV has no agreed future callback; CAB requires a confirmed outbound callback with specific timeframe. If customer says they're busy but STILL engages in conversation (e.g., \"I have a minute, go ahead\"), the call is convenient enough \u2014 do NOT use NCV.\nFew-shots: Customer says \"I'm at work, I can't talk right now\" and hangs up \u2192 NCV. Customer says \"Now is not a good time\" without specifying when to call back \u2192 NCV. Customer says \"I'm busy but go ahead\" and continues talking \u2192 NOT NCV.\n\n\n- `CAB`: Description: Callback Requested - The ACCOUNT HOLDER (or someone confirmed/claimed as the account holder) explicitly requests or agrees to a future outbound callback and the callback arrangement is the clear final disposition of the call.\nUse when: The account holder (confirmed or claimed) requests or agrees to be called back at a specific future time. A \"reasonably specific\" window includes \"tomorrow,\" \"Monday,\" \"next week,\" \"in a couple of weeks,\" \"anytime tomorrow,\" provided the assistant acknowledges and confirms. A timeframe tied to a financial event (e.g., \"call me when I get my check\" + \"in two weeks\") is valid. CAB strictly means scheduling an OUTBOUND call from the agent to the account holder.\nEdge cases: CRITICAL PREREQUISITE \u2014 CAB only applies when the ACCOUNT HOLDER themselves requests a callback. If a THIRD PARTY (someone who is NOT the account holder \u2014 e.g., a spouse, family member, roommate, or unknown person) provides a callback time for reaching the account holder, classify as TPC (Third-Party Contact), NOT CAB. The key distinction: TPC = third party provides info to help reach the account holder; CAB = the account holder schedules their own callback. MANDATORY OVERRIDE \u2014 CAB takes absolute precedence over HCH, RTP, and failed negotiations. If assistant says \"I will call you back on [Timeframe]\" and user agrees, STOP evaluating for Hardship. Once callback is confirmed, it remains the disposition regardless of subsequent administrative turns. Do NOT use CAB for vague statements like \"call me later\" or \"whenever\" where NO timeframe is established.\nFew-shots: Account holder says \"call me back in 2 weeks when I get paid,\" agent confirms \u2192 CAB. Third party says \"She's not here, call back after 7:30\" \u2192 TPC (not CAB). Wife says \"He's not available, try later\" \u2192 TPC (not CAB). Customer mentions job loss but schedules own callback \u2192 CAB (not HCH).\n\n\n- `WCR`: Description: Written Communication Only Requested - Customer requested all future communications be conducted in writing only (mail/email), with no further phone calls.\nUse when: Customer directs phone contact to cease and specifies an alternative written channel. This applies even if prompted by frustration with call frequency, provided the customer specifies writing as the preferred method.\nEdge cases: Distinguish from DNC \u2014 WCR allows written contact; DNC refuses all phone contact but doesn't specify a preference for writing. Distinguish from CDS \u2014 CDS stops ALL communication; WCR redirects to written methods. Distinguish from CPR \u2014 WCR requires a specific demand to cease phone contact in favor of writing only.\nFew-shots: Customer says \"Don't call me, just send everything by mail\" \u2192 WCR. Customer says \"I only want emails, no more phone calls\" \u2192 WCR. Customer says \"Stop calling\" without specifying written preference \u2192 DNC (not WCR).\n\n\n- `CDS`: Description: Cease and Desist - The VERIFIED account holder (IDV passed: name confirmed AND DOB or SSN matched) has explicitly requested complete cessation of ALL communication methods regarding this account, including calls, emails, and texts.\nUse when: ALL THREE conditions are met simultaneously: (1) IDV passed \u2014 caller confirmed name AND DOB or SSN was verified, (2) caller is confirmed as the account holder (not a 3rd party, not a wrong number, not a business), AND (3) caller explicitly requests cessation of ALL communication methods using phrases like \"stop all communication,\" \"cease all contact,\" \"cease and desist,\" or \"remove me from everything.\"\nEdge cases: CRITICAL \u2014 IDV MUST PASS before CDS can apply. If IDV was not completed, failed (DOB denied or refused), or the caller refused to verify \u2014 classify as DNC (not CDS), regardless of how broadly the caller phrases their request. \"Stop all communication\" from an unverified caller = DNC, not CDS. CRITICAL \u2014 Reflection variable `rpc = unknown` means the caller's identity was NOT confirmed \u2014 CDS cannot apply when rpc is unknown. Even if `exc_comms = cease_all` and `exc_comms_confirmed = confirmed`, if rpc is unknown or IDV states (verify_dob, verify_ssn) are absent from list_current_state \u2192 use DNC, NOT CDS. The exc_comms variable records the scope of the request but does NOT confirm identity. CRITICAL \u2014 `third_party = no` does NOT mean the caller is the verified account holder. It only means no third-party pattern was detected. The caller must still pass IDV (rpc must NOT be unknown) for CDS to apply. `third_party = no` + `rpc = unknown` = unidentified caller \u2192 DNC, not CDS. CRITICAL \u2014 If the caller is a confirmed wrong party (said \"This is not the right person,\" denied being the named person, used 3rd-person pronouns, said \"nobody here received a call\") \u2014 classify as WRN (not CDS), even if they say \"restrict all communication\" or use legal cease-and-desist language. Scope language is evaluated ONLY after both identity and IDV gates pass. Distinct from DNC (phone-only stop, no IDV required) and WRN (wrong party, number removed only).\nFew-shots: Wrong party (DOB mismatch, said \"This is not the right person\") says \"Restrict all communication\" \u2192 WRN (not CDS \u2014 wrong party gate fires first). Inbound caller skips IDV, says \"Stop all communication\" \u2192 DNC (not CDS \u2014 IDV not completed). Caller confirms name but DOB denied \u2192 DNC (not CDS \u2014 IDV failed). Verified account holder (name + DOB confirmed) says \"Cease all contact, phone email everything\" \u2192 CDS. Caller who identifies as a business says \"I don't wanna be contacted at all\" \u2192 WRN (not CDS). CRITICAL NEGATIVE EXAMPLE \u2014 Inbound caller says \"Stop calling me\" then \"All communication\" then \"Yes\" (exc_comms=cease_all, exc_comms_confirmed=confirmed, third_party=no) BUT rpc=unknown and list_current_state shows only inbound_opening \u2192 exc_cease_comms with NO verify_dob or verify_ssn states \u2192 DNC (NOT CDS). The absence of IDV states in list_current_state means identity was never verified \u2014 exc_comms_confirmed only records that the caller confirmed their request, NOT that their identity was confirmed.\n\n\n- `CPR`: Description: Complaint Received - Customer expressed dissatisfaction, frustration, or concern regarding their account, collection practices, communication methods, or service experience, whether stated formally or implied through behavior. This includes complaints about confusing or unhelpful notifications (SMS, email, letters), annoyance with automated systems, or dissatisfaction with how they were contacted.\nUse when: Customer is unhappy with lack of notification details, expresses annoyance with SMS/text/email content (e.g., \"The text didn\u2019t say who this was,\" \"I didn\u2019t click the link because it looked like spam\"), rejects provided responses as unhelpful, repeatedly demands a live agent when unavailable, or persistently questions the assistant\u2019s inability to help. Key indicator: dissatisfaction with communication quality or practices WITHOUT disputing the debt itself.\nEdge cases: CRITICAL DISTINCTION FROM DIS \u2014 Complaints about HOW the customer was contacted (confusing texts, unclear notifications, spam-like messages) are CPR, NOT DIS. A customer calling to find out who texted them and expressing frustration about unclear communications is making a complaint about contact quality, not disputing the debt. DIS requires an explicit challenge to the debt\u2019s validity, accuracy, or legitimacy. If the customer expresses willingness to pay or asks for payment details while complaining about communication, this reinforces CPR over DIS. Also distinct from HCH: a customer who is frustrated about communications but not describing financial hardship should be CPR, not HCH.\nFew-shots: Customer says \"I didn\u2019t know who was texting me, the message didn\u2019t include any details\" and asks for payment address \u2192 CPR (not DIS). Customer says \"I wasn\u2019t clicking links because of scams\" but wants to pay \u2192 CPR. Customer repeatedly asks for a live agent and expresses frustration \u2192 CPR.\n\n\n- `HCH`: Description: Hardship Concern - ONLY for LONG-TERM, severe hardships where the consumer sees NO ability to resolve the account in the foreseeable future. HCH means the consumer has NO path forward \u2014 not just \"broke right now.\" IMPORTANT: Do NOT include HCH in your call_code_list if (a) a callback is arranged, OR (b) the customer expresses any willingness to pay in the future. If either condition is true, HCH does not apply at all \u2014 exclude it entirely from your output.\nUse when: ALL conditions must be true: (1) Customer describes a LONG-TERM hardship with no foreseeable end \u2014 permanent job loss, long-term disability, ongoing serious medical condition, homelessness, or chronic financial inability; (2) The customer explicitly conveys they see NO way to pay now or in the near future AND shows no willingness to pay later; (3) NO callback or follow-up arrangement exists in the conversation; (4) The hardship is substantively discussed (not just a passing mention). If ANY of these conditions is false, do NOT include HCH in your call_code_list.\nEdge cases: SHORT-TERM \u2260 HCH. \"I'm broke right now,\" \"I can't pay today,\" \"I don't have a credit card,\" \"I'm going through a separation\" are SHORT-TERM situational difficulties, NOT long-term hardship \u2014 do NOT include HCH. Customer says \"I'll pay when I get a chance\" or \"when things improve\" = willing to pay = NOT HCH \u2014 exclude HCH entirely. If ANY callback is arranged (reflection variable exc_cb_consent=yes, or agent says \"I'll call you back,\" or customer says \"call me back in X\"), completely exclude HCH from your call_code_list \u2014 output CAB instead. Even if the customer describes extreme financial difficulty, if they show ANY willingness to engage later or ANY callback is set, HCH does not belong in the list at all. A brief mention of difficulty (e.g., \"facing difficulties,\" \"got arrested,\" \"family issues\") without substantive long-term hardship discussion \u2192 use IDV (if verified), not HCH.\nFew-shots: Customer describes permanent disability, no income, no prospect of recovery, no callback \u2192 HCH. Customer says \"I'm broke currently\" + callback in 2 weeks \u2192 exclude HCH, use CAB. Customer says \"I can't pay today but I'll pay when I can\" \u2192 exclude HCH (willingness to pay = short-term). Customer explains separation, agrees to callback \u2192 exclude HCH, use CAB. Customer says \"I have no job, no income, no way to pay, and I don't see that changing\" with no callback \u2192 HCH.\n\n\n- `PPA`: Description: Payment Plan Agreed - Customer agreed to a structured payment plan with specific terms (amounts, frequency, and duration) for resolving the debt. Also applies when the customer agreed to pay, the DTMF payment flow was initiated but failed, and the call ended BEFORE a transfer to a live agent was triggered.\nUse when: Customer formally accepts a structured payment arrangement with defined payment amounts and schedule. Customer mentions a payment made within the last 14 days via any channel, providing payment date and amount. Also use when the customer agreed to pay, the system initiated DTMF payment but it failed (e.g., PIN authentication failed, payment instrument retrieval failed), and the call ended/hung up before the system could trigger a transfer to a live agent. The payment was attempted but failed, and no transfer followed.\nEdge cases: Special case \u2014 customer unable to respond at the time and requests later contact \u2192 same PPA classification applies. Requires clear, focused confirmation of payment terms \u2014 casual \"yeah\" or \"okay\" as filler while distracted does NOT qualify. CRITICAL DISTINCTION \u2014 PPA applies when DTMF payment failed AND call ended before transfer was triggered. If transfer WAS triggered \u2192 use TSR (connected) or WFR (busy) instead. If DTMF failed and no transfer and no hang-up \u2192 use FTP.\nFew-shots: Customer agrees to $50/month for 6 months and gets transferred to payment \u2192 PPA. Customer says \"I already paid $100 last week via check\" with details \u2192 PPA. Customer agrees to pay full $500, enters DTMF, PIN fails, call hangs up before transfer is triggered \u2192 PPA (not PPIF, not FTP). Customer says \"yeah, sure\" while talking about unrelated topics \u2192 NOT PPA.\n\n\n- `PPIF`: Description: Promise to Pay in Full - Customer verbally committed to paying 100% of the full outstanding balance in a single payment, with no discounts or settlement reductions. IMPORTANT: Do NOT use PPIF if the call ends with a transfer to a live agent \u2014 when a transfer occurs after a payment failure, the final disposition is TSR, not PPIF.\nUse when: Customer confirms the full amount due and agrees to a specific payment date or time (e.g., \"I'll take care of it later today,\" \"Call me back at noon to get my card\"). Use even if a callback is required to collect payment details or finalize the transaction. PPIF requires that NO transfer to a live agent occurs after the payment commitment.\nEdge cases: CRITICAL \u2014 Do NOT classify as CAB when a clear commitment to pay full balance is made. If the customer commits to paying the full balance AND arranges a callback to provide card details, this is ALWAYS PPIF, never CAB. The payment commitment takes precedence over the callback arrangement. Distinguish from PSIF \u2014 PPIF = 100% original balance; PSIF = discounted/reduced settlement amount. TRANSFER EXCEPTION \u2014 If the customer agreed to pay BUT the system fails to process payment (e.g., \"The system can not retrieve your payment information\") AND the AI agent then transfers to a live agent (\"Let me connect you with a live agent\"), classify as TSR, NOT PPIF. The transfer overrides the payment commitment. Distinguish from PPA \u2014 if the DTMF payment flow was initiated but failed, and the call ended before a transfer to a live agent was triggered, classify as PPA (not PPIF).\nFew-shots: Customer says \"I'll pay the full $393.92 tomorrow\" \u2192 PPIF. Customer says \"Call me back at noon, I'll have my card ready to pay it all\" \u2192 PPIF (not CAB). Customer agrees to pay $248 settlement instead of $352 full balance \u2192 PSIF (not PPIF). Customer agrees to pay full $2112.50, provides PIN 123456, system fails to retrieve payment info, agent says \"Let me connect you with a live agent\" \u2192 TSR (NOT PPIF \u2014 transfer overrides payment commitment). Customer enters DTMF payment flow, payment fails, call hangs up before transfer is triggered \u2192 PPA (not PPIF).\n\n\n- `PSIF`: Description: Promise to Settle in Full - Customer agreed to a discounted settlement offer that will fully resolve the account for less than the original outstanding balance.\nUse when: Customer accepts a reduced settlement amount with a specific payment timeline that fully settles the account. No further payments are required after the agreed discounted amount is paid.\nEdge cases: Distinguish from PPIF \u2014 PSIF = reduced/discounted amount; PPIF = 100% original balance. Full settlement must be confirmed \u2014 account fully resolved with no remaining balance.\nFew-shots: Customer agrees to pay $248 instead of $352.90 full balance to settle \u2192 PSIF. Customer agrees to pay full $352.90 \u2192 PPIF (not PSIF).\n\n\n- `WRN`: Description: Wrong Number - The person who answered or called is confirmed NOT the account holder: they explicitly denied being the intended recipient, identified as a 3rd party or business, stated wrong number, used 3rd-person pronouns about the account holder, denied the DOB/identity while expressing confusion (\"I have no idea what you're talking about\"), or signaled the number is not associated with the account holder. Only the phone number is removed \u2014 no account-level restriction.\nUse when: ANY of these wrong-party signals are present: (a) explicit denial \u2014 \"This is not the right person,\" \"No, I'm not [name],\" \"You have the wrong number,\" (b) 3rd-party pronoun \u2014 \"Take HIM off your list,\" \"She doesn't want contact,\" (c) business identification \u2014 \"This is a business,\" (d) nobody-here signal \u2014 \"Nobody by that name lives here,\" \"There's no [name] here\" \u2014 explicit statement that the named person does not exist at this number, (e) confusion + DOB denial \u2014 caller says \"I have no idea what you're talking about\" after DOB is read (suggests wrong number, not just IDV failure), (f) caller explicitly says \"No\" when asked \"Is this [name]?\". An explicit denial of identity or identification as a wrong party is sufficient regardless of any additional requests (even \"stop all communication\" or \"restrict all communication\" \u2014 scope is irrelevant when caller is confirmed not the account holder). NOTE: ambiguous phrases like \"nobody ever received a call from you\" or \"take me off your list\" without an explicit identity denial \u2192 prefer DNC over WRN (no confirmed wrong-party signal).\nEdge cases: CRITICAL PRIORITY \u2014 WRN TAKES PRIORITY OVER DNC when an explicit wrong-party signal is present. If the caller says \"This is not the right person,\" \"No\" to \"Is this [name]?\", \"wrong number,\" or any equivalent explicit denial \u2014 classify as WRN even if IDV also failed or the caller then requests stop-contact. The wrong-party signal overrides the unverified-identity DNC pattern. CRITICAL \u2014 When a wrong party says \"Restrict all communication,\" \"Stop all contact,\" or uses legal cease-and-desist language \u2014 this is still WRN, NOT CDS and NOT DNC. A confirmed wrong party CANNOT authorize account-level restrictions regardless of what they request. The identity gate fires before the scope gate. CRITICAL \u2014 When a caller denies the DOB AND expresses confusion (\"I have no idea what you're talking about\"), treat as wrong-party \u2192 WRN (not IDF or DNC), because the denial signals they are not the account holder. Distinct from DNC (unknown-identity inbound caller with NO explicit wrong-party signal \u2014 prefer DNC only when there is no clear evidence the caller is not the account holder).\nFew-shots: Outbound call, DOB mismatch, caller says \"This is not the right person\" then \"Restrict all communication\" \u2192 WRN (not CDS \u2014 wrong party gate fires first, scope irrelevant). Outbound, AI asks \"Is this [name]?\" \u2014 caller says \"No. Don't call again.\" \u2192 WRN. Caller confirms name but says \"That DOB is totally incorrect, I have no idea what you're talking about. Leave me alone.\" \u2192 WRN (complete confusion + DOB denial signals wrong party, not failed IDV). Inbound caller says \"Take my number off the list, this is a business\" \u2192 WRN. Caller says \"You have the wrong number\" \u2192 WRN. Caller says \"Nobody by that name lives here\" \u2192 WRN.\n\n\n- `TPC`: Description: Third-Party Contact - Person other than the account holder provided information or context to help reach the intended recipient, including callback times or availability windows.\nUse when: Third party acknowledges knowing the account holder. Third party provides alternative phone number, address, availability time, or any contextual detail about the recipient. Third party offers to relay messages or suggests future contact times. Third party provides a callback time or availability window for reaching the account holder (e.g., \"call back after 7:30,\" \"she'll be home in the morning\").\nEdge cases: Distinguish from WRN \u2014 TPC requires explicit evidence of a relationship (acknowledging knowing the person, providing info about them). Even vague or incomplete info that aids in locating the recipient qualifies as TPC. No relationship evidence \u2192 WRN. CRITICAL DISTINCTION FROM CAB \u2014 If a third party (not the account holder) provides a callback time for reaching the account holder, this is TPC, NOT CAB. CAB requires the account holder themselves to schedule a callback. A third party arranging a callback time is providing information to reach the recipient, which is the core function of TPC.\nFew-shots: Person says \"He's not here, try calling after 5pm\" \u2192 TPC (not CAB). Wife says \"He's not available, call back later\" \u2192 TPC (not CAB). Person says \"That's my son, I'll tell him you called\" \u2192 TPC. Sister calls and agent arranges callback for 9am \u2192 TPC (not CAB). Person says \"I don't know that person, wrong number\" \u2192 WRN (not TPC).\n\n\n- `FRA`: Description: Fraud Reported - Customer claims the account was opened fraudulently, through identity theft, or without their knowledge or consent.\nUse when: Customer explicitly alleges fraud or identity theft. Customer categorically denies the account's existence or their responsibility for creating it (even without using the word \"fraud\").\nEdge cases: Distinguish from DIS \u2014 FRA = customer denies they ever created/owned the account; DIS = disputes accuracy or balance of a recognized account. Categorical denial of account ownership \u2192 FRA (not DIS). Requires immediate escalation for fraud investigation.\nFew-shots: Customer says \"I never opened that account, someone stole my identity\" \u2192 FRA. Customer says \"I have no connection to this debt whatsoever\" \u2192 FRA. Customer says \"The balance is wrong, I already paid some\" \u2192 DIS (not FRA).\n\n\n- `DNC`: Description: Do Not Call - The caller (NOT a business or clearly wrong number) has requested to be removed from phone contact lists or to cease calls to the specific phone number. Identity verification is NOT required for DNC \u2014 an angry caller demanding \"stop calling\" is sufficient.\nUse when: Caller says \"stop calling,\" \"don't call this number,\" \"put me on your do not call list.\" Formal or informal/frustrated language qualifies equally. DNC applies even if the caller refuses to confirm their name \u2014 the explicit demand to stop phone calls is the primary signal. If the assistant interprets the statement as an opt-out request, this supports DNC. Applies specifically to phone contact at this number \u2014 differs from CDS (all communication).\nEdge cases: DNC overrides NVR and HUA when the caller explicitly demands to stop calls. If the caller refuses to verify identity AND demands \"stop calling,\" classify as DNC (not NVR). CRITICAL \u2014 When rpc = unknown (caller identity not confirmed) AND exc_comms = cease_all, classify as DNC (not CDS). An unidentified caller requesting \"all communication\" stopped cannot authorize account-level CDS \u2014 only a verified account holder can. Even if exc_comms_confirmed = confirmed, if rpc is unknown \u2192 DNC. CRITICAL \u2014 An unidentified inbound caller saying \"Stop calling me\" or \"Take me off your list. All.\" with no IDV \u2192 DNC (not CDS). The scope of the request (this number vs all communication) is irrelevant when the caller is unidentified \u2014 DNC applies to the number regardless. EXCEPTION: If the caller identifies as a BUSINESS or explicitly denies being the account holder AND says the person doesn't live there (e.g., \"There's no [Name] here, stop calling\"), classify as WRN \u2014 the number is simply wrong. DNC is for callers who COULD be the account holder (didn't deny it) but refuse to engage and want calls stopped.\nFew-shots: Caller says \"I don't give a damn. Stop calling my damn phone\" without confirming name \u2192 DNC (not NVR). Caller says \"Don't call this damn phone again\" \u2192 DNC. CRITICAL PATTERN \u2014 Inbound caller says \"Stop calling me\" \u2192 \"All communication\" \u2192 \"Yes\" with rpc=unknown, exc_comms=cease_all, exc_comms_confirmed=confirmed, third_party=no, AND list_current_state=[inbound_opening, exc_cease_comms, exc_cease_comms, ...] (no verify_dob or verify_ssn states present) \u2192 DNC (NOT CDS). Reasoning: list_current_state shows the call went from opening directly to communication restriction \u2014 IDV was never attempted. exc_comms_confirmed=confirmed means the caller confirmed their STOP REQUEST, not their identity. rpc=unknown confirms identity was never established. Despite third_party=no, the caller is still unidentified. Inbound caller says \"Nobody ever received a call. Take me off your list. All.\" with no identity denial \u2192 DNC (no confirmed wrong-party signal, identity unknown). Caller says \"This is a business, take my number off the list\" \u2192 WRN (not DNC). Caller says \"There's no Robin here, stop calling\" \u2192 WRN (not DNC \u2014 wrong number). Verified account holder (IDV passed) says \"Stop all communication\" \u2192 CDS (not DNC \u2014 IDV passed and scope is all communication).\n\n\n- `DIS`: Description: Debt Disputed - The customer explicitly challenged the accuracy, validity, or legitimacy of the debt itself. This includes explicitly stating the debt is not theirs, the amount is wrong, previous payments are not reflected, or asserting the debt is void, canceled, settled, or legally discharged. This code also applies if the customer challenges the creditor's right to collect or the legality of the debt transfer (e.g., \"sold without consent\"). DIS takes precedence over CAB if the customer disputes the debt even if a callback is scheduled.\nUse when: Customer explicitly states the debt is not theirs, the amount is wrong, previous payments are not reflected, or asserts the debt is void/canceled/settled. Also applies when customer claims not to recognize the amount or implies the balance is incorrect (e.g., \"I wasn't aware it was that much\"). If a customer requests to stop contact specifically because they dispute the debt (e.g., \"Stop calling, I don't owe this\"), classify as DIS.\nEdge cases: CRITICAL \u2014 Do NOT classify as DIS if the customer is merely complaining about HOW they were contacted (confusing texts, unclear SMS, spam-looking links). Asking for details because a notification lacked specifics is a communication complaint (CPR), NOT a dispute. A dispute must be an explicit challenge to the DEBT ITSELF \u2014 its existence, amount, validity, or legitimacy. Also do NOT classify as DIS for \"sticker shock\" (e.g., \"Wow, that's a lot\") without questioning accuracy. Do NOT apply if customer made a payment within the last 14 days. If the customer expresses willingness to pay (e.g., \"I was gonna pay\") while complaining about notifications, this is strong evidence AGAINST DIS \u2014 use CPR instead.\nFew-shots: Customer says \"I don't owe this money\" \u2192 DIS. Customer says \"The text didn't say who this was for\" but asks for payment address \u2192 CPR (not DIS). Customer says \"I wasn't aware it was that much\" \u2192 DIS.\n\n\n- `CSM`: Description: SCRA Coverage Reported - Customer verified active military service status invoking Servicemembers Civil Relief Act protections.\nUse when: Customer provides details about military service (branch, status, anticipated service period) invoking SCRA protections. SCRA protections include interest rate caps, foreclosure prevention, and other accommodations that must be immediately applied.\nEdge cases: N/A\nFew-shots: Customer says \"I'm active duty military, you need to apply SCRA protections\" \u2192 CSM. Customer says \"I'm deployed overseas with the Army\" \u2192 CSM.\n\n\n- `PRS`: Description: In Prison - Customer or third party confirmed that the account holder is CURRENTLY incarcerated in a correctional facility.\nUse when: Incarceration in a correctional facility is confirmed as a CURRENT, ongoing status. Specific facility name or release date not required.\nEdge cases: PRS takes precedence over financial codes if both are mentioned. CRITICAL \u2014 PRS requires CURRENT incarceration. Past-tense references to arrest or jail (e.g., \"I got arrested\" as an explanation for default circumstances) do NOT qualify if the customer is clearly not currently incarcerated (e.g., they are on the phone freely discussing the account). Use the surrounding context to determine if the arrest is current or historical.\nFew-shots: Customer says \"I'm currently in jail\" \u2192 PRS. Third party says \"He's incarcerated at the county jail right now\" \u2192 PRS. Customer says \"I got arrested\" as an explanation for why they defaulted, but is freely conversing on the phone \u2192 NOT PRS (use IDV or appropriate code based on conversation outcome).\n\n\n- `LGH`: Description: Legal Guardian Handling - A legally authorized guardian is managing the account holder's affairs due to the account holder's incapacity or death.\nUse when: Guardian provides verifiable information about their legal relationship and authority to discuss the account. Third party presents power of attorney (POA) or demonstrates legal authority over the account. Communication must be directed exclusively to this authorized representative.\nEdge cases: Distinguish from ATY \u2014 use LGH for general guardian/POA scenarios; use ATY when a specific attorney or legal counsel is mentioned. Distinguish from TPC \u2014 LGH requires demonstrated legal authority (guardian, POA); TPC is any third party providing info without legal standing.\nFew-shots: Third party calls with power of attorney, negotiates settlement on account holder's behalf \u2192 LGH. \"She's deceased... her daughter has financial power of attorney\" \u2192 LGH. Agent confirms caller has power of attorney over incapacitated account holder \u2192 LGH.\n\n\n- `ATY`: Description: Attorney Representation - Customer stated they have retained or are seeking legal counsel, or legal representation is indicated through any signal in the conversation.\nUse when: Customer mentions \"my attorney,\" \"I'm getting a lawyer,\" \"my attorney has contacted you,\" or references a POA/legal authority. Agent prompts caller for proof of POA or legal representation documentation. Multiple or repeated references to an attorney, even if brief or fragmented. Consumer indicates attorney involvement even indirectly or amidst emotional distress.\nEdge cases: ATY takes priority over ALL other codes including RTP. Fragmented speech about attorney (\"her attorney,\" even amidst distress) still qualifies \u2014 scan the ENTIRE conversation for any mention of \"attorney,\" \"lawyer,\" or \"legal counsel.\" Agent's prompt for POA is a secondary signal even if caller gives unclear response. Distinguish from LGH \u2014 ATY = specific attorney/legal counsel mentioned; LGH = general guardian without specific attorney reference. CRITICAL DISTINCTION FROM DSA \u2014 If the customer uses the word \"lawyer\" or \"attorney\" ANYWHERE in their description, classify as ATY even if they also mention debt consolidation/settlement context. \"Debt consolidation LAWYER\" = ATY (the word \"lawyer\" is the decisive signal). Only use DSA if the customer names a financial program/agency WITHOUT any mention of a lawyer or attorney.\nFew-shots: Customer says \"Talk to my lawyer\" \u2192 ATY. Customer says \"I turned my account over to a debt consolidate lawyer\" \u2192 ATY (word \"lawyer\" overrides \"debt consolidate\"). Fragmented speech \"on her journey... her attorney\" \u2192 ATY. Customer says \"I'm working with National Debt Relief\" (no mention of lawyer) \u2192 DSA (not ATY).\n\n\n- `BKP`: Description: Bankruptcy Pending - Customer reported current bankruptcy proceedings or intent to file bankruptcy that would include this account.\nUse when: Customer provides specific bankruptcy details (case number, chapter, filing date) or states intent to file. Triggers immediate cessation of collection activities per automatic stay provisions.\nEdge cases: Requires verification with bankruptcy court records. Intent to file is sufficient even without specific details.\nFew-shots: Customer says \"I filed Chapter 7 last month, case number 12345\" \u2192 BKP. Customer says \"I'm about to file for bankruptcy\" \u2192 BKP.\n\n\n- `NNP`: Description: Negotiated No Payment - Customer passed identity verification, at least one specific payment option was offered by the agent, customer clearly declined the offered option(s) without using explicit refusal language, expressed no hardship or dispute, and the call ended without a payment commitment.\nUse when: ALL of the following must be true: (1) Customer verified identity successfully, (2) the agent offered at least one specific payment amount or plan, (3) customer clearly declined or said \"No\" to the offered amount(s), (4) customer did NOT use explicit refusal language (e.g., \"I won't pay,\" \"I refuse to pay,\" \"I will never pay\"), (5) no hardship or financial difficulty was expressed, (6) no dispute was raised about the debt, and (7) the call ended with no payment arrangement.\nEdge cases: CRITICAL DISTINCTION FROM IDV \u2014 If the customer gave non-committal responses (\"possibly,\" \"maybe,\" \"I'm not sure,\" \"I'll think about it\") without clearly declining, use IDV (not NNP). If the customer declined to share personal circumstances or explain default reasons but no specific payment amounts were offered and declined, use IDV (not NNP). CRITICAL \u2014 NNP requires the customer's explicit decline to be PRESENT AND VISIBLE in the conversation. If the conversation ends after a payment offer with no customer response shown, the customer did NOT decline \u2014 use IDV (not NNP). Do NOT infer a decline from a truncated or incomplete conversation. NNP requires a CLEAR DECLINE of at least one specific offer \u2014 vague, ambiguous, non-committal responses, or absent responses do NOT qualify. CRITICAL DISTINCTION FROM RTP \u2014 RTP requires explicit, unambiguous refusal language (\"I refuse,\" \"I won't pay,\" \"I will never pay\"). Simply saying \"No\" to offered amounts is NNP, not RTP. CRITICAL DISTINCTION FROM HCH \u2014 If the customer mentions any hardship language (job loss, medical issues, financial difficulty, inability to afford), classify as HCH, not NNP. CRITICAL DISTINCTION FROM DIS \u2014 If the customer challenges the debt's validity, existence, or amount, classify as DIS, not NNP. If mixed signals appear (hardship AND refusal together), assign HCH.\nFew-shots: Agent offers $76/month, customer says \"No,\" agent offers $61/month, customer deflects and call ends with no commitment \u2192 NNP. Agent offers $66/month, customer clearly says \"No\" to that offer and call ends \u2192 NNP (customer explicitly responded to the payment offer). Customer declines all payment options saying \"I just can't do those amounts right now\" with no hardship or refusal language \u2192 NNP. Customer verified, declines to share circumstances of default, no payment amounts offered \u2192 IDV (not NNP \u2014 no payment negotiation occurred). Customer says \"Possibly\" or \"Maybe\" to a payment offer without declining \u2192 IDV (not NNP \u2014 non-committal is not a decline). Customer verified, payment amount mentioned but conversation ends before customer clearly declines \u2192 IDV (not NNP \u2014 no clear decline visible). Agent asks about default circumstances, customer says \"No\" (declining to share circumstances), agent then offers monthly payment amount, conversation ends with no further customer response \u2192 IDV (not NNP \u2014 the \"No\" was about sharing circumstances, not a response to the payment offer; no customer response to the offer is shown). Customer says \"I refuse to pay this\" \u2192 RTP (not NNP \u2014 explicit refusal). Customer says \"I lost my job, I can't pay\" \u2192 HCH (not NNP \u2014 hardship language present).\n\n\n- `DSA`: Description: Debt Settlement Agreement - Customer indicates they are working with a third-party debt settlement, consolidation, or relief program to manage their debt.\nUse when: Customer explicitly or implicitly directs agent to contact a named debt relief/settlement program (Beyond Finance, National Debt Relief, Debt Solutions, etc.). Customer states \"a company is handling that for me\" or \"check with my debt negotiator.\" Consumer or representative claims they are working with a program for debt/credit settlement, consolidation, relief, management, or financial solutions.\nEdge cases: Distinguish from ATY \u2014 DSA = financial relief/settlement program; ATY = law office or attorney. If third party is not explicitly identified as a law office, assume it is a debt settlement service. Directing agent to contact a named debt relief agency is sufficient signal regardless of explicit confirmation. Do not let identity verification attempts or other conversational elements distract from settlement agency signals. Do not let the assistant\u2019s mention of \"attorney\" trigger ATY if the consumer only identifies a financial program.\nFew-shots: Customer says \"You need to call National Debt Relief, they\u2019re handling my account\" \u2192 DSA. Customer says \"A company is managing my debts\" \u2192 DSA. Customer says \"Talk to my lawyer about this\" \u2192 ATY (not DSA).\n\n\n\n\n\n## Reflection Variable Descriptions\n```\n- `mini_miranda`: <Determine whether _assistant has delivered the mini-Miranda statement in full - \"This is an attempt to collect a debt by a debt collector. Any information obtained will be used for that purpose.\" ONLY consider whether or not _assistant has completed this statement; it does not matter what _user said.>\n  + `yes` : This mini-Miranda statement has been delivered in full by _assistant without any interruption by _user, \"This is an attempt to collect a debt by a debt collector. Any information obtained will be used for that purpose.\"\n  + `no` : This statement has either not been delivered, or interrupted or otherwise only partially delivered.\n- `willing_to_pay`:\n  + `yes` : The consumer clearly expresses **intent** or **willingness** to resolve the debt. This includes any statement or request to **make a payment**, **arrange a payment plan** (e.g., \"I want to pay,\" \"Can I make a payment?,\" \"Let's set up a payment plan,\" or any opening statement inquiring about resolution options).\n  + `no` : The consumer does not express any intent or willingness to resolve the debt.\n  + `settlement` : The consumer explicitly discusses a **settlement** offer or agreement, indicating their intent to continue with settlement amounts and terms. (e.g. \"I agree to settle, \", \"Some settlement or something.\")\n- `promise`: <Captures _user's commitment to pay, refusal to pay, or an unresolved stance. A clear refusal (`no`) or firm commitment (`yes`) made during the conversation overrides any prior ambiguity or hedging.>\n  + `yes` : _user has clearly agreed to a specific payment plan or resolution, or has confirmed a past payment was made. For a promise to be `yes`, _user must first demonstrate awareness of the debt being discussed.\n    -- A `yes` is indicated when _user agrees to the financial terms of a proposed plan (e.g., \"Yes, that's okay,\" \"That works for me\"). This applies even if they subsequently request a procedural step like a transfer to an agent to finalize the transaction.\n    -- This includes confirmations of past payments (e.g., \"I already sent it,\" \"I mailed the check yesterday\"), as they represent a firm commitment to the debt's resolution.\n    -- A user's counter-proposal or conditional offer is only considered a `yes` once _assistant explicitly accepts or confirms the new terms.\n  + `no` : _user has explicitly stated a definitive inability or unwillingness to make **any** payment towards the debt, or has definitively rejected the obligation entirely. This requires that _user understands the context of the debt being discussed.\n    -- This applies only to unambiguous, complete rejections of payment (e.g., \"I can't pay anything,\" \"I will not pay,\" \"I'm not working and have no income\").\n    -- Rejecting a specific plan proposed by _assistant while offering an alternative or continuing to negotiate is **not** a `no`; this is considered an unresolved negotiation and should be labeled `unknown`. A `no` indicates _user has stopped negotiating and is refusing to pay.\n    -- This does not apply if _user says \"No\" in response to a non-payment, administrative question (e.g., agent: \"Is there anything else?\", user: \"No.\").\n  + `unknown` : _user's intent regarding payment is genuinely ambiguous, conditional and unresolved, or otherwise unclear. This is the default if the strict preconditions for `yes` or `no` are not met.\n    -- **Contextual Confusion:** If _user expresses significant confusion about the caller's identity, the debt's origin, or their obligation (e.g., \"Who are you?\", \"What is this for?\"), their intent is `unknown` until they acknowledge the debt.\n    -- **Unresolved Negotiations:** A promise is `unknown` during an active negotiation where terms have not been mutually agreed upon. This includes:\n      --- _user rejects _assistant's plan but proposes a counter-offer (e.g., a different amount or timeframe).\n      --- The negotiation is deadlocked because _user's offer is below _assistant's stated minimum, but _user has not withdrawn their intent to pay.\n      --- The conversation ends on _user's counter-offer or clarifying question before _assistant can respond.\n    -- **Pre-agreement Agent Request:** The intent is `unknown` if _user requests to speak to _assistant *before* or *instead of* agreeing to proposed financial terms.\n    -- **No Active Obligation:** This category is used when no explicit promise or refusal is made, if the account is already marked as resolved, or if the conversation does not concern _user's direct financial obligation (e.g., _user is not the debtor).\n- `amount` : The total amount of payment in **dollars** that _user clearly and finally commits to pay, expressed as a NUMBER and unit of currency (e.g., '1038 dollars' or '100.42 dollars'). Always use the decimal number, including cents, as a single value with two decimal places if applicable\u2014do **not** express cents as separate terms. For example, return \"650.45 dollars\" instead of \"650 dollars 45 cents.\".\nWhen the assistant proposes an amount that includes cents (e.g., \"six hundred and fifty dollars and forty-five cents\") or a numeric value with cents, the amount variable MUST reflect the full decimal value\u2014e.g., \"650.45 dollars\".\nA commitment is only considered final when _user unambiguously agrees to a specific proposal from _assistant; a _user proposal or counter-offer is not a final commitment until confirmed by both parties. Follow this strict order of priority:\n  1. **Agreed Settlement Amount (Highest Priority):** If _user agrees to a specific **settlement** amount proposed by the assistant, use that settlement amount. This takes highest priority over any other balances or calculations.\n    -- Agreement includes asking about payment terms for the proposed settlement (e.g., \"Can I pay that $1038.55 settlement in three months?\"). This counts as agreement to the total settlement amount.\n    -- Agreement followed by a request to speak with a live agent to finalize details (e.g., \"Yes, I agree to that. But let me talk to an agent.\") is still considered a final commitment to the agreed-upon amount.\n  2. **Agreed Plan to Pay Full Balance:** If no settlement was agreed upon and _user agrees to a payment plan explicitly proposed by _assistant to resolve their \"full balance,\" use the full outstanding balance, `seven hundred and thirty-nine dollars and seventeen cents`. This variable MUST reflect a decimal value (e.g., \"650.45 dollars\") if cents are present. The commitment is to resolve the full balance, even if the installment terms (e.g., \"$190 for 24 months\") calculate to a different total.\n  3. **Calculated Total from an Agreed Plan:** If _user agrees to a payment plan defined by both an installment amount and a duration (e.g., \"Yes, I agree to $100.55 for 12 months\") and the plan is NOT explicitly for a settlement (Rule 1) or the full balance (Rule 2), you MUST calculate the total amount by multiplying the installment by the duration. Use this calculated total as a decimal value if applicable (e.g., 1200.50 dollars).\n  4. **Agreement by Reference:** If _user agrees to a specific amount proposed by the assistant using referential language (e.g., \"I'll pay that amount,\" \"I wanna make the same number for that one\"), use the specific amount mentioned by _assistant, in decimal format if expressed that way, with priority given to Rules 1\u20133.\n  5. **No Final Commitment (Return 'unknown'):** Return 'unknown' if no clear and final commitment to a total amount is made according to the rules above. This is the default if no higher-priority rule applies. This includes:\n    -- **_user Proposals or Counter-offers:** A _user's statement of what they *can* or *want* to pay (e.g., \"I can do $500,\" \"I want to do $200 for 24 months\") is a proposal, NOT a final commitment until the assistant accepts it and _user re-confirms.\n    -- **Contradictory or Conditional Agreement:** An agreement immediately followed by a negation (e.g., \"Yes. No...\") or a condition that cannot be met at the time of the call (e.g., \"Yes, but it has to be next month because my account was tampered with\") voids the commitment.\n    -- **Vague Intent:** Vague promises (e.g., \"I'll pay next week\") are not a commitment to a specific amount.\n    -- **Temporary or \"Keep-in-Touch\" Plans:** An agreement to a short-term, temporary, or partial plan (e.g., \"$50 for 3 months to keep the account current\") is not a commitment to a final total amount.\n    -- **Voided Intent / Rejection:** If a _user states a specific amount, then rejects a subsequent, different proposal, the original amount is voided. If _user rejects all options or withdraws a previous commitment, the commitment is voided. Only the last firmly agreed-upon amount should be used.\n- `first_date` : The specific calendar date (YYYY-MM-DD) when _user expresses a clear and confirmed intention to make their **first** payment, whether it's an initial payment or the first of installments. A \"clear and confirmed intention\" is a direct commitment to *pay on* a specific date, not a promise to call back to arrange a payment or an agreement to an offer with a payment deadline (e.g., 'must be paid by [Date]'). \n  -- The extracted date must always be on or after Today (2026-05-11, which is Monday). The date can be an absolute date (e.g., \"December 15th\") or a relative term (e.g., \"next Monday,\" \"the 30th\"). All relative dates must be calculated as the *next upcoming calendar occurrence* from Today. **Strictly enforce this rule for day-of-week terms:** \"next [Day of Week]\" (e.g., \"next Friday\") must resolve to the single chronologically closest upcoming occurrence of that day. For example, if Today is Tuesday, \"next Friday\" is the Friday of the current week (3 days away), not the Friday of the following week. \n  -- **Strictly enforce futurity for day-of-month terms:** for instance, if Today is the 20th and _user says \"the 15th\" (providing only a day number), the date must resolve to the 15th of the *following* month. This also includes correctly resolving year rollovers for future dates (e.g., 'January 4th' stated in December resolves to January of the *next* calendar year). If _user agrees to pay immediately, they must explicitly state 'today', 'right now', or 'now' to resolve to Today's date (2026-05-11); do not infer immediacy from a general intent to pay (e.g., \"I'm calling to make a payment\") or from agreement to a settlement offer that lacks a specific timing component. \n  -- If the consumer changes their mind or a stated date is unviable, return the *most recent confirmed and viable* payment date. Do not carry over a day of the month from a previously invalidated or past date unless _user explicitly confirms it in their new commitment; for example, if a payment for 'the 15th' is invalidated because it is in the past, and _user then says 'next month', the date is 'unknown' because the day '15th' was not re-confirmed. \n  -- Return 'unknown' if: \n    (1) _user explicitly refuses to pay or denies payment details; \n    (2) _user makes no commitment to a specific calendar date, which includes providing a vague timeframe (e.g., \"sometime next week,\" \"in January,\" \"next month\" without a confirmed day), a general intent lacking a date (e.g., \"I'll make a payment\"), or a commitment to call back to arrange a payment (e.g., \"I will call you back next Friday to start payments\"); \n    (3) _user agrees to an offer with a deadline (e.g., \"must be paid before Dec 13th\") but does not commit to a specific day *for* the transaction; \n    (4) any stated date is unconfirmed, ambiguous, or invalidated. A date is considered ambiguous if _user's intent is unclear due to fragmented sentences (e.g., \"...on the first... pardon?\") or garbled/non-sequitur responses where a number's meaning as a date is not certain (e.g., _user says \"Lease number eleven\" when asked for a date). A date is invalidated if it has already passed (e.g., stating \"November 5th\" when Today is November 13th), contradicts an agreed-upon timeframe, or is mentioned in the past tense (e.g., \"I was paying on the 1st\"). Do not roll invalidated past dates to the next year. \n  -- This variable is ONLY for the first Promise-to-Pay date; do NOT extract other entity types; focus strictly on the initial payment commitment.\n- `months` : the NUMBER of months for installments. \n  -- Use the duration explicitly stated by _user or the inclusive count of months in a confirmed timeline (e.g., \"starting in January and settling in March\" is \"3\"). If _user agrees to, proposes, or counter-offers a specific monthly dollar amount (including saying \"Yes\" to a plan proposed by _assistant, agreeing to \"continue\" an existing plan, or stating an amount like \"One hundred\" in response to a monthly payment discussion) but no specific duration is mentioned, you MUST calculate the value, by dividing the total balance mentioned by _assistant by that monthly amount and round up to the nearest whole number. \n  -- Return \"1\" ONLY for an explicit commitment to pay the full balance or a settlement in a single installment that is specifically scheduled for \"today\", \"now\", \"all at once\", or \"one-time\"; do not return \"1\" for a general expression of intent to pay (e.g., \"I'm calling to make a payment,\" \"I want to settle\") unless a specific timing for a single payment is confirmed. \n  -- Return \"unknown\" if _user agrees to a total settlement amount or expresses a desire to pay but does not specify a timeframe (\"now\", \"today\", \"one-time\") or number of payments, or if _user requests a human representative or ends the call BEFORE any specific amount or duration is agreed upon. If an agreement on a duration or monthly amount is reached, return that value even if _user subsequently requests a human representative, UNLESS the agreement is immediately followed by a contradiction, hedge, or statement of financial hardship that indicates _user cannot actually fulfill the obligation (e.g., \"Yes, but I don't have the money right now\"), iall by Automatic Speech Recognition (ASR). The text may contain typos, recognition errors, missing punctuation, or incomplete sentences.\n- The collection agent is marked as \"assistant|agent|bot\", and the caller is marked as \"user|customer|human\".\n- Available call codes below are the codes you can output; definitions and descriptions are authoritative.\n- Use only MASTER codes from the source-of-truth call-disposition reference. Do not use external alias code systems.\n\n# Instruction:\n- Read ## Call Code Descriptions first, then ## Conversation History.\n- Use user utterances as primary evidence of intent. Use assistant prompts only to interpret what the user is responding to.\n- Select only codes supported by evidence in the transcript to reflect the latest intent of the caller/ customer. Output 1 to 3 codes.\n- Prefer concise reasoning tied to explicit transcript evidence and code definitions.\n- Respect code boundaries and stage context (Phone Number / Pre-IDV / Post-IDV).\n- Prioritize call codes that reflect the latest intent of the caller/ customer of the call. Explicitly stated intent is more important than implicit intent.\n- If user updated their intent, update the call code accordingly. For example, if user requests to speak to a live agent, and then changes their mind and agrees to continue the conversation, update the call code to the latest intent. Or if user expressed harship (HCH), but the agreed to pay and went through with payment --> the PAY is valid, drop the HCH as HCH is no longer valid.\n- Stage guidance: treat as Post-IDV only when identity verification is completed (or Mini-Miranda appears, typically after successful IDV). Otherwise stay in Phone Number / Pre-IDV space.\n- If available, use ### Reflection Variable Descriptions and Values for additional context, reasoning for your decision. \n- Output plain text wrapped in XML tags exactly as shown in # Output.\n\n#  Notes:\n- Make sure the reasoning is clear, specific, and grounded to the conversation history and the call code descriptions.\n- Consider alternatives, but do not over-label when evidence is weak.\n- The call code is used to capture the latest status of the call, and use to plan the next action of the call.\n\n# Input Information\n## Call Code Descriptions\n- `PIF`: Description: Paid in Full - Customer paid full balance.\nUse when: Customer successfully paid the full outstanding balance during the call.\nEdge cases: Distinguish from PAY \u2014 PAY is any successful in-call payment and may be partial; PIF requires the total overdue balance to be paid successfully during the call. Distinguish from PPIF/FDP \u2014 those are promises or scheduled future payments, not completed in-call payment.\nFew-shots: Customer agrees to pay the full overdue balance, the payment is processed successfully during the call \u2192 PIF. Customer makes only a partial successful payment \u2192 PAY (not PIF). Customer promises to pay full balance later \u2192 PPIF or FDP (not PIF).\n\n- `TLM`: Description: Transfer Loan Modification - Verified customer requests loan-modification assistance that is beyond AI capability. Transfer to Collections representative.\nUse when: Customer asks for loan-modification options, terms restructuring, payment-term change outside supported AI flow, or explicitly requests a specialist for loan modification.\nEdge cases: Tie-break vs EPT \u2014 use EPT when the limitation is payment assistance capability (amount/method/payment handling). Use TLM when the request is specifically about loan modification options. Tie-break vs HTT \u2014 use HTT only when a technical/system failure blocks completion; use TLM when there is no system failure and the request is business-support escalation.\nFew-shots: Customer says \"I need loan modification options, please transfer me\" \u2192 TLM. Customer asks to restructure loan terms beyond bot capability \u2192 TLM.\n\n- `FDP`: Description: Future Dated Payment - Verified customer commits to a SPECIFIC FUTURE DATE to pay the FULL balance in a single payment.\nUse when both (a) a specific calendar date in the future is named (\"Friday the 25th\", \"next Tuesday\", \"May 10th\"), AND (b) full-balance commitment is given for that date.\nDTMF capture is the typical flow but NOT REQUIRED \u2014 agreed-and-scheduled future-dated payment counts as FDP even if card collection is deferred to a callback or a transfer to a specialist. The bot's transfer-to-specialist does NOT downgrade FDP to TSR; if the user gave a specific future date and full-balance commitment, FDP is the primary code.\nDistinct from: PAY (same-day completed), PPA (structured multi-installment plan), PPIF (commit to pay full but NO specific date), TSR (bare transfer request without future-date commitment), EPT (partial today, not full-future).\n\n- `TPM`: Description: Third-Party Message - A third party answers and the agent leaves a message for the account holder without disclosing account details.\nUse when: Non-account-holder confirms target person is unavailable, and agent leaves a compliant callback/return-call message with no account disclosure.\nEdge cases: Tie-break vs TPC \u2014 TPC requires third party providing new contact details or actionable recipient-location info; TPM is message-left behavior only. Tie-break vs LM \u2014 LM is voicemail/answering-system path; TPM is a live third-party human interaction.\nFew-shots: Third party says \"He's not here,\" agent leaves callback request \u2192 TPM. Family member answers and agrees to pass message, no account details shared \u2192 TPM.\n\n- `ECH`: Description: Robot Call - Pre-recorded call or IVR detected. No human response received. No message left and no transfer initiated.\nUse when: Pre-recorded message or IVR system answers (including iOS call screening). No human picks up.\nEdge cases: Tie-break vs NKP \u2014 ECH = IVR/pre-recorded system detected; NKP = silent connection with no IVR signal.\nFew-shots: Call answered by \"Thank you for calling XYZ, press 1 for...\" \u2192 ECH. iOS call screening intercepts the call with automated response \u2192 ECH.\n\n- `HTT`: Description: Technical Issue Transfer - Any API call or technical process failure during the call prevents the AI agent from completing the collections interaction. Transfer to human Collections agent.\nUse when: Any system failure (including /pay API errors) prevents the AI from running the collections interaction normally.\nEdge cases: CRITICAL \u2014 Use HTT for system/technical failures. Use EPT when the failure is due to payment scope limitations (amount or method beyond AI capability), not a technical error.\nFew-shots: /pay API fails mid-call and AI cannot complete the interaction \u2192 HTT. System error prevents account retrieval \u2192 HTT.\n\n- `EPT`: Description: Elevated Payment Transfer - Verified customer offers a partial payment AND asks for human/specialist help on the remainder of the balance. Bot transfers to Collections.\nUse when both (a) a specific partial-pay amount or partial-pay willingness is in the user's turns (\"I can pay $X today\"), AND (b) a request for a human/specialist for the rest of the balance.\nEven if the bot completes the transfer (\"connecting you to a live agent\"), the primary code is EPT \u2014 the user's intent is partial-payment scope, NOT bare transfer. EPT is preferred over TSR whenever partial-pay framing is present in the transcript.\nDistinct from: HTT (system/API failure, not user-side scope), TLM (loan-modification request, not partial-pay-this-cycle), TSR (bare human-agent request with NO partial-pay framing), FDP (future-dated full payment, not partial today).\n\n- `DCP`: Description: Already Paid (other channel, same day) - Customer states that today's payment was made via a channel OTHER than this call's DTMF (online portal, prior agent, check, bank transfer). The AI does not pursue further payment.\nUse when: Customer explicitly claims a payment was made today via another channel, providing enough specificity to make the claim concrete (channel, amount, or confirmation number). Must be a SAME-DAY payment.\nEdge cases: Tie-break vs PAY \u2014 PAY = successful DTMF payment in THIS call; DCP = payment made today via a different channel. Tie-break vs DIS \u2014 DIS = customer disputes the debt, including claims that the debt was already paid in the past (prior-day or earlier). DCP is specifically for SAME-DAY alternate-channel payments. If the customer claims payment from a prior day or further back, that's a balance dispute \u2192 DIS, not DCP.\nFew-shots: Customer says \"I paid this online today before you called, confirmation XYZ123\" \u2192 DCP. Customer says \"I just paid through the portal an hour ago\" \u2192 DCP. Customer says \"I paid this off three months ago, why are you calling?\" \u2192 DIS (not DCP \u2014 prior-payment balance dispute).\n\n- `DEC`: Description: Deceased - A third party informs the agent that the account holder has passed away. The AI closes the call respectfully with no payment pressure and no transfer.\nUse when: A third party (family, spouse, executor) unambiguously states the account holder is deceased (\"died,\" \"passed away,\" \"deceased\"). The statement must be definite, not hypothetical or uncertain.\nEdge cases: Tie-break vs INC \u2014 INC = account holder is incapacitated but alive (hospitalized, dementia, coma, brain injury); DEC = account holder has died. Statements like \"she's not well\" or \"he's very ill\" without mentioning death \u2192 INC, not DEC. Tie-break vs LGH \u2014 DEC is the notification of death; LGH is for a guardian/POA who then engages substantively on account matters. If a family member notifies of death AND then substantively discusses the estate account as POA, both DEC and LGH may apply \u2014 LGH primary if substantive account discussion follows.\nFew-shots: Spouse says \"He passed away last month\" \u2192 DEC. Daughter says \"My mother is deceased\" \u2192 DEC. Executor says \"She died, I'm handling her estate, let's talk about the account\" \u2192 DEC + LGH (LGH primary if substantive engagement). Caller says \"She's not available, very ill\" without saying deceased \u2192 INC (not DEC).\n\n- `NLM`: Description: Voicemail - Agent encounters a voicemail or automated answering system, the agent may speak briefly in confusion, say nothing useful after the beep, or terminate the call without leaving a formal message containing a callback number, reason for call, or identification.\nUse when: Voicemail system is detected but the agent does not leave a substantive, actionable message after the tone. Includes cases where the agent says \"May I speak with [Name]?\" into the machine, utters filler words, or disconnects without leaving callback info.\nEdge cases: Tie-break vs LM \u2014 LM = voicemail reached AND substantive message (callback number, stated reason, or formal identification) left AFTER the beep; NLM = voicemail reached but no such message left. Tie-break vs NKP \u2014 NKP = no voicemail system detected at all (silent connection); NLM = voicemail system was reached.\nFew-shots: Agent hears voicemail greeting, says \"May I speak with John?\" then disconnects \u2192 NLM. Agent hears beep but call drops with no message \u2192 NLM. Agent hears beep, leaves name and callback number \u2192 LM (not NLM).\n\n- `LM`: Description: Voicemail - Agent encounters a voicemail, automated/answering system AND leaves a substantive message (callback details, reason for call, and CUSTOMER's NAME).\nUse when: Voicemail system is detected (system prompts like \"record your name,\" \"after the tone,\" \"state your reason\"). Agent explicitly leaves a callback number, states reason for call, AND LEAVE CUSTOMER's NAME AFTER the recording tone.\nEdge cases: Agent merely speaks in confusion to the machine without leaving a formal message \u2192 NLM, not LM. Must have substantive, actionable content (callback number, stated reason, and CUSTOMER's NAME) AFTER the beep. If call terminates or agent gets confused without leaving a formal message \u2192 NLM.\nFew-shots: Agent hears beep, then says \"This is Anna from Kompato, please call us back at 1-888-555-1234, could I talk to [CUSTOMER NAME]\" \u2192 LM. Agent hears beep, says \"May I speak with John?\" then disconnects \u2192 NLM (not LM).\n\n- `NKP`: Description: No Pick Up - Connection established but no substantive customer response followed. No voicemail was reached. The transcript contains only the agent's greeting (or similar system output) with no meaningful customer text.\nUse when: The conversation transcript shows the agent opening followed by silence or system noise with no customer speech. No voicemail prompt or system answering message detected.\nEdge cases: Tie-break vs LM/NLM \u2014 LM/NLM = voicemail system reached (with/without substantive message left); NKP = no voicemail system reached, the line simply never produced a customer response. Tie-break vs HUP \u2014 HUP = customer DID pick up and produced a brief/cryptic/unrelated phrase before the call ended; NKP = no response at all (silent connection). Tie-break vs ECH \u2014 ECH = IVR / pre-recorded system answered; NKP = silence with no IVR signal. In practice this code is often assigned by system rules from call-duration/no-transcript signals; the LLM should use NKP only when the transcript itself confirms no customer engagement.\nFew-shots: Transcript shows agent opening, then silence, then call end \u2192 NKP. Transcript shows \"Hello?\" then disconnect \u2192 HUP (not NKP \u2014 brief pickup). Transcript shows \"You have reached the voicemail of...\" \u2192 LM/NLM (not NKP). Transcript shows a recorded business greeting (\"Thank you for calling XYZ...\") \u2192 ECH (not NKP).\n\n- `TPC`: Description: Third-Party Contact - Person other than the account holder provided information or context to help reach the intended recipient, including callback times or availability windows.\nUse when: Third party acknowledges knowing the account holder. Third party provides alternative phone number, address, availability time, or any contextual detail about the recipient. Third party offers to relay messages or suggests future contact times. Third party provides a callback time or availability window for reaching the account holder (e.g., \"call back after 7:30,\" \"she'll be home in the morning\").\nEdge cases: Distinguish from WRN \u2014 TPC requires explicit evidence of a relationship (acknowledging knowing the person, providing info about them). Even vague or incomplete info that aids in locating the recipient qualifies as TPC. No relationship evidence \u2192 WRN. CRITICAL DISTINCTION FROM CAB \u2014 If a third party (not the account holder) provides a callback time for reaching the account holder, this is TPC, NOT CAB. CAB requires the account holder themselves to schedule a callback. A third party arranging a callback time is providing information to reach the recipient, which is the core function of TPC.\nFew-shots: Person says \"He's not here, try calling after 5pm\" \u2192 TPC (not CAB). Wife says \"He's not available, call back later\" \u2192 TPC (not CAB). Person says \"That's my son, I'll tell him you called\" \u2192 TPC. Sister calls and agent arranges callback for 8AM \u2192 TPC (not CAB). Person says \"I don't know that person, wrong number\" \u2192 WRN (not TPC).\n\n- `WRN`: Description: Wrong Number - The person who answered or called explicitly denied being the intended recipient (e.g., \"No, this is not [name]\", \"You've got the wrong number\") or identified themselves as a business or non-consumer entity unrelated to the account holder (e.g., \"This is a business\", \"This is [Business Name]\"). This code is used when there is an identity mismatch and the respondent has no connection to the account holder.\nUse when: The person explicitly denies being the intended recipient, states the number belongs to a business, identifies themselves as a non-consumer entity, or otherwise confirms the number is not associated with the account holder. An explicit denial of identity or identification as a business line is sufficient regardless of any additional engagement or requests to stop contact. To classify as TPC instead of WRN, there must be explicit evidence of a relationship (acknowledging knowing the recipient or providing info about them).\nEdge cases: CRITICAL \u2014 When a caller identifies as a business or non-consumer and requests to stop contact (\"take my number off the list,\" \"I don't wanna be contacted at all\"), this is WRN, NOT CDS or DNC. The business identification is the primary signal \u2014 it means the number is wrong. Even if the caller says \"stop all communication\" or uses strong language about ceasing contact, the fact that they are NOT the account holder means only the phone number should be removed (WRN behavior), not account-level restrictions applied (CDS/DNC behavior). CDS and DNC require the caller to be the verified account holder or a potential debtor. An unverified business caller CANNOT trigger account-level restrictions.\nFew-shots: Inbound caller says \"Take my number off the list\" + \"This is a business. I don't wanna be contacted at all\" \u2192 WRN (not CDS). Caller says \"You have the wrong number\" \u2192 WRN. Caller says \"No, this is not [name]\" \u2192 WRN. Caller says \"Stop calling this number, this is a business\" \u2192 WRN (not DNC).\n\n- `IDF`: Description: ID Verification Failed - Customer confirms the right name, but DOB/SSN/zip information does not match with data in the system, OR customer refuses to verify their identity through standard verification protocols.\nUse when: Customer says \"No\" when asked if DOB on file is correct (data mismatch). Customer provides a DOB, SSN, or zip that does not match system records. Customer says \"No,\" \"Nope,\" \"I'm not giving you that,\" \"I refuse\" when asked for DOB/SSN (active refusal while still on the line). IDF should stay in neutral-to-positive customer confirmation space.\nEdge cases: Key distinction from HUA \u2014 IDF = customer provided WRONG data (DOB/SSN doesn't match) OR customer is still on the line ACTIVELY refusing/engaging (saying \"No,\" asking questions, arguing). HUA = customer confirmed name but the call ENDED (hung up, went silent, line dropped, timed out) during verification \u2014 no active engagement, just disconnection. If the customer says \"No\" to DOB and CONTINUES the conversation (asks questions, argues, refuses more) \u2192 IDF. If the customer goes silent and call times out \u2192 HUA. If the customer provided wrong data earlier but then the call also drops \u2192 still IDF (data mismatch occurred).\nFew-shots: Customer says \"No\" to \"Is Feb 22 1961 your DOB?\" then says \"It's not\" \u2192 IDF (data mismatch). Customer provides SSN 2549 that doesn't match \u2192 IDF. Customer says \"Nope\" repeatedly to DOB while still talking \u2192 IDF (active refusal). Customer provides wrong DOB \"2 3 65\" that doesn't match \u2192 IDF (data doesn't match even if conversation continues). Customer says \"No\" to DOB on file, then provides different DOB + wrong SSN, then goes silent \u2192 IDF (data mismatch happened before silence). Customer confirms name, agent asks for DOB, customer goes silent \u2192 call ends \u2192 HUA (no data provided, just disconnected).\n\n- `NVR`: Description: Name Verification Refused - Customer failed to confirm their name/identity following agent's attempt, through explicit refusal, evasion, incoherence, or hostility.\nUse when: After the agent asks \"Is this [Name]?\" or similar, the customer responds with SUBSTANTIVE verbal engagement that avoids confirming identity \u2014 defensive questions (\"Who's calling?,\" \"What do you want?\"), evasion (\"Hold on,\" \"Wait a minute\"), incoherent/irrelevant answers, hostility (profanity, aggression), or repeated demands for context. The key signal: the customer engages in a back-and-forth exchange with the agent without confirming their name.\nEdge cases: Distinguish from HUP \u2014 NVR requires SUBSTANTIVE verbal interaction after a name verification attempt (multiple exchanges, questions, hostility). A single \"Hello?\" or brief response followed by immediate disconnection is still HUP if no real exchange occurred. Use NVR when: (1) the customer asks questions about the caller/company, (2) the customer responds with hostility or profanity, (3) the customer engages in multiple turns without confirming identity. Use HUP when: the call ends before any meaningful exchange, or the customer provides only a brief/single-word response before disconnecting. Distinguish from CAB \u2014 if callback arranged specifically because identity could not be verified \u2192 NVR.\nFew-shots: Agent asks \"Is this John Smith?\" and customer says \"Who is calling? What do you want?\" \u2192 NVR. Agent asks for name, customer says \"Kiss my ass, bitch\" \u2192 NVR. Agent asks \"Is this Jeffrey Soliz?\" and customer asks \"Who's this?\" then \"Big Sky?\" (multiple turns) \u2192 NVR. Customer picks up, says \"Hello?\" once, then disconnects \u2192 HUP (not NVR).\n\n- `IDV`: Description: ID Verification Successful - Customer successfully passed all required identity verification checks \u2014 confirmed name AND at least one additional identifier (DOB, or SSN). This becomes the mandatory default classification for the rest of the call unless a more specific terminal disposition is reached.\nUse when: Customer explicitly confirms name AND provides/confirms at least one additional identifier. IDV stays as the default unless a more specific outcome occurs. Switch away from IDV when: the customer declines one or more payment offers (use NNP), a payment arrangement is made (use PPA/PPIF/PSIF), the customer explicitly refuses to pay any amount (use RTP), or any other terminal disposition applies.\nEdge cases: Customer expresses uncertainty about debt or agency \u2192 still IDV. Customer gives non-committal response to payment offer (\"I'm not sure,\" \"Maybe,\" \"Possibly,\" \"I'll think about it\") without clearly declining \u2192 still IDV (not NNP \u2014 non-committal is not a clear decline). Declining to share personal circumstances or explain default reasons is NOT a refusal to pay and NOT NNP \u2192 still IDV. If no specific payment amounts were offered at all, the call remains IDV. CRITICAL \u2014 If a payment offer was made but NO customer response to that offer is present in the conversation (the conversation ends immediately after the offer, or the customer's reply to the offer is missing), this is NOT NNP \u2192 still IDV. NNP requires the customer's explicit decline to be visible in the conversation. If payment was offered AND the customer explicitly said \"No\" or clearly declined, use NNP (not IDV). Only override with RTP if customer makes direct, unambiguous statement refusing to pay ANY amount (e.g., \"I won't pay,\" \"I refuse\"). Hostility, profanity, or incoherent outbursts (e.g., \"don't fuck yourself,\" random aggressive words) without explicit payment refusal \u2192 still IDV, NOT RTP and NOT CPR. A customer who becomes hostile or disengaged after verification but has NOT made a formal complaint about service/practices is NOT CPR \u2014 general hostility or profanity directed at no specific service issue is just a failed conversation, which remains IDV.\nFew-shots: Customer confirms name + DOB, then says \"No\" to sharing circumstances \u2192 IDV. Customer verified, payment discussed but customer says \"Possibly\" or \"Maybe\" without committing or declining \u2192 IDV (not NNP). Customer verified, declines to explain default circumstances, no payment amounts offered \u2192 IDV (not NNP). Customer verified, becomes hostile and uses profanity (\"don't fuck yourself\") but never explicitly refuses to pay \u2192 IDV (not RTP, not CPR). Customer verified, says incoherent hostile things and call ends \u2192 IDV. Customer verified, says \"I'm not familiar with this agency\" \u2192 IDV. Agent asks about circumstances, customer says \"No,\" agent then offers monthly payment amount, conversation ends with no customer response to the offer \u2192 IDV (customer only declined to share circumstances \u2014 no explicit decline of payment offer was shown).\n\n- `DIM`: Description: Debt Sale 2025 - Customer raises questions about the sale of their loan to a third-party buyer, or explicitly asks about a debt sale letter/email they received. Requires transfer to a human Collections agent.\nUse when: Customer mentions receiving a notice about their debt being sold, questions who now owns the debt, or asks about a third-party buyer taking over the account.\nEdge cases: Tie-break vs DIS \u2014 DIM = customer asking about a debt sale/transfer event; DIS = customer disputing the validity or amount of the debt. If the customer disputes that the sale was legal or authorized, both DIM and DIS may apply.\nFew-shots: Customer says \"I got a letter saying my loan was sold, what does that mean?\" \u2192 DIM. Customer says \"Who did you sell my debt to?\" \u2192 DIM.\n\n- `GVT`: Description: Government Shutdown Impact - Customer identifies themselves as affected by a US federal-government shutdown (furloughed federal employee, federal contractor without pay, etc.) and ties that impact to their ability to pay on this account.\nUse when: Customer explicitly names a federal-government-shutdown impact on income/employment and connects it to payment ability. The shutdown must be specifically identified as the cause \u2014 not generic unemployment or hardship language.\nEdge cases: Tie-break vs HCH \u2014 HCH = general long-term hardship; GVT = government-shutdown-specific hardship that may trigger distinct handling. Use GVT when the shutdown is explicitly named; HCH otherwise. Tie-break vs CSM \u2014 CSM = active military service under SCRA; GVT = federal civilian impacted by shutdown. Different legal bases.\nFew-shots: Customer says \"I'm a federal worker, I've been furloughed since the shutdown, I can't pay until it ends\" \u2192 GVT. Customer says \"I'm a government contractor and haven't been paid because of the shutdown\" \u2192 GVT. Customer says \"I lost my job, I have no income\" without referring to the shutdown \u2192 HCH (not GVT).\n\n- `INC`: Description: Consumer Incapacitated - A third party (or the customer) reports the account holder is alive but unable to handle debt-related matters due to severe illness, long-term hospitalization, or mental/physical incapacity.\nUse when: Caller states account holder has a severe or long-term condition preventing engagement (dementia, coma, brain injury, long-term hospitalization, severe cognitive impairment).\nEdge cases: Deceased reports belong to DEC, not INC. Minor/temporary illness (\"they have a cold,\" \"they're sleeping\") \u2192 NOT INC. Incapacitation must imply serious, potentially long-term inability to engage.\nFew-shots: \"She has brain fog. How can I help you?\" \u2192 INC. \"She's been in the hospital for a couple of weeks, she's battling cancer.\" \u2192 INC. \"He passed away last month.\" \u2192 DEC (not INC).\n\n- `LGB`: Description: Language Barrier - Communication could not proceed effectively due to language differences between agent and customer.\nUse when: Customer indicates inability to understand or communicate in the language being used. Language barrier makes meaningful conversation impossible.\nEdge cases: N/A\nFew-shots: Customer responds only in Spanish to English-speaking agent \u2192 LGB. Customer says \"I don't understand English\" \u2192 LGB.\n\n- `RCR`: Description: Recording Consent Refused - Customer explicitly declined consent for the call to be recorded.\nUse when: Customer says \"I do not consent to be recorded,\" \"I don't want to be recorded,\" \"No\" when asked for recording consent, or similar refusal of recording. This applies even if the customer also complains about other issues during the call.\nEdge cases: RCR takes PRIORITY over CPR (Complaint). If a customer refuses recording consent AND also complains about practices, the recording refusal is the primary classification \u2014 use RCR, not CPR. The complaint is secondary to the compliance-critical consent refusal.\nFew-shots: Agent says \"This call is being recorded\" and customer says \"I don't want to be recorded\" \u2192 RCR. Customer says \"No\" when asked for recording consent \u2192 RCR.\n\n- `TSR`: Description: Transfer to Representative (Post-IDV) \u2014 BARE human-agent request with no other meaningful context.\nUse when: Customer requests a human/representative AND the conversation contains NO payment commitment, NO specific future date, NO partial-pay framing, NO loan-mod request, and NO technical-failure signal. Transfer connects in post-IDV path.\nPrecedence: TSR is the FALLBACK for transfer-shaped conversations. If the transcript carries any of these signals, the more-specific code is primary (TSR may co-appear in list_call_codes but NOT as primary):\n  - FDP if customer commits to a specific future date + full balance\n  - EPT if partial-pay willingness + human help on the remainder is in the transcript\n  - TLM if loan-modification language is present\n  - HTT if a technical/system failure is mentioned in the transfer reason\n  - PPIF if customer commits to pay full balance but without a specific date\nPre-IDV equivalent: PTSR (post-process rule). Transfer attempted but not connected: WFR (post-IDV) or PWFR (pre-IDV). Customer refuses verification + requests live agent: HUA/IDF based on evidence.\n\n- `NCV`: Description: Not Convenient - Customer confirmed identity and indicated the current time is inconvenient for financial discussion. NCV describes the customer's STATE (\"now is not good\"), not a mechanism. It can co-occur with CAB when the inconvenience prompts a callback to be scheduled.\nUse when: Customer explicitly says \"now is not a good time,\" \"I can't talk,\" \"I'm busy,\" \"I have to go,\" \"Let's do this later.\" Customer disengages after identity verification due to circumstantial factors.\nEdge cases: Identity verified BUT user then disengages due to circumstances \u2192 NCV (not IDV). If customer says they're busy but STILL engages substantively in conversation (e.g., \"I have a minute, go ahead\"), the call is convenient enough \u2014 do NOT use NCV. Tie-break vs CAB/HCH: NCV = transient inconvenience (no specific time, no long-term reason); CAB = callback mechanism arranged at a specific time; HCH = long-term hardship state. NCV and CAB CAN co-exist \u2014 if the customer expresses inconvenience AND a callback is scheduled, include both in `list_call_code`. NCV and HCH do NOT typically co-occur \u2014 a long-term hardship is not the same as \"bad time right now.\" Pre-IDV equivalent: PNCV (post-process rule handles the mapping).\nFew-shots: Customer says \"I'm at work, I can't talk right now\" and hangs up \u2192 NCV. Customer says \"Now is not a good time\" without specifying when to call back \u2192 NCV. Customer says \"Now is not a good time, can you call me tomorrow at 3pm?\" with agent confirmation \u2192 NCV + CAB (both). Customer says \"I'm busy but go ahead\" and continues talking \u2192 NOT NCV.\n\n- `CAB`: Description: Callback Requested - The ACCOUNT HOLDER explicitly requests or agrees to a future outbound callback at a reasonably specific time. CAB is the MECHANISM (callback scheduled), not a state \u2014 it can co-occur with HCH (hardship state) or NCV (inconvenience state) in `list_call_code` when the callback is arranged because of those states.\nUse when: The account holder (confirmed or claimed) requests or agrees to be called back at a specific future time. A \"reasonably specific\" window includes \"tomorrow,\" \"Monday,\" \"next week,\" \"in a couple of weeks,\" provided the assistant acknowledges and confirms. A timeframe tied to a financial event (e.g., \"call me when I get my check\") is valid. CAB strictly means scheduling an OUTBOUND call from the agent to the account holder.\nEdge cases: CRITICAL PREREQUISITE \u2014 CAB only applies when the ACCOUNT HOLDER themselves requests a callback. If a THIRD PARTY (spouse, family member, roommate, unknown person) provides a callback time for reaching the account holder, classify as TPC, NOT CAB. Tie-break vs HCH/NCV: CAB = callback scheduled (mechanism); HCH = long-term hardship state; NCV = transient inconvenience state. CAB CAN co-occur with HCH or NCV \u2014 if the customer describes hardship AND a callback is arranged, include both in `list_call_code`. CAB is a mechanism, not a veto on state codes. Vs PPIF \u2014 if the customer commits to paying the full balance AND arranges a callback to provide card details, this is PPIF (primary), not CAB alone. Do NOT use CAB for vague statements like \"call me later\" or \"whenever\" where NO timeframe is established. Pre-IDV equivalent: PCAB (post-process rule handles the mapping).\nFew-shots: Account holder says \"call me back in 2 weeks when I get paid,\" agent confirms \u2192 CAB. Customer describes long-term medical hardship AND schedules a callback \u2192 CAB + HCH (both in `list_call_code`). Third party says \"She's not here, call back after 7:30\" \u2192 TPC (not CAB). Customer commits to pay full balance and asks to be called at noon with card ready \u2192 PPIF (not CAB).\n\n- `WCR`: Description: Written Communication Only Requested - Customer explicitly requested all future communications be in writing (mail / email / letter), with no further phone calls. WCR REQUIRES the customer to name a written channel as the preference \u2014 generic \"stop calling\" without a written preference is DNC, not WCR.\nUse when: Customer directs phone contact to cease AND specifies an alternative written channel (mail, email, letter, text-only, \"send it in writing,\" \"write me a letter\"). Both parts must be present \u2014 the phone-stop AND the written-channel preference. This applies even when prompted by frustration with call frequency.\nEdge cases: Tie-break vs CDS/DNC (channel scope): WCR = redirect to written only (phone out, written in); DNC = stop THIS phone (written still OK, not specified); CDS = stop ALL channels (phone + written + electronic). Distinguish from CPR \u2014 WCR is a specific channel-preference demand; CPR is a general complaint about communication practice without specifying the fix. If the customer only says \"stop calling\" without naming a written alternative \u2192 DNC, not WCR. If the customer says \"send it all in writing\" without asking phone calls to stop \u2192 still WCR (the written-only demand implies phone-stop).\nFew-shots: Customer says \"Don't call me, just send everything by mail\" \u2192 WCR. Customer says \"I only want emails, no more phone calls\" \u2192 WCR. Customer says \"Send me a letter, I don't want calls\" \u2192 WCR. Customer says \"Stop calling\" with no written preference \u2192 DNC (not WCR). Customer says \"Stop all contact, don't mail, don't call, nothing\" \u2192 CDS (not WCR \u2014 all channels stopped).\n\n- `CDS`: Description: Cease and Desist - The account holder (or someone reasonably presumed to be the account holder) has requested the complete cessation of all communication attempts regarding this account across all methods, including calls, emails, and texts.\nUse when: The caller explicitly demands cessation of ALL communication methods using phrases like \"stop all communication,\" \"cease all contact,\" \"remove me from everything,\" or \"cease and desist.\" Agent acknowledgment can be brief. This takes precedence even if the caller also requests documentation. Formal legal terminology is not required if intent is clear. The caller does not need to have completed full identity verification, but they must NOT have identified themselves as a third party or business.\nEdge cases: CRITICAL EXCLUSION \u2014 If the caller identifies as a BUSINESS or explicitly states they are NOT the account holder (e.g., \"This is a business,\" \"I'm not that person\"), classify as WRN (not CDS), because the caller is not the debtor and cannot trigger account-level restrictions. CDS applies when: (1) the caller is the verified account holder, OR (2) the caller is reasonably presumed to be the account holder (e.g., they are at the account holder's number and have not denied being the account holder). Distinct from DNC (phone-only stop) and WCR (written preference).\nFew-shots: Caller at account holder's number says \"Stop all communication\" without completing verification \u2192 CDS. Caller who identifies as a business says \"I don't wanna be contacted at all\" \u2192 WRN (not CDS). Verified account holder says \"Cease and desist\" \u2192 CDS. Caller says \"Can you take me off your call list? All communication.\" \u2192 CDS.\n\n- `CPR`: Description: Complaint Received - Customer expressed dissatisfaction, frustration, or concern regarding their account, collection practices, communication methods, or service experience, whether stated formally or implied through behavior. This includes complaints about confusing or unhelpful notifications (SMS, email, letters), annoyance with automated systems, or dissatisfaction with how they were contacted.\nUse when: Customer is unhappy with lack of notification details, expresses annoyance with SMS/text/email content (e.g., \"The text didn't say who this was,\" \"I didn't click the link because it looked like spam\"), rejects provided responses as unhelpful, repeatedly demands a live agent when unavailable, or persistently questions the assistant's inability to help. Key indicator: dissatisfaction with communication quality or practices WITHOUT disputing the debt itself.\nEdge cases: CRITICAL DISTINCTION FROM DIS \u2014 Complaints about HOW the customer was contacted (confusing texts, unclear notifications, spam-like messages) are CPR, NOT DIS. A customer calling to find out who texted them and expressing frustration about unclear communications is making a complaint about contact quality, not disputing the debt. DIS requires an explicit challenge to the debt's validity, accuracy, or legitimacy. If the customer expresses willingness to pay or asks for payment details while complaining about communication, this reinforces CPR over DIS. Also distinct from HCH: a customer who is frustrated about communications but not describing financial hardship should be CPR, not HCH.\nFew-shots: Customer says \"I didn't know who was texting me, the message didn't include any details\" and asks for payment address \u2192 CPR (not DIS). Customer says \"I wasn't clicking links because of scams\" but wants to pay \u2192 CPR. Customer repeatedly asks for a live agent and expresses frustration \u2192 CPR.\n\n- `ATY`: Description: Attorney Representation - Customer stated they have retained or are seeking legal counsel, or legal representation is indicated through any signal in the conversation.\nUse when: Customer mentions \"my attorney,\" \"I'm getting a lawyer,\" \"my attorney has contacted you,\" or references a POA/legal authority. Agent prompts caller for proof of POA or legal representation documentation. Multiple or repeated references to an attorney, even if brief or fragmented. Consumer indicates attorney involvement even indirectly or amidst emotional distress.\nEdge cases: ATY captures explicit attorney engagement or intent to seek one. Distinguish from LGH \u2014 ATY = specific attorney/legal counsel mentioned; LGH = guardian/POA handling without attorney framing. Distinguish from DSA \u2014 keep DSA priority for debt-settlement-program handling unless attorney/legal counsel is explicitly the primary representation path.\nFew-shots: Customer says \"Talk to my lawyer\" \u2192 ATY. Customer says \"I turned my account over to a debt consolidate lawyer\" \u2192 ATY (word \"lawyer\" overrides \"debt consolidate\"). Fragmented speech \"on her journey... her attorney\" \u2192 ATY. Customer says \"I'm working with National Debt Relief\" (no mention of lawyer) \u2192 DSA (not ATY).\n\n- `DIS`: Description: Debt Disputed - The customer explicitly challenged the accuracy, validity, or legitimacy of the debt itself. This includes explicitly stating the debt is not theirs, the amount is wrong, previous payments are not reflected, or asserting the debt is void, canceled, settled, or legally discharged. This code also applies if the customer challenges the creditor's right to collect or the legality of the debt transfer (e.g., \"sold without consent\"). DIS takes precedence over CAB if the customer disputes the debt even if a callback is scheduled.\nUse when: Customer explicitly states the debt is not theirs, the amount is wrong, previous payments are not reflected, or asserts the debt is void/canceled/settled. Also applies when customer claims not to recognize the amount or implies the balance is incorrect (e.g., \"I wasn't aware it was that much\"). If a customer requests to stop contact specifically because they dispute the debt (e.g., \"Stop calling, I don't owe this\"), classify as DIS.\nEdge cases: CRITICAL \u2014 Do NOT classify as DIS if the customer is merely complaining about HOW they were contacted (confusing texts, unclear SMS, spam-looking links). Asking for details because a notification lacked specifics is a communication complaint (CPR), NOT a dispute. A dispute must be an explicit challenge to the DEBT ITSELF \u2014 its existence, amount, validity, or legitimacy. Also do NOT classify as DIS for \"sticker shock\" (e.g., \"Wow, that's a lot\") without questioning accuracy. DIS and PPA are opposite planes: DIS challenges debt validity/amount; PPA confirms willingness to resolve via payment terms.\nFew-shots: Customer says \"I don't owe this money\" \u2192 DIS. Customer says \"The text didn't say who this was for\" but asks for payment address \u2192 CPR (not DIS). Customer says \"I wasn't aware it was that much\" \u2192 DIS.\n\n- `FRA`: Description: Fraud Reported - Customer claims the account was opened fraudulently, through identity theft, or without their knowledge or consent.\nUse when: Customer explicitly alleges fraud or identity theft. Customer categorically denies the account's existence or their responsibility for creating it (even without using the word \"fraud\").\nEdge cases: Distinguish from DIS \u2014 FRA = customer denies they ever created/owned the account; DIS = disputes accuracy or balance of a recognized account. Categorical denial of account ownership \u2192 FRA (not DIS). Requires immediate escalation for fraud investigation.\nFew-shots: Customer says \"I never opened that account, someone stole my identity\" \u2192 FRA. Customer says \"I have no connection to this debt whatsoever\" \u2192 FRA. Customer says \"The balance is wrong, I already paid some\" \u2192 DIS (not FRA).\n\n- `BKP`: Description: Bankruptcy Pending - Customer reported current bankruptcy proceedings or intent to file bankruptcy that would include this account.\nUse when: Customer provides specific bankruptcy details (case number, chapter, filing date) or states intent to file. Triggers immediate cessation of collection activities per automatic stay provisions.\nEdge cases: Requires verification with bankruptcy court records. Intent to file is sufficient even without specific details.\nFew-shots: Customer says \"I filed Chapter 7 last month, case number 12345\" \u2192 BKP. Customer says \"I'm about to file for bankruptcy\" \u2192 BKP.\n\n- `PPA`: Description: Payment Plan Agreed - Customer agreed to a structured payment plan with specific terms (amounts, frequency, and duration) for resolving the debt. Also applies when the customer agreed to pay, the DTMF payment flow was initiated but failed, and the call ended BEFORE a transfer to a live agent was triggered.\nUse when: Customer formally accepts a structured payment arrangement with defined payment amounts and schedule. Also use when the customer agreed to pay, the system initiated DTMF payment but it failed (e.g., PIN authentication failed, payment instrument retrieval failed), and the call ended/hung up before the system could trigger a transfer to a live agent. The payment was attempted but failed, and no transfer followed.\nEdge cases: Special case \u2014 customer unable to respond at the time and requests later contact \u2192 same PPA classification applies. Requires clear, focused confirmation of payment terms \u2014 casual \"yeah\" or \"okay\" as filler while distracted does NOT qualify. CRITICAL DISTINCTION \u2014 PPA applies when DTMF payment failed AND call ended before transfer was triggered. If transfer WAS triggered \u2192 use TSR (connected) or WFR (busy) instead. If DTMF failed and no transfer and no hang-up \u2192 use FTP.\nFew-shots: Customer agrees to $50/month for 6 months and gets transferred to payment \u2192 PPA. Customer agrees to pay full $500, enters DTMF, PIN fails, call hangs up before transfer is triggered \u2192 PPA (not PPIF, not FTP). Customer says \"yeah, sure\" while talking about unrelated topics \u2192 NOT PPA.\n\n- `RTP`: Description: Refusal to Pay - Verified customer EXPLICITLY refuses with HARD, UNAMBIGUOUS language. The customer signals intent NOT TO PAY AT ALL \u2014 not just \"not today\" but a flat, unconditional rejection of the debt itself.\nUse ONLY when the customer's wording is HARD and explicit. Examples that qualify: \"I refuse to pay\", \"I'll never pay this\", \"I'm not paying, period\", \"I'm not paying anything\", \"Absolutely not. I won't pay.\", \"You can take this to court\", \"I don't owe this and I won't pay\", \"There's no way I'm paying this\", \"Forget it, I'm not paying\".\nPrecedence: A polite decline of multiple offers using SOFT language (\"I'll pass\", \"not today\", \"I'd rather not\", \"perhaps another time\", \"won't be doing that today\") is NNP \u2014 even after 5+ attempts. Number of declines is NOT a signal for RTP; only HARD refusal language is. The customer must signal INTENT NOT TO PAY AT ALL.\nDistinct from: NNP (soft/neutral declines that leave the door open). HCH (hardship-driven inability: \"I can't afford it\"). DIS (disputes the debt's validity). IDV (no specific payment offer was made and declined).\nEdge cases: Profanity or hostility alone is NOT RTP \u2014 RTP requires an explicit refusal statement. A customer who becomes hostile or disengaged before any payment discussion occurs should NOT be classified as RTP.\n\n- `CSM`: Description: SCRA Coverage Reported - Customer verified active military service status invoking Servicemembers Civil Relief Act protections.\nUse when: Customer provides details about military service (branch, status, anticipated service period) invoking SCRA protections. SCRA protections include interest rate caps, foreclosure prevention, and other accommodations that must be immediately applied.\nEdge cases: N/A\nFew-shots: Customer says \"I'm active duty military, you need to apply SCRA protections\" \u2192 CSM. Customer says \"I'm deployed overseas with the Army\" \u2192 CSM.\n\n- `PRS`: Description: In Prison - Customer or third party confirmed that the account holder is CURRENTLY incarcerated in a correctional facility.\nUse when: Incarceration in a correctional facility is confirmed as a CURRENT, ongoing status. Specific facility name or release date not required.\nEdge cases: PRS takes precedence over financial codes if both are mentioned. CRITICAL \u2014 PRS requires CURRENT incarceration. Past-tense references to arrest or jail (e.g., \"I got arrested\" as an explanation for default circumstances) do NOT qualify if the customer is clearly not currently incarcerated (e.g., they are on the phone freely discussing the account). Use the surrounding context to determine if the arrest is current or historical.\nFew-shots: Customer says \"I'm currently in jail\" \u2192 PRS. Third party says \"He's incarcerated at the county jail right now\" \u2192 PRS. Customer says \"I got arrested\" as an explanation for why they defaulted, but is freely conversing on the phone \u2192 NOT PRS (use IDV or appropriate code based on conversation outcome).\n\n- `LGH`: Description: Legal Guardian Handling - A legally authorized guardian is managing the account holder's affairs due to the account holder's incapacity or death.\nUse when: Guardian provides verifiable information about their legal relationship and authority to discuss the account. Third party presents power of attorney (POA) or demonstrates legal authority over the account. Communication must be directed exclusively to this authorized representative.\nEdge cases: Distinguish from ATY \u2014 use LGH for general guardian/POA scenarios; use ATY when a specific attorney or legal counsel is mentioned. Distinguish from TPC \u2014 LGH requires demonstrated legal authority (guardian, POA); TPC is any third party providing info without legal standing.\nFew-shots: Third party calls with power of attorney, negotiates settlement on account holder's behalf \u2192 LGH. \"She's deceased... her daughter has financial power of attorney\" \u2192 LGH. Agent confirms caller has power of attorney over incapacitated account holder \u2192 LGH.\n\n- `PSIF`: Description: Promise to Settle in Full - Customer agreed to a discounted settlement offer that will fully resolve the account for less than the original outstanding balance.\nUse when: Customer accepts a reduced settlement amount with a specific payment timeline that fully settles the account. No further payments are required after the agreed discounted amount is paid.\nEdge cases: Distinguish from PPIF \u2014 PSIF = reduced/discounted amount; PPIF = 100% original balance. Full settlement must be confirmed \u2014 account fully resolved with no remaining balance.\nFew-shots: Customer agrees to pay $248 instead of $352.90 full balance to settle \u2192 PSIF. Customer agrees to pay full $352.90 \u2192 PPIF (not PSIF).\n\n- `HCH`: Description: Hardship Concern - Customer describes a LONG-TERM, substantive hardship that materially limits ability to pay \u2014 permanent or long-duration job loss, long-term disability, ongoing serious medical condition, homelessness, or chronic financial inability. HCH is a STATE code describing the customer's situation, not an outcome override. HCH may co-occur with CAB (callback scheduled because of hardship) or PPA (payment plan structured around the hardship) in `list_call_code`.\nUse when: Customer substantively discusses a long-term hardship \u2014 not a passing mention. The hardship must be (1) long-term or open-ended in duration, and (2) described with enough context that a reviewer can identify the specific hardship (unemployment duration, medical condition, etc.). Short passing phrases without elaboration do not qualify.\nEdge cases: SHORT-TERM \u2260 HCH. \"I'm broke right now,\" \"I can't pay today,\" \"I don't have a credit card with me\" are situational difficulties without long-term context \u2014 do NOT include HCH. A brief mention of difficulty (e.g., \"facing difficulties,\" \"got arrested,\" \"family issues\") without substantive discussion \u2192 use IDV (if verified), not HCH. Tie-break vs CAB/NCV: CAB = callback scheduled (mechanism); NCV = transient inconvenience (no callback); HCH = long-term hardship state. CAB and HCH CAN co-exist \u2014 if the customer describes real hardship AND a callback is arranged, include both in `list_call_code`. Tie-break vs RTP: HCH describes inability; RTP describes unwillingness after multiple payment offers.\nFew-shots: Customer describes permanent disability, no income, no foreseeable recovery \u2192 HCH (may also include CAB if callback is set). Customer says \"I lost my job six months ago and still haven't found work, I'm trying but can't afford payments\" \u2192 HCH. Customer says \"I'm broke currently\" without elaborating on duration or cause \u2192 NOT HCH (short-term situational). Customer mentions \"got arrested\" briefly while freely conversing \u2192 NOT HCH (use IDV). Customer describes chronic illness and agrees to a callback in 2 weeks \u2192 HCH + CAB (both).\n\n- `HUA`: Description: Hang Up During Authentication - Customer confirmed their name but the call ENDED (hung up, disconnected, went silent) during the ID verification process. The verification was never completed \u2014 the call was cut short.\nUse when: Customer confirmed their name but the call ended during verification \u2014 customer hung up, went silent (multiple SILENCE markers), line dropped, or call timed out. The customer did NOT provide any DOB/SSN data and did NOT actively refuse \u2014 the call simply ended. Also applies when customer asks context questions (\"Who is this?\", \"What's this about?\") but the call ends before any verification data is exchanged.\nEdge cases: Key distinction from IDF \u2014 If the customer says \"No\" to the DOB on file (data mismatch) or actively says \"Nope,\" \"I refuse\" while still engaging \u2192 IDF (not HUA). HUA is for calls that ENDED during auth without data being checked. If the customer asks \"Who is this?\" then goes silent \u2192 HUA (call ended, no verification data). If the customer says \"I don't know\" to DOB and the call continues \u2192 IDF (refusal while engaged). If the customer says \"I don't know\" and immediately hangs up \u2192 HUA (call ended).\nFew-shots: Customer confirms name, agent asks for DOB, customer goes silent \u2192 call ends \u2192 HUA. Customer confirms name, asks \"Who is this? What's this about?\" \u2192 call ends \u2192 HUA. Customer confirms name, DOB question asked, customer says \"What's this concerning?\" then silence \u2192 HUA. Customer confirms name, says \"I don't know it\" to DOB and call ends \u2192 HUA (call ended, no data checked). Customer says \"No\" to DOB on file \u2192 IDF (not HUA \u2014 data mismatch). Customer says \"Nope\" repeatedly while still on line \u2192 IDF (not HUA \u2014 active refusal). Call truncated right after DOB question is asked, before customer responds \u2192 HUA (not IDV \u2014 verification was never completed).\n\n- `HUP`: Description: Hang Up - Call ends or is effectively abandoned before any meaningful two-way conversation occurs and before any identity or account information is verified. This includes cases where the agent only delivers the opening, the customer says nothing further, the line goes silent, the customer disconnects immediately, or the customer gives only a cryptic, random, or irrelevant phrase (e.g., random nouns, a business name like \"Orange Wagon\" or \"Joe's Pizza\") without clearly expressing intent to engage or continue the conversation. CRITICAL: A customer answering with what sounds like a business name (e.g., \"Orange Wagon\") is NOT the same as the customer explicitly stating \"this is a business\" or \"you have the wrong number.\" Answering with a business-sounding phrase alone \u2014 without the caller explicitly confirming they are NOT the intended person \u2014 does NOT qualify as WRN. Use HUP. WRN requires the caller to EXPLICITLY state it is a wrong number or that they are a business, not merely answer with a phrase that could be a business name.\nUse when: The interaction never progresses beyond the initial contact attempt and the customer's response does not confirm their identity or a clear intent to continue the conversation. A single unrelated, cryptic, or nonsensical phrase does not qualify as engagement unless the customer provides further input indicating an intent to engage, continue, or clarify their response.\nEdge cases: Distinguish from NVR \u2014 If the agent asks \"Is this [Name]?\" and the customer engages in a SUBSTANTIVE back-and-forth exchange (asking questions, demanding context, showing hostility) without confirming identity, use NVR. If the customer provides only a brief response (\"Hello?\") and the call ends quickly without real engagement, use HUP. The key question: was there a meaningful exchange after the name question, or did the call just die? Do NOT use HUP if voicemail is reached (use NLM/LM), if the person explicitly refuses name or ID verification after substantive engagement (use NVR/HUA), if identity was confirmed and the call dropped during authentication (use HUA), or if the person clearly states they are the wrong party (use WRN). WRN requires EXPLICIT confirmation of wrong number. Simply answering with a business name or unrelated phrase without explicitly stating it is a wrong number does NOT qualify as WRN \u2014 use HUP instead.\nFew-shots: Customer says \"Orange Wagon\" then call ends \u2192 HUP (not WRN) \u2014 answering with a business-sounding name without explicitly saying \"this is a business\" or \"wrong number\" is HUP. Customer answers, says nothing, line goes silent \u2192 HUP. Customer says \"Hello?\" then immediately disconnects \u2192 HUP. Even if reflection variable says response=business, if the caller never EXPLICITLY said \"this is a business\" or \"wrong number,\" classify as HUP.\n\n- `NNP`: Description: Negotiated No Payment - Verified customer declines payment options using SOFT, NEUTRAL, NON-COMMITTAL language. The customer says \"no for now\" (door open), NOT \"no forever\" (door slammed shut).\nUse when ALL of these are true: (a) customer verified, (b) agent offered \u22651 specific payment option, (c) customer declined politely without committing, (d) wording is SOFT \u2014 examples (any of these = NNP): \"I'll pass\", \"not today\", \"I'd rather not\", \"won't be doing that today\", \"I'm afraid not today\", \"thank you, but no\", \"I shall pass\", \"not at this time\", \"perhaps another time\", \"I'll have to decline at this time\", \"going to let that one go\", \"Nope, not today\", \"Pass on that one\", \"Maybe later\". (e) customer did NOT use HARD refusal language (see RTP). (f) customer expressed NO hardship or dispute.\nPrecedence: THE NUMBER OF DECLINES DOES NOT MATTER. Multiple polite declines (3, 5, even 8 attempts) remain NNP as long as the language stays soft. Only the LANGUAGE distinguishes NNP from RTP \u2014 not the count.\nDistinct from: RTP (HARD refusal language only \u2014 \"I refuse\", \"I'll never pay\", \"I'm not paying anything\", \"absolutely not\", \"take this to court\"). HCH (hardship: \"I can't afford it\", \"things are tight\", \"I lost my job\"). DIS (questions debt validity). IDV (customer was non-committal \u2014 \"possibly\", \"I'll think about it\" \u2014 without clearly declining a specific offer; or no payment offer was actually made).\n\n- `DSA`: Description: Debt Settlement Agreement - Customer indicates they are working with a third-party debt settlement, consolidation, or relief program to manage their debt.\nUse when: Customer explicitly or implicitly directs agent to contact a named debt relief/settlement program (Beyond Finance, National Debt Relief, Debt Solutions, etc.). Customer states \"a company is handling that for me\" or \"check with my debt negotiator.\" Consumer or representative claims they are working with a program for debt/credit settlement, consolidation, relief, management, or financial solutions.\nEdge cases: Distinguish from ATY \u2014 DSA = financial relief/settlement program; ATY = law office or attorney. If third party is not explicitly identified as a law office, assume it is a debt settlement service. Directing agent to contact a named debt relief agency is sufficient signal regardless of explicit confirmation. Do not let identity verification attempts or other conversational elements distract from settlement agency signals. Do not let the assistant's mention of \"attorney\" trigger ATY if the consumer only identifies a financial program.\nFew-shots: Customer says \"You need to call National Debt Relief, they're handling my account\" \u2192 DSA. Customer says \"A company is managing my debts\" \u2192 DSA. Customer says \"Talk to my lawyer about this\" \u2192 ATY (not DSA).\n\n- `DNC`: Description: Do Not Call - The caller (NOT a business or clearly wrong number) has requested to stop calls to THIS phone number. DNC is a PHONE-level flag; it suppresses further calls to this number without suppressing written channels or account-level activity. Identity verification is NOT required.\nUse when: Caller says \"stop calling,\" \"don't call this number,\" \"put me on your do not call list.\" Formal or informal/frustrated language qualifies equally. DNC applies even if the caller refuses to confirm their name \u2014 the explicit demand to stop phone calls is the primary signal.\nEdge cases: DNC is phone-level and CAN co-occur with post-IDV outcomes in `list_call_code`. If the customer makes a payment commitment (PPA/PPIF) and also says \"don't call me again,\" include DNC alongside the financial outcome \u2014 the phone-stop and the payment arrangement are independent facts. DNC overrides NVR and HUA when the caller explicitly demands to stop calls \u2014 the phone-stop is the terminal disposition, not \"hung up / refused name.\" Tie-break vs CDS/WCR (channel scope): DNC = stop THIS phone; CDS = stop ALL channels (phone + written + electronic); WCR = redirect phone contact to written only. EXCEPTION: If the caller identifies as a BUSINESS or explicitly denies being the account holder AND says the person doesn't live there (e.g., \"There's no [Name] here, stop calling\"), classify as WRN \u2014 the number is simply wrong. DNC requires the caller to COULD be the account holder (didn't deny it).\nFew-shots: Caller says \"Don't call this damn phone again\" without confirming name \u2192 DNC. Caller agrees to a $50/month plan AND says \"but stop calling me about this\" \u2192 primary PPA + DNC in `list_call_code`. Caller says \"This is a business, take my number off the list\" \u2192 WRN (not DNC). Caller says \"There's no Robin here, stop calling\" \u2192 WRN (not DNC \u2014 wrong number). Caller says \"Stop calling\" then \"Do not contact\" then agrees to stop ALL communication channels \u2192 CDS (not DNC \u2014 escalated to all channels).\n\n- `PPIF`: Description: Promise to Pay in Full - Customer verbally committed to paying 100% of the full outstanding balance in a single payment, with no discounts or settlement reductions. IMPORTANT: Do NOT use PPIF if the call ends with a transfer to a live agent \u2014 when a transfer occurs after a payment failure, the final disposition is TSR, not PPIF.\nUse when: Customer confirms the full amount due and agrees to a specific payment date or time (e.g., \"I'll take care of it later today,\" \"Call me back at noon to get my card\"). Use even if a callback is required to collect payment details or finalize the transaction. PPIF requires that NO transfer to a live agent occurs after the payment commitment.\nEdge cases: CRITICAL \u2014 Do NOT classify as CAB when a clear commitment to pay full balance is made. If the customer commits to paying the full balance AND arranges a callback to provide card details, this is ALWAYS PPIF, never CAB. The payment commitment takes precedence over the callback arrangement. Distinguish from PSIF \u2014 PPIF = 100% original balance; PSIF = discounted/reduced settlement amount. TRANSFER EXCEPTION \u2014 If the customer agreed to pay BUT the system fails to process payment (e.g., \"The system can not retrieve your payment information\") AND the AI agent then transfers to a live agent (\"Let me connect you with a live agent\"), classify as TSR, NOT PPIF. The transfer overrides the payment commitment. Distinguish from PPA \u2014 if the DTMF payment flow was initiated but failed, and the call ended before a transfer to a live agent was triggered, classify as PPA (not PPIF).\nFew-shots: Customer says \"I'll pay the full $393.92 tomorrow\" \u2192 PPIF. Customer says \"Call me back at noon, I'll have my card ready to pay it all\" \u2192 PPIF (not CAB). Customer agrees to pay $248 settlement instead of $352 full balance \u2192 PSIF (not PPIF). Customer agrees to pay full $2112.50, provides PIN 123456, system fails to retrieve payment info, agent says \"Let me connect you with a live agent\" \u2192 TSR (NOT PPIF \u2014 transfer overrides payment commitment). Customer enters DTMF payment flow, payment fails, call hangs up before transfer is triggered \u2192 PPA (not PPIF).\n\n## Stage Hints\n- Current state path (if available): []\n- If \"negotiation_from_script\" is present in current states, Post-IDV is likely active.\n- Mini-Miranda language in transcript is a strong cue that Post-IDV has started.\n\n# Output\n<reasoning>\nYour concise reasoning for the classification, reflection of instruction, notes, conversation history, and call code descriptions.\n</reasoning>\n<call_code_list>\n[\"CALL_CODE_1\", \"CALL_CODE_2\", \"CALL_CODE_3\"]\n</call_code_list>\n\n## Reflection Variable Descriptions\n```\n\n```\n\n## Reflection Variable Values\n```\n\n```\n\n## Conversation History\n```\nassistant: <break time=\"2s\"/> Hi, this is Chris, a virtual assistant on a recorded line. How can I assist you today?\nuser: I got yeah. Is this a I need to find out about a loan.\nassistant: Am I speaking to Kim Hall?\nuser: Yes.\nassistant: Thank you, Kim. To protect your privacy, could you please provide your day and month of birth?\nuser: Two twenty three fifty nine.\nassistant: This is an attempt to collect a debt by a debt collector. Any information obtained will be used for that purpose. Could I call you back if we're disconnected?\nuser: Yes.\nassistant: I understand. Kim, I'm calling today about an account placed for collection with us by Republic Finance with a balance of twelve thousand, three hundred and fifteen dollars and twenty-one cents. We can assist in options to help you take care of this balance. How would you like to resolve this matter?\nuser: What options do I have?\nassistant: Noted. You have several options to resolve this balance. You can pay the full amount of twelve thousand, three hundred and fifteen dollars and twenty-one cents, set up an installment plan, or we can discuss a potential reduction. Which option would you like to explore?\nuser: Potential reduction.\nassistant: Understood. We can offer a reduction of 70 percent on your overdue payment, bringing it down to 3,695 dollars. Would this work for you?\nuser: Will that be paid off?\nassistant: Well. Yes, if you pay the reduced amount of 3,695 dollars, the debt will be considered settled in full. Would you like to proceed with this option?\nuser: Yes.\nassistant: Understood. Would you like to pay the settlement amount of 3,695 dollars in full, or would you prefer to set up an installment plan?\nuser: I would like to pay it off in full, but I can't do it today. I'll call you back as soon as my check hit the bank, and I'll let you know where I can pay it off.\nassistant: Okay. Would you like to schedule a specific date for us to follow up, or would you prefer to reach out when you're ready?\nuser: Nope. I follow-up on the June the first.\nassistant: Noted.\nuser: June the third. June the third. June the third.\nassistant: Understood. Before we wrap up, could you confirm your contact information? Is your phone number still six six two six six nine zero two zero seven?\nuser: Correct.\nassistant: I see. Please note that nothing we discuss overshadows your rights as expressed in our email to you. May I get your permission to text you regarding account updates and upcoming payments?\nuser: Yes.\nassistant: Okay. Are you planning to pay by card or bank transfer?\nuser: I'm gonna pay back\nassistant: Noted.\nuser: I can do\nassistant: Understood. Could you confirm if the billing address for the payment is one six five eight <break time=\"0.6s\" /> one six five eight <break time=\"0.6s\" /> one six five eight <break time=\"0.6s\" /> Wilson Chapel R, Pontotoc, Mississippi, three eight eight six three <break time=\"0.6s\" />?\nuser: Correct. Correct.\nassistant: \n```"
[2026-05-13 22:02:22 +0700] [CODEX] output/from_zero/main_yaml_v1_full/per_conversation/0104_eUoE1KUGZVcVtWhnW-7juw/llm_call_0001.json:28:      "content": "You are an expert in call disposition classification.\nClassify the ## Conversation History into 1 to 3 most relevant call codes.\nUse # Context and # Instruction to guide your decision.\n\n# Context:\n- The conversation is transcribed from a phone call by Automatic Speech Recognition (ASR). The text may contain typos, recognition errors, missing punctuation, or incomplete sentences.\n- The collection agent is marked as \"assistant|agent|bot\", and the caller is marked as \"user|customer|human\".\n- Available call codes below are the codes you can output; definitions and descriptions are authoritative.\n- Use only MASTER codes from the source-of-truth call-disposition reference. Do not use external alias code systems.\n\n# Instruction:\n- Read ## Call Code Descriptions first, then ## Conversation History.\n- Use user utterances as primary evidence of intent. Use assistant prompts only to interpret what the user is responding to.\n- Select only codes supported by evidence in the transcript to reflect the latest intent of the caller/ customer. Output 1 to 3 codes.\n- Prefer concise reasoning tied to explicit transcript evidence and code definitions.\n- Respect code boundaries and stage context (Phone Number / Pre-IDV / Post-IDV).\n- Prioritize call codes that reflect the latest intent of the caller/ customer of the call. Explicitly stated intent is more important than implicit intent.\n- If user updated their intent, update the call code accordingly. For example, if user requests to speak to a live agent, and then changes their mind and agrees to continue the conversation, update the call code to the latest intent. Or if user expressed harship (HCH), but the agreed to pay and went through with payment --> the PAY is valid, drop the HCH as HCH is no longer valid.\n- Stage guidance: treat as Post-IDV only when identity verification is completed (or Mini-Miranda appears, typically after successful IDV). Otherwise stay in Phone Number / Pre-IDV space.\n- If available, use ### Reflection Variable Descriptions and Values for additional context, reasoning for your decision. \n- Output plain text wrapped in XML tags exactly as shown in # Output.\n\n#  Notes:\n- Make sure the reasoning is clear, specific, and grounded to the conversation history and the call code descriptions.\n- Consider alternatives, but do not over-label when evidence is weak.\n- The call code is used to capture the latest status of the call, and use to plan the next action of the call.\n\n# Input Information\n## Call Code Descriptions\n- `PIF`: Description: Paid in Full - Customer paid full balance.\nUse when: Customer successfully paid the full outstanding balance during the call.\nEdge cases: Distinguish from PAY \u2014 PAY is any successful in-call payment and may be partial; PIF requires the total overdue balance to be paid successfully during the call. Distinguish from PPIF/FDP \u2014 those are promises or scheduled future payments, not completed in-call payment.\nFew-shots: Customer agrees to pay the full overdue balance, the payment is processed successfully during the call \u2192 PIF. Customer makes only a partial successful payment \u2192 PAY (not PIF). Customer promises to pay full balance later \u2192 PPIF or FDP (not PIF).\n\n- `TLM`: Description: Transfer Loan Modification - Verified customer requests loan-modification assistance that is beyond AI capability. Transfer to Collections representative.\nUse when: Customer asks for loan-modification options, terms restructuring, payment-term change outside supported AI flow, or explicitly requests a specialist for loan modification.\nEdge cases: Tie-break vs EPT \u2014 use EPT when the limitation is payment assistance capability (amount/method/payment handling). Use TLM when the request is specifically about loan modification options. Tie-break vs HTT \u2014 use HTT only when a technical/system failure blocks completion; use TLM when there is no system failure and the request is business-support escalation.\nFew-shots: Customer says \"I need loan modification options, please transfer me\" \u2192 TLM. Customer asks to restructure loan terms beyond bot capability \u2192 TLM.\n\n- `FDP`: Description: Future Dated Payment - Verified customer commits to a SPECIFIC FUTURE DATE to pay the FULL balance in a single payment.\nUse when both (a) a specific calendar date in the future is named (\"Friday the 25th\", \"next Tuesday\", \"May 10th\"), AND (b) full-balance commitment is given for that date.\nDTMF capture is the typical flow but NOT REQUIRED \u2014 agreed-and-scheduled future-dated payment counts as FDP even if card collection is deferred to a callback or a transfer to a specialist. The bot's transfer-to-specialist does NOT downgrade FDP to TSR; if the user gave a specific future date and full-balance commitment, FDP is the primary code.\nDistinct from: PAY (same-day completed), PPA (structured multi-installment plan), PPIF (commit to pay full but NO specific date), TSR (bare transfer request without future-date commitment), EPT (partial today, not full-future).\n\n- `TPM`: Description: Third-Party Message - A third party answers and the agent leaves a message for the account holder without disclosing account details.\nUse when: Non-account-holder confirms target person is unavailable, and agent leaves a compliant callback/return-call message with no account disclosure.\nEdge cases: Tie-break vs TPC \u2014 TPC requires third party providing new contact details or actionable recipient-location info; TPM is message-left behavior only. Tie-break vs LM \u2014 LM is voicemail/answering-system path; TPM is a live third-party human interaction.\nFew-shots: Third party says \"He's not here,\" agent leaves callback request \u2192 TPM. Family member answers and agrees to pass message, no account details shared \u2192 TPM.\n\n- `ECH`: Description: Robot Call - Pre-recorded call or IVR detected. No human response received. No message left and no transfer initiated.\nUse when: Pre-recorded message or IVR system answers (including iOS call screening). No human picks up.\nEdge cases: Tie-break vs NKP \u2014 ECH = IVR/pre-recorded system detected; NKP = silent connection with no IVR signal.\nFew-shots: Call answered by \"Thank you for calling XYZ, press 1 for...\" \u2192 ECH. iOS call screening intercepts the call with automated response \u2192 ECH.\n\n- `HTT`: Description: Technical Issue Transfer - Any API call or technical process failure during the call prevents the AI agent from completing the collections interaction. Transfer to human Collections agent.\nUse when: Any system failure (including /pay API errors) prevents the AI from running the collections interaction normally.\nEdge cases: CRITICAL \u2014 Use HTT for system/technical failures. Use EPT when the failure is due to payment scope limitations (amount or method beyond AI capability), not a technical error.\nFew-shots: /pay API fails mid-call and AI cannot complete the interaction \u2192 HTT. System error prevents account retrieval \u2192 HTT.\n\n- `EPT`: Description: Elevated Payment Transfer - Verified customer offers a partial payment AND asks for human/specialist help on the remainder of the balance. Bot transfers to Collections.\nUse when both (a) a specific partial-pay amount or partial-pay willingness is in the user's turns (\"I can pay $X today\"), AND (b) a request for a human/specialist for the rest of the balance.\nEven if the bot completes the transfer (\"connecting you to a live agent\"), the primary code is EPT \u2014 the user's intent is partial-payment scope, NOT bare transfer. EPT is preferred over TSR whenever partial-pay framing is present in the transcript.\nDistinct from: HTT (system/API failure, not user-side scope), TLM (loan-modification request, not partial-pay-this-cycle), TSR (bare human-agent request with NO partial-pay framing), FDP (future-dated full payment, not partial today).\n\n- `DCP`: Description: Already Paid (other channel, same day) - Customer states that today's payment was made via a channel OTHER than this call's DTMF (online portal, prior agent, check, bank transfer). The AI does not pursue further payment.\nUse when: Customer explicitly claims a payment was made today via another channel, providing enough specificity to make the claim concrete (channel, amount, or confirmation number). Must be a SAME-DAY payment.\nEdge cases: Tie-break vs PAY \u2014 PAY = successful DTMF payment in THIS call; DCP = payment made today via a different channel. Tie-break vs DIS \u2014 DIS = customer disputes the debt, including claims that the debt was already paid in the past (prior-day or earlier). DCP is specifically for SAME-DAY alternate-channel payments. If the customer claims payment from a prior day or further back, that's a balance dispute \u2192 DIS, not DCP.\nFew-shots: Customer says \"I paid this online today before you called, confirmation XYZ123\" \u2192 DCP. Customer says \"I just paid through the portal an hour ago\" \u2192 DCP. Customer says \"I paid this off three months ago, why are you calling?\" \u2192 DIS (not DCP \u2014 prior-payment balance dispute).\n\n- `DEC`: Description: Deceased - A third party informs the agent that the account holder has passed away. The AI closes the call respectfully with no payment pressure and no transfer.\nUse when: A third party (family, spouse, executor) unambiguously states the account holder is deceased (\"died,\" \"passed away,\" \"deceased\"). The statement must be definite, not hypothetical or uncertain.\nEdge cases: Tie-break vs INC \u2014 INC = account holder is incapacitated but alive (hospitalized, dementia, coma, brain injury); DEC = account holder has died. Statements like \"she's not well\" or \"he's very ill\" without mentioning death \u2192 INC, not DEC. Tie-break vs LGH \u2014 DEC is the notification of death; LGH is for a guardian/POA who then engages substantively on account matters. If a family member notifies of death AND then substantively discusses the estate account as POA, both DEC and LGH may apply \u2014 LGH primary if substantive account discussion follows.\nFew-shots: Spouse says \"He passed away last month\" \u2192 DEC. Daughter says \"My mother is deceased\" \u2192 DEC. Executor says \"She died, I'm handling her estate, let's talk about the account\" \u2192 DEC + LGH (LGH primary if substantive engagement). Caller says \"She's not available, very ill\" without saying deceased \u2192 INC (not DEC).\n\n- `NLM`: Description: Voicemail - Agent encounters a voicemail or automated answering system, the agent may speak briefly in confusion, say nothing useful after the beep, or terminate the call without leaving a formal message containing a callback number, reason for call, or identification.\nUse when: Voicemail system is detected but the agent does not leave a substantive, actionable message after the tone. Includes cases where the agent says \"May I speak with [Name]?\" into the machine, utters filler words, or disconnects without leaving callback info.\nEdge cases: Tie-break vs LM \u2014 LM = voicemail reached AND substantive message (callback number, stated reason, or formal identification) left AFTER the beep; NLM = voicemail reached but no such message left. Tie-break vs NKP \u2014 NKP = no voicemail system detected at all (silent connection); NLM = voicemail system was reached.\nFew-shots: Agent hears voicemail greeting, says \"May I speak with John?\" then disconnects \u2192 NLM. Agent hears beep but call drops with no message \u2192 NLM. Agent hears beep, leaves name and callback number \u2192 LM (not NLM).\n\n- `LM`: Description: Voicemail - Agent encounters a voicemail, automated/answering system AND leaves a substantive message (callback details, reason for call, and CUSTOMER's NAME).\nUse when: Voicemail system is detected (system prompts like \"record your name,\" \"after the tone,\" \"state your reason\"). Agent explicitly leaves a callback number, states reason for call, AND LEAVE CUSTOMER's NAME AFTER the recording tone.\nEdge cases: Agent merely speaks in confusion to the machine without leaving a formal message \u2192 NLM, not LM. Must have substantive, actionable content (callback number, stated reason, and CUSTOMER's NAME) AFTER the beep. If call terminates or agent gets confused without leaving a formal message \u2192 NLM.\nFew-shots: Agent hears beep, then says \"This is Anna from Kompato, please call us back at 1-888-555-1234, could I talk to [CUSTOMER NAME]\" \u2192 LM. Agent hears beep, says \"May I speak with John?\" then disconnects \u2192 NLM (not LM).\n\n- `NKP`: Description: No Pick Up - Connection established but no substantive customer response followed. No voicemail was reached. The transcript contains only the agent's greeting (or similar system output) with no meaningful customer text.\nUse when: The conversation transcript shows the agent opening followed by silence or system noise with no customer speech. No voicemail prompt or system answering message detected.\nEdge cases: Tie-break vs LM/NLM \u2014 LM/NLM = voicemail system reached (with/without substantive message left); NKP = no voicemail system reached, the line simply never produced a customer response. Tie-break vs HUP \u2014 HUP = customer DID pick up and produced a brief/cryptic/unrelated phrase before the call ended; NKP = no response at all (silent connection). Tie-break vs ECH \u2014 ECH = IVR / pre-recorded system answered; NKP = silence with no IVR signal. In practice this code is often assigned by system rules from call-duration/no-transcript signals; the LLM should use NKP only when the transcript itself confirms no customer engagement.\nFew-shots: Transcript shows agent opening, then silence, then call end \u2192 NKP. Transcript shows \"Hello?\" then disconnect \u2192 HUP (not NKP \u2014 brief pickup). Transcript shows \"You have reached the voicemail of...\" \u2192 LM/NLM (not NKP). Transcript shows a recorded business greeting (\"Thank you for calling XYZ...\") \u2192 ECH (not NKP).\n\n- `TPC`: Description: Third-Party Contact - Person other than the account holder provided information or context to help reach the intended recipient, including callback times or availability windows.\nUse when: Third party acknowledges knowing the account holder. Third party provides alternative phone number, address, availability time, or any contextual detail about the recipient. Third party offers to relay messages or suggests future contact times. Third party provides a callback time or availability window for reaching the account holder (e.g., \"call back after 7:30,\" \"she'll be home in the morning\").\nEdge cases: Distinguish from WRN \u2014 TPC requires explicit evidence of a relationship (acknowledging knowing the person, providing info about them). Even vague or incomplete info that aids in locating the recipient qualifies as TPC. No relationship evidence \u2192 WRN. CRITICAL DISTINCTION FROM CAB \u2014 If a third party (not the account holder) provides a callback time for reaching the account holder, this is TPC, NOT CAB. CAB requires the account holder themselves to schedule a callback. A third party arranging a callback time is providing information to reach the recipient, which is the core function of TPC.\nFew-shots: Person says \"He's not here, try calling after 5pm\" \u2192 TPC (not CAB). Wife says \"He's not available, call back later\" \u2192 TPC (not CAB). Person says \"That's my son, I'll tell him you called\" \u2192 TPC. Sister calls and agent arranges callback for 8AM \u2192 TPC (not CAB). Person says \"I don't know that person, wrong number\" \u2192 WRN (not TPC).\n\n- `WRN`: Description: Wrong Number - The person who answered or called explicitly denied being the intended recipient (e.g., \"No, this is not [name]\", \"You've got the wrong number\") or identified themselves as a business or non-consumer entity unrelated to the account holder (e.g., \"This is a business\", \"This is [Business Name]\"). This code is used when there is an identity mismatch and the respondent has no connection to the account holder.\nUse when: The person explicitly denies being the intended recipient, states the number belongs to a business, identifies themselves as a non-consumer entity, or otherwise confirms the number is not associated with the account holder. An explicit denial of identity or identification as a business line is sufficient regardless of any additional engagement or requests to stop contact. To classify as TPC instead of WRN, there must be explicit evidence of a relationship (acknowledging knowing the recipient or providing info about them).\nEdge cases: CRITICAL \u2014 When a caller identifies as a business or non-consumer and requests to stop contact (\"take my number off the list,\" \"I don't wanna be contacted at all\"), this is WRN, NOT CDS or DNC. The business identification is the primary signal \u2014 it means the number is wrong. Even if the caller says \"stop all communication\" or uses strong language about ceasing contact, the fact that they are NOT the account holder means only the phone number should be removed (WRN behavior), not account-level restrictions applied (CDS/DNC behavior). CDS and DNC require the caller to be the verified account holder or a potential debtor. An unverified business caller CANNOT trigger account-level restrictions.\nFew-shots: Inbound caller says \"Take my number off the list\" + \"This is a business. I don't wanna be contacted at all\" \u2192 WRN (not CDS). Caller says \"You have the wrong number\" \u2192 WRN. Caller says \"No, this is not [name]\" \u2192 WRN. Caller says \"Stop calling this number, this is a business\" \u2192 WRN (not DNC).\n\n- `IDF`: Description: ID Verification Failed - Customer confirms the right name, but DOB/SSN/zip information does not match with data in the system, OR customer refuses to verify their identity through standard verification protocols.\nUse when: Customer says \"No\" when asked if DOB on file is correct (data mismatch). Customer provides a DOB, SSN, or zip that does not match system records. Customer says \"No,\" \"Nope,\" \"I'm not giving you that,\" \"I refuse\" when asked for DOB/SSN (active refusal while still on the line). IDF should stay in neutral-to-positive customer confirmation space.\nEdge cases: Key distinction from HUA \u2014 IDF = customer provided WRONG data (DOB/SSN doesn't match) OR customer is still on the line ACTIVELY refusing/engaging (saying \"No,\" asking questions, arguing). HUA = customer confirmed name but the call ENDED (hung up, went silent, line dropped, timed out) during verification \u2014 no active engagement, just disconnection. If the customer says \"No\" to DOB and CONTINUES the conversation (asks questions, argues, refuses more) \u2192 IDF. If the customer goes silent and call times out \u2192 HUA. If the customer provided wrong data earlier but then the call also drops \u2192 still IDF (data mismatch occurred).\nFew-shots: Customer says \"No\" to \"Is Feb 22 1961 your DOB?\" then says \"It's not\" \u2192 IDF (data mismatch). Customer provides SSN 2549 that doesn't match \u2192 IDF. Customer says \"Nope\" repeatedly to DOB while still talking \u2192 IDF (active refusal). Customer provides wrong DOB \"2 3 65\" that doesn't match \u2192 IDF (data doesn't match even if conversation continues). Customer says \"No\" to DOB on file, then provides different DOB + wrong SSN, then goes silent \u2192 IDF (data mismatch happened before silence). Customer confirms name, agent asks for DOB, customer goes silent \u2192 call ends \u2192 HUA (no data provided, just disconnected).\n\n- `NVR`: Description: Name Verification Refused - Customer failed to confirm their name/identity following agent's attempt, through explicit refusal, evasion, incoherence, or hostility.\nUse when: After the agent asks \"Is this [Name]?\" or similar, the customer responds with SUBSTANTIVE verbal engagement that avoids confirming identity \u2014 defensive questions (\"Who's calling?,\" \"What do you want?\"), evasion (\"Hold on,\" \"Wait a minute\"), incoherent/irrelevant answers, hostility (profanity, aggression), or repeated demands for context. The key signal: the customer engages in a back-and-forth exchange with the agent without confirming their name.\nEdge cases: Distinguish from HUP \u2014 NVR requires SUBSTANTIVE verbal interaction after a name verification attempt (multiple exchanges, questions, hostility). A single \"Hello?\" or brief response followed by immediate disconnection is still HUP if no real exchange occurred. Use NVR when: (1) the customer asks questions about the caller/company, (2) the customer responds with hostility or profanity, (3) the customer engages in multiple turns without confirming identity. Use HUP when: the call ends before any meaningful exchange, or the customer provides only a brief/single-word response before disconnecting. Distinguish from CAB \u2014 if callback arranged specifically because identity could not be verified \u2192 NVR.\nFew-shots: Agent asks \"Is this John Smith?\" and customer says \"Who is calling? What do you want?\" \u2192 NVR. Agent asks for name, customer says \"Kiss my ass, bitch\" \u2192 NVR. Agent asks \"Is this Jeffrey Soliz?\" and customer asks \"Who's this?\" then \"Big Sky?\" (multiple turns) \u2192 NVR. Customer picks up, says \"Hello?\" once, then disconnects \u2192 HUP (not NVR).\n\n- `IDV`: Description: ID Verification Successful - Customer successfully passed all required identity verification checks \u2014 confirmed name AND at least one additional identifier (DOB, or SSN). This becomes the mandatory default classification for the rest of the call unless a more specific terminal disposition is reached.\nUse when: Customer explicitly confirms name AND provides/confirms at least one additional identifier. IDV stays as the default unless a more specific outcome occurs. Switch away from IDV when: the customer declines one or more payment offers (use NNP), a payment arrangement is made (use PPA/PPIF/PSIF), the customer explicitly refuses to pay any amount (use RTP), or any other terminal disposition applies.\nEdge cases: Customer expresses uncertainty about debt or agency \u2192 still IDV. Customer gives non-committal response to payment offer (\"I'm not sure,\" \"Maybe,\" \"Possibly,\" \"I'll think about it\") without clearly declining \u2192 still IDV (not NNP \u2014 non-committal is not a clear decline). Declining to share personal circumstances or explain default reasons is NOT a refusal to pay and NOT NNP \u2192 still IDV. If no specific payment amounts were offered at all, the call remains IDV. CRITICAL \u2014 If a payment offer was made but NO customer response to that offer is present in the conversation (the conversation ends immediately after the offer, or the customer's reply to the offer is missing), this is NOT NNP \u2192 still IDV. NNP requires the customer's explicit decline to be visible in the conversation. If payment was offered AND the customer explicitly said \"No\" or clearly declined, use NNP (not IDV). Only override with RTP if customer makes direct, unambiguous statement refusing to pay ANY amount (e.g., \"I won't pay,\" \"I refuse\"). Hostility, profanity, or incoherent outbursts (e.g., \"don't fuck yourself,\" random aggressive words) without explicit payment refusal \u2192 still IDV, NOT RTP and NOT CPR. A customer who becomes hostile or disengaged after verification but has NOT made a formal complaint about service/practices is NOT CPR \u2014 general hostility or profanity directed at no specific service issue is just a failed conversation, which remains IDV.\nFew-shots: Customer confirms name + DOB, then says \"No\" to sharing circumstances \u2192 IDV. Customer verified, payment discussed but customer says \"Possibly\" or \"Maybe\" without committing or declining \u2192 IDV (not NNP). Customer verified, declines to explain default circumstances, no payment amounts offered \u2192 IDV (not NNP). Customer verified, becomes hostile and uses profanity (\"don't fuck yourself\") but never explicitly refuses to pay \u2192 IDV (not RTP, not CPR). Customer verified, says incoherent hostile things and call ends \u2192 IDV. Customer verified, says \"I'm not familiar with this agency\" \u2192 IDV. Agent asks about circumstances, customer says \"No,\" agent then offers monthly payment amount, conversation ends with no customer response to the offer \u2192 IDV (customer only declined to share circumstances \u2014 no explicit decline of payment offer was shown).\n\n- `DIM`: Description: Debt Sale 2025 - Customer raises questions about the sale of their loan to a third-party buyer, or explicitly asks about a debt sale letter/email they received. Requires transfer to a human Collections agent.\nUse when: Customer mentions receiving a notice about their debt being sold, questions who now owns the debt, or asks about a third-party buyer taking over the account.\nEdge cases: Tie-break vs DIS \u2014 DIM = customer asking about a debt sale/transfer event; DIS = customer disputing the validity or amount of the debt. If the customer disputes that the sale was legal or authorized, both DIM and DIS may apply.\nFew-shots: Customer says \"I got a letter saying my loan was sold, what does that mean?\" \u2192 DIM. Customer says \"Who did you sell my debt to?\" \u2192 DIM.\n\n- `GVT`: Description: Government Shutdown Impact - Customer identifies themselves as affected by a US federal-government shutdown (furloughed federal employee, federal contractor without pay, etc.) and ties that impact to their ability to pay on this account.\nUse when: Customer explicitly names a federal-government-shutdown impact on income/employment and connects it to payment ability. The shutdown must be specifically identified as the cause \u2014 not generic unemployment or hardship language.\nEdge cases: Tie-break vs HCH \u2014 HCH = general long-term hardship; GVT = government-shutdown-specific hardship that may trigger distinct handling. Use GVT when the shutdown is explicitly named; HCH otherwise. Tie-break vs CSM \u2014 CSM = active military service under SCRA; GVT = federal civilian impacted by shutdown. Different legal bases.\nFew-shots: Customer says \"I'm a federal worker, I've been furloughed since the shutdown, I can't pay until it ends\" \u2192 GVT. Customer says \"I'm a government contractor and haven't been paid because of the shutdown\" \u2192 GVT. Customer says \"I lost my job, I have no income\" without referring to the shutdown \u2192 HCH (not GVT).\n\n- `INC`: Description: Consumer Incapacitated - A third party (or the customer) reports the account holder is alive but unable to handle debt-related matters due to severe illness, long-term hospitalization, or mental/physical incapacity.\nUse when: Caller states account holder has a severe or long-term condition preventing engagement (dementia, coma, brain injury, long-term hospitalization, severe cognitive impairment).\nEdge cases: Deceased reports belong to DEC, not INC. Minor/temporary illness (\"they have a cold,\" \"they're sleeping\") \u2192 NOT INC. Incapacitation must imply serious, potentially long-term inability to engage.\nFew-shots: \"She has brain fog. How can I help you?\" \u2192 INC. \"She's been in the hospital for a couple of weeks, she's battling cancer.\" \u2192 INC. \"He passed away last month.\" \u2192 DEC (not INC).\n\n- `LGB`: Description: Language Barrier - Communication could not proceed effectively due to language differences between agent and customer.\nUse when: Customer indicates inability to understand or communicate in the language being used. Language barrier makes meaningful conversation impossible.\nEdge cases: N/A\nFew-shots: Customer responds only in Spanish to English-speaking agent \u2192 LGB. Customer says \"I don't understand English\" \u2192 LGB.\n\n- `RCR`: Description: Recording Consent Refused - Customer explicitly declined consent for the call to be recorded.\nUse when: Customer says \"I do not consent to be recorded,\" \"I don't want to be recorded,\" \"No\" when asked for recording consent, or similar refusal of recording. This applies even if the customer also complains about other issues during the call.\nEdge cases: RCR takes PRIORITY over CPR (Complaint). If a customer refuses recording consent AND also complains about practices, the recording refusal is the primary classification \u2014 use RCR, not CPR. The complaint is secondary to the compliance-critical consent refusal.\nFew-shots: Agent says \"This call is being recorded\" and customer says \"I don't want to be recorded\" \u2192 RCR. Customer says \"No\" when asked for recording consent \u2192 RCR.\n\n- `TSR`: Description: Transfer to Representative (Post-IDV) \u2014 BARE human-agent request with no other meaningful context.\nUse when: Customer requests a human/representative AND the conversation contains NO payment commitment, NO specific future date, NO partial-pay framing, NO loan-mod request, and NO technical-failure signal. Transfer connects in post-IDV path.\nPrecedence: TSR is the FALLBACK for transfer-shaped conversations. If the transcript carries any of these signals, the more-specific code is primary (TSR may co-appear in list_call_codes but NOT as primary):\n  - FDP if customer commits to a specific future date + full balance\n  - EPT if partial-pay willingness + human help on the remainder is in the transcript\n  - TLM if loan-modification language is present\n  - HTT if a technical/system failure is mentioned in the transfer reason\n  - PPIF if customer commits to pay full balance but without a specific date\nPre-IDV equivalent: PTSR (post-process rule). Transfer attempted but not connected: WFR (post-IDV) or PWFR (pre-IDV). Customer refuses verification + requests live agent: HUA/IDF based on evidence.\n\n- `NCV`: Description: Not Convenient - Customer confirmed identity and indicated the current time is inconvenient for financial discussion. NCV describes the customer's STATE (\"now is not good\"), not a mechanism. It can co-occur with CAB when the inconvenience prompts a callback to be scheduled.\nUse when: Customer explicitly says \"now is not a good time,\" \"I can't talk,\" \"I'm busy,\" \"I have to go,\" \"Let's do this later.\" Customer disengages after identity verification due to circumstantial factors.\nEdge cases: Identity verified BUT user then disengages due to circumstances \u2192 NCV (not IDV). If customer says they're busy but STILL engages substantively in conversation (e.g., \"I have a minute, go ahead\"), the call is convenient enough \u2014 do NOT use NCV. Tie-break vs CAB/HCH: NCV = transient inconvenience (no specific time, no long-term reason); CAB = callback mechanism arranged at a specific time; HCH = long-term hardship state. NCV and CAB CAN co-exist \u2014 if the customer expresses inconvenience AND a callback is scheduled, include both in `list_call_code`. NCV and HCH do NOT typically co-occur \u2014 a long-term hardship is not the same as \"bad time right now.\" Pre-IDV equivalent: PNCV (post-process rule handles the mapping).\nFew-shots: Customer says \"I'm at work, I can't talk right now\" and hangs up \u2192 NCV. Customer says \"Now is not a good time\" without specifying when to call back \u2192 NCV. Customer says \"Now is not a good time, can you call me tomorrow at 3pm?\" with agent confirmation \u2192 NCV + CAB (both). Customer says \"I'm busy but go ahead\" and continues talking \u2192 NOT NCV.\n\n- `CAB`: Description: Callback Requested - The ACCOUNT HOLDER explicitly requests or agrees to a future outbound callback at a reasonably specific time. CAB is the MECHANISM (callback scheduled), not a state \u2014 it can co-occur with HCH (hardship state) or NCV (inconvenience state) in `list_call_code` when the callback is arranged because of those states.\nUse when: The account holder (confirmed or claimed) requests or agrees to be called back at a specific future time. A \"reasonably specific\" window includes \"tomorrow,\" \"Monday,\" \"next week,\" \"in a couple of weeks,\" provided the assistant acknowledges and confirms. A timeframe tied to a financial event (e.g., \"call me when I get my check\") is valid. CAB strictly means scheduling an OUTBOUND call from the agent to the account holder.\nEdge cases: CRITICAL PREREQUISITE \u2014 CAB only applies when the ACCOUNT HOLDER themselves requests a callback. If a THIRD PARTY (spouse, family member, roommate, unknown person) provides a callback time for reaching the account holder, classify as TPC, NOT CAB. Tie-break vs HCH/NCV: CAB = callback scheduled (mechanism); HCH = long-term hardship state; NCV = transient inconvenience state. CAB CAN co-occur with HCH or NCV \u2014 if the customer describes hardship AND a callback is arranged, include both in `list_call_code`. CAB is a mechanism, not a veto on state codes. Vs PPIF \u2014 if the customer commits to paying the full balance AND arranges a callback to provide card details, this is PPIF (primary), not CAB alone. Do NOT use CAB for vague statements like \"call me later\" or \"whenever\" where NO timeframe is established. Pre-IDV equivalent: PCAB (post-process rule handles the mapping).\nFew-shots: Account holder says \"call me back in 2 weeks when I get paid,\" agent confirms \u2192 CAB. Customer describes long-term medical hardship AND schedules a callback \u2192 CAB + HCH (both in `list_call_code`). Third party says \"She's not here, call back after 7:30\" \u2192 TPC (not CAB). Customer commits to pay full balance and asks to be called at noon with card ready \u2192 PPIF (not CAB).\n\n- `WCR`: Description: Written Communication Only Requested - Customer explicitly requested all future communications be in writing (mail / email / letter), with no further phone calls. WCR REQUIRES the customer to name a written channel as the preference \u2014 generic \"stop calling\" without a written preference is DNC, not WCR.\nUse when: Customer directs phone contact to cease AND specifies an alternative written channel (mail, email, letter, text-only, \"send it in writing,\" \"write me a letter\"). Both parts must be present \u2014 the phone-stop AND the written-channel preference. This applies even when prompted by frustration with call frequency.\nEdge cases: Tie-break vs CDS/DNC (channel scope): WCR = redirect to written only (phone out, written in); DNC = stop THIS phone (written still OK, not specified); CDS = stop ALL channels (phone + written + electronic). Distinguish from CPR \u2014 WCR is a specific channel-preference demand; CPR is a general complaint about communication practice without specifying the fix. If the customer only says \"stop calling\" without naming a written alternative \u2192 DNC, not WCR. If the customer says \"send it all in writing\" without asking phone calls to stop \u2192 still WCR (the written-only demand implies phone-stop).\nFew-shots: Customer says \"Don't call me, just send everything by mail\" \u2192 WCR. Customer says \"I only want emails, no more phone calls\" \u2192 WCR. Customer says \"Send me a letter, I don't want calls\" \u2192 WCR. Customer says \"Stop calling\" with no written preference \u2192 DNC (not WCR). Customer says \"Stop all contact, don't mail, don't call, nothing\" \u2192 CDS (not WCR \u2014 all channels stopped).\n\n- `CDS`: Description: Cease and Desist - The account holder (or someone reasonably presumed to be the account holder) has requested the complete cessation of all communication attempts regarding this account across all methods, including calls, emails, and texts.\nUse when: The caller explicitly demands cessation of ALL communication methods using phrases like \"stop all communication,\" \"cease all contact,\" \"remove me from everything,\" or \"cease and desist.\" Agent acknowledgment can be brief. This takes precedence even if the caller also requests documentation. Formal legal terminology is not required if intent is clear. The caller does not need to have completed full identity verification, but they must NOT have identified themselves as a third party or business.\nEdge cases: CRITICAL EXCLUSION \u2014 If the caller identifies as a BUSINESS or explicitly states they are NOT the account holder (e.g., \"This is a business,\" \"I'm not that person\"), classify as WRN (not CDS), because the caller is not the debtor and cannot trigger account-level restrictions. CDS applies when: (1) the caller is the verified account holder, OR (2) the caller is reasonably presumed to be the account holder (e.g., they are at the account holder's number and have not denied being the account holder). Distinct from DNC (phone-only stop) and WCR (written preference).\nFew-shots: Caller at account holder's number says \"Stop all communication\" without completing verification \u2192 CDS. Caller who identifies as a business says \"I don't wanna be contacted at all\" \u2192 WRN (not CDS). Verified account holder says \"Cease and desist\" \u2192 CDS. Caller says \"Can you take me off your call list? All communication.\" \u2192 CDS.\n\n- `CPR`: Description: Complaint Received - Customer expressed dissatisfaction, frustration, or concern regarding their account, collection practices, communication methods, or service experience, whether stated formally or implied through behavior. This includes complaints about confusing or unhelpful notifications (SMS, email, letters), annoyance with automated systems, or dissatisfaction with how they were contacted.\nUse when: Customer is unhappy with lack of notification details, expresses annoyance with SMS/text/email content (e.g., \"The text didn't say who this was,\" \"I didn't click the link because it looked like spam\"), rejects provided responses as unhelpful, repeatedly demands a live agent when unavailable, or persistently questions the assistant's inability to help. Key indicator: dissatisfaction with communication quality or practices WITHOUT disputing the debt itself.\nEdge cases: CRITICAL DISTINCTION FROM DIS \u2014 Complaints about HOW the customer was contacted (confusing texts, unclear notifications, spam-like messages) are CPR, NOT DIS. A customer calling to find out who texted them and expressing frustration about unclear communications is making a complaint about contact quality, not disputing the debt. DIS requires an explicit challenge to the debt's validity, accuracy, or legitimacy. If the customer expresses willingness to pay or asks for payment details while complaining about communication, this reinforces CPR over DIS. Also distinct from HCH: a customer who is frustrated about communications but not describing financial hardship should be CPR, not HCH.\nFew-shots: Customer says \"I didn't know who was texting me, the message didn't include any details\" and asks for payment address \u2192 CPR (not DIS). Customer says \"I wasn't clicking links because of scams\" but wants to pay \u2192 CPR. Customer repeatedly asks for a live agent and expresses frustration \u2192 CPR.\n\n- `ATY`: Description: Attorney Representation - Customer stated they have retained or are seeking legal counsel, or legal representation is indicated through any signal in the conversation.\nUse when: Customer mentions \"my attorney,\" \"I'm getting a lawyer,\" \"my attorney has contacted you,\" or references a POA/legal authority. Agent prompts caller for proof of POA or legal representation documentation. Multiple or repeated references to an attorney, even if brief or fragmented. Consumer indicates attorney involvement even indirectly or amidst emotional distress.\nEdge cases: ATY captures explicit attorney engagement or intent to seek one. Distinguish from LGH \u2014 ATY = specific attorney/legal counsel mentioned; LGH = guardian/POA handling without attorney framing. Distinguish from DSA \u2014 keep DSA priority for debt-settlement-program handling unless attorney/legal counsel is explicitly the primary representation path.\nFew-shots: Customer says \"Talk to my lawyer\" \u2192 ATY. Customer says \"I turned my account over to a debt consolidate lawyer\" \u2192 ATY (word \"lawyer\" overrides \"debt consolidate\"). Fragmented speech \"on her journey... her attorney\" \u2192 ATY. Customer says \"I'm working with National Debt Relief\" (no mention of lawyer) \u2192 DSA (not ATY).\n\n- `DIS`: Description: Debt Disputed - The customer explicitly challenged the accuracy, validity, or legitimacy of the debt itself. This includes explicitly stating the debt is not theirs, the amount is wrong, previous payments are not reflected, or asserting the debt is void, canceled, settled, or legally discharged. This code also applies if the customer challenges the creditor's right to collect or the legality of the debt transfer (e.g., \"sold without consent\"). DIS takes precedence over CAB if the customer disputes the debt even if a callback is scheduled.\nUse when: Customer explicitly states the debt is not theirs, the amount is wrong, previous payments are not reflected, or asserts the debt is void/canceled/settled. Also applies when customer claims not to recognize the amount or implies the balance is incorrect (e.g., \"I wasn't aware it was that much\"). If a customer requests to stop contact specifically because they dispute the debt (e.g., \"Stop calling, I don't owe this\"), classify as DIS.\nEdge cases: CRITICAL \u2014 Do NOT classify as DIS if the customer is merely complaining about HOW they were contacted (confusing texts, unclear SMS, spam-looking links). Asking for details because a notification lacked specifics is a communication complaint (CPR), NOT a dispute. A dispute must be an explicit challenge to the DEBT ITSELF \u2014 its existence, amount, validity, or legitimacy. Also do NOT classify as DIS for \"sticker shock\" (e.g., \"Wow, that's a lot\") without questioning accuracy. DIS and PPA are opposite planes: DIS challenges debt validity/amount; PPA confirms willingness to resolve via payment terms.\nFew-shots: Customer says \"I don't owe this money\" \u2192 DIS. Customer says \"The text didn't say who this was for\" but asks for payment address \u2192 CPR (not DIS). Customer says \"I wasn't aware it was that much\" \u2192 DIS.\n\n- `FRA`: Description: Fraud Reported - Customer claims the account was opened fraudulently, through identity theft, or without their knowledge or consent.\nUse when: Customer explicitly alleges fraud or identity theft. Customer categorically denies the account's existence or their responsibility for creating it (even without using the word \"fraud\").\nEdge cases: Distinguish from DIS \u2014 FRA = customer denies they ever created/owned the account; DIS = disputes accuracy or balance of a recognized account. Categorical denial of account ownership \u2192 FRA (not DIS). Requires immediate escalation for fraud investigation.\nFew-shots: Customer says \"I never opened that account, someone stole my identity\" \u2192 FRA. Customer says \"I have no connection to this debt whatsoever\" \u2192 FRA. Customer says \"The balance is wrong, I already paid some\" \u2192 DIS (not FRA).\n\n- `BKP`: Description: Bankruptcy Pending - Customer reported current bankruptcy proceedings or intent to file bankruptcy that would include this account.\nUse when: Customer provides specific bankruptcy details (case number, chapter, filing date) or states intent to file. Triggers immediate cessation of collection activities per automatic stay provisions.\nEdge cases: Requires verification with bankruptcy court records. Intent to file is sufficient even without specific details.\nFew-shots: Customer says \"I filed Chapter 7 last month, case number 12345\" \u2192 BKP. Customer says \"I'm about to file for bankruptcy\" \u2192 BKP.\n\n- `PPA`: Description: Payment Plan Agreed - Customer agreed to a structured payment plan with specific terms (amounts, frequency, and duration) for resolving the debt. Also applies when the customer agreed to pay, the DTMF payment flow was initiated but failed, and the call ended BEFORE a transfer to a live agent was triggered.\nUse when: Customer formally accepts a structured payment arrangement with defined payment amounts and schedule. Also use when the customer agreed to pay, the system initiated DTMF payment but it failed (e.g., PIN authentication failed, payment instrument retrieval failed), and the call ended/hung up before the system could trigger a transfer to a live agent. The payment was attempted but failed, and no transfer followed.\nEdge cases: Special case \u2014 customer unable to respond at the time and requests later contact \u2192 same PPA classification applies. Requires clear, focused confirmation of payment terms \u2014 casual \"yeah\" or \"okay\" as filler while distracted does NOT qualify. CRITICAL DISTINCTION \u2014 PPA applies when DTMF payment failed AND call ended before transfer was triggered. If transfer WAS triggered \u2192 use TSR (connected) or WFR (busy) instead. If DTMF failed and no transfer and no hang-up \u2192 use FTP.\nFew-shots: Customer agrees to $50/month for 6 months and gets transferred to payment \u2192 PPA. Customer agrees to pay full $500, enters DTMF, PIN fails, call hangs up before transfer is triggered \u2192 PPA (not PPIF, not FTP). Customer says \"yeah, sure\" while talking about unrelated topics \u2192 NOT PPA.\n\n- `RTP`: Description: Refusal to Pay - Verified customer EXPLICITLY refuses with HARD, UNAMBIGUOUS language. The customer signals intent NOT TO PAY AT ALL \u2014 not just \"not today\" but a flat, unconditional rejection of the debt itself.\nUse ONLY when the customer's wording is HARD and explicit. Examples that qualify: \"I refuse to pay\", \"I'll never pay this\", \"I'm not paying, period\", \"I'm not paying anything\", \"Absolutely not. I won't pay.\", \"You can take this to court\", \"I don't owe this and I won't pay\", \"There's no way I'm paying this\", \"Forget it, I'm not paying\".\nPrecedence: A polite decline of multiple offers using SOFT language (\"I'll pass\", \"not today\", \"I'd rather not\", \"perhaps another time\", \"won't be doing that today\") is NNP \u2014 even after 5+ attempts. Number of declines is NOT a signal for RTP; only HARD refusal language is. The customer must signal INTENT NOT TO PAY AT ALL.\nDistinct from: NNP (soft/neutral declines that leave the door open). HCH (hardship-driven inability: \"I can't afford it\"). DIS (disputes the debt's validity). IDV (no specific payment offer was made and declined).\nEdge cases: Profanity or hostility alone is NOT RTP \u2014 RTP requires an explicit refusal statement. A customer who becomes hostile or disengaged before any payment discussion occurs should NOT be classified as RTP.\n\n- `CSM`: Description: SCRA Coverage Reported - Customer verified active military service status invoking Servicemembers Civil Relief Act protections.\nUse when: Customer provides details about military service (branch, status, anticipated service period) invoking SCRA protections. SCRA protections include interest rate caps, foreclosure prevention, and other accommodations that must be immediately applied.\nEdge cases: N/A\nFew-shots: Customer says \"I'm active duty military, you need to apply SCRA protections\" \u2192 CSM. Customer says \"I'm deployed overseas with the Army\" \u2192 CSM.\n\n- `PRS`: Description: In Prison - Customer or third party confirmed that the account holder is CURRENTLY incarcerated in a correctional facility.\nUse when: Incarceration in a correctional facility is confirmed as a CURRENT, ongoing status. Specific facility name or release date not required.\nEdge cases: PRS takes precedence over financial codes if both are mentioned. CRITICAL \u2014 PRS requires CURRENT incarceration. Past-tense references to arrest or jail (e.g., \"I got arrested\" as an explanation for default circumstances) do NOT qualify if the customer is clearly not currently incarcerated (e.g., they are on the phone freely discussing the account). Use the surrounding context to determine if the arrest is current or historical.\nFew-shots: Customer says \"I'm currently in jail\" \u2192 PRS. Third party says \"He's incarcerated at the county jail right now\" \u2192 PRS. Customer says \"I got arrested\" as an explanation for why they defaulted, but is freely conversing on the phone \u2192 NOT PRS (use IDV or appropriate code based on conversation outcome).\n\n- `LGH`: Description: Legal Guardian Handling - A legally authorized guardian is managing the account holder's affairs due to the account holder's incapacity or death.\nUse when: Guardian provides verifiable information about their legal relationship and authority to discuss the account. Third party presents power of attorney (POA) or demonstrates legal authority over the account. Communication must be directed exclusively to this authorized representative.\nEdge cases: Distinguish from ATY \u2014 use LGH for general guardian/POA scenarios; use ATY when a specific attorney or legal counsel is mentioned. Distinguish from TPC \u2014 LGH requires demonstrated legal authority (guardian, POA); TPC is any third party providing info without legal standing.\nFew-shots: Third party calls with power of attorney, negotiates settlement on account holder's behalf \u2192 LGH. \"She's deceased... her daughter has financial power of attorney\" \u2192 LGH. Agent confirms caller has power of attorney over incapacitated account holder \u2192 LGH.\n\n- `PSIF`: Description: Promise to Settle in Full - Customer agreed to a discounted settlement offer that will fully resolve the account for less than the original outstanding balance.\nUse when: Customer accepts a reduced settlement amount with a specific payment timeline that fully settles the account. No further payments are required after the agreed discounted amount is paid.\nEdge cases: Distinguish from PPIF \u2014 PSIF = reduced/discounted amount; PPIF = 100% original balance. Full settlement must be confirmed \u2014 account fully resolved with no remaining balance.\nFew-shots: Customer agrees to pay $248 instead of $352.90 full balance to settle \u2192 PSIF. Customer agrees to pay full $352.90 \u2192 PPIF (not PSIF).\n\n- `HCH`: Description: Hardship Concern - Customer describes a LONG-TERM, substantive hardship that materially limits ability to pay \u2014 permanent or long-duration job loss, long-term disability, ongoing serious medical condition, homelessness, or chronic financial inability. HCH is a STATE code describing the customer's situation, not an outcome override. HCH may co-occur with CAB (callback scheduled because of hardship) or PPA (payment plan structured around the hardship) in `list_call_code`.\nUse when: Customer substantively discusses a long-term hardship \u2014 not a passing mention. The hardship must be (1) long-term or open-ended in duration, and (2) described with enough context that a reviewer can identify the specific hardship (unemployment duration, medical condition, etc.). Short passing phrases without elaboration do not qualify.\nEdge cases: SHORT-TERM \u2260 HCH. \"I'm broke right now,\" \"I can't pay today,\" \"I don't have a credit card with me\" are situational difficulties without long-term context \u2014 do NOT include HCH. A brief mention of difficulty (e.g., \"facing difficulties,\" \"got arrested,\" \"family issues\") without substantive discussion \u2192 use IDV (if verified), not HCH. Tie-break vs CAB/NCV: CAB = callback scheduled (mechanism); NCV = transient inconvenience (no callback); HCH = long-term hardship state. CAB and HCH CAN co-exist \u2014 if the customer describes real hardship AND a callback is arranged, include both in `list_call_code`. Tie-break vs RTP: HCH describes inability; RTP describes unwillingness after multiple payment offers.\nFew-shots: Customer describes permanent disability, no income, no foreseeable recovery \u2192 HCH (may also include CAB if callback is set). Customer says \"I lost my job six months ago and still haven't found work, I'm trying but can't afford payments\" \u2192 HCH. Customer says \"I'm broke currently\" without elaborating on duration or cause \u2192 NOT HCH (short-term situational). Customer mentions \"got arrested\" briefly while freely conversing \u2192 NOT HCH (use IDV). Customer describes chronic illness and agrees to a callback in 2 weeks \u2192 HCH + CAB (both).\n\n- `HUA`: Description: Hang Up During Authentication - Customer confirmed their name but the call ENDED (hung up, disconnected, went silent) during the ID verification process. The verification was never completed \u2014 the call was cut short.\nUse when: Customer confirmed their name but the call ended during verification \u2014 customer hung up, went silent (multiple SILENCE markers), line dropped, or call timed out. The customer did NOT provide any DOB/SSN data and did NOT actively refuse \u2014 the call simply ended. Also applies when customer asks context questions (\"Who is this?\", \"What's this about?\") but the call ends before any verification data is exchanged.\nEdge cases: Key distinction from IDF \u2014 If the customer says \"No\" to the DOB on file (data mismatch) or actively says \"Nope,\" \"I refuse\" while still engaging \u2192 IDF (not HUA). HUA is for calls that ENDED during auth without data being checked. If the customer asks \"Who is this?\" then goes silent \u2192 HUA (call ended, no verification data). If the customer says \"I don't know\" to DOB and the call continues \u2192 IDF (refusal while engaged). If the customer says \"I don't know\" and immediately hangs up \u2192 HUA (call ended).\nFew-shots: Customer confirms name, agent asks for DOB, customer goes silent \u2192 call ends \u2192 HUA. Customer confirms name, asks \"Who is this? What's this about?\" \u2192 call ends \u2192 HUA. Customer confirms name, DOB question asked, customer says \"What's this concerning?\" then silence \u2192 HUA. Customer confirms name, says \"I don't know it\" to DOB and call ends \u2192 HUA (call ended, no data checked). Customer says \"No\" to DOB on file \u2192 IDF (not HUA \u2014 data mismatch). Customer says \"Nope\" repeatedly while still on line \u2192 IDF (not HUA \u2014 active refusal). Call truncated right after DOB question is asked, before customer responds \u2192 HUA (not IDV \u2014 verification was never completed).\n\n- `HUP`: Description: Hang Up - Call ends or is effectively abandoned before any meaningful two-way conversation occurs and before any identity or account information is verified. This includes cases where the agent only delivers the opening, the customer says nothing further, the line goes silent, the customer disconnects immediately, or the customer gives only a cryptic, random, or irrelevant phrase (e.g., random nouns, a business name like \"Orange Wagon\" or \"Joe's Pizza\") without clearly expressing intent to engage or continue the conversation. CRITICAL: A customer answering with what sounds like a business name (e.g., \"Orange Wagon\") is NOT the same as the customer explicitly stating \"this is a business\" or \"you have the wrong number.\" Answering with a business-sounding phrase alone \u2014 without the caller explicitly confirming they are NOT the intended person \u2014 does NOT qualify as WRN. Use HUP. WRN requires the caller to EXPLICITLY state it is a wrong number or that they are a business, not merely answer with a phrase that could be a business name.\nUse when: The interaction never progresses beyond the initial contact attempt and the customer's response does not confirm their identity or a clear intent to continue the conversation. A single unrelated, cryptic, or nonsensical phrase does not qualify as engagement unless the customer provides further input indicating an intent to engage, continue, or clarify their response.\nEdge cases: Distinguish from NVR \u2014 If the agent asks \"Is this [Name]?\" and the customer engages in a SUBSTANTIVE back-and-forth exchange (asking questions, demanding context, showing hostility) without confirming identity, use NVR. If the customer provides only a brief response (\"Hello?\") and the call ends quickly without real engagement, use HUP. The key question: was there a meaningful exchange after the name question, or did the call just die? Do NOT use HUP if voicemail is reached (use NLM/LM), if the person explicitly refuses name or ID verification after substantive engagement (use NVR/HUA), if identity was confirmed and the call dropped during authentication (use HUA), or if the person clearly states they are the wrong party (use WRN). WRN requires EXPLICIT confirmation of wrong number. Simply answering with a business name or unrelated phrase without explicitly stating it is a wrong number does NOT qualify as WRN \u2014 use HUP instead.\nFew-shots: Customer says \"Orange Wagon\" then call ends \u2192 HUP (not WRN) \u2014 answering with a business-sounding name without explicitly saying \"this is a business\" or \"wrong number\" is HUP. Customer answers, says nothing, line goes silent \u2192 HUP. Customer says \"Hello?\" then immediately disconnects \u2192 HUP. Even if reflection variable says response=business, if the caller never EXPLICITLY said \"this is a business\" or \"wrong number,\" classify as HUP.\n\n- `NNP`: Description: Negotiated No Payment - Verified customer declines payment options using SOFT, NEUTRAL, NON-COMMITTAL language. The customer says \"no for now\" (door open), NOT \"no forever\" (door slammed shut).\nUse when ALL of these are true: (a) customer verified, (b) agent offered \u22651 specific payment option, (c) customer declined politely without committing, (d) wording is SOFT \u2014 examples (any of these = NNP): \"I'll pass\", \"not today\", \"I'd rather not\", \"won't be doing that today\", \"I'm afraid not today\", \"thank you, but no\", \"I shall pass\", \"not at this time\", \"perhaps another time\", \"I'll have to decline at this time\", \"going to let that one go\", \"Nope, not today\", \"Pass on that one\", \"Maybe later\". (e) customer did NOT use HARD refusal language (see RTP). (f) customer expressed NO hardship or dispute.\nPrecedence: THE NUMBER OF DECLINES DOES NOT MATTER. Multiple polite declines (3, 5, even 8 attempts) remain NNP as long as the language stays soft. Only the LANGUAGE distinguishes NNP from RTP \u2014 not the count.\nDistinct from: RTP (HARD refusal language only \u2014 \"I refuse\", \"I'll never pay\", \"I'm not paying anything\", \"absolutely not\", \"take this to court\"). HCH (hardship: \"I can't afford it\", \"things are tight\", \"I lost my job\"). DIS (questions debt validity). IDV (customer was non-committal \u2014 \"possibly\", \"I'll think about it\" \u2014 without clearly declining a specific offer; or no payment offer was actually made).\n\n- `DSA`: Description: Debt Settlement Agreement - Customer indicates they are working with a third-party debt settlement, consolidation, or relief program to manage their debt.\nUse when: Customer explicitly or implicitly directs agent to contact a named debt relief/settlement program (Beyond Finance, National Debt Relief, Debt Solutions, etc.). Customer states \"a company is handling that for me\" or \"check with my debt negotiator.\" Consumer or representative claims they are working with a program for debt/credit settlement, consolidation, relief, management, or financial solutions.\nEdge cases: Distinguish from ATY \u2014 DSA = financial relief/settlement program; ATY = law office or attorney. If third party is not explicitly identified as a law office, assume it is a debt settlement service. Directing agent to contact a named debt relief agency is sufficient signal regardless of explicit confirmation. Do not let identity verification attempts or other conversational elements distract from settlement agency signals. Do not let the assistant's mention of \"attorney\" trigger ATY if the consumer only identifies a financial program.\nFew-shots: Customer says \"You need to call National Debt Relief, they're handling my account\" \u2192 DSA. Customer says \"A company is managing my debts\" \u2192 DSA. Customer says \"Talk to my lawyer about this\" \u2192 ATY (not DSA).\n\n- `DNC`: Description: Do Not Call - The caller (NOT a business or clearly wrong number) has requested to stop calls to THIS phone number. DNC is a PHONE-level flag; it suppresses further calls to this number without suppressing written channels or account-level activity. Identity verification is NOT required.\nUse when: Caller says \"stop calling,\" \"don't call this number,\" \"put me on your do not call list.\" Formal or informal/frustrated language qualifies equally. DNC applies even if the caller refuses to confirm their name \u2014 the explicit demand to stop phone calls is the primary signal.\nEdge cases: DNC is phone-level and CAN co-occur with post-IDV outcomes in `list_call_code`. If the customer makes a payment commitment (PPA/PPIF) and also says \"don't call me again,\" include DNC alongside the financial outcome \u2014 the phone-stop and the payment arrangement are independent facts. DNC overrides NVR and HUA when the caller explicitly demands to stop calls \u2014 the phone-stop is the terminal disposition, not \"hung up / refused name.\" Tie-break vs CDS/WCR (channel scope): DNC = stop THIS phone; CDS = stop ALL channels (phone + written + electronic); WCR = redirect phone contact to written only. EXCEPTION: If the caller identifies as a BUSINESS or explicitly denies being the account holder AND says the person doesn't live there (e.g., \"There's no [Name] here, stop calling\"), classify as WRN \u2014 the number is simply wrong. DNC requires the caller to COULD be the account holder (didn't deny it).\nFew-shots: Caller says \"Don't call this damn phone again\" without confirming name \u2192 DNC. Caller agrees to a $50/month plan AND says \"but stop calling me about this\" \u2192 primary PPA + DNC in `list_call_code`. Caller says \"This is a business, take my number off the list\" \u2192 WRN (not DNC). Caller says \"There's no Robin here, stop calling\" \u2192 WRN (not DNC \u2014 wrong number). Caller says \"Stop calling\" then \"Do not contact\" then agrees to stop ALL communication channels \u2192 CDS (not DNC \u2014 escalated to all channels).\n\n- `PPIF`: Description: Promise to Pay in Full - Customer verbally committed to paying 100% of the full outstanding balance in a single payment, with no discounts or settlement reductions. IMPORTANT: Do NOT use PPIF if the call ends with a transfer to a live agent \u2014 when a transfer occurs after a payment failure, the final disposition is TSR, not PPIF.\nUse when: Customer confirms the full amount due and agrees to a specific payment date or time (e.g., \"I'll take care of it later today,\" \"Call me back at noon to get my card\"). Use even if a callback is required to collect payment details or finalize the transaction. PPIF requires that NO transfer to a live agent occurs after the payment commitment.\nEdge cases: CRITICAL \u2014 Do NOT classify as CAB when a clear commitment to pay full balance is made. If the customer commits to paying the full balance AND arranges a callback to provide card details, this is ALWAYS PPIF, never CAB. The payment commitment takes precedence over the callback arrangement. Distinguish from PSIF \u2014 PPIF = 100% original balance; PSIF = discounted/reduced settlement amount. TRANSFER EXCEPTION \u2014 If the customer agreed to pay BUT the system fails to process payment (e.g., \"The system can not retrieve your payment information\") AND the AI agent then transfers to a live agent (\"Let me connect you with a live agent\"), classify as TSR, NOT PPIF. The transfer overrides the payment commitment. Distinguish from PPA \u2014 if the DTMF payment flow was initiated but failed, and the call ended before a transfer to a live agent was triggered, classify as PPA (not PPIF).\nFew-shots: Customer says \"I'll pay the full $393.92 tomorrow\" \u2192 PPIF. Customer says \"Call me back at noon, I'll have my card ready to pay it all\" \u2192 PPIF (not CAB). Customer agrees to pay $248 settlement instead of $352 full balance \u2192 PSIF (not PPIF). Customer agrees to pay full $2112.50, provides PIN 123456, system fails to retrieve payment info, agent says \"Let me connect you with a live agent\" \u2192 TSR (NOT PPIF \u2014 transfer overrides payment commitment). Customer enters DTMF payment flow, payment fails, call hangs up before transfer is triggered \u2192 PPA (not PPIF).\n\n## Stage Hints\n- Current state path (if available): []\n- If \"negotiation_from_script\" is present in current states, Post-IDV is likely active.\n- Mini-Miranda language in transcript is a strong cue that Post-IDV has started.\n\n# Output\n<reasoning>\nYour concise reasoning for the classification, reflection of instruction, notes, conversation history, and call code descriptions.\n</reasoning>\n<call_code_list>\n[\"CALL_CODE_1\", \"CALL_CODE_2\", \"CALL_CODE_3\"]\n</call_code_list>\n\n## Reflection Variable Descriptions\n```\n\n```\n\n## Reflection Variable Values\n```\n\n```\n\n## Conversation History\n```\nassistant: Hello\nuser: Hello?\nassistant: Hello, I am Sarah, a virtual agent on a recorded line.\nassistant: May I please speak with Elizabeth Washington?\nuser: Speaking.\nassistant: Hi Elizabeth, to protect your privacy and consent to proceed with the call, could you please confirm your month and day of birth?\nuser: July thirty first nineteen fifty nine.\nassistant: Thanks.\nassistant: Please note that this is an attempt to collect a debt by a debt collector.\nassistant: Any information obtained will be used for that purpose.\nassistant: Again, my name is Sarah, could I call you back if we're disconnected?\nuser: Yeah.\nassistant: Thank you.\nassistant: Elizabeth, I'm calling today about an account placed for collection with us by Republic Finance, account number eight one zero two seven five eight eight one one five six.\nassistant: The current balance is five thousand, nine hundred and seventy-four dollars and eighty-nine cents.\nassistant: Could you share what happened that caused this outstanding balance?\nassistant: Please note that nothing we discuss overshadows your rights as expressed in our email to you.\nuser: I had death in the family.\nassistant: Gotcha  I'm sorry to hear about your loss, Elizabeth.\nassistant: That must have been a very difficult time for you.\nassistant: How have you been managing things since then?\nuser: I've been doing good. I've been doing okay.\nassistant: I'm glad to hear you're doing okay now, Elizabeth.\nassistant: Have things improved financially for you recently, or are you still facing challenges?\nuser: I'm placing some small challenge.\nuser: But\nuser: I'm I'm a be okay.\nassistant: It's good to hear that you're staying positive, Elizabeth.\nassistant: Given your current situation, how would you like to resolve this balance?\nassistant: I'm here to help find a solution that works for you.\nuser: Yes. I I really don't have the full balance I was wondering, can I set up, like, a monthly payment or something?\nassistant: Okay.\nassistant: We can definitely set up a monthly payment plan for you, Elizabeth.\nassistant: I can offer you a plan of 50 dollars per month.\nassistant: Would that work for you?\nuser: Yes.\nassistant: Great!\nassistant: Could you let me know a convenient date each month to make the payment?\nuser: That'd be after the fifteenth of each month.\nassistant: Got it.\nassistant: So, we\u2019ll set the payment date for the 16th of each month.\nassistant: Just to confirm, you'll be making monthly payments of 50 dollars starting on May 16, 2025.\nassistant: Is that correct?\nuser: Yes.\nassistant: Perfect, Elizabeth.\nassistant: Your payment plan is set for 50 dollars per month, starting on May 16, 2025.\nassistant: Before we wrap up, could you confirm if your contact information, such as your phone number and email address, is still up to date?\nuser: Yeah.\nassistant: Thanks for confirming.\nassistant: If you have any questions or need assistance, feel free to reach out.\nassistant: Have a great day, Elizabeth!\nuser: Alright. Thank you.\nassistant: You're welcome, Elizabeth!\nassistant: Take care!\n```"
