[2026-05-13 22:02:36 +0700] [CODEX] ===== docs/signal_experiment_40_postcall_rerun_report_20260513.md =====
[2026-05-13 22:02:36 +0700] [CODEX] # Signal Experiment 40: Postcall Rerun Report
[2026-05-13 22:02:36 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-13 22:02:36 +0700] [CODEX] Date: 2026-05-13
[2026-05-13 22:02:36 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-13 22:02:36 +0700] [CODEX] ## Verdict
[2026-05-13 22:02:36 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-13 22:02:36 +0700] [CODEX] The small-scale hypothesis test is runnable end to end. The 40-row signal packet produced real postcall classifier outputs for both YAML routes with no terminal row failures. Classifier exact match is **33/40 = 82.5%**, leaving **7** reviewable mismatch rows for the revive loop.
[2026-05-13 22:02:36 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-13 22:02:36 +0700] [CODEX] This is enough to move from planning into a controlled revive experiment, but not enough to scale seeding yet. The next step should target the mismatch rows and keep matched anchors as regression controls.
[2026-05-13 22:02:36 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-13 22:02:36 +0700] [CODEX] ## Hypothesis Tested
[2026-05-13 22:02:36 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-13 22:02:36 +0700] [CODEX] If we select a compact, transcript-backed signal packet from the AGI-9466 source pool, then we can convert it into runner inputs, rerun the current postcall classifier by YAML route, and get a human-auditable ledger of where zero-shot labels agree or fail.
[2026-05-13 22:02:36 +0700] [CODEX] 
