[2026-05-13 22:02:44 +0700] [CODEX] | `85aceddec…\|93a01279…` (mixed) | 0 | 5 | **100.0%** |
[2026-05-13 22:02:44 +0700] [CODEX] | `93a01279…\|ca1e150e…` (mixed) | 1 | 3 | 75.0% |
[2026-05-13 22:02:44 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-13 22:02:44 +0700] [CODEX] Any conv whose two End events were rendered against different ccd_hashes is on a YAML-version boundary and flips **2–5× more often** than a single-hash conv. This matches the session-recap finding that `0ded5781…→…` was a mid-window CDS/WRN/DNC policy revision; the Affirm tenant happened to straddle that revision for ~44 convs.
[2026-05-13 22:02:44 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-13 22:02:44 +0700] [CODEX] ## Why each top pair flips (verified from transcripts)
[2026-05-13 22:02:44 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-13 22:02:44 +0700] [CODEX] ### HUP → NLM (29) — rule-based vs LLM, voicemail snippet
[2026-05-13 22:02:44 +0700] [CODEX] The fast classifier's `callcode_reason` is verbatim "Rule-based call code detection matched HUP; skipped LLM detection.". The transcript is a voicemail greeting fragment ("seven three six six zero zero two is not available.", "three three one two three four five seven is not available."). Bot state is `["pre_opening", "pre_opening"]`. The final LLM pass sees the same content but the postprocess promotes NLM (no live message left) over the rule-based HUP. **Single ccd_hash, so not a YAML drift case — purely classifier-architecture (rule vs LLM).**
[2026-05-13 22:02:44 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-13 22:02:44 +0700] [CODEX] ### NVR → HUP (10) — YAML drift across mid-window policy change
[2026-05-13 22:02:44 +0700] [CODEX] Every example carries `ccd_hash: 5f3c90558def0c59|93a01279721d8a8d` (multiple hashes in conv → policy changed mid-window). Bot state advanced to `check_rpc`/`exc_inconvenient_time`. The final-pass `callcode_reason` describes substantive engagement ("Who's this?", "I can't really hear you", asks who is calling). NVR ("no verbal response") was the old definition; the final pass against the new YAML reclassifies the same content as HUP. **Pure YAML-policy drift.**
[2026-05-13 22:02:44 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-13 22:02:44 +0700] [CODEX] ### HUP → HUA (5) — transcript completeness + boundary code ambiguity
[2026-05-13 22:02:44 +0700] [CODEX] Two patterns: (a) Spanish-only response ("Sí") → bot says English-only → silence → final LLM picks HUA (Hung Up After greeting). (b) Brief "Hello?" + ID prompt + silence — the fast HUP and final HUA differ only in whether the silence-after-greeting counts as "abandoned" (HUP) or "hung up after" (HUA). Definitions are too close.
[2026-05-13 22:02:44 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-13 22:02:44 +0700] [CODEX] ### NKP → HUP (5) — system rule fired NKP, LLM disagreed
[2026-05-13 22:02:44 +0700] [CODEX] `list_call_codes: ["NKP"]` (rule fired) but the final label is HUP. Transcripts are 1-2 lines of "Hello?" + assistant attempt + silence. The system-rule NKP definition ("no substantive customer response") and LLM-emit HUP definition ("call ends before meaningful conversation") describe the same evidence; LLM final wins ties. **Inherent overlap in the taxonomy.**
[2026-05-13 22:02:44 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-13 22:02:44 +0700] [CODEX] ### HUA → HUP (5), HUP → NKP (3), HUP → LGB (3) — boundary-code disambiguation
[2026-05-13 22:02:44 +0700] [CODEX] Same pattern: short greeting + identity prompt + silence/disengagement. Pre-RPC gatekeeping codes (HUP/HUA/NKP/LGB/NLM) all overlap on minimal-engagement transcripts; whichever the LLM picks last is what sticks.
[2026-05-13 22:02:44 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-13 22:02:44 +0700] [CODEX] ## Mechanism breakdown across the 110 flips
[2026-05-13 22:02:44 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-13 22:02:44 +0700] [CODEX] | mechanism | n | % | notes |
[2026-05-13 22:02:44 +0700] [CODEX] |---|---:|---:|---|
[2026-05-13 22:02:44 +0700] [CODEX] | Rule-based first → LLM final | 33 | 30.0 | 29 are HUP→NLM voicemails; rest are scattered |
[2026-05-13 22:02:44 +0700] [CODEX] | Mixed `ccd_hash` (YAML drift) | 44 | 40.0 | flip rate 39.7% on 2-hash, 100% on the rare 2-hash combos |
[2026-05-13 22:02:44 +0700] [CODEX] | Transcript < 100 chars at fast time | 42 | 38.2 | heavily overlaps with rule-based; fast had no signal |
[2026-05-13 22:02:44 +0700] [CODEX] | LLM-vs-LLM disagreement, same YAML, long transcript | ~25 | ~23 | residual after subtracting overlaps |
[2026-05-13 22:02:44 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-13 22:02:44 +0700] [CODEX] Buckets overlap (e.g. a rule-based HUP→NLM voicemail is also a sub-100-char transcript). The residual ~23% are "real" LLM disagreements — same YAML, same transcript, the LLM legitimately changed its mind. These are the only ones where call_code_descriptions tuning could move the needle; the other ~85% are upstream of definitions.
[2026-05-13 22:02:44 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-13 22:02:44 +0700] [CODEX] ## Why this matters
[2026-05-13 22:02:44 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-13 22:02:44 +0700] [CODEX] - The **HUP→NLM voicemail bucket (29 of 110)** is a fast-classifier rule-set bug, not a taxonomy issue. The rule that promotes HUP on a voicemail-shape transcript should defer to LLM detection when the user-line begins with "<name/number> is not available." This is a one-line fix in the rule layer (not in `call_code_descriptions`).
[2026-05-13 22:02:44 +0700] [CODEX] - The **YAML-drift bucket (44 of 110)** is unfixable by editing definitions — those convs literally got classified against two different YAMLs. Going forward, treat any conv with multi-hash `ccd_hash` as low-confidence and exclude from accuracy reporting OR re-classify both against the newest hash.
[2026-05-13 22:02:44 +0700] [CODEX] - The **boundary-code overlap among HUP/HUA/NKP/NLM/NVR/LGB** (about ~30 flips) is the *only* slice where definition tuning helps. These five codes collectively mean variants of "no live person engaged enough." This is exactly the MECE-audit candidate for Mode 1.
[2026-05-13 22:02:44 +0700] [CODEX] - Affirm-only **20.18% flip rate** is acceptable for ops codes (Tier B target ≥90% means ≤10% drift — we're slightly over), but only because **zero compliance codes flipped cross-category** in this Affirm subset. If a future window pushes a compliance flip into the top pairs, it becomes a Tier A failure.
[2026-05-13 22:02:44 +0700] [CODEX] 
