[2026-05-13 22:02:46 +0700] [CODEX] ## TL;DR
[2026-05-13 22:02:46 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-13 22:02:46 +0700] [CODEX] - **Bracket redaction alone is almost cosmetic.** Identical-after-normalization convs agree 22/23 (96%) between raw (with-brackets) and redacted (stripped). My earlier observational claim "31% of flips will evaporate by aligning renderers" was overstated — production has variance that doesn't reappear in a controlled rerun.
[2026-05-13 22:02:46 +0700] [CODEX] - **The dominant cause of disagreement is content addition, not rendering.** APPENDED bucket: 47% agreement. REAL bucket: 65%. PURE_RENDER: 96%.
[2026-05-13 22:02:46 +0700] [CODEX] - **Number of turns is NOT the driver.** Median Δturns is +2 for both agreed and disagreed groups. **Δchars is the driver**: agreed +3, disagreed +94. New *content*, not new turn boundaries, is what flips codes.
[2026-05-13 22:02:46 +0700] [CODEX] - **The user's LGB / Spanish observation is confirmed but it's a content-addition effect, not a redaction effect.** Conv `69l2rLntLFb4LIr-ndEWAw` — fast saw 72 chars of English only, final added a Spanish sentence (`"Bueno, bueno, bueno, ¿no va a ir home?"`) → HUP → LGB. The Spanish content appeared only in the final pass because the final pass captures more transcript, not because the redacted version drops English.
[2026-05-13 22:02:46 +0700] [CODEX] - **Match against production labels**: RAW prediction matches the production fast label 54.7% (decent); REDACTED matches production final label 32% (poor). The model difference (gpt-5.5 vs prod gpt-4o) explains a chunk of the alignment gap — but the RAW-with-brackets is consistently closer to fast-pass production behavior, suggesting brackets are *signal* to the LLM in the same direction as they were to the production model.
[2026-05-13 22:02:46 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-13 22:02:46 +0700] [CODEX] ## Experimental design
[2026-05-13 22:02:46 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-13 22:02:46 +0700] [CODEX] 1. **75 convs** (the filtered-flipped Affirm subset; rule-based + error/timeout already excluded).
[2026-05-13 22:02:46 +0700] [CODEX] 2. **Two versions per conv**:
[2026-05-13 22:02:46 +0700] [CODEX]    - `RAW_with_brackets` = the fast-pass transcript (has `[happy]`, `[calm]`, `[company_name: Affirm]`, compound assistant turns).
[2026-05-13 22:02:46 +0700] [CODEX]    - `REDACTED_stripped` = the final-pass transcript (no brackets, compound turns split).
[2026-05-13 22:02:46 +0700] [CODEX] 3. **Constant prompt + constant model + constant `call_code_descriptions`**. The only thing that varies is the transcript text.
[2026-05-13 22:02:46 +0700] [CODEX] 4. **150 LLM calls** (75 × 2), concurrency 8, async via LLM Hub.
[2026-05-13 22:02:46 +0700] [CODEX] 5. **Outputs**: predicted CallCode + reason + token usage per call.
[2026-05-13 22:02:46 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-13 22:02:46 +0700] [CODEX] ## Headline result — agreement by bucket
[2026-05-13 22:02:46 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-13 22:02:46 +0700] [CODEX] | bucket | n | agreed (same code) | disagreed |
[2026-05-13 22:02:46 +0700] [CODEX] |---|---:|---:|---:|
[2026-05-13 22:02:46 +0700] [CODEX] | PURE_RENDER (identical content after norm) | 23 | **22 (96%)** | 1 |
[2026-05-13 22:02:46 +0700] [CODEX] | APPENDED (final extends fast) | 15 | 7 (47%) | 8 |
[2026-05-13 22:02:46 +0700] [CODEX] | REAL (transcripts genuinely differ) | 37 | 24 (65%) | 13 |
[2026-05-13 22:02:46 +0700] [CODEX] | **total** | **75** | **53 (70.7%)** | **22 (29.3%)** |
[2026-05-13 22:02:46 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-13 22:02:46 +0700] [CODEX] The 96% PURE_RENDER agreement rate is the headline. The LLM does not flip codes on bracket stripping alone — it's robust to the formatting differences between fast and final renderers. The one disagreement in this bucket (`3666GqgxGInT1k8G7PLZHg` WRN→HUP, predicted WRN→NVR) is the residual LLM nondeterminism the user already ruled out as out-of-scope.
[2026-05-13 22:02:46 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-13 22:02:46 +0700] [CODEX] ## What actually drives disagreement (transcript-level)
[2026-05-13 22:02:46 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-13 22:02:46 +0700] [CODEX] | group | n | Δchars med | Δturns med | Δuser-turns med | Spanish hits med (raw/red) |
[2026-05-13 22:02:46 +0700] [CODEX] |---|---:|---:|---:|---:|---:|
[2026-05-13 22:02:46 +0700] [CODEX] | AGREED | 53 | **+3** | +2 | 1 | 0 / 0 |
[2026-05-13 22:02:46 +0700] [CODEX] | DISAGREED | 22 | **+94** | +2 | 1 | 0 / 0.5 |
[2026-05-13 22:02:46 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-13 22:02:46 +0700] [CODEX] - Turn delta is identical between agreed and disagreed (median +2 each) → **turn count is not the driver**.
[2026-05-13 22:02:46 +0700] [CODEX] - Char delta is **30× larger** for disagreed (+94 vs +3) → **volume of new content is**.
[2026-05-13 22:02:46 +0700] [CODEX] - Spanish hit count is slightly higher in the redacted version for disagreed (0.5 vs 0) — small effect, present.
[2026-05-13 22:02:46 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-13 22:02:46 +0700] [CODEX] ## Top RAW → REDACTED prediction transitions (the 22 disagreements)
[2026-05-13 22:02:46 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-13 22:02:46 +0700] [CODEX] | RAW prediction | REDACTED prediction | n |
[2026-05-13 22:02:46 +0700] [CODEX] |---|---|---:|
[2026-05-13 22:02:46 +0700] [CODEX] | NKP | HUP | 3 |
[2026-05-13 22:02:46 +0700] [CODEX] | NKP | NLM | 2 |
[2026-05-13 22:02:46 +0700] [CODEX] | WRN | NVR | 2 |
[2026-05-13 22:02:46 +0700] [CODEX] | HTT | WRN | 2 |
[2026-05-13 22:02:46 +0700] [CODEX] | NKP | ECH | 2 |
[2026-05-13 22:02:46 +0700] [CODEX] | HUP | LGB | 1 |
[2026-05-13 22:02:46 +0700] [CODEX] | TLM | FDP | 1 |
[2026-05-13 22:02:46 +0700] [CODEX] | TSR | HCH | 1 |
[2026-05-13 22:02:46 +0700] [CODEX] | HUP | NKP | 1 |
[2026-05-13 22:02:46 +0700] [CODEX] | (other) | (other) | 7 |
[2026-05-13 22:02:46 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-13 22:02:47 +0700] [CODEX] The pattern: 7 of 22 disagreements have RAW=NKP (no key person on the line) flipping to HUP/NLM/ECH. All 7 are in the APPENDED bucket — the final transcript adds content (silence turns, customer response, voicemail beep) that changes the code from "no engagement detected" to a more specific terminal code.
[2026-05-13 22:02:47 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-13 22:02:47 +0700] [CODEX] ## The LGB / Spanish content observation — confirmed for content, not for redaction
[2026-05-13 22:02:47 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-13 22:02:47 +0700] [CODEX] Two convs flipped HUP → LGB between RAW and REDACTED:
[2026-05-13 22:02:47 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-13 22:02:47 +0700] [CODEX] ### Conv `69l2rLntLFb4LIr-ndEWAw` (the clean confirmation)
[2026-05-13 22:02:47 +0700] [CODEX] ```
[2026-05-13 22:02:47 +0700] [CODEX] RAW (72 chars, English-only):
[2026-05-13 22:02:47 +0700] [CODEX]   user: When it when it went off, nobody home or other place?
[2026-05-13 22:02:47 +0700] [CODEX]   assistant: -
[2026-05-13 22:02:47 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-13 22:02:47 +0700] [CODEX] REDACTED (187 chars):
[2026-05-13 22:02:47 +0700] [CODEX]   user: When it went went off.
[2026-05-13 22:02:47 +0700] [CODEX]   user: When it when it went off, nobody home or other place?
[2026-05-13 22:02:47 +0700] [CODEX]   assistant: I'm sorry, I didn't quite understand that.
[2026-05-13 22:02:47 +0700] [CODEX]   user: Bueno, bueno, bueno, ¿no va a ir home?    ← Spanish sentence appears ONLY in REDACTED
[2026-05-13 22:02:47 +0700] [CODEX] ```
[2026-05-13 22:02:47 +0700] [CODEX] The new Spanish turn is the trigger. RAW (no Spanish) → HUP. REDACTED (added Spanish + bot confusion turn) → LGB. **This is a content-addition flip, not a redaction flip.**
[2026-05-13 22:02:47 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-13 22:02:47 +0700] [CODEX] ### Conv `vToIkPujyyHOi0VRkfvrew` (the negative example)
[2026-05-13 22:02:47 +0700] [CODEX] Both RAW and REDACTED contain `"Aló. Aló."` Spanish AND the bot's explicit `"I understand that you want to speak in another language other than English. Do you want me to connect you with a live agent…"`. Yet the experiment predicted HUP (raw) and NVR (redacted) — **not LGB**, despite obvious language-barrier signal. The yaml's LGB definition is apparently not matching this pattern well; the classifier missed a clear case in both directions. **This is a definition-tuning issue for LGB, independent of redaction.**
[2026-05-13 22:02:47 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-13 22:02:47 +0700] [CODEX] ## Match against production labels (sanity check)
[2026-05-13 22:02:47 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-13 22:02:47 +0700] [CODEX] | | matches observed_fast | matches observed_final |
[2026-05-13 22:02:47 +0700] [CODEX] |---|---:|---:|
[2026-05-13 22:02:47 +0700] [CODEX] | RAW prediction | **41/75 (54.7%)** | 11/75 (14.7%) |
[2026-05-13 22:02:47 +0700] [CODEX] | REDACTED prediction | 29/75 (38.7%) | 24/75 (32.0%) |
[2026-05-13 22:02:47 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-13 22:02:47 +0700] [CODEX] Interpretation:
[2026-05-13 22:02:47 +0700] [CODEX] - RAW-with-brackets is the better proxy for production fast-pass behavior (55% match) — supporting that brackets do influence the LLM, at least with this model.
[2026-05-13 22:02:47 +0700] [CODEX] - REDACTED's match with production final is only 32%. The remaining 68% gap is mostly the model difference (gpt-5.5 vs prod gpt-4o), which we cannot close without a key that can call gpt-4o.
[2026-05-13 22:02:47 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-13 22:02:47 +0700] [CODEX] ### Per-bucket alignment
[2026-05-13 22:02:47 +0700] [CODEX] | bucket | n | RAW=fast | RAW=fin | RED=fast | RED=fin |
[2026-05-13 22:02:47 +0700] [CODEX] |---|---:|---:|---:|---:|---:|
[2026-05-13 22:02:47 +0700] [CODEX] | APPENDED | 15 | **14 (93%)** | 1 (7%) | 6 (40%) | 8 (53%) |
[2026-05-13 22:02:47 +0700] [CODEX] | REAL | 37 | 15 (41%) | 5 (14%) | 12 (32%) | 11 (30%) |
[2026-05-13 22:02:47 +0700] [CODEX] | PURE_RENDER | 23 | 12 (52%) | 5 (22%) | 11 (48%) | 5 (22%) |
[2026-05-13 22:02:47 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-13 22:02:47 +0700] [CODEX] The APPENDED row is the cleanest: RAW predicts the *fast* observed label 93% of the time, REDACTED predicts the *final* observed label 53% of the time. When the conversation grows between passes, both production and our controlled rerun pick up the new content and migrate to a new code.
[2026-05-13 22:02:47 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-13 22:02:47 +0700] [CODEX] ## What this means for the redaction question
[2026-05-13 22:02:47 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-13 22:02:47 +0700] [CODEX] 1. **Stop fixing the bracket renderers**. The earlier "~31% of flips are pure-render" claim was an artifact of single-observation production noise. A controlled rerun shows 96% agreement on the pure-render bucket. Aligning fast and final renderers will not move the needle.
[2026-05-13 22:02:47 +0700] [CODEX] 2. **Focus on transcript availability timing.** The dominant fixable cause is the final pass seeing more content than the fast pass — 7 of 22 disagreements are NKP (fast saw silence) → HUP/NLM/ECH (final saw what came next). If the fast pass is going to run early on a partial transcript, its emission should be marked as preliminary; only the final-pass emission should be production-of-record. (This is already true for `label_v0_last` by convention; the question is what UI/reports consume `label_v0_first`.)
[2026-05-13 22:02:47 +0700] [CODEX] 3. **Tune LGB definition for clear language-barrier markers.** Conv `vToIkPujyyHOi0VRkfvrew` contains explicit `"I understand that you want to speak in another language other than English"` — the bot itself flags the language barrier — yet the classifier picked HUP/NVR. LGB is being missed in production. A definition tweak (or few-shot) is overdue.
[2026-05-13 22:02:47 +0700] [CODEX] 4. **PII redaction (names, phones) was not exercised here.** The R2 experiment would require name/phone masking applied to both bot and customer utterances. Based on this R1 experiment's robustness, I'd predict PII redaction would also have minimal effect on the dominant flip pairs (HUP/HUA/NKP/NLM/NVR/LGB) since they don't depend on the literal identity. Worth running a small follow-up (~$1-2) if there's PII-policy pressure.
[2026-05-13 22:02:47 +0700] [CODEX] 
