[2026-05-13 22:04:32 +0700] [CODEX] # Affirm raw-vs-redacted transcript: controlled classifier experiment
[2026-05-13 22:04:32 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-13 22:04:32 +0700] [CODEX] - timestamp: 2026-05-13 18:30 UTC / 01:30 +07 (next day)
[2026-05-13 22:04:32 +0700] [CODEX] - author: claude (claude-opus-4-7)
[2026-05-13 22:04:32 +0700] [CODEX] - model: `openai/gpt-5.5` via LLM Hub (production uses `gpt-4o-2024-11-20`; we use what's accessible to our local key — for the *relative* effect of redaction this is sound, absolute accuracy may differ from prod)
[2026-05-13 22:04:32 +0700] [CODEX] - inputs: 75 filtered-flipped Affirm convs from `affirm_flip_full_transcripts_20260513.csv`
[2026-05-13 22:04:32 +0700] [CODEX] - prompt: minimal classifier built from the active Affirm `call_code_descriptions` (45 codes, ~15k tokens)
[2026-05-13 22:04:32 +0700] [CODEX] - scripts: `scripts/affirm_redaction_classifier_experiment_20260513.py`, `scripts/affirm_redaction_experiment_analyze_20260513.py`
[2026-05-13 22:04:32 +0700] [CODEX] - artifacts: `data/inputs/sanity_v2/affirm_redaction_experiment_20260513.csv`
[2026-05-13 22:04:32 +0700] [CODEX] - cost: 150 LLM calls / 1.99M input + 44k output tokens / ~$4 / 3 min wall
[2026-05-13 22:04:32 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-13 22:04:32 +0700] [CODEX] ## TL;DR
[2026-05-13 22:04:32 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-13 22:04:32 +0700] [CODEX] - **Bracket redaction alone is almost cosmetic.** Identical-after-normalization convs agree 22/23 (96%) between raw (with-brackets) and redacted (stripped). My earlier observational claim "31% of flips will evaporate by aligning renderers" was overstated — production has variance that doesn't reappear in a controlled rerun.
[2026-05-13 22:04:32 +0700] [CODEX] - **The dominant cause of disagreement is content addition, not rendering.** APPENDED bucket: 47% agreement. REAL bucket: 65%. PURE_RENDER: 96%.
[2026-05-13 22:04:32 +0700] [CODEX] - **Number of turns is NOT the driver.** Median Δturns is +2 for both agreed and disagreed groups. **Δchars is the driver**: agreed +3, disagreed +94. New *content*, not new turn boundaries, is what flips codes.
[2026-05-13 22:04:32 +0700] [CODEX] - **The user's LGB / Spanish observation is confirmed but it's a content-addition effect, not a redaction effect.** Conv `69l2rLntLFb4LIr-ndEWAw` — fast saw 72 chars of English only, final added a Spanish sentence (`"Bueno, bueno, bueno, ¿no va a ir home?"`) → HUP → LGB. The Spanish content appeared only in the final pass because the final pass captures more transcript, not because the redacted version drops English.
[2026-05-13 22:04:32 +0700] [CODEX] - **Match against production labels**: RAW prediction matches the production fast label 54.7% (decent); REDACTED matches production final label 32% (poor). The model difference (gpt-5.5 vs prod gpt-4o) explains a chunk of the alignment gap — but the RAW-with-brackets is consistently closer to fast-pass production behavior, suggesting brackets are *signal* to the LLM in the same direction as they were to the production model.
[2026-05-13 22:04:32 +0700] [CODEX] 
