[2026-05-13 22:04:55 +0700] [CODEX] +## What I Did
[2026-05-13 22:04:55 +0700] [CODEX] +
[2026-05-13 22:04:55 +0700] [CODEX] +> ### What I did
[2026-05-13 22:04:55 +0700] [CODEX] +> That morning I moved OKR2 from an accounting plan into a signal-first dataset design: the unit is no longer only a final conversation label, but a conversation signal with assistant inquiry, user evidence, neighbor codes, priority, and adjudication source. By the afternoon I turned that design into a 40-row experiment, built separate DTMF and Affirm rerun inputs, ran the postcall classifier by YAML route, reconciled results, and prepared the human-review and redaction-impact materials. I also ran a major-voter pilot on 100 source-pool rows to test whether multi-reviewer labels can recover below-floor and flip-disagreement signals before scaling.
[2026-05-13 22:04:55 +0700] [CODEX] +
[2026-05-13 22:04:55 +0700] [CODEX] +**Result.**
[2026-05-13 22:04:56 +0700] [CODEX] +
[2026-05-13 22:04:56 +0700] [CODEX] +- Signal experiment: **PASS** across source reconciliation, version routing, evidence quality, signal lift, Auto-QC lift, fixture separation, and reviewer usability.
[2026-05-13 22:04:56 +0700] [CODEX] +- Postcall rerun: **33/40 exact match = 82.5%**, with no terminal row failures and 7 mismatch rows ready for the revive loop.
[2026-05-13 22:04:56 +0700] [CODEX] +- Human review: 40 rows packaged for review, 7 mismatches indexed, and redaction impact classified so sensitive rows are not over-decided from masked text.
[2026-05-13 22:04:56 +0700] [CODEX] +- Major-voter pilot: 100 conversations processed, average 3-way Jaccard **0.737**, below-floor recovery **0.58**, overall target recovery **0.48**, with reviewer-prod recall still below target and 3 rows needing error follow-up.
[2026-05-13 22:04:56 +0700] [CODEX] +- Affirm flip analysis: isolated tenant-specific fast-vs-final disagreement risk and separated timing/content-growth effects from pure rendering effects.
[2026-05-13 22:04:56 +0700] [CODEX] +
