[2026-05-14 22:02:03 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-14 22:02:03 +0700] [CODEX] Mode: company-wide brief (OKR-anchored, privacy-safe)
[2026-05-14 22:02:03 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-14 22:02:03 +0700] [CODEX] ## Summary
[2026-05-14 22:02:03 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-14 22:02:03 +0700] [CODEX] Today's work moved Q2 postcall evaluation from analysis into governed sample generation and stability decisioning. The main contribution was an experiment ladder for the KR1 sample database: start with voter outputs, test real-conversation extraction, calibrate against human judgement, then pivot to controlled canonical-example generation when the earlier paths did not meet the bar. In parallel, the fast-vs-final classifier work was reframed as a quality-gate problem rather than a headline accuracy claim.
[2026-05-14 22:02:03 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-14 22:02:03 +0700] [CODEX] ## Q2 OKR Alignment
[2026-05-14 22:02:03 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-14 22:02:03 +0700] [CODEX] | OKR | Today's Progress | Reporting Value |
[2026-05-14 22:02:03 +0700] [CODEX] |---|---|---|
[2026-05-14 22:02:03 +0700] [CODEX] | KR1: increase call-code test data size to >=750 and >=10 per call code | Advanced the sample database path with a controlled exemplar-generation method that covers the current call-code taxonomy across difficulty levels and is ready for team review. | Coverage growth can now proceed from a repeatable seed set instead of ad hoc examples or unreliable extraction from messy conversations. |
[2026-05-14 22:02:03 +0700] [CODEX] | KR2: reduce human-QC bug reports through Auto-QC | Turned fast-vs-final instability, reviewer disagreement, and model-alignment risk into explicit review gates. | Human review can focus on cases where the system has a measurable reason to be uncertain, rather than rechecking every row manually. |
[2026-05-14 22:02:03 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-14 22:02:03 +0700] [CODEX] ## Work Captured From Today's Recaps
[2026-05-14 22:02:03 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-14 22:02:03 +0700] [CODEX] - KR1 sample database: audited the voter-based path and the real-conversation extractor, found the calibration gap, and pivoted to synthetic canonical exemplars with stricter single-intent rules.
[2026-05-14 22:02:03 +0700] [CODEX] - Canonical exemplars: delivered a review-ready seed set across the current call-code taxonomy, using authentic bot-question patterns and stronger boundary-specific prompts.
[2026-05-14 22:02:03 +0700] [CODEX] - Fast-vs-final stability: separated instability into early rule behavior, added transcript content, version alignment, rendering sensitivity, and boundary-code overlap.
[2026-05-14 22:02:03 +0700] [CODEX] - Classifier decisioning: clarified that final stabilized labels should be treated as the production record, while preliminary labels are diagnostic signals.
[2026-05-14 22:02:03 +0700] [CODEX] - Persona-aware voting: validated persona diversification as a way to stabilize stochastic predictions, while keeping majority-vote failures visible as taxonomy or label-quality signals.
[2026-05-14 22:02:03 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-14 22:02:03 +0700] [CODEX] ## Experiment Trail
[2026-05-14 22:02:03 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-14 22:02:03 +0700] [CODEX] | Trial | What We Tried | Outcome | Decision |
[2026-05-14 22:02:03 +0700] [CODEX] |---|---|---|---|
[2026-05-14 22:02:03 +0700] [CODEX] | Phase 1: voter-review path | Reused the multi-reviewer call-code outputs as a candidate source for the KR1 sample database. | The review surface worked, but the primitive was wrong for KR1: it verifies and critiques labels rather than reliably producing clean per-code training examples. | Keep it as a KR2 Auto-QC and disagreement-detection baseline, not as the KR1 seed source. |
[2026-05-14 22:02:03 +0700] [CODEX] | Phase 1B: real-conversation extractor | Asked an LLM to inspect real conversations, locate the evidence for a target code, and assign difficulty level and confidence. | The first pass looked promising, but human calibration showed unstable rule-following at the exact boundaries KR1 needs. The model often read beyond the intended evidence pair and chose plausible judgements instead of strict labels. | Do not scale this as the main KR1 path. Archive it as a future augmentation path after better calibration. |
[2026-05-14 22:02:03 +0700] [CODEX] | Phase 1B calibration retry | Tightened the prompt with single-intent rules, better-fit-code logic, and code-specific disambiguation. | Agreement stayed below the target. Failure modes repeated around single-word answers, question-mark handling, multi-turn evidence, and adjacent code boundaries. | Treat real-conversation extraction with broad abstract rules as too brittle for the first seed. |
[2026-05-14 22:02:03 +0700] [CODEX] | Phase 1C: synthetic canonical generation | Inverted the task: generate clean examples for each code and difficulty level instead of extracting them from messy conversations. | Much cheaper and more controllable. It produced broad taxonomy coverage quickly, but the first version still mixed multiple intents in some easy examples. | Accept the direction, but add stricter single-intent constraints and review gates. |
[2026-05-14 22:02:03 +0700] [CODEX] | Phase 1C v2: tightened canonical generation | Regenerated with stronger boundary examples, authentic bot-question patterns, and a stronger model for rule adherence. | Easy-level quality improved materially on the reviewed boundary families. The output is now good enough to seed simulator review, while medium and hard levels still need spot-checking. | Use this as the current KR1 seed, with review and selective regeneration before treating it as final coverage. |
[2026-05-14 22:02:03 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-14 22:02:03 +0700] [CODEX] ## Compromise And Rationale
[2026-05-14 22:02:03 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-14 22:02:03 +0700] [CODEX] The compromise is to prioritize **clean controllable coverage first** over immediate real-production anchoring. Real conversations remain the long-term grounding source, but today's calibration showed that extracting clean single-intent examples from messy transcripts is not reliable enough to scale first. The safer path is to seed the sample database with controlled canonical examples, then use human review, selective regeneration, and later real-conversation augmentation to close realism gaps.
[2026-05-14 22:02:03 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-14 22:02:03 +0700] [CODEX] This is an acceptable compromise for KR1 because the near-term goal is balanced, reviewable coverage across the taxonomy. It is not a final truth set. The risk is that synthetic examples may be cleaner than production behavior; the control is to keep review notes, spot-check harder levels, and use real-conversation augmentation only where it adds value after the canonical seed is stable.
[2026-05-14 22:02:03 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-14 22:02:03 +0700] [CODEX] ## Approach
[2026-05-14 22:02:03 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-14 22:02:03 +0700] [CODEX] 1. Start from the OKR target, not from the available artifacts: KR1 needs balanced coverage; KR2 needs measurable reduction in manual QC effort.
[2026-05-14 22:02:03 +0700] [CODEX] 2. Use calibration as the gate for real-conversation extraction; if the extractor cannot match reviewer judgement, do not scale it as the seed source.
[2026-05-14 22:02:03 +0700] [CODEX] 3. Prefer controlled generation for canonical examples when the goal is to seed clean behavior, then use review to catch boundary contamination.
[2026-05-14 22:02:03 +0700] [CODEX] 4. Separate sample-building work from Auto-QC work so coverage growth and classifier-quality diagnostics do not blur into one metric.
[2026-05-14 22:02:03 +0700] [CODEX] 5. Treat fast-vs-final differences as a pipeline-stability question first, not as a direct classifier-quality score.
[2026-05-14 22:02:03 +0700] [CODEX] 6. Require model-aligned validation before turning redaction or rendering conclusions into shared recommendations.
[2026-05-14 22:02:03 +0700] [CODEX] 7. Keep failed or partial trials as reusable assets, but report them under the workstream they actually support.
[2026-05-14 22:02:03 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-14 22:02:03 +0700] [CODEX] ## Data Selection And Alignment
[2026-05-14 22:02:03 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-14 22:02:03 +0700] [CODEX] - Selection gate: include examples because they cover a target code and difficulty level, not because they are easy to find.
[2026-05-14 22:02:03 +0700] [CODEX] - L1 gate: require one substantive intent; rows that combine multiple code signals should be reviewed or regenerated.
[2026-05-14 22:02:03 +0700] [CODEX] - Coverage gate: keep the seed set tied to the current call-code taxonomy and the quarter target for per-code balance.
[2026-05-14 22:02:03 +0700] [CODEX] - Production-record gate: use final stabilized labels for reporting; keep preliminary labels as diagnostic inputs.
[2026-05-14 22:02:04 +0700] [CODEX] - Model-alignment gate: do not publish rendering or redaction conclusions until checked against the production classifier setup.
[2026-05-14 22:02:04 +0700] [CODEX] - Review gate: treat voter disagreement and instability as routing signals for Auto-QC, not as failures to hide.
[2026-05-14 22:02:04 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-14 22:02:04 +0700] [CODEX] ## Sharing Boundary
[2026-05-14 22:02:04 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-14 22:02:04 +0700] [CODEX] This company-wide brief shares aggregate methodology, OKR movement, and decision gates only. Detailed source records, generated review materials, and reconstruction materials are intentionally excluded here; any evidence sharing should follow the approved data-governance channel.
[2026-05-14 22:02:04 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-14 22:02:04 +0700] [CODEX] ## Next Actions
