[2026-05-14 22:03:17 +0700] [CODEX] - session topic: end-to-end investigation of Affirm-tenant fast→final call-code flips (2026-05-13 + 2026-05-14); rolls together the dual-label delta analysis, transcript-rendering vs content-change decomposition, controlled raw-vs-redacted classifier experiment on `gpt-5.5`, fast→final confusion matrix, and explicit error case enumeration into one reference document for future cold readers
[2026-05-14 22:03:17 +0700] [CODEX] - git branch: main
[2026-05-14 22:03:17 +0700] [CODEX] - recap author: claude (claude-opus-4-7)
[2026-05-14 22:03:17 +0700] [CODEX] - supersedes: `docs/session_recap/20260513_affirm-flip-delta-redaction-experiment.md` (kept for audit, but this file is the load-bearing reference)
[2026-05-14 22:03:17 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-14 22:03:17 +0700] [CODEX] ## TL;DR
[2026-05-14 22:03:17 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-14 22:03:17 +0700] [CODEX] - Affirm tenant carries a flip rate ~4× the global rate: 110/545 paired convs flip between fast (first `EndPostCallAnalysis`) and final (last `EndPostCallAnalysis`) classifier passes — **20.18% vs the 4.59% cross-tenant baseline**. Flipped median fast→final delay is 19,392s (~5.4h); consistent median is 143,174s (~40h). Disagreements appear early or not at all.
[2026-05-14 22:03:17 +0700] [CODEX] - The HUP→NLM block (29 of 110) was rule-based first-pass detection on voicemail snippets — upstream of any LLM definition tuning. After dropping rule-based (146 across consistent + flipped) and explicit ERROR (2), 75 flipped convs remain. The new dominant pair is **NVR→HUP (13.3% of post-filter flips), entirely on the mixed-hash `5f3c905…|93a01279…` ccd cohort** — i.e. YAML mid-window policy drift, not classifier behaviour.
[2026-05-14 22:03:17 +0700] [CODEX] - Side-by-side reading of full fast + final transcripts for the 75 sampled convs surfaces **three systematic rendering differences** in every Affirm conv: stage-direction tags (`[happy]/[calm]/[professional]`) stripped in final, compound assistant utterances split into separate turns in final, `[company_name: Affirm]` placeholder being substituted to an empty string in final (template-variable bug, not deliberate redaction).
[2026-05-14 22:03:17 +0700] [CODEX] - Normalizing both transcripts (strip brackets, collapse compound turns) and bucketing: **PURE_RENDER 23 (content identical after norm), APPENDED 15 (final extends fast), REAL 37 (genuinely different).** This decomposes the flip population by the *kind* of underlying input difference, before any classifier work.
[2026-05-14 22:03:17 +0700] [CODEX] - Controlled raw-vs-redacted experiment on `openai/gpt-5.5` via LLM Hub (150 calls, ~$4, 186s wall): **PURE_RENDER bucket 96% agreement (22/23 → 4.3% disagreement), APPENDED 47%, REAL 65%**. Bracket redaction alone is almost cosmetic on a modern LLM; the dominant flip driver is content addition (final pass captures more of the call), not the rendering layer. The earlier observational claim that "31% of flips are pure-render and would evaporate by aligning renderers" was overstated by production variance.
[2026-05-14 22:03:17 +0700] [CODEX] - Critical caveat the user flagged: production call-code classifier is **`gemini-3-flash` at `temperature: 0.0`, `max_retry: 3`** (yaml line 5884–5888 of `agi-sm-dsci-configs/scripts/en_collin_kompato_affirm/main.yaml`), NOT `gpt-4o` (that's reflection/response) and NOT `gpt-5.5` (what our local key allows). Temp=0 + retry-3 implies every observed production flip is a deterministic input-difference effect, never LLM lottery. The 96% PURE_RENDER agreement number needs re-validation on `gemini-3-flash` before being used as a load-bearing claim.
[2026-05-14 22:03:17 +0700] [CODEX] - Fast→final confusion matrix on all 545 paired Affirm convs surfaces the per-code stability ranking: **NLM 96%, IDV 96%, NKP 93% are near-trust-anchor; HUP 77% drives the bulk of flips (45 of 110 originate from HUP); NVR 27% / ECH 36% / LGB 0% are unstable**. Only 2 explicit ERROR convs exist (both `["ERROR"]` in `list_call_codes`, both `NO_ACTION_CODE → HUP`); no TIMEOUT cases.
[2026-05-14 22:03:17 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-14 22:03:17 +0700] [CODEX] ## What was tried
[2026-05-14 22:03:17 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-14 22:03:17 +0700] [CODEX] ### Day 1 — 2026-05-13
[2026-05-14 22:03:17 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-14 22:03:17 +0700] [CODEX] 1. **Built Affirm flip-delta join** (`scripts/affirm_callcode_flip_delta_20260513.py`): joined `master_30d_accounting_20260512.csv` (tenant axis) + `per_conv_labels_30d_20260512_v5.csv` (first + last End labels + timestamps) + `per_conv_30d_20260511_v4.csv` (diagnostic columns) for the 1,301-conv Affirm subset. Computed `delta_seconds = last_end_ts − first_end_ts` for the 545 paired convs, split consistent/flipped, ranked top flip pairs, broke down by `ccd_hash` / `end_event_count` / `usecase_id`.
[2026-05-14 22:03:17 +0700] [CODEX] 2. **Diagnosed top flip pairs by reading transcripts** (`scripts/affirm_flip_diagnose_20260513.py`): pulled 3 example transcripts per top pair plus `callcode_reason`, `list_call_codes`, `list_current_state`. Identified three mechanism buckets — rule-based fast pass overridden by LLM final pass (HUP→NLM on voicemails, 29 cases), YAML mid-window drift on multi-hash convs (NVR→HUP, 10 cases), boundary-code overlap (HUP/HUA/NKP/NLM/NVR/LGB).
[2026-05-14 22:03:17 +0700] [CODEX] 3. **Applied user-requested filters** (`scripts/affirm_callcode_flip_delta_filtered_20260513.py`): dropped 4 convs with `ERROR`/`TIMEOUT` markers and 146 convs with rule-based first labels (matched by `callcode_reason` containing "Rule-based call code detection matched … skipped LLM detection"). Of the 146 rule-based, 33 were flipped (HUP→NLM block) and 113 were consistent (HUP/HUP). Post-filter rate 18.56%, new top pair NVR→HUP (13.3%).
[2026-05-14 22:03:17 +0700] [CODEX] 4. **Sampled ≤10 conv_ids per flip pair** (seed=42, 75 convs across 42 pairs) and one-pass-streamed the 9.3GB `datadog/hybrid_30d_20260511/events.jsonl` to extract every `StartPostCallAnalysis` + `EndPostCallAnalysis` event for those convs (`scripts/affirm_sample_and_extract_snapshots_20260513.py`). Wrote per-snapshot CSV (168 rows = 75 convs × 2+ snapshot indices each).
[2026-05-14 22:03:17 +0700] [CODEX] 5. **Compared fast vs final per conv on chars / turns / user-turns** (`scripts/affirm_flip_fast_vs_final_20260513.py`): only 1.3% byte-identical, 62.7% grew, 34.7% shrank. Median Δturns = +2 across the board; median Δchars = +13 overall. Turn count is *not* the driver for boundary-code flips. Content volume is.
[2026-05-14 22:03:17 +0700] [CODEX] 6. **Surfaced three systematic rendering differences** by reading full snapshots side-by-side (`scripts/affirm_flip_diff_pairs_20260513.py`): (a) stage-direction tags `[happy]/[calm]/[professional]/[concerned]/[understanding]` present in 73% of fast transcripts, 0% of final; (b) compound `assistant: Hello. Am I speaking with X?` (1 turn) → final renders as 2 separate `assistant:` turns; (c) `Kate from [company_name: Affirm]` → `Kate from ,` (placeholder template variable becomes empty, not the actual value).
[2026-05-14 22:03:17 +0700] [CODEX] 7. **Normalized both transcripts** (strip `[stage_dir]`, strip `[placeholder]`, collapse consecutive same-role turns, normalize whitespace) and bucketed (`scripts/affirm_flip_full_transcript_diff_20260513.py`): **PURE_RENDER 23 / APPENDED 15 / REAL 37**. The same script wrote `affirm_flip_full_transcripts_20260513.csv` with full fast + final + normalized text for downstream experiments.
[2026-05-14 22:03:17 +0700] [CODEX] 8. **Quantified redaction-target presence in the population** (`scripts/affirm_redaction_effect_20260513.py`): 73.3% of fast transcripts have stage tags, 62.7% have placeholders; both 0% in final. 54.7% contain a name token ("Am I speaking with <Name>"), 8% contain a phone/digit sequence. The smoking-gun pair: `JY8UiTKvbxz29H-lOCwD2g` and `MD3V3tflKoy0kU9yINXvrQ` (both HUP→NKP) are byte-identical except `[company_name: Affirm]` → empty; both flipped.
[2026-05-14 22:03:17 +0700] [CODEX] 9. **Ran the controlled raw-vs-redacted classifier experiment** (`scripts/affirm_redaction_classifier_experiment_20260513.py`): for each of 75 convs, classified `fast_text` (RAW with brackets) and `final_text` (REDACTED stripped) under identical prompt + identical 45-code `call_code_descriptions` (60KB, ~15k tokens) + identical model = `openai/gpt-5.5` (the only model the local LLM Hub key allows). Concurrency 8, async, 0 errors, 1.99M input + 44.4k output tokens, ~$4 cost, 186s wall.
[2026-05-14 22:03:17 +0700] [CODEX] 10. **Analyzed the experiment** (`scripts/affirm_redaction_experiment_analyze_20260513.py`): **PURE_RENDER 22/23 = 96% agreement; APPENDED 7/15 = 47%; REAL 24/37 = 65%; overall 53/75 = 70.7%**. The top RAW→REDACTED disagreement pair under controlled conditions was NKP→HUP (3 cases) — not the observational HUP→NLM. The user's LGB/Spanish hypothesis was confirmed on conv `69l2rLntLFb4LIr-ndEWAw` (Spanish sentence "Bueno, bueno, bueno, ¿no va a ir home?" appears only in the final pass → HUP→LGB flip), but mechanism is content addition, not bracket redaction.
[2026-05-14 22:03:17 +0700] [CODEX] 11. **User correction on model**: production uses `gemini-3-flash` at temp=0 (verified by reading `agi-sm-dsci-configs/scripts/en_collin_kompato_affirm/main.yaml` lines 5882–5888). Our experiment ran on gpt-5.5. The 96% PURE_RENDER agreement is unconfirmed for the production model.
[2026-05-14 22:03:17 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-14 22:03:17 +0700] [CODEX] ### Day 2 — 2026-05-14
[2026-05-14 22:03:17 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-14 22:03:17 +0700] [CODEX] 12. **Elaborated the bucket table for audience consumption**. The terse "PURE_RENDER / APPENDED / REAL" labels were ambiguous; the user asked whether PURE_RENDER means "calling the same prompt twice". It does not. Re-stated explicitly: we feed two DIFFERENT transcripts (production's actual fast-pass text and final-pass text) into the SAME classifier prompt with the SAME model; the bucket characterizes what kind of difference exists between the two inputs after normalization. Confirmed verbally — no file edit yet on the report.
[2026-05-14 22:03:17 +0700] [CODEX] 13. **Built fast→final confusion matrix** for all 545 paired Affirm convs (`scripts/affirm_fast_final_confusion_20260514.py`). Rows = fast label, columns = final label. Diagonal = consistent (435), off-diagonal = flipped (110). Top 12 labels by combined volume cover 21 distinct fast labels × 18 final labels.
[2026-05-14 22:03:17 +0700] [CODEX] 14. **Enumerated error/timeout cases**: 2 convs with `["ERROR"]` in `list_call_codes` (`QnL89w-Ki73W5bPiJ-1kHw`, `DBsoEZbeqQzkPxckoFhcPw`) — both first label `NO_ACTION_CODE`, both flipped to HUP on final. No TIMEOUT markers. The other 2 NO_ACTION_CODE first labels (`hxSN4t5WU7WJo3rqa1FWLQ`, `jukpUoK_4b_fqOXL7xTZKw`) have non-ERROR `list_call_codes` — those are classifier-returned-no-code cases, not infrastructure failures.
[2026-05-14 22:03:17 +0700] [CODEX] 15. **Computed per-code stability ranking** from the confusion matrix (diagonal / row total, min n ≥ 10): NLM 96%, IDV 95.5%, NKP 92.5%, HUP 77%, WRN 75%, ECH 36.4%, NVR 26.7%. HUP is the dominant flip source by absolute count (45 of 110 flips originate from a fast-HUP row); NVR is dominant by *rate* (only 4 of 15 fast-NVR survive to final).
[2026-05-14 22:03:17 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-14 22:03:17 +0700] [CODEX] ## What was decided
[2026-05-14 22:03:17 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-14 22:03:17 +0700] [CODEX] - **Drop ERROR/TIMEOUT (2 found) + rule-based first labels (146 found)** before reasoning about flip causes. Quote: "drop those with call code error or time out, and those which have rule-based (they applied recently)". The rule-based block is upstream of any definition tuning and dwarfed the real signal.
[2026-05-14 22:03:17 +0700] [CODEX] - **Sample ≤10 convs per flip pair** for transcript-level diagnosis rather than chasing all 110 flips. Quote: "select up to 10 conversation_ids per code that different between first (fast) and later (post) call codes". Yielded 75 convs across 42 pairs.
[2026-05-14 22:03:17 +0700] [CODEX] - **Use turn count + chars + Spanish content as candidate flip drivers**. User volunteered the LGB/Spanish observation. Result: turn count is *not* the driver (Δturns identical between agreed and disagreed groups in the experiment); content volume *is* (Δchars +94 disagreed vs +3 agreed).
[2026-05-14 22:03:17 +0700] [CODEX] - **Run the controlled experiment locally on gpt-5.5** despite the model mismatch, because the local key can't access `gemini-3-flash` and the *relative* effect of bracket redaction on a modern LLM is informative even on a different model. Quote: "yes, let kick off the comparison between raw transcript and redacted one". Cost stayed under the $5 / 20-min auto-run threshold.
[2026-05-14 22:03:17 +0700] [CODEX] - **Pause on the experiment conclusions pending a gemini-3-flash rerun**. User: "We used gpt-4o or gemini-3-flash as the model for classifcation, not gpt-5.5". The headline 96% PURE_RENDER agreement is held as a tentative finding; needs production-model validation before being acted on (e.g., before claiming "bracket renderer alignment is not worth fixing" in any shared doc).
[2026-05-14 22:03:17 +0700] [CODEX] - **Treat `label_v0_first` as preliminary and `label_v0_last` as production-of-record** going forward. The fast pass runs while AssemblyAI is still completing; it sees a partial transcript, sometimes runs rule-based, and uses cached reflection from the live call. Only the final pass has the full transcript + fully settled `dict_variable`. This decision is consistent with the prior session-recap note about "fast-vs-final classifier IS double-run pipeline" but is being formalized here.
[2026-05-14 22:03:17 +0700] [CODEX] 
