[2026-05-14 22:03:23 +0700] [CODEX] ## What was tried (hypothesis → experiment → result → reflect)
[2026-05-14 22:03:23 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-14 22:03:23 +0700] [CODEX] ### Cycle 1 — Audit yesterday's voter Phase 1 (review-CSV + viewer)
[2026-05-14 22:03:23 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-14 22:03:23 +0700] [CODEX] **Hypothesis**: Yesterday's voter ensemble output (`testset_review_postprocessed.csv`, 160 rows) is review-ready for KR1, provided the schema is reshaped to fit `CsvReview_v2.html`'s dialect and Google Sheets co-edit workflow.
[2026-05-14 22:03:23 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-14 22:03:23 +0700] [CODEX] **Experiment**: Aligned `build_testset_rows.py` output schema to §7.5 of the runbook (column-order chunking by 5-8 cognitive chunks; `reviewer_notes` next to evidence; voter dialect badges in viewer). Re-rendered 160 rows.
[2026-05-14 22:03:23 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-14 22:03:23 +0700] [CODEX] **Result**: CSV opens cleanly in `CsvReview_v2.html` with the new voters-dialect badges (level / reviewer_verdict / agreement). Distributions: 56 strict / 60 miss / 44 defensible.
[2026-05-14 22:03:23 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-14 22:03:23 +0700] [CODEX] **Reflect**: The schema work was useful plumbing, but the user's question — *"what is the next step on Phase 2?"* — surfaced a deeper problem: the voter ensemble is a classifier-verifier (KR2 territory), not the evidence-locator that KR1 needs. Voter outputs *happen* to include evidence_turns, but the primitive is wrong. Quotation captured in [`20260514_reflection_may13_planning_docs.md`](../thinking/20260514_reflection_may13_planning_docs.md).
[2026-05-14 22:03:23 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-14 22:03:23 +0700] [CODEX] ### Cycle 2 — Phase 1B intent extractor (real-conv mining)
[2026-05-14 22:03:23 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-14 22:03:23 +0700] [CODEX] **Hypothesis**: Treating `(conv_id, target_code)` as input where `target_code ∈ prod.list_call_codes`, a single LLM call per pair can locate user-utterance evidence + tag L1/L2/L3 + emit 4-axis confidence (lexical / position / phase-alignment / discriminative power). 149 rows, all 45 codes, ~$5 budget.
[2026-05-14 22:03:23 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-14 22:03:23 +0700] [CODEX] **Experiment**: Built `src/intent_extract/{prompt,sampler,runner,build_csv,postprocess_map}.py`. Sampler stratified by target code from `master_30d_accounting_20260512.csv` + `per_conv_30d_20260511_v3.csv`, filtered to Kompato + newer-policy hash. Runner: async per-row LLM calls via LLM Hub, `gpt-4o`, concurrency=5.
[2026-05-14 22:03:23 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-14 22:03:23 +0700] [CODEX] **Result**: 149 rows, $3.82, 93% `evidence_found=true`, distribution L1: 75% / L2: 23% / L3: 1%. Quality on quick inspection looked solid. Notable finding (validated yesterday's voter spot-check): the 5 prod-emitted `INC` rows in this sample are actually `DEC` cases — the extractor refused to anchor INC to "she died" utterances, with explicit notes.
[2026-05-14 22:03:23 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-14 22:03:23 +0700] [CODEX] **Reflect**: Output looked good but a deeper review against the user's hand-grading exposed systematic issues — load-bearing rules in the prompt were ignored. Details in next cycle.
[2026-05-14 22:03:23 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-14 22:03:23 +0700] [CODEX] ### Cycle 3 — L1 calibration against 14 user-annotated rows
[2026-05-14 22:03:24 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-14 22:03:24 +0700] [CODEX] **Hypothesis**: A v2 prompt with tighter L1 (single substantive intent; pair-in-isolation litmus) + a `better_fit_code` field + code-specific disambiguation (ATY/BKP/NNP/CAB/DNC/TPC) achieves ≥80% agreement with the user's hand-grading on the 17-row calibration subset.
[2026-05-14 22:03:24 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-14 22:03:24 +0700] [CODEX] **Experiment**: User reviewed 17 rows in Google Sheets ([`intent_review` tab](https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1jwTsoz3jRuZ3AyxlDN9OgwHMw4v-6F91X8G27Ez5kTc/edit?gid=1480612147)) and wrote `reviewer_notes` on 14. Rewrote prompt to v2; re-ran extractor on same 17 rows.
[2026-05-14 22:03:24 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-14 22:03:24 +0700] [CODEX] **Result**: **Only 6 of 17 clearly agreed (35%); 4 partial; 7 clearly disagreed.** Four recurring failure modes:
[2026-05-14 22:03:24 +0700] [CODEX] 1. *Q-mark and single-word rules ignored* when broader transcript eventually resolves intent (the model reads past the evidence pair).
[2026-05-14 22:03:24 +0700] [CODEX] 2. *"Information value" rule too rigid* on ATY ↔ BKP boundary — user's actual heuristic is "what is the user asking us to act on", not "which signal is named first".
[2026-05-14 22:03:24 +0700] [CODEX] 3. *better_fit_code* restricted to prod-emitted codes, so multi-turn DNC-from-CDS case couldn't flag DNC.
[2026-05-14 22:03:24 +0700] [CODEX] 4. *Multi-turn evidence pattern* not detected (TPC + PCAB packed into "Five." answering "When's a good callback time?").
[2026-05-14 22:03:24 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-14 22:03:24 +0700] [CODEX] **Reflect**: Stacking explicit rules into a single prompt fails when the LLM has to apply 4-5 rules simultaneously in one inference. Rule-following is unreliable in single-shot — the model defaults to plausible-sounding judgement instead of strict rule application. **Real-conv extraction with abstract rules is a dead end.**
[2026-05-14 22:03:24 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-14 22:03:24 +0700] [CODEX] ### Cycle 4 — Pivot to synthetic generation (Phase 1C)
[2026-05-14 22:03:24 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-14 22:03:24 +0700] [CODEX] **Hypothesis** (user-prompted): Generating canonical (Q, A) exemplars per (code, level) with a light-weight LLM is cheaper, more controllable, and dodges the rule-application problem — the LLM only needs to *produce* clean exemplars, not *detect* their cleanliness in messy real text.
[2026-05-14 22:03:24 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-14 22:03:24 +0700] [CODEX] **Experiment**: Built `src/intent_extract/generate_exemplars.py`. One LLM call per code generates 5 exemplars × 3 levels = 15 exemplars. Smoke on 5 codes (ATY, BKP, DNC, CAB, DSA) with `gpt-4o-mini`. Output schema: `code, level, exemplar_idx, evidence_qa_pair, assistant_question_verbatim, user_response_verbatim, rationale, lexical_evidence_match, information_value, stylistic_notes, reviewer_notes`.
[2026-05-14 22:03:24 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-14 22:03:24 +0700] [CODEX] **Result**: 75 exemplars, $0.01, ~60s wall. Quality strong on visual inspection — BKP L1 had chapter + case number; CAB L1 had explicit time; ATY L1 had attorney mention with name; DNC L1 was clean stop-call; DSA L1 named a debt-relief company. Scaled to full 45 codes (1 parse error on DSA, retried with `gpt-4o`): 675 exemplars total, $0.13, ~4.5 min. Uploaded to Sheet tab [`1c_intents`](https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1jwTsoz3jRuZ3AyxlDN9OgwHMw4v-6F91X8G27Ez5kTc/edit?gid=763087654).
[2026-05-14 22:03:24 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-14 22:03:24 +0700] [CODEX] **Reflect**: Synthetic generation is the right primitive for KR1 sample-DB seed. The simulator team can lift any (code, level) exemplar directly. **Cost ratio vs Phase 1B**: $0.13 vs $3.82 for inferior output. The rule-application problem dissolves because the LLM is producing, not detecting.
[2026-05-14 22:03:24 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-14 22:03:24 +0700] [CODEX] ### Cycle 5 — L1 single-intent refinement (Phase 1C v2)
[2026-05-14 22:03:24 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-14 22:03:24 +0700] [CODEX] **Hypothesis** (after user review): L1 currently has multi-intent contamination (the user pointed to `"I'm their sister, you can call back after 6 PM"` as a TPC + PCAB pack). Refining the prompt with (a) the single-substantive-intent rule, (b) concrete TPC/BKP/ATY/CAB/DNC counter-examples, (c) the 4-stage bot question repertoire (so assistant Qs are authentic), and (d) upgrading to `gpt-4o` for stricter rule-following, will produce clean single-intent L1.
[2026-05-14 22:03:24 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-14 22:03:24 +0700] [CODEX] **Experiment**: Saved `feedback_L1_single_intent.md` to memory. Rewrote prompt with code-specific disambiguation rules. Smoked on 5 codes (TPC, DNC, ATY, BKP, CAB) with `gpt-4o-mini` — TPC L1 still contaminated. Switched to `gpt-4o` and ran full 45-code regeneration.
[2026-05-14 22:03:24 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-14 22:03:24 +0700] [CODEX] **Result**: 675 exemplars, $1.75, ~87s wall, 0 parse errors. L1 quality dramatically cleaner:
[2026-05-14 22:03:24 +0700] [CODEX] - TPC L1: third-party identification + alternative contact (different number / location), no callback-time contamination.
[2026-05-14 22:03:24 +0700] [CODEX] - BKP L1: all past-tense filed + Chapter or case number.
[2026-05-14 22:03:24 +0700] [CODEX] - ATY L1: all present-tense attorney references.
[2026-05-14 22:03:24 +0700] [CODEX] - CAB L1: all explicit date + time.
[2026-05-14 22:03:24 +0700] [CODEX] - DNC L1: clean single-intent stop-call.
[2026-05-14 22:03:24 +0700] [CODEX] - WCR L1: correctly combines stop-calling + alternate-channel preference (which IS WCR's definition).
[2026-05-14 22:03:24 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-14 22:03:24 +0700] [CODEX] Uploaded to Sheet tab [`1c_intents_v2`](https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1jwTsoz3jRuZ3AyxlDN9OgwHMw4v-6F91X8G27Ez5kTc/edit?gid=659663005).
[2026-05-14 22:03:24 +0700] [CODEX] 
[2026-05-14 22:03:24 +0700] [CODEX] **Reflect**: Two things landed the win: (1) **model-strength matters more than prompt cleverness** — `gpt-4o-mini` failed at TPC even with explicit counter-examples; `gpt-4o` got it on the first try; (2) **concrete counter-examples beat abstract rules** — the prompt now says `L1 BAD: "This is his sister, call back after 5 PM."` next to `L1 GOOD: "This is his sister. You can reach him at his work, 555-1234."` rather than just stating the single-intent principle.
