[2026-05-14 22:05:56 +0700] [CODEX] +## Post-Baseline Work
[2026-05-14 22:05:56 +0700] [CODEX]  
[2026-05-14 22:05:56 +0700] [CODEX] -1. Start from the OKR target, not from the available artifacts: KR1 needs balanced coverage; KR2 needs measurable reduction in manual QC effort.
[2026-05-14 22:05:56 +0700] [CODEX] -2. Use calibration as the gate for real-conversation extraction; if the extractor cannot match reviewer judgement, do not scale it as the seed source.
[2026-05-14 22:05:56 +0700] [CODEX] -3. Prefer controlled generation for canonical examples when the goal is to seed clean behavior, then use review to catch boundary contamination.
[2026-05-14 22:05:56 +0700] [CODEX] -4. Separate sample-building work from Auto-QC work so coverage growth and classifier-quality diagnostics do not blur into one metric.
[2026-05-14 22:05:56 +0700] [CODEX] -5. Treat fast-vs-final differences as a pipeline-stability question first, not as a direct classifier-quality score.
[2026-05-14 22:05:56 +0700] [CODEX] -6. Require model-aligned validation before turning redaction or rendering conclusions into shared recommendations.
[2026-05-14 22:05:56 +0700] [CODEX] -7. Keep failed or partial trials as reusable assets, but report them under the workstream they actually support.
[2026-05-14 22:05:56 +0700] [CODEX] +**Why.** The earlier snapshot already summarized the broader KR1 and KR2 movement. The net-new afternoon work adds a narrower diagnostic layer: compare day-to-day call-code distribution movement so the next review can prioritize the largest changes instead of scanning every daily output.
[2026-05-14 22:05:56 +0700] [CODEX]  
