[2026-05-14 22:06:11 +0700] [CODEX] -| Phase 1B: real-conversation extractor | Asked an LLM to inspect real conversations, locate the evidence for a target code, and assign difficulty level and confidence. | The first pass looked promising, but human calibration showed unstable rule-following at the exact boundaries KR1 needs. The model often read beyond the intended evidence pair and chose plausible judgements instead of strict labels. | Do not scale this as the main KR1 path. Archive it as a future augmentation path after better calibration. |
[2026-05-14 22:06:11 +0700] [CODEX] -| Phase 1B calibration retry | Tightened the prompt with single-intent rules, better-fit-code logic, and code-specific disambiguation. | Agreement stayed below the target. Failure modes repeated around single-word answers, question-mark handling, multi-turn evidence, and adjacent code boundaries. | Treat real-conversation extraction with broad abstract rules as too brittle for the first seed. |
[2026-05-14 22:06:11 +0700] [CODEX] -| Phase 1C: synthetic canonical generation | Inverted the task: generate clean examples for each code and difficulty level instead of extracting them from messy conversations. | Much cheaper and more controllable. It produced broad taxonomy coverage quickly, but the first version still mixed multiple intents in some easy examples. | Accept the direction, but add stricter single-intent constraints and review gates. |
